0.entry: #A#, _pron._ he, XIII _a_ 27, 47, 48; they, XIII _a_ 13, _b_ 22, 36, 39,61, 64, 66. [Unaccented form of ME. _ha_. _See_ Hare, Ham.]

1.entry: #A#, _v. inf._ have, I 127. [Reduced unaccented form of _haue_; _see_Habbe(n).]

2.entry: #A(n)#, _adj._ one, IV _b_ 34; _indef. art._ a(n), I 22, VIII _b_ 7, &c._See_ Ane, On(e).

3.entry: #A(n)#, _prep._ on, in, &c. II 137, III _introd._, 22, VIII _a_ 43, XIII_a_ 11, _b_ 19, 34, &c.; _a blode_, with blood, XV _g_ 16; _a nyghtes_,at night (OE. _on niht_, _nihtes_), VIII _b_ 16; _a þre_, in three, XIII_b_ 49 (_see_ Ato, Atwynne); _a Goddes half_, for God's sake, XII _b_80. [Weakened form of On, _q.v._; _an_ in III is possibly dialectal; _a_is used only before following consonant.] _See_ Ane.

6.entry: #Abate#, _v._ to lessen, XIV _b_ 19; reduce, VIII _a_ 209 (_imper.sg._); _intr._ XVII 445; #Abatid# (_of_), _pp._ ceased, VII 104. [OFr._abatre_.]

9.entry: #Abide#, #Abyde#, #Habide#, _v._ (i) _intr._ to wait, remain, stay, II84, IX 197, XVII 531; tarry, II 348; _imper._ wait!, V 149; halt!, XVI213; (ii) _trans._ to await, XVII 334; withstand, endure, XIV _b_ 31;

10.entry: #Abode#, _pa. t._ XIV _c_ 68, XVII 373; #Abyde#, _pp._ in _ys abyde_,has survived, XIII _b_ 50. [OE. _ā-bīdan_.] _See_ Bide.

15.entry: #Aboue(n)#, #Abovin#, #Abuf#, _adv._ above, overhead, on top, V 149, VII105, 135, IX 56, X 61; on the surface, VII 160; _prep._ above, higherthan, XI _b_ 182, XVII 83; _quasi-sb._ in _be at here aboue_, get theupper hand of them, XIII _a_ 61. [OE. _*on-bufan_, _abufan_.] _See_Abone.

17.entry: #Aboute(n)#, #Abowte#, #Obout# (XIV _a_), (i) _adv._ about, round, onall sides, here and there, to and fro, I 233, V 165, VIII _a_ 297, XI_b_ 270, XII _a_ 143, _b_ 117, XIV _a_ 15, XV _i_ 3, XVII 303, 351, &c.;round about, VII 83, &c.; round it, II 359; _al aboute round_, all roundabout, XII _a_ 79; (ii) _prep._ about, round, &c. (often following _n._or _pron._), I 54, II 274, 284, V 95, XIV _b_ 68, &c.; on, XI _b_ 236;in, XI _b_ 293, 296; _about al_, in all directions, II 387; _aboute_with _for to (vnbynde)_, XVI 7. [OE. _onbūtan_, _ābūtan_.]

23.entry: #Accordandly#, _adv._ accordingly, IV _b_ 33. [From pres. p. of Acorde.]

24.entry: #Acord(e)#, #Accord#, _n._ agreement, VI 149, XI _a_ 32; concurrence,united will, XVII 30; _made acorde of care and me_, associated me with,caused me to know, care, VI 11. [OFr. _acord(e)_.]

25.entry: #Acorde(n)#, _v. trans._ to reconcile, V 337; _to acorde me with_, toassociate myself with, V 312; _intr._ agree, XI _b_ 128, XII _b_ 145,XIII _b_ 52. [OFr. _acorder_.] _See_ Corden.

29.entry: #Aday#, _adv._ in _dyne aday_, eat at (mid-day) meal, VIII _a_ 303. [OE._on dæge_, by day.]

30.entry: #Ademand#, _n._ loadstone (magnetic iron ore), IX 123, 125, &c. [OFr._adema(u)nt_, L. _adamantem_ (acc.), properly 'diamond'. The applicationto 'loadstone' was due to false association with L. _ad-amāre_. Themediaeval 'adamant' in consequence often combined the properties ofdiamond and loadstone.] _See_ Dyamand.

35.entry: #Adresced#, _pp._; _therupon him hath adresced_, has fastened himself toit, XII _b_ 85. _See_ Dresse. [OFr. _adresser_.]

36.entry: #Aduersouris#, _n. pl._ adversaries, X 144. [OFr. _adversier_ withalteration of suffix.]

37.entry: #Afelde#, _adv._ to the fields, VIII _a_ 136, 283. [OE. _on felda_.]_See_ Feld(e).

49.entry: #After# (#-ir#, #-yr#, #-ur#), _adv._ after, behind, II 378, VII 24, XVI376, &c.; afterwards, then, VII 46, VIII _a_ 5, &c.; _be the whiche ...after_, in accordance with which (mixed Fr. and E. constr.), IX 302;_prep._ after, next to, I 215, XI _b_ 27, &c.; according to, IX 220,291, XI _b_ 189, &c.; for (after _desire_, _ask_, &c.), VII 20, VIII _a_291, XV _h_ 5, XVI 242, &c.; _conj._ after, XVII 148. _After þan_,afterwards, II 597. [OE. _æfter_; _æfter þā̆m_.]

51.entry: #Agayn(e)#, #Agane#, _adv._ back, again, IV _b_ 83, XVI 11, XVII 180,479, &c. _See_ Aȝayn.

53.entry: #Agaynste#, _prep._ against, XVI 280; _to loke a._, to gaze on, XVI 92.[Extended from prec.]

54.entry: #Agast#, _pp._ afraid, XIV _c_ 51, XVII 184, 297; astonished, XVII 449.[_a-_ + OE. _gæsted_, afflicted.] _See_ Gastli.

55.entry: #Age#, _n._ age, time of life, VI 52, XII _introd._; mature age, IX 22;old age, VII 6, XIV _c_ 106, &c. [OFr. _age_.]

61.entry: #Aȝayn#, #Aȝen#, #Aȝein#, #Aye#, #Oȝain#, _prep._ against,III 58, V 48, IX 19; towards (of time), II 497, XII _b_ 18. [As prec.]_See_ Agayn.

68.entry: #Ai#, #Ay#, _adv._ always, ever, IV _a_ 1, 14, VII 18, X 61, XV _a_ 10,17, &c.; _for ay_, for ever, XVII 26. [ON. _ei_.]

69.entry: #Ay#, _n._ fear, in _for loue or ay_, in any event, II 571. [OE. _ege_.]

75.entry: #Aither#, #Ayþer#, #Athir#, #Eyþer#, _adj._ and _pron._ both, VII 65;either, V 112; _eyþer oþer_, each other, XIII _b_ 57; _athir othir in_,one in the other, X 22. [OE. _ǣgþer_, both; _ā(w)þer_, either.]_See_ Euþer.

76.entry: #Ayther#, #Aþer#, _conj._ or, VI 131; _ayther ... or_, either ... or,XVII 477. [As prec.] _See_ Or^2; Oþer, _conj._

80.entry: #Al#, _adj._ all, I 120, II 114, III 6, &c.; #Alle#, I 19, &c.; _pl._III 55, &c.; _al(l) a(n)_, a whole, VII 183, VIII _a_ 253, XIII _a_ 32,44, XIV _c_ 4; _al(le) maner(e)_, all kinds of, II 589, XI _a_ 12 (_cf._Alkyn); _al(le) þing(e)_, _see_ Þing; _all way_, _weys_, _see_ Alway,Way; _all it_ (_þei_, _we_), all of it (them, us), XV _g_ 16, IX 104,XVII 456, &c.; _here names of alle_, the names of them all, I 37; _of aland sum_, in general and particular, in full, VI 224; as _sb._ all, XVI303, &c.; every one (with _sg._ verb), VI 87. [OE. _al(l)_.] _See_Algate, Alkyn, Alsaume, &c.

81.entry: #Al#, #All(e)#, _adv._ entirely, quite, very, I 108, II 76, V 304, VIII_a_ 138, &c.; in comb. with To-, II 81, 106, 262, IV _a_ 78, VII 147;with For-, II 398, XV _c_ 29. _Al away_, quite away, IV _a_ 75; _alone_, alone, V 87, XII _a_ 131, _b_ 15; _al oon_, all one (and the samething), XI _a_ 41; _al to_, up to (the number of), III 56; _all be(were) it þat_, although, IX 50, 171, 302, 312; _all if_, although, XVII231. [OE. _al(l)_.]

82.entry: #Al#, #All(e)#, _n._ all, everything, III 43, 51, &c.; _about al_, inall directions, II 387; _ouer al_, everywhere, II 208 (OE. _ofer all_).[OE. _al(l)_.]

86.entry: #Algate#, _adv._ by all means, at any rate, I 107, II 231. [_Cf._ ON._alla götu_, all along, always.] _See_ Gate, _n._^2

90.entry: #Aliri#, _adv._ ? across one another (of legs), VIII _a_ 116. [? Relatedto Lyre, _n._^2]

95.entry: #Alleg(g)e(n)#, _v._ to cite (in support of a contention), XI _b_ 56,XVI 277; to contend, XI _b_ 79. [OFr. _esligier_, _aligier_, associatedwith unrelated L. _allēgāre_.]

96.entry: #Allowe#, _v._ approve, receive with approval, XVI 330; #Alod#, _pp._XVII 56 (note). [OFr. _alouer_, from L. _allaudāre_.]

99.entry: #Almes(se)#, _n. sg._ an act, or works, of charity, charitable gift oroffering, VIII _a_ 121, 140, XI _b_ 2, 163, 270, &c.; #Elmesses# _pl._(OKt. _elmessan_), III 17. [OE. _ælmesse_.]

102.entry: #Alofte#, _adv._ in the air, aloft, V 220, XII _a_ 94, &c. [ON. _áloft_.] _See_ Lofte.

105.entry: #Als#, _adv._ also, as well, V 292, VIII _a_ 148, X 8, 11, XVII 126,127. [Reduced form of Also, _q.v._]

106.entry: #Als#, #Alss#, _conj._ as (_esp._ in _als ... as_, as ... as), like, IV_a_ 2, 63, 84, _b_ 86, VIII _a_ 37, &c.; as for instance, like, XVI 306,308, 311; as, while, IV _b_ 43, XV _a_ 4; _als ... þat_, so ... that, IX151; _als b(i)liue_, as quickly (as possible), straightway, II 531, 584.[As prec.] _See_ As.

108.entry: #Also#, #Alsua# (X), _adv._ also, as well, I 35, II 144, X 33, &c.;_conj._ like, II 508; _also bliue_, _also spac_, _also swiþe_, asquickly (as possible), straightway, II 142, 343, 574. [OE. _al-swā_.]_See_ Als, As.

109.entry: #Al(l)way#, #-wey#, _adv._ always, (for) ever, continually, XIII _a_ 3,_b_ 63, XVI 150, 168, &c.; in any case, certainly, XVI 164. [OE. _alneweg_.] _See_ Algate(s).

110.entry: #Am#, _1 sg. pres. ind._ am, V 90, &c.; coalescing with prec. pron. inIcham, Ycham (_q.v._). [OE. _am_.] _See_ Ar, Art, Is, &c.

112.entry: #Amang#, _adv._ in the meanwhile, XVII 247; #Emang#, at times, from timeto time, XVI 262, 301. [OE. _on-(ge)máng_.] _See_ Amonge.

113.entry: #Ame#, _v._ to guess; _as y kan ame_, I guess, I 45. [OFr. _aesmer_,_amer_.]

114.entry: #Amend(e)#, _v._ to make better, reform, set right, VIII _a_ 268, IX338, XI _a_ 48, XVII 256. [OFr. _amender_.] _See_ Mend(e).

118.entry: #Amiddes#, _adv._ in the midst, XII _a_ 170; _prep._ (from) among, II191. [Prec. + adv. _-es_.]

121.entry: #Among(e)#, _prep._ among, II 220, VIII _a_ 89, &c.; #Emang#, #Emong#,XVII 112; (follows noun) XVII 400. [OE. _on-(ge)máng_.] _See_ Amang,Mong.

123.entry: #Amorwe#, _adv._ on the next day, II 181, 497. [OE. _on morgene_.]

124.entry: #An#, #And#, #Ant#, _conj._ and, I 254, VIII _a_ 205, XI _a_ 1, XV _b_11, _d_ 2, _e_ 6, _g_ 25, 26, _i_ 5, &c.; _an te_, and the, XV _e_ 19;if, II 43, VI 200, 238, VIII _a_ 250, XIII _a_ 44, _b_ 39, XIV _c_ 14,103, XVI 208 (even if), XVII 297, 502. On postponement of _and_ in Gowersee note to XII _a_ 26. [OE. _and_.]

127.entry: #Ane#, _indef. art._ a, X 5, 16, 31, &c.; representing older inflectedforms, III 11 (first), 13, 49; _adj._ one, a single, IV _a_ 58, X 157;(predicatively) one, united, IV _a_ 56; _pron._ one, IV _b_ 1, 43; acertain person, IV _a_ 69, X 169. _See_ A(n), On(e).

128.entry: #Ane#, _prep._ on; _ane his lhordes haf_, on his master's behalf, III11. [From OE. _on_, _an_, on anal. of _in_, _inne_.]

138.entry: #Anoynt#, _v._ to smear, XVII 127. [Formed on OFr. _enoint_ pp. of_enoindre_.]

139.entry: #Anon(e)#, _adv._ at once, straightway, next, II 385, 499, VI 224, XVII490, 526, &c.; #Onone#, VII 149, XVII 275. [OE. _on ān_.]

140.entry: #Anothire#, #Anoþer#, _adj._ and _pron._ another, IV _b_ 3, 34, IX 37,&c.; #Anoþur#, XIV _c_ 27; #Anouþer#, I 140; #Anodir#, XVI 87. [OE._ān_ + _ōþer_.]

142.entry: #*Anowrned#, _pp._ adorned, II 363 (MS. anowed). [OFr. _aourner_; ? _a-_to _an-_ on anal. of E. alternation _a-_, _an-_.]

150.entry: #Ap(p)ere#, #Appiere#, _v._ to appear, VI 45, XII _a_ 132, XVI 368, XVII173. [OFr. _aper-_; _apareir_.]

151.entry: #Ap(p)eyre#, _v._ to do harm to, injure, impair, VIII _a_ 126, 164, 212,XIII _b_ 14; #Apeyryng#, _n._ impairing, XIII _b_ 15. [OFr. _empeirer_.]_See_ Empeyre.

152.entry: #Apert#, _adj._ plain, V 324; _adv._ openly, plainly, I 200, VI 229; forall to see, II 586. [OFr. _apert_.]

154.entry: #Aposede#, _pa. t._ put a (hard) question to, VIII _b_ 10. [OFr._oposer_, _aposer_.]

163.entry: #Ar#, _conj._ before (usually with _subj._), VIII _a_ 93, 196, 258, 261,269, XV _g_ 33, &c. [OE. _ǣr_, and with weak stress _æ̆r_(?).]_See_ Are; Er(e), _adv._; Or.

164.entry: #Ar(e)#, _pres. ind. pl._ are, IV _b_ 18, V 9, 27, &c.; #Aren#, VIII _a_268, 270, &c.; #Arn(e)#, II 13, VI 24, 42, &c. [OE. (Nth.) _aron_.]_See_ Art, Er(e), Ben, &c.

165.entry: #Aray#, _n._ array, X 68; rank, estate, VI 131; _of aray_, stately, XVII539 (or _grete of aray_, great in magnificence). [OFr. _arei_.]

169.entry: #Are#, _adv._ before, I 93, XVI 38, 98, 345. [ON. _ár_ (? late Nth._ar_); but see Ar, _conj._]

172.entry: #Aryȝt#, _adv._ rightly, right well, XIII _b_ 46; #Ariht#, XII _a_67, XIV _c_ 61. [OE. _on-riht_, _ariht_.]

173.entry: #Arise#, #Aryse#, _v._ to arise, rise, get up, come to pass, II 311,VIII _a_ 112, 261, 319, _b_ 15; #Aros#, _pa. t. sg._ II 318, XV _g_ 1(note). [OE. _ā-rīsan_.]

175.entry: #Armes#, _n. pl._ arms, weapons, (knightly) warfare, II 182, IX 109, &c.[OFr. _armes_.]

178.entry: #Arryuen#, #Aryue#, _v._ to come to land, IX 184; to come (to adestination), VI 87. [OFr. _arriver_.]

179.entry: #Art#, _2 sg. pres. ind._ art, I 202, 204, II 422, &c.; #Artow#, artthou, II 421 (_see_ Þou); #Ert#, VIII _b_ 34. [OE. _eart_.]

180.entry: #Artetykes#, _adj. pl._ arthritic, accompanied with inflammation of thejoints, IX 314. _See_ Gowtes. [OFr. _artetique_, corruptly from L._arthrīticus_.]

182.entry: #As(e)#, _conj._ as, I 24, II 290, III 48, &c.; _as ... as_ (foll. byaccus.), XVII 19; _as that_, as, XVII 182; _as hys desserte_, accordingto his deserts, VI 235; even as, seeing that, XVII 427, 552; _as euer_,as sure as ever, XVII 237, 395; so (in oaths, &c.), V 55, &c.; as if(usually with _subj._) I 31, 121, 195, II 108, 402, V 106, 133, 134,189, 194, 221, 326, VII 45; as relative particle, I _introd._, XVII 325;_as swyþe_, _tyte_, straightway, I 111, XVII 219. [Further reduced fromAls, _q.v._]

185.entry: #Aske(n)#, #Aski# (II), _v._ to ask for, demand, I 131, II 450, 467, VI220, &c.; require, VIII _b_ 71; inquire, I 132, IX 176. [OE._ā̆xian_.] _See_ Axe(n).

186.entry: #Aspien#, #Asspye#, _v._ to detect, observe, VIII _a_ 123, 217, XI _a_60; #Aspide#, _pa. t._ III 42. [OFr. _espier_.] _See_ Spie.

187.entry: #Assai#, #Assay#, _n._ test, trial; _at assai_, when put to the test,XIV _c_ 5; _set in, till, hard(e) assay_, place in sore straits, X 62,170, 188. [OFr. _essai_, _assai_.]

188.entry: #Assaie#, #Assay(e)#, #Asay#, _v._ to test, prove, make trial, II 452,568, V 294, IX 61, 102, 121, XIV _c_ 66, XVII 219, 249, 433; toendeavour, VIII _a_ 24, XII _b_ 81. [OFr. _essayer_.] _See_ Saye.

189.entry: #Assaylle#, #As(s)ale#, #Assa(i)lȝe# (X), _v._ to assail, attack, IX88, X 4, 12, 43, 114, 132, 144, XVII 295, &c.; #Assaling#, _n._ assault,X 41, 60. [OFr. _as(s)aillir_.]

195.entry: #As(s)ente#, _n._ agreement; compliance, VI 31; _of þare assente_, oflike mind with them, XVI 310. [OFr. _asente_.]

201.entry: #Asunder#, #-yr#, _adv._ apart, I 224; pleon. with _parte_, I 103. [OE._on-sundran_.] _See_ Sonder.

202.entry: #Aswon(e)#, _adj._ in a swoon, I 195 (note), II 549. [OE._geswōgen_.] _See_ Falle(n); Swone.

203.entry: #At#, _prep._ at, I 13, 74, &c.; in, VII 66, VIII _a_ 63; IX 253; _atwordes_, in words, II 139; (of time) V 23, 100, IX 284, XI _a_ 12; to, V108, VII 13; with infin. (_at do_), _see_ Do; according to, I 82, II271, XIV _b_ 56, XVI 258, XVII 4, 322; at the value of, VIII _a_ 162,_b_ 101, XVII 364; at the hands of, from, I 239, 240, 245, II 179, III4, 31 (_see_ Atte). #At on#, at one, in accord, VI 18; _at þe full_,completely, XI _b_ 198; _haue at þe_, _see_ Habbe(n). [OE. _æt_.] _See_Atte; Þare.

204.entry: #At#, _rel. particle_; _þat at_, that which, what, VI 176 (note); _quharat_, _see_ Whar. [ON. _at_; _þat at_ is possibly for _þat tat_ (cf.Atte, Þou, &c.).]

212.entry: #Ato#, _adv._ in two, apart, II 125, IX 140; #Atwo#, VIII _a_ 97. [OE._on twā_.] _See_ A(n) _prep._; Tuo.

216.entry: #Atslyke#, _v._ to slip away; _atslykeȝ_, is spent, VI 215. [OE._æt-_ + _slīcan_.]

217.entry: #Atte#, #Ate#, at the, II 232, 379, III 4, VIII _a_ 96, _b_ 29; of the,III 31; in fixed expressions where Mn. E. has 'at', as: _atte chirche_,VIII _a_ 50; _at(t)e firste_, _last(e)_, _mete_, _see_ Furste, Laste,Mete; _atte nale_ = _atten_ (OE. _æt þam_) _ale_, over the ale, VIII _a_109. _See_ At.

218.entry: #Atteynte#, _v._ to convict, prove guilty, XVI 278. [From _ateint_,convicted, pp. of OFr. _ateindre_. See next.]

222.entry: #Avayll#, #Avale#, _v._ to be of use to, XVII 154; _it avalis you_, (it)is your best course, XVII 296. [_a-_ + OFr. _vail-_, _valeir_.]

223.entry: #Avale#, #Availl# (X), _v. intr._ to descend, IX 195; _trans._ to letdown, X 28. [OFr. _avaler_.]

226.entry: #Auctour#, _n._ original authority, author, IX 304; #Autours#, _pl._ XI_a_ 23. [OFr. _autour_, and (from 14th c.) _auctour_, &c.]

228.entry: #Aue Maria#, an Ave, Hail Mary, IX 323. [First two words of Latinprayer.]

229.entry: #Auentur(e)#, #Auentour#, _n._ chance, (notable) occurrence, feat, II15, 18, 32, &c.; risk, X 118; _an auenture_, (as _conj._) in case, VIII_a_ 43; _at auentur_, as chance directed, recklessly, XIV _c_ 34. [OFr._aventure_.] _See_ Aunter.

235.entry: #Aunsetris#, _n. pl._ ancestors, men of former days, VII 5. [OFr._ancestre_, nom. sg.]

236.entry: #Aunter#, _n._ chance, event, VII 5, 67, 155. [As Auentur; but due toolder and more popular borrowing.]

240.entry: #Awai#, #Away(e)#, #Awei(e)#, #Awey(e)#, _adv._ away, VIII _a_ 184, XII_b_ 132, &c.; #Avay#, X 58, 187; #Oway#, II 192, 261, 329; #Owy# (inrime), II 96, 491, 561; _don awei_, abolished, XI _b_ 206; _wanneawaye_, rescued, XVI 171; _predic._, gone, over, II 59 (_oway_), XVII537. [OE. _on-weg_, _aweg_; ? with _owy_, cf. rare OE. _wig_.]

241.entry: #Awake#, _v. intr._ to be aroused, wake up, II 77, VIII _a_ 318, _b_ 1,&c.; _trans._ to wake, II 73; #Awake#, _pp._ wakened, XV _g_ 14. [OE._ā-wæcnan_, str.; _ā-wacian_, wk.; both intr.] _See_ Forwake,Wackenet, Wake.

244.entry: #Awe#, _n._ fear; _for Crystys awe_, for fear of Christ, I 83. [ON._agi_.] _See_ Aȝleȝ.

245.entry: #Awede#, _v._ go mad, II 87; #Awedde#, _pp._ (gone) mad, II 400. [OE._ā-wēdan_.] _See_ Wode, _adj._

246.entry: #Aweyward#, _adv._ (turned) in the opposite direction, XIII _a_ 35. [OE._onweg_ + adv. _-ward_.]

248.entry: #Awenden#, _pa. t. pl._ thought, XV _g_ 17. [_a-_ + OE. _wēnan_.]_See_ Wene(n).

253.entry: #Axe(n)#, _v._ to ask, demand, inquire (of), VIII _a_ 291, XI _b_ 207,XII _a_ 145, &c.; #Acsede#, _pa. t._ III 4, 25, 31. [OE. _ā̆xian_.]_See_ Aske(n).

257.entry: #Bayarde#, _n._ bay horse (as typical horse name); _þat was bake for B._= coarse horse-bread, VIII _a_ 187. [OFr. _baiard_.] _See_ Bred.

260.entry: #Bailyues#, _n. pl._ bailiffs, managers of estates, XI _b_ 288. [OFr._baillif_.]

261.entry: #Baill#, _n._^1 wall (of the outer court in a feudal castle), XVI 195;

262.entry: #Bale#, prison, custody, XVI 161 (but this may belong to Bale, _q.v._).[OFr. _bail_.]

266.entry: #Bak#, #Bac# (II), #Backe#, _n._ back, II 344, VII 126, XVII 264, &c.;_bak and bone_, all over the body, XVII 407. [OE. _bæc_.]

270.entry: #Bale#; #Bayle#, #Bayll# (XVII); _n._ torment, misery, sorrow, IV _a_77, V 351, VI 13, XIV _a_ 28, XVI 275, XVII 26, 311, 552, &c.; at XVI161 'torment' is possible, but _see_ Bail, _n._^1 [OE. _balu_.]

271.entry: #Balȝ#, _adj._ rounded, or ? with level surface, V 104 (_cf._ SirGaw. 2032, and Prompt. Parv. _balwe_, planus).

272.entry: #Balkes#, _n. pl._ (unploughed) ridges in a field, VIII _a_ 101. [OE._balc(a)_.]

273.entry: #Ban#, _v._ to curse, XIV _b_ 94, XVII 94; #Banned# (_MS._) I 188, ?read Bende (_q.v._). [OE. _bannan_, proclaim; ON. _banna_, forbid,curse.]

279.entry: #Barbe#, _n._ cutting edge, V 242. [OFr. _barbe_, beard, barb (of arrow,spear, &c.).]

281.entry: #Bare#, #Bair# (X), _adj._ bare, naked, V 9, 188, VII 164, X 190, &c.;_on bonkes bare_, XIV _b_ 20; despoiled, XIV _a_ 20; bald (in style),VII 74; mere, V 284, X 113. [OE. _bær_.]

287.entry: #Barge#, _n._ a smaller sea-going ship belonging to a larger vessel, XIV_c_ 53, 65; ship, VII 90. [OFr. _barge_.]

298.entry: #Batail(e)#, #Bataill#, #Batayl#, #Batel(l)#, _n._ embattled host, XIV_b_ 52; battle, VII 56, 91, *XI _b_ 154, XIV _b_ 31, XVI 131, &c. [OFr._bataille_.]

299.entry: #Bataild#, _adj._ embattled, with battlements, II 360. [Modelled on OFr._bataillé_.]

303.entry: #Baundoun#, _n._ control; _in hire baundoun_, at her disposal, XV _c_ 8.[OFr. _bandun_.]

304.entry: #Be#, _conj._ by the time (that), X 157. Cf. _bi þat_. _See_ next.

305.entry: #Be#, #Beo# (XIV _c_ 44), _prep._ by (way of), IX 179, 192, 198;through, IX 112, 136, 137; (of _time_) by, at, in, VI 163, IX 204, 339,XII _a_ 117, 131, XV _i_ 15, 20; by (means of), through, III 22, VII 23,IX 67, 130, XII _a_ 23, _b_ 199, XVI 355, &c.; by (of _agent_), III 30,IX 112 (first), 298, 305, XII _b_ 217, &c.; by (in oaths, &c.), XII _b_45, 164. _Counted ... beo_, set value on, XIV _c_ 44; for idiomaticexpressions see the nouns. [OE. _be_.] _See_ Bi.

309.entry: #Bede#, _v._ to bid, offer, V 254, XIV _a_ 9; #Bede#, _pa. t. sg._ (bade),V 22; offered, 180, 284. [OE. _bēodan_, early confused with_biddan_.] _See_ Bidde, Forbede.

311.entry: #Bedd(e)#, #Bede# (IV), _n._ bed, II 93, 242, XII _a_ 99, &c.; _dat.sg._ in _to bedde_, to bed, VIII _a_ 93, XII _b_ 105; _þe bede ofblysse_, ? the joyful bridal bed (of Christ and the soul), IV _a_ 11.[OE. _bedd_.] _See_ Abedde.

314.entry: #Bedele#, _n._ herald, one who delivers the message of an authority, XI_b_ 48. [OE. _bydel_; OFr. _bedel_.]

318.entry: #Befalle#, _v._ to happen, chance, IX 129, &c.; to befall, XVII 514;_pa. t. sg._ Befell(e), VII 67, 155; #Bevil#, #Bifel#, it chanced, II57, III 41; #Befalle(n)#, _pp._ II 21, IX 194. [OE. _be-fallan_.] _See_Falle(n).

321.entry: #Begyn(ne)#, #Bigin(ne)#, #Bygyn(ne)#, &c., _v._ to begin, act, do, comeabout, I 69, IV _b_ 57, VI 187, VIII _a_ 160, XIV _b_ 25, _c_ 83, XVI268, 280, XVII 267, &c.; _begyn of_, b. with, XVII 253; #Be-#, #Bi-#,

322.entry: #Bygan#, _pa. t. sg._ began, I 154, &c.; did, XV _a_ 7; came to pass, II598; made (it) in the beginning, XVII 29; #Bygan#, _pa. t. pl._ I 72;

324.entry: #Bygynnyng(e)#, _n._ IV _b_ 58, IX 334, XIII _b_ 9. [OE. _beginnan_;_begouth_ is due to confusion of _gan_ with _can_ (_couþe_); _See_ Gan;Can, _auxil._]

329.entry: #Beȝonde#, #Beȝounde# (I), #Biȝonde# (V), _prep._ across,beyond, I 252, V 132, IX 8, 76, 135, &c.; _see_ See. [As prec.]

331.entry: #Behalue#, _n._ behalf; _on Goddes b._, in God's name, I 78. [Originally_be_ prep. and _halfe_ dat. sg.; _cf._ Half.]

344.entry: #Beleue#, #Bileue#, _v._ to believe, I 89, VIII _a_ 82, IX 120, XV _g_9. [OE. _ge-lēfan_, (late) _be-lēfan_.] _See_ Leue, _v._^3;Ylefde.

345.entry: #Belyue#, _adv._ quickly, at once, straightway, VII 161, XVI 211;

346.entry: #Belife#, XVII 192; #Bilyue#, V 3; #Blyue#, IX 18; #Bliue#, in _alsobliue_, II 142, _als bliue_, II 531, 584, as quickly as possible,immediately. [OE. _*be līfe_.]

348.entry: #Ben#, _v._ to be, II 207, VIII _a_ 96, &c.; #Be(e)#, I 4, XVI 7, &c.;

349.entry: #Buen#, XV _c_ 18; _future, 2 sg._ #Best#, II 173; _3 sg._ #Bees#, IV_a_ 35, XVII 373, #Betȝ#, VI 251; _pl._ #Be#, V 43, XVI 331; _pres.pl._ #Be(n)#, are, II 3, 4, 12, &c.; #Beo#, XIV _c_ 5; #Beoþ#, XIV _c_103; #Beth#, #Beþ#, II 59, 110, 273, 582, VIII _a_ 199, XV _f_ 5; #Buþ#,XIII _a_ 1, 6, 10, 13, &c.; #Be(e)#, #Beo#, _pres. subj._, II 165, 433,XIV _c_ 98, _d_ 3, &c.; #Ben#, XI _b_ 73, 218, &c.; #Be(o)#, _imper. 2sg._ XV _g_ 10, _f_ 7, &c.; _3 sg._ IV _a_ 55; _pl._ VIII _a_ 118, XIV_d_ 11 (first); #Be#, _pp._ I 195, VIII _b_ 74, XI _a_ 44, XII _a_ 20,XVII 192, &c.; #Ben#, II 103, V 196, &c.; #Bene#, V 275, XVI 40; #Beyn#,XVII 445, 532; #Ybe#, XIII _a_ 16; #Beyng#, _pres. p._ in _in hytselfbeyng_, inherent, VI 86. _Ben_ (_drepit_, &c.), have been (smitten,&c.), VII 9, 11; _be(e) war_, _see_ War(e); _lete ben_, &c., cease from,II 114, XVI 234. [OE. _bēon_.] _See_ Ar(e), Es, Was, &c.

350.entry: #Bend#, _v._ X 90, 98, XVII 253; #Bende#, _pa. t._ XII _a_ 58, *I 188(MS. banned); #Bende#, _pp._ V 47, 156; #Bendit#, X 80. The divergentsenses are all derived from the original one of stringing, bending, abow: ? to bind, *I 188 (note); to set ready for discharging, X 80, 90,98; to make curve, bend, V 156, XII _a_ 58, XVII 253; ? to make bow,bring low, beat down, in _hatȝ ... on bent much baret bende_, ? hasupon the field overcome much strife (many opponents), V 47. [OE._bendan_.]

352.entry: #Bene#, _n._ bean, VIII _a_ 175, 188, 209, 278, 288, 298, IX 54; assomething of no value (cf. _pees_), XIV _c_ 43. [OE. _bēan_.]

353.entry: #Benedicite# (L. _imper. pl._) bless (me, us); as exclamation ofamazement, XVII 163.

354.entry: #Benethe(n)#, #Beneyth# (XVII), _adv._ underneath, IX 56, XVII 137; inthe lower part, IX 247. [OE. _beneoþan_.]

356.entry: #Bent#, _n._ grass-slope, field, V 165; esp. in the allit. tag _onbent_, on the field (of battle), or (as variant of _vpon grounde_, &c.)on earth, V 47, 80, VII 91; _on þis bent_, here, V 270. [Perhaps aspecial use of _bent_, bent-grass, OE. _beonet_.]

359.entry: #Ber(e)#, _v._ to bear, carry, wear, lift, take; to hold, possess, keep;to give birth to, produce; V 83, VIII _a_ 136, IX 69, 109, XII _a_ 197,XIII _a_ 51, XVII 318, &c.; _2 sg. subj._ VI 106; #Berth#, _3 sg. pres.ind._ XII _a_ 81; #Bar(e)#, _pa. t. sg._ I 146, VIII _a_ 93, XIV _c_ 23,59, XV _i_ 3; #Ber#, V 193, VI 66; #Baren#, _pl._ IX 148; #Bere#, II307; #Bore#, _pp._ I 85, II 210; #Born(e)#, II 41, V 252, 326, XIV _b_12, &c.; #Ybore#, II 546; #Yborn#, II 174. _Bar þe flour_, _see_ Flour;_b. þe felaȝschip_, keep thee company, V 83; _the depnes ... webere_, the depth (of water) we draw, XVII 434, 460; _born open_, laidopen, V 2 (cf. OE. _beran ūp_). [OE. _beran_.] _See_ Forbere.

362.entry: #Bere-bag#, _n._ bag-carrier, a contemptuous nickname for Scots, XIV _a_20 (note). [Stem of Bere _v._ + ON. _baggi_.] _See_ Bagge.

375.entry: #Best(e)#, _adj. superl._ best, IV _a_ 84, VIII _a_ 197, IX 42, &c.; as_sb._, best (food), VIII _a_ 295; _do þi (doþ ȝour) best_, _see_ Don;_wyth þe beste_, among the best (people), with the saints, IV _a_ 4;_adv._ best, most readily, most, VIII _a_ 81, 107, XVII 472, &c.; _þebest_, VIII _a_ 22. [OE. _betst_.]

377.entry: #Best(e)#, _n._ animal, creature, II 214, 280, VIII _a_ 134, IX 88, XII_a_ 78, &c.; #Beest#, XVII 3, 135, &c. [OFr. _beste_.]

379.entry: #Bet#, _adv. compar._; _predic._ in _he was þe bet_, he was better offon that account, VIII _b_ 100. [OE. _bet_.] _See_ Best(e), Betre.

380.entry: #Bete#, _v._^1 to beat, I 6, VIII _a_ 73, XVII 407; _betes the stretes_,frequents the streets, XIV _a_ 25; #Bette#, _pa. t. sg._ VIII _a_ 171;

381.entry: #Byete#, _pa. t. subj. sg._ III 40 (OE. _bēote_); #Bet#, _pp._ XVII413; #Betin#, #Betyn#, XIV _a_ 8, XVII 381. [OE. _bēatan_.] _See_Forbette.

382.entry: #Bete#, _v._^2 to assuage, remedy, IV _a_ 77, VIII _a_ 233, XIV _a_ 28,29. [OE. _bētan_.] _See_ Beytter.

385.entry: #Bet(e)re#, #Better(e)#, #Bettre#, _adj. compar._ better, II 40, XI _b_37, XIII _a_ 60, XV _c_ 33, &c.; _him were betre_, it would be b. forhim, XII _b_ 101; _þat war better_, for whom it would be b., XIV _a_ 32;_adv._ better, XI _b_ 275, XIV _d_ 14, &c.; rather, XI _b_ 288; _þebetter_, all the better (for it), V 28, XVII 353; as _conj._, so that... (the) better, VIII _a_ 46, XVII 175. [OE. _betera_, _bet(t)ra_,adj.]

387.entry: #Betweche#, _v._ ? to commit (to protection of God), XV _i_ 18. Only inthis passage; perhaps an error for _becwethe_ (bequeath, commit), or_beteche_ (_see_ Bitaiste).

388.entry: #Betwen(e)#, #Bytuene# (XV), #Bytwene# _prep._ between, among, IX 162,166, XII _a_ 68, _b_ 89, XV _c_ 1, &c.; (follows case), V 174, VII 91.[OE. _betwēon(an)_.]

393.entry: #Beweile#, _v. refl._ to lament, XII _a_ 32. [_be-_ + ON. _*veila_; cf._veilan_, lamentation.]

395.entry: #Bewounde#, _pp._; _it hath b._, wound (itself) about it, XII _b_ 72.[OE. _be-wíndan_.]

397.entry: #By#, _adv._ at the side, by; alongside (without coming on board), XVII373; _þat ... by_, by which, IX 300. [OE. _bī_.] _See_ Þer(e).

398.entry: #Bi#, #By#, _prep._ (i) On, at, by, II 156, 470, VIII _a_ 167, XV _g_16, XVII 75, &c.; _bi ... side_, beside, II 66, V 76; by (way of), over,through, I 62, V 10, 16, 52, 93, X 11, XVII 477; along (with), beside,II 280, 308, V 9, VIII _a_ 4, &c.; (following its case) II 301, V 21,XVII 18; against, touching, V 242; past, II 252, 290, V 36, 39. (ii) In,on, for (of _time_), II 8, 15, VIII _a_ 95, 274, XV _a_ 24, &c.; _see_Dai, While. (iii) Measured by, compared with, according to, &c., V 28,158, 296, 297, VIII _a_ 35, 58, 159, 248, _b_ 57, XI _b_ 5, &c. (iv) By(means of), through, &c., II 408, VII 6, &c.; by virtue of, XI _b_ 20;_lyue by_, &c., live on, II 257, VIII _a_ 284, _b_ 26; by (of _agent_),XI _a_ 59, &c. (v) By (in oaths, &c.), II 316, V 54, &c. _Bi al þing_,by every token, II 321, 375; _by so_, provided that, VIII _b_ 40; _biþan_, thereby, _or_ thereupon (cf. _after þan_), II 553; _bi þat_,thereupon, V 84; by that time, VIII _a_ 285; as _conj._, by the timethat, VIII _a_ 294. [OE. _bī̆_.] _See_ Be.

402.entry: #Bycause# (_of_), _prep._ because (of), XIII _b_ 16; _bycause_, _becauseþat_, (conj.) because, XIII _b_ 61, 62, IX 114, 226. [Be, Bi + Cause,_q.v._]

405.entry: #Bicome#, #Become#, _v._ to arrive; become; befit; _hyt bycomeþ for_, itbefits, VIII _b_ 65; #Becam#, _pa. t. sg._ XII _b_ 13; #Becomen#, _pl._IX 148; #Bicome#, II 288; #Bicome#, _pp._ II 194; _wher sche wasbicome_, _whider þai bicome_, _wher he becam_, what had become (became)of her (them, him), II 194, 288, XII _b_ 13. [OE. _be-cuman_.]

406.entry: #Bidde#, #Bydde#, #Bid#, _v._ to pray, beg, VIII _a_ 233; to bid, I 265,VI 160, VIII _a_ 210, XI _b_ 79, XII _a_ 48, XIV _d_ 3, XVI 118, XVII418, &c.; #Bad(de)#, _pa. t. sg._ bade, XII _a_ 46, XV _i_ 16, XVI 201,XVII 309, &c.; _bad to_, bade, XII _b_ 87; #Bed#, prayed to, III 46(OKt. _bed_); #Bad#, _pl._ II 88, 137; #Bede#, _pp._ XII _a_ 42(prayed), 101 (commanded). [OE. _biddan_; the confusion with _bēodan_began in OE.] _See_ Bede.

408.entry: #Byd(d)yng#, #Bidding#, _n._ bidding, commands, I 86, XVI 257, XVII 76,121, 375. [From Bidde.]

409.entry: #Bide#, #Byde#, _v._ to abide (_intr._ remain, _trans._ await, face,endure), V 224, VI 39, XIV _c_ 21, 47, XVI 23, 207, &c. [OE._bīdan_.] _See_ Abide.

410.entry: #Bidene#, #Bydene#, #Bedeyn# (XVII), _adv._ forthwith, withal (oftenmeaningless), VII 79, 127, XIV _b_ 74, XVII 442; _al bidene_, XIV _b_11. [See _N.E.D._]

413.entry: #Bifor(e)#, #Byforn#, #Befor(e)#, #Beuore#, &c., _adv._ before (hand),II 147, VII 121, &c.; _eir befor_, X 140; as _sb._, XVII 331; _prep._before, in presence of, &c., II 42, III 58, V 4, IX 126, &c.; (of_time_) VI 238, XI _b_ 48, &c.; _bifore þat_, before (_conj._), XI _b_195; #Byfore#, _conj._ (with _subj._), before, VI 170. [OE. _be-foran_.]

414.entry: #Big#, #Bigge#, _v._ to take up one's abode; _to big his boure_, toestablish his dwelling, XIV _b_ 26; _bigges him_, settles himself, XIV_b_ 24. [ON. _byggja_.] _See_ Biging.

416.entry: #Bigge#, #Bygge#, _adj._ strong, lusty, big, IV _a_ 51, V 33, VI 14, VII139, VIII _a_ 207. [See _N.E.D._]

417.entry: #Bigge#, _v._ to buy, purchase, pay for, redeem, VIII _a_ 275; #Beie#,XII _b_ 24; #By(e)#, IV _a_ 65, IX 113; #Byye#, VI 118; #Bugge#, XV _g_3; _pa. t._ #Boght#, IV _a_ 38; #Bouȝte#, VIII _a_ 201; #Bouhte#,VIII _b_ 100; #Boght#, _pp._ IV _a_ 80, XII _b_ 153, XVII 373;

418.partOfSpeech: , you will pay for it dearly, XVII 373. [OE.
418.entry: #Bought(e)#, XVI 8, 275; #Iboust#, XV _g_ 26 (_see_ App. p. 278); _itbees boght full dere_, you will pay for it dearly, XVII 373. [OE._bycgan_, (Kt.) _becgan_.] _See_ Abugge.

420.entry: #Bigile#, #Bygyle#, _v._ to deceive, V 345, 348, 359, XIV _b_ 44. [OE._be-_ + OFr. _guiler_.] _See_ Gile.

423.entry: #Bigruccheth#, _3 sg. pres._ grumbles at, VIII _a_ 69. [OE. _be-_ + OFr._groucher_.] _See_ Grucche.

425.entry: #Bihold#, #Behald(e)#, _v._ to behold, look, II 387, 502, IV _a_ 81,XVII 509, 534, &c.; _bihold on_, _behold to_, look at, II 367, XVII 343;

429.entry: #Bihote#, #Byhote#, _v._ to promise, vow, VIII _a_ 227; _byhote God_, Ivow to God, VIII _a_ 273; #Behihtest#, _2 sg. pa. t._ XII _b_ 43;

431.entry: #Bihoue#, _v._ to need; _impers._ in _me bihoues_, I must, it is timefor me to, V 228; _pers._ in #Bus#, _2 sg. pres._; _þou bus be_, youought to be, XVI 338; #Behufit#, _pa. t._ had need (to), X 156. [OE._be-hōfian_; with the reduced form _bus_ cf. _has_, _hast_, &c.]

433.entry: #Bying#, _n._ redemption, XVI 12. [From By, to buy. _See_ Bigge, _v._;Byggynge.]

435.entry: #Biknowe#, #Byknowe#, _v._ to confess, V 317 (_I b. yow_, I confess toyou), VIII _b_ 96; #Beknowen#, _pp._ in _þou art b. of_, you haveconfessed, V 323. [OE. _be-cnāwan_, only recorded in sense 'know'.]

437.entry: #Byled#, _pa. t._ boiled, bubbled, V 14; #Boyled#, _pp._ V 106. [OFr._boillir_; for similar development of vowel in V, _see_ Nye,Disstryeȝ.]

439.entry: #Bylongeth#, _v. impers._ it belongs to, befits, VIII _b_ 70. [Be- +Longe, _v._^2]

441.entry: #Bilt#, _n._ dwelling, *II 483 (MS. ybilt, but required sense 'lodged'is unexampled). [Obscurely rel. to ME. _bilden_, build; see _N.E.D._]

442.entry: #Binam#, _pa. t. sg._ in _b. [hym] his mnam_, deprived him of histalent, VIII _a_ 237; #Benome#, _pp._ in _b. þe poure ane peny_,deprived the poor of a penny, III 13. [OE. _be-niman_.] _See_ Nyme.

443.entry: #Bynde#, _v._ to bind, unite, IV _a_ 54, XVI 97; #Bond#, _pa. t. sg._XII _b_ 120 (but _sb._ = _trosse_ is possible; _see_ Bonde, _n._);

446.entry: #Bir#, #Byr#, #Bur# (V), _n._ a following wind, VII 126; speed (in _witha byr_, speedily) XVII 371; violence, V 254; strength, V 193. [ON._byr-r_.]

448.entry: #Bireue#, _v._ to deprive; _I wil it hym b._, I will deprive him of it,VIII _a_ 242. [OE. _be-rēafian_, _be-rēfan_.]

450.entry: #Byrne#, #Burne#, _v. trans._ and _intr._ to burn, X 21 (rime with _in_requires Bryn, _q.v._), X 181, &c.; #Byrnand#, _pres. p._ IV _a_ 26, X27, 30. [OE. _birnan_, _byrnan_, &c., intr.] _See_ Bren, Brin.

452.entry: #Biseche#, #Bysech#, #Beseche#, _v._ to implore, II 113, 453, VI 30, IX269, 328, XII _a_ 38; #Besoghte#, _pa. t._ XII _a_ 26; #Besoughte#, IX294. [OE. _be_ + _sēcan_.] _See_ Seche.

454.entry: #Bisyde#, #Besyde#, _adv._ at the side, at one's side, hard by, I 209, V20, 162, XII _b_ 125. [OE. _be sīdan_, at the side.]

455.entry: #Biside(n)#, #Be-#, #Bysyde#, _prep._ beside, XI _b_ 57; (following itscase) I 243, II 303, V 197, XIV _b_ 28, &c. _See_ prec.

456.entry: #Bisides#, #Bisydeȝ#, _adv._ at the side(s), round about, II 401, V96. [Prec. + adv. _-es_.]

459.entry: #Bysynes(se)#, #Besynes# (IV), _n._ restlessness, IV _b_ 28; industry,XIII _b_ 24; _worldly b._ attention to worldly affairs, XI _b_ 2, 309;_b. of worldly occupacion_, preoccupation with w. affairs, XI _b_ 251.[OE. _bisig_ + _-nes_.]

460.entry: #Bis(s)chop#, #Bysshop(p)e#, #Bissoppe#, _n._ bishop, I 246, III 58(_dat. sg._), VIII _a_ 143, _b_ 74, XI _a_ 66, &c. [OE. _biscop_.]

463.entry: #Bitaiste# (= bitaihte), _pa. t._ entrusted, XV _g_ 21. [OE._betǣcan_, pa. t. _betǣ̆hte_; on spelling _see_ App. p. 278.]

464.entry: #Byte#, _v._ to bite, XVII 229; _apon the bone shal it byte_, it shallcut to the bone, XVII 220. [OE. _bītan_.]

465.entry: #Bitide#, #Bytyde#, &c., _v._ to happen; to happen to, befall, VI 37;_pres. subj._ V 127, 315, 341, XIV _a_ 12; #Betidde#, _pp._ XVI 100;_tide wat bitide_, come what may, II 339. [OE. _be_ + _tīdan_.] _See_Tide.

466.entry: #Bityme#, _adv._ in _all bityme_, in good time, XIV _b_ 27. [From _bityme_, in time; cf. OE. _tō tīman_.] _See_ Tyme.

467.entry: #Bitte#, #Bytte#, _n._ cutting edge, V 242; blade, V 156. [ON. _bit_,cutting edge; OE. _bite_, a cut.]

468.entry: #Bittir#, #Bytter#, _adj._ bitter, IV _b_ 27; salt (of water), IX 244;grievous, XIV _c_ 68, XVI 207, &c. [OE. _bitter_.]

470.entry: #Bytwyste#, _prep._ between (following its noun), VI 104. [A form of ME._be-twixt(e)_, extended from Betwix, _q.v._]

471.entry: #Biwyled#, _pp._ deluded, V 357. [? OE. _be_ + _wiglian_; cf._biwiȝelien_, Layamon 969.] _See_ Wiles.

473.entry: #Blac#, #Blak#, _adj._ black, II 265, IX 23, XII _a_ 99; _rowe andblac_, with shaggy black hair, II 459; #Blake#, _oblique_ and _pl._ IX4, XII _a_ 137, XV _c_ 14. [OE. _blæc_.]

474.entry: #Blame#, _n._ blame; scolding, XVII 299; _v._ to blame, V 300, IX 274(mistranslation; _see_ note), &c.; _to blame_, in the wrong, XIV _b_ 85.[OFr. _bla(s)me_; _bla(s)mer_.]

478.entry: #Ble#, #Bleo# (XV), _n._ hue, complexion, in _briȝt on ble_, fair offace, II 455; radiance, XV _b_ 16. [OE. _blēo_.]

479.entry: #Blede#, _v._ to bleed, XIV _c_ 13; #Bled(de)#, _pa. t._ I 119, II 80.[OE. _blēdan_.]

481.entry: #Blende#, _pa. t._ mingled, in _blende in his face_, rose to his cheeks,V 303; #Blent#, _pp._ in _blent ... in blysse_, set amidst joy, VI 25.[ME. _blenden_ obscurely related to OE. _blándan_, or ON. _blanda_.]_See_ Vnblendyde.

483.entry: #Blenk#, _v._ to gleam, V 247. [OE. _*blencan_, possibly identical withrecorded _blencan_, to cheat; for ME. _blenchen_, _blenken_, &c. = togleam, look at, glance aside, blench, cheat. Compare Glent, Glyfte.]

485.entry: #Bleþeliche#, _adv._ gladly, III 53. [? Obscure alteration of OE._blīþelīce_.]

486.entry: #Bleue#, _v._ to remain; _pres. subj._ III _introd._; #Blefte#, _pa. t._III 18. [OE. _belǣfan_.] _See_ Leue, _v._^1

488.entry: #Blew#, _n._ blue (stuff), XVII 200 (note); _cled in Stafford blew_,beaten black and blue; cf. _clothe here well yn Stafford blewe_, Rel.Ant., I, p. 29. [OFr. _bleu_.] _See_ Blwe.

489.entry: #Blynde#, _adj. pl._ blind, deluded, XI _b_ 79; as _sb._, the blind,VIII _a_ 115, 185. [OE. _blínd_.]

490.entry: #Blyndiþ#, _3 sg. pres._ (blinds), deludes, XI _b_ 7, 107. [OE._bléndan_ infl. by _blínd_, adj.] _See_ Blended.

492.entry: #Blyn(ne)# (_of_), _v._ to cease (from), IV _a_ 39, V 254, XVI 16, 236,XVII 110 (_or I blyn_ = without stopping); #Blan#, _pa. t. pl._ I 73.[OE. _blinnan_.]

493.entry: #Blis(se)#, #Blys(se)#, _n._ happiness, joy, IV _a_ 11, 40, VI 12, XIV_b_ 19, XV _b_ 3, &c.; _as haue I blys_, so may I have (eternal) joy,XVII 402. [OE. _bliss_.]

494.entry: #Bliss(e)#, #Blesse#, _v._ to bless, I _introd._, VI 76, XVI 400, 404,XVII 174, 256, 300, 467; bless with sign of the cross, V 3, XII _b_ 86;

495.entry: #Blist#, _pp._ XVII 514. [OE. _blē̆tsian_, already infl. by_blī̆tsian_, _blissian_, to gladden.]

496.entry: #Blisseful#, #Blysful#, _adj._ joyous, II 412, 438, VI 49; as _sb._,blissful one, VI 61; #*Blissefulest# (MS. blifulest), _superl._ II 527.[OE. _bliss_ + _ful_.]

498.entry: #Bliþe#, #Blyþe#, #Blith# (XIV _b_), _adj._ happy, glad, V 253, XIV _b_49; _bliþe of_, glad at, II 573; _þatow be bliþe of hir_, that you mayhave joy of her, II 471. [OE. _blīþe_.]

502.entry: #Blod(e)#, #Bloode#, _n._ blood, I 119, V 246, IX 141, XV _g_ 16, XVI12, &c.; creature, XII _b_ 220; _byndes blode and bane_, keeps the bodytogether, IV _a_ 54. [OE. _blōd_.]

503.entry: #Blodi#, #Blody#, _adj._ bloody, II 110, IV _a_ 80, 86, &c.; _blodybretheren_, brothers in blood, fellow men, VIII _a_ 201. [OE._blōdig_.]

506.entry: #Blowe(n)#, _v._ to blow, VII 106, XIII _a_ 7, XV _h_ 6, &c.; to brag,XIV _c_ 101; #Bleuȝ#, _pa. t. sg._ XIV _c_ 77; #Blew#, VII 130,(sounded the trumpet) X 43; #Blawene#, _pp._ IV _b_ 13. [OE._blāwan_.]

511.entry: #Bo#, _adv._ as well, too, II 27. [OE. _bā_, adj. neut.] _See_ Boþe.

514.entry: #Bodi(e)#, #Body#, _n._ body, I 113, II 105, XVI 23, &c.; _gon on bodiand bones_, be in the flesh, live, II 54. [OE. _bodig_.]

515.entry: #Bodyly#, #Bodely#, _adj._ of (the) body, bodily (opposed to'spiritual'), VI 118, XI _b_ 147, 158, &c.; _bodely almes_, (giving of)charitable gifts for the needs of the body, XI _b_ 2, 270, 301, 303.[From prec.]

517.entry: #Bogh#, #Boȝeȝ# (_pl._ V), #Bouȝ# (II), _n._ bough, branch, II61, V 9, XV _a_ 14, XVII 535. [OE. _bōg_.]

519.entry: #Boȝe#, _v._ to bend, bow; turn, go, V 110; #Boȝen#, _pa. t. pl._turned, went their way, V 9; #Bowand#, _pres. p._ (bowing), obedient,XVII 76 (_cf._ Buxome, and Lowte). [OE. _būgan_.]

522.entry: #Bok(e)#, #Boc#, _n._ book, III _introd._, VII 14, 65, IX 294, XI _b_229, &c.; Bible, VIII _a_ 248, _b_ 39; Bible, or other book (as a bookof the Gospels, a psalter, &c.) on which an oath could be taken, XII _b_165. [OE. _bōc_.]

523.entry: #Bold(e)#, #Balde#, _adj._ bold, II 139, IV _a_ 51, 83, &c.; _and thatbe ye bold_, and be sure of that, XVII 524; #Boldely#, _adv._ XVI 178.[OE. _báld_.]

526.entry: #Bollyng#, _n._ swelling; _for b. of her wombe_, to prevent the swellingof their bellies, VIII _a_ 209. [ME. _bolle-n_, _bolne-n_, ON._bolgna_.]

528.entry: #Bon(e)#, #Bane#, _n._ bone, II 54, IV _a_ 54, VIII _a_ 85, IX 141, XVII220, 253, &c.; _see_ Bak, Blod(e), Bodi, Flesch. [OE. _bān_.]

530.entry: #Bond(e)#, _n._ bond; _bond to sheues_, the straw binding for sheaves,VIII _b_ 14; _her bonde_, the bondage they imposed, XIV _c_ 47;

531.entry: #Bandis#, _pl._ bonds, XVI 190, 196; Our Lady's bonds, pregnancy, XVII209 (see _N.E.D._, s.v. _Band_, _Bond_). [ON. _band_.]

533.entry: #Bondemenne#, _gen. pl._ VIII _b_ 74. [OE. _bōnda_ (from ON. _bóndi_)+ _mann_, influenced in sense by prec. (etymol. unconnected).]

535.entry: #Bonk(e)#, #Bonkke#, #Bank(k)e#, _n._ bank, XIII _a_ 40; shore, VII 126;hill-side, V 9, 14, 94, 97, 104, 132, 149, XIV _b_ 20. [ON. _bakki_,older _*banke_.]

536.entry: #Bood-worde#, _n._ tidings, XVI 366. [Stem of OE. _bodian_ + _wórd_; cf.ON. _boð-orð_, command.]

538.entry: #Bord(e)#, _n._ board, XII _a_ 92, XVII 119, 279; table, II 578, VIII_a_ 262. [OE. _bórd_.]

543.entry: #Borne#, #Burn#, _n._ stream, V 106, XIV _a_ 2; #Buerne#, flood, sea (anallit. use), VII 159. [OE. _búrne_.]

544.entry: #Borow#, _n._ surety; _I dar be thi b._, I'll go bail (for you), XVII204. [OE. _borg_.]

546.entry: #Boste#, #Booste# (XVI), _n._ boasting, XIV _a_ 20; pride, XIV _a_ 8;arrogance, XIV _b_ 85, XVI 214. [Obscure.]

548.entry: #Bot(e)#, #But#, _adv._ only, but, II 228, IV _a_ 32, V 97, VI 22, VIII_a_ 276, IX 17, X 159, XIII _a_ 38, &c. [OE. _būtan_.] _See_ next,and Boute.

549.entry: #Bot(e)#, #But#, _conj._ (i) Except, but, VI 136, VIII _b_ 9, IX 198,&c.; _ne ... bote_, only, III 6, 22, &c. (_cf._ Bote, _adv._); _noȝtdeop bote to þe kneo_, only knee deep, XIII _a_ 39; _bote ȝef_,except that, XIII _b_ 5. (ii) Unless (with _subj._), VI 68, VIII _a_ 1,39, 112, 143, _b_ 95, X 73, XV _c_ 17, _g_ 21, XVII 44, 386, 550;_bot(e) if_, &c., unless, VIII _a_ 17, 53, X 78, XVII 247, &c.; _botþat_, unless, II 428. (iii) But, however, yet, I 21, II 74, IV _a_ 57, V61, VI 14, &c.; (misplaced) XII _a_ 79 (note), 105; _bot yit_(_ȝeit_), and yet, X 95, XVII 35, 64, 213. [OE. _būtan_,_būte_.]

550.entry: #Bot(e)#, _n._ cure, redress, salvation, IV _a_ 7, VIII _a_ 187, XIV _c_84; #bote of#, cure for, II 552. [OE. _bōt_.]

553.entry: #Boþ(e)#, #Both#, #Bath# (IV, X), _adj._ and _pron._ both, IV _a_ 56, V315, VI 13; _in hem boþe_ (after negative), in either of them, XI _b_27; _vs both_, us two, XVII 185; _on bath halfis_, on both sides, X 198;_vpon boþe halue_, on either side, V 2, 97; as _adv._ (originally_pron._ in apposition), as well, too, V 306, VIII _a_ 119, 162, 252,274, _b_ 46; _boþ(e) ... and_, _bath ... and_, both ... and, I 52, II86, IV _a_ 66, &c. [ON. _báði-r_.] _See_ Bo.

557.entry: #Boun(e)#, #Bowne#, _adj._ ready, IV _a_ 81, XIV _a_ 9, XVI 201; prompt,XVI 257; _make youe b._, prepare yourselves, arm, XVI 178; _make þe b._,hasten, XVI 339; _watȝ nawhere b._, was not to be found anywhere, VI174. [ON. _búin-n_, _bún-_.] _See_ Busk.

567.entry: #Braide#, #Brayd#, #Brade#, _n._ a sudden movement; _in a brade_, in atrice, XVII 21; _bittir braide_, grievous onslaught, XIV _c_ 68, XVI207. [OE. _brægd_.]

568.entry: #Brayde#, _v._ to move quickly; draw, V 251; #Brayde#, _pa. t._ threw, V309; #Brayde#, _pp._ in _brayde down_, lowered, V 1. [OE. _bregdan_.]

571.entry: #Brandis#, _n. pl._ pieces of burnt wood, X 113. [OE. _bránd_.]

575.entry: #Bre#, _n._ foaming sea, VII 152. [App. a curious allit. use of OE._brīw_, _*brēo_, broth.]

576.entry: #Bred(e)#, _n._ bread, VIII _a_ 18, 129, 131, 207, 298; _as euer ete Ibrede_ = so may I live, on my life, XVII 395; _hors bred_, _houndesbred_, bread of beans, bran, &c., for the food of horses and dogs, VIII_a_ 208. [OE. _brēad_.]

578.entry: #Brede#, #Breed#, _n._ breadth, XVII 126; of breed, in breadth, XVII259. [OE. _brǣdu_.]

582.entry: #Breke(n)#, _v._ to break, violate, VIII _a_ 31, IX 46, XI _b_ 187, XVI257, XVII 387, &c.; _intr._ II 338, IX 118; #Brak#, _pa. t. sg._ X 106;

583.entry: #Breke#, _pa. t. pl._ V 14; #Broke#, _pp._ injured, VIII _b_ 34 (_see_Broke-legged, VIII _a_ 130); #Brokynne#, broken, XVI 195. [OE._brecan_.]

584.entry: #Brekynge#, _n._ breaking; _smale b._, breaking a long note into anumber of short ones, fine trilling, XI _b_ 138. [OE. _brecung_.]

585.entry: #Brem(e)#, _adj._ fierce, violent, V 132, VII 139, 152, &c.;threatening, wild, V 77; passionate, VII 104; glorious, II 61; _adv._gloriously, XV _b_ 27. [OE. _brēme_, adj. and adv.]

586.entry: #Brem(e)ly#, _adv._ fiercely, violently, V 251, VII 106; exceedingly, V165. [From prec.]

588.entry: #Bren#, _v._ to burn; #Brent#, _pp._ VII 152, 159; #Brennynge#, _pres.p._ fervent, XI _b_ 67; #Brennynge#, _n._ burning, IX 10. [ON._brenna_.] _See_ Byrne, Brin.

590.entry: #Bren-waterys#, _n. pl._ XV _h_ 22, 'water-burners', _i.e._ blacksmiths(from the hiss of the hot iron when plunged in water). Compare_burn-the-wind_, a nickname for blacksmiths. [Bren, _v._ + Watter.]

593.entry: #Brest(e)#, #Brast# (XVII), _v. trans._ and _intr._ to burst, IV _a_ 81,XV _h_ 6, XVII 264; #Barste#, _pa. t. sg._ VIII _a_ 171; #Brosten#,_pp._ XVI 196. [OE. _berstan_; ON. _bresta_.]

594.entry: #Bretfull#, _adj._ full to the brim, VII 164. [OE., ME. _brerdfull_,prob. with substitution of ON. cognate form _*bredd-_; cf. Swed._bräddfull_.]

596.entry: #Breue#, _v._ to set down in writing; #Breuyt#, _pa. t. sg._ VII 65;_pp._ VII 14. [Med.L. _breviāre_, OE. _brēfan_.]

597.entry: #Brid(d)#, #Byrd# (XVII), _n._ young bird, XII _a_ 196; (small) bird, II305, VII 104, XII _a_ 169, 172, XVII 514, &c. [OE. _bridd_, young bird(late Nth. pl. _birdas_).]

600.entry: #Bryght(e)#, #Briȝt#, #Bryȝt#, #Briht# (XII), #Bryht# (XV), &c.,_adj._ and _adv._ bright, II 152, 269, 455, IV _a_ 72, _b_ 6, V 158, XII_b_ 130, XV _b_ 26, XVII 9, &c. [OE. _berht_, _byrht_.]

603.entry: #Brin#, #Bryn#, _v. trans._ to burn, X 21 (implied by rime); #Brynt#,

605.entry: #Bring(e)#, #Bryng(e)#, _v._ to bring, take, escort; cause to be; IV _a_7, _b_ 46, VIII _a_ 64, IX 60, X 17, XI _a_ 3 (adduce), XII _a_ 193, XIV_b_ 68, &c.; #Broght(e)#, #Broȝt(e)#, #Brought#, #Brouȝt(e)#, _pa.t._ I 123, II 93, III 11, VIII _a_ 288, XII _a_ 25, _b_ 47 (_subj._),XVI 161, &c.; _pp._ V 77, VII 90, XIV _b_ 72, &c.; #Ybrouȝt#, II 389,563; _bryng it to an ende_, accomplish it, IX 169; _bringen forth_,bring forth, produce, IX 60, XII _a_ 193; _to thay bryng_, until theybring (something), XVII 499; _broughte oute of_, rescued from, XVI 161;_brought it so breff_, made it so meagre, VII 74; _broght dede_, broughtto death, I 213. [OE. _bringan_.]

607.entry: #Brytouns#, _n. pl._ men of Brittany, II 16. [OFr. _Breton_; L._Brit(t)ōnem_, Briton.]

608.entry: #Britoner#, #Brytonere#, _n._ a man of Brittany, VIII _a_ 148, 169.[From prec.]

610.entry: #Brode#, _adj._ broad, V 1, 165, VII 106, XV _g_ 5; #Brood#, XIII _a_39; #Braid#, X 24. [OE. _brād_.]

619.entry: #Broþer#, _n._ brother, I 210, XII _a_ 6; #Brother#, _gen. sg._ XII _a_18; #Brether#, _pl._ XVII 318, 320 (_see_ note); #Breþeren#, brethren,VIII _a_ 201, XI _b_ 243, &c. [OE. _brōþor_; ON. _brǽðr_, pl.]

622.entry: #Broun(e)#, #Browne#, _adj._ brown, VIII _a_ 301, XV _c_ 14; dull-hued,IX 38, 98; dark, VI 177. [OE. _brūn_.]

629.entry: #Burde#, _pa. t. subj. impers._ (it would befit) in _me burde_, I hadbetter, ought to, V 210, 360. [OE. _ge-byrian_.]

630.entry: #Burgase#, #Buriays#, _n. pl._ burgesses, citizens, II 504, XIV _b_ 65.[OFr. _burgeis_, sg. and pl.]

633.entry: #Burne#, _n._ warrior, knight, man, V 3, 21, 210, 247, 252, 270, 309, VI37; _voc._ sir (knight), V 216, 254; #Buernes#, _pl._ VII 90, 91. [OE._béorn_.]

637.entry: #Busk#, _v._ (to prepare oneself); make haste, V 216; _refl._ in _buskþe_, hasten, XIV _a_ 22; _trans._ (prepare), make, V 180. [ON. _búa-sk_,refl.] _See_ Boune.

638.entry: #Busshel#, _n._ bushel (a measure of volume varying very greatly atdifferent times and places), VIII _a_ 64. [OFr. _buissiel_.]

640.entry: #Butras#, _n._ (? _pl._) buttress, II 361. [? OFr. _bouterez_, nom. sg.,or pl., of _bouteret_.]

642.entry: #Buxome#, _adj._ obedient, willing, VIII _a_ 188. [Stem of OE._būgan_ + _-sum_.] _See_ Boȝe.

644.entry: #Cagge(n)#, _v._ to tie up, VI 152. [Not known; only allit.]

648.entry: #Call(e)#, _v._ to call (cry, summon, name), I 32, IV _b_ 47, VI 182, X70, XVI 126, XVII 432, &c.; _subj. sg._ XVI 141; #Cald#, _pp._ named,VII 70, XVII 513. [OE. (late) _ceallian_, from ON. _kalla_.]

650.entry: #Cammede#, _adj._ XV _h_ 5; ? snub-nosed (cf. _Reeve's Tale_, 14); ?crooked (fits context better, but see etym.). [Cf. OFr., ME. _camus_,snub-nosed; _cammed_, bent (from Welsh _cam_), is not else recorded tilllater.]

651.entry: #Can#, _v._^1 I know, know how to, can. _Pres. ind. 1, 3 sg._ #Can#, II22, 437, XIII _b_ 38 (knows), &c.; #Con#, V 70, 215, XV _c_ 26;

652.entry: #Kan(ne)#, I 45, IV _a_ 11, 90, XVI 74; _2 sg._ #Can(ne)#, XVI 100, XVII229; #Canstow# (_see_ Þou), VIII _b_ 12; _pl._ #Can#, IX 208; #Con#, VI21; #Conen#, know, IX 185, 208; #Conne#, VI 161; #Conneþ#, VIII _a_ 116,XIII _a_ 17, _b_ 22, 38 (know); #Cunne#, XIV _c_ 101; #Kan(e)#, IV _b_21, 41, 44, 86; #Konne#, VIII _a_ 70; #Kunnen#, XI _b_ 153 (know), 275;_pres. subj._ #Conne#, VIII _a_ 143; #Kun(ne)#, XIV _b_ 90, VIII _a_250; _pa. t._ #Couþe#, #Cowþe#, I _introd._, V 115, 205, XII _introd._,_b_ 200, &c.; _cowþeȝ_ (2 sg.) with double constr., VI 124 (note);_pa. t. subj._ could, might (have), #Coude#, XI _b_ 271, XVII 286;

653.entry: #Couþe#, V 276, 353; #Cowth#, XVII 473. _Can no other red_, XII _b_ 102,_see_ Red; _how I can of_, what I can do in the way of, XVII 250. It issometimes difficult to distinguish this verb from the next (_e.g._ at V205, VI 139, XVII 468). [OE. _can_, _con_; _cūþe_.]

654.entry: #Can#, #Con#, _v._^2 _auxil._ used with infin. as equivalent of simplepa. t. (_con calle_ = called, V 144), and also, by confusion with prec.,of a present (_con dresse_ = brings about, VI 135); _1, 3 sg._ #Con#, V167, 227, VI 51, 77, 93, 181, 221, 223, &c.; _2 sg._ #Coneȝ#, VI 122;_pl._ #Can#, X 50, 66, 108, 112; #Con#, VI 149, 191; _pa. t._ did, ? V205 (_see_ prec.). [Due to confusion in form, and partly also in sense,between Gan (_q.v._) and prec.; cf. _begouth_ (_s.v._ Begynne).]

658.entry: #Care#, #Kare#, _n._ woe, misery, IV _a_ 18, 44, 60, V 316, VI 11, &c.;_care (of)_, anxiety (concerning), V 311. [OE. _caru_.]

661.entry: #Caroigne#, #Caryon#, _n._ dead body, carrion, VIII _a_ 85, XVII 502.[ONFr. _caroigne_; the phonology of the second form is obscure.]

662.entry: #Carp#, _v._ to converse, VI 21; prate, XVII 360. [ON. _karpa_, brag.]

664.entry: #Cart#, _n._ cart, VIII _b_ 13, XVII 534; _v._ to cart, VIII _b_ 66;

665.entry: #Cartere#, _n._ carter (as a name), XIV _d_ 3; #Cart-mare#, _n._draught-mare, VIII _a_ 282. [ON. _kart-r_, OE. _cræt_.]

666.entry: #Cas#, #Case#, _n._ chance, general run of events, circumstances,plight, II 175, III 20, VII 25, 73, XII _a_ 49, _b_ 194, &c.; #Caas#,_pl._ XIII _b_ 40; _in cas_, it may be, XI 101, 105, 216; _per cas_, bychance, XII _a_ 7, _b_ 4. [OFr. _cas_.]

667.entry: #Cast(e)#, _v._; #Cast(e)#, _pa. t._ V 249, XII _b_ 70, &c.; #Kest#, V207; #Casten#, _pp._ IV _a_ 60; #Icast#, XIV _c_ 79; #Kast#, I 143;

668.entry: #Kest#, V 174; to cast, throw, put, I 143, IV _b_ 3, VIII _a_ 61, X 33,XII _b_ 103, &c.; (in charity), VIII _a_ 16; to cast off, XVII 262;_icast out_, abandoned, XIV _c_ 79; to offer, propose, V 174, 207; toscheme, XI _b_ 306. [ON. _kasta_; for _e_ forms before _st_ cf.Morsbach, _ME. Gram._ § 87, n. 2.] _See_ Kest, _n._; Vpcaste.

669.entry: #Castel(l)#, _n._ castle, II 159, X 173, XVII 349, 538; a tower orraised structure on the deck of a ship (_see_ Topcastell), XVII 272.[OE. (late) _castel_ from ONFr. _castel_.]

670.entry: #Catel#, #Catayll#, #Catall#, _n. sg. collect._, goods, property, VIII_a_ 86, 141, 214, XIV _c_ 75, XVI 242, XVII 156 (cattle), 326. [ONFr._catel_.]

671.entry: #Cateractes#, _n. pl._ flood-gates, XVII 343, 451 (_see_ Genesis, vii.11, viii. 2; Vulgate _cataractæ_, sluices).

673.entry: #Cause# (_of_), _n._ cause, reason (of), XI _a_ 17, 54, XIII _b_ 66, XIV_c_ 9; _cause þerto_, cause for it, XVII 102; cause, side in a quarrel,&c., IX 82, XI _a_ 50. [OFr. _cause_.]

676.entry: #Certayn(e)#, #Certeyn(e)#, #Sarteyn(e)# (XVI), _adj._ certain, sure;fixed, definite, XI _b_ 113, XVI 225; some particular, IX 268; _come tono certeyn_, came to nothing, I 179; _nouȝt of certeyne_, no definiterule, VIII _a_ 145; _adv._ assuredly, indeed, I 231, XVI 94, XVII 176,&c. [OFr. _certain_.]

678.entry: #Cesse#, #Sesse#, _v._ to cease, leave off, come to an end, VIII _a_172, XI _b_ 205, XVI 44, 294; #Cest#, _pp._ XVII 451; #Cessynge#, _n._ceasing, XI _b_ 85. [OFr. _cesser_.]

680.entry: #Chace(n)#, to pursue, drive, IX 167, 229; _chace of_, drive, oust from,VI 83. [OFr. _chacier_.]

681.entry: #Chaffare#, _v._ to engage in trade, VIII _a_ 235, _b_ 98. [From ME._chapfare_, _chaffare_, n.; _see_ Chapuare.]

685.entry: #Chapel(le)#, _n._ chapel, private oratory (attached to a castle, &c.),V 35, 118, &c.; #Schapellis#, _pl._ XI _b_ 234. [OFr. _chapelle_.]

686.entry: #Chapelleyn#, #Chaplayn#, _n._ chaplain (a priest serving a 'chapel';_see_ prec.), VIII _a_ 12, V 39. [OFr. _chapelain_.]

689.entry: #Charde#, _pa. t. sg._ turned back, ceased to flow, VI 248. [OE._cerran_.]

690.entry: #Charge#, _n._ burden; weight, IV _b_ 48; _a þing of charge_, a weighty,important matter, XIV _c_ 52. [OFr. _charge_.] _See_ next.

691.entry: #Charge(n)#, _v._ to burden, IV _b_ 51; _charge(n) with_, to burdenwith, to impose as an obligation, XI _b_ 150, 198, 199, &c.; to enjoin,order (a person), XI _b_ 15, 31, 71, 120, 193; to attach weight,importance, to, XI _b_ 104, 106, 184, 188, 225. [OFr. _charger_.]

693.entry: #Charité#, #Charyté#, _n._ charity, christian love (for God or one'sfellows), IV _b_ 15, VI 110, XI _b_ 25, &c.; _out of ch._, not in astate of ch., XI _b_ 26, 89; _I will kepe ch._, I will not lose mytemper, XVII 235; _par charité_, _for ch._, _for of saynte ch._,(formulæ used in prayers, or requests), in the name of (holy) charity,VIII _a_ 250, XV _d_ 5, XVII 165, 174; _amen for ch._, a formula ofconclusion, XVII 558. [OFr. _charité_; _(de) par (sainte) charité_.]

698.entry: #Chaud(e)#, _adj._ hot, VIII _a_ 306; (Fr. word indicating affectationof manners above labourers' station.)

699.entry: #Chaumber#, #Chambre# (XVII), _n._ room (usually a smaller private roomor bedroom), II 100, 196, 584, XVII 129, 281 (_see_ Ches, and note), &c.[OFr. _chambre_.]

700.entry: #Chaunce#, #Chance#, _n._ chance, fortune, adventure, event, I 22, 25,28, 135, 221, V 331, VII 16; _for ch. þat may falle_, whatever mayhappen, V 64; _he cheueȝ þat chaunce_, he contrives that event,brings it to pass, V 35; _per chance_, XII _b_ 18, 57. [OFr._ch(e)ance_.]

701.entry: #Chaunge#, #Change#, _v._ to alter, change, _trans._ and _intr._, IV _a_2, 42, XII _a_ 125, XIII _a_ 4, 56, XV _a_ 22, &c.; #Chayngede#, _pa.t._ XIII _b_ 28; #Ychaunged#, _pp._ VIII _b_ 85, XIII _b_ 27. _Chaungedhis cher_, V 101, _see_ Chere. [OFr. _changier_; _chaingier_.]

702.entry: #Chaungyng#, _n._ vicissitudes, VII 16; _ch. of wit_, alteration ofsense, mistranslation, XI _a_ 47.

705.entry: #Chekes#, _n. pl._ cheeks, VIII _a_ 169; _maugré Medes (thi) chekes_, inMeed's (thy) despite, VIII _a_ 41, 151; _see_ Maugré. [OE. _cēace_,_cēce_.]

710.entry: #Cher(e)#, #Chiere# (XII), _n._ face, XV _c_ 15; looks, XII _a_ 120;demeanour, VI 47; _mery chere_, gladness, XVII 463. _Chaunged his cher_,V 101; ? altered the direction in which he faced, turned this way andthat (cf. _Sir Gaw._, 711); but the phrase elsewhere always refers tocolour or expression of face. [OFr. _chiere_, _chere_.]

711.entry: #Cherche#, #Chirche#, #Churche#, _n._ church, Church, I 3, 21, VIII _a_12, 50, _b_ 12, 63 (note), XI _a_ 62, _b_ 178, &c. [OE. _cirice_,_circe_.] _See_ Kirke.

712.entry: #Chercheȝerd#, _n._ churchyard, I 3, 66, 263; #Cherche porche#,church porch, I 77. [Prec. + OE. _géard_; OFr. _porche_.]

715.entry: #Ches#, #Chese# (MS. chefe), _n._ in _thre ches(e)_, three tiers or rowsof, XVII 129, 281 (followed by sg. noun). [Perhaps a use of ME. _ches_,chess, as 'rows of squares' (OFr. _eschez_, pl. of _eschec_, _see_Chekke).]

716.entry: #Chese#, _v._ to choose; _chese ȝou_, choose (for) yourselves, II217; #Chees#, #Ches#, _pa. t. sg._ XI _b_ 56, XII _a_ 110; for pastpple. _see_ Ycore. [OE. _cēosan_.]

718.entry: #Chesible#, _n._ chasuble (the outer vestment of a priest whencelebrating Mass), VIII _a_ 12. [OFr. _chesible_.]

719.entry: #Chesouns#, _n. pl._ reasons, XI _a_ 50. [Shortened from OFr._ache(i)son_; _see_ Enchesone.]

721.entry: #Cheue#, _v._ (to acquire), control, bring about; _cheueȝ þatchaunce_, brings that event to pass, V 35; #Cheuyt#, _pp._ broughtabout, VII 16. [OFr. _chever_ and _achever_.] _See_ Acheue.

723.entry: #Chibolles#, _n. pl._ chibols, a variety of small onion, VIII _a_ 289.[ONFr. _*chiboule_, OFr. _ciboule_.]

725.entry: #Chyde#, _v. intr._ to complain, find fault, VI 43, VIII _a_ 307, 314.[OE. _cīdan_.]

727.entry: #Child#, #Chylde#, _n._ child, III 39, IV _a_ 73, &c., _child hys_,child's, XIII _b_ 23; #Childer#, #Chylder#, _pl._ XVII 327, 527;

730.entry: #Chillyng#, _n._ becoming cold, in _for chillyng of here mawe_, toprevent their stomachs getting cold, VIII _a_ 306. [OE. _cilian_; butsee _N.E.D._]

734.entry: #Chiualrye#, _n._ knighthood, the knights as a body, XIV _c_ 42. [OFr._chev-_, _chivalerie_.] _See_ Cheualrous.

736.entry: #Cité#, #Cyté#, #Cytee#, #Citie#, #Sité#, _n._ city, II 48, 479, VII 66,85, VIII _b_ 94, IX 23, XIII _b_ 67, &c. [OFr. _cité_.]

742.entry: #Cled#, _pp._ clad; _cled in Stafford blew_, beaten black and blue, XVII200; _see_ Blew. [OE. _clǣþan_ (rare).]

744.entry: #Clene#, _adj._ clean, IV _b_ 6, V 323, 325; unmixed, VIII _a_ 299;pure, VII 179, XI _b_ 295, XV _i_ 7; elegant, VII 77; splendid, VII 150(or _adv._). [OE. _clǣne_.] _See_ Clanly, Clense.

747.entry: #Clense#, _v._ to cleanse, clear out, IV _a_ 7, VIII _a_ 98. [OE._clǣ̆nsian_.]

748.entry: #Clepe(n)#, #Clepyn#, _v._ to call (cry, summon, name), I _introd._, II201, III 12, 24, IX 27, XII _a_ 76, _b_ 16; #Cleped#, #Clept#, _pp._ II49, IX 3, XII _a_ 6, &c.; #Ycleped#, II 52, III 17, 32. [OE._cleopian_.]

749.entry: #Clere#, _adj._ clear, bright, glorious, fair, II 269, 358, V 283, VII107, 123, XVI 128, 389; free (from guilt), *XVI 356 (MS. clene); _adv._clearly, VII 77; #Clerlych#, _adv._ clearly, XIII _a_ 12. [OFr. _cler_.]

750.entry: #Clerematyn#, _n._ (? _lit._ 'fine morning') appar. name of a fineflour, or bread made from it, VIII _a_ 299. [? OFr. _cler matin_.]

751.entry: #Clerk(e)#, _n._ one in holy orders, ecclesiastic (opp. to 'lay'),scholar, writer, II 2, VII 53, VIII _b_ 56, 58, XI _a_ 36, 59, _b_ 55,177, XVI 283, &c.; #Clerkus#, _pl._ VIII _b_ 65. [OE. _cler(i)c_; OFr._clerc_.]

752.entry: #Clete#, _n._ cleat, small (wedge-shaped) piece of wood; _ȝafnouȝt a cl. of_ = cared not a rap for, XIV _c_ 54. [OE. _*clēat_;cf. OHG. _chlōȥ_, MDu. _cloot_.]

755.entry: #Clingge#, _v._ XV _a_ 8; _the clot him clingge_, may the earth of thegrave cling to him (_or_ waste him; cf. _alþaȝ oure corses inclotteȝ clynge_, Pearl 857); #Yclongen#, _pp._ withered, II 508. [OE._clíngan_, shrivel, shrink.] _See_ Clengeȝ.

760.entry: #Clomben#, _pa. t. pl._ climbed, V 10. [OE. _clímban_; pa. t. pl._clúmbon_.]

762.entry: #Clos#, #Cloise# (oi = ō, _cf._ Coyll), _adj._ closed; secluded,forbidden, VII 179; close, VI 152 (_man hit cl._, make it secure);_adv._ (or _predic. adj._) close, near, VII 137. [OFr. _clos_.]

763.entry: #Close#, _v._ to close, enclose, IX 172, XI _b_ 39; #Yclosed#, _pp._XIII _a_ 24, 40. [From prec.] _See_ Enclose.

765.entry: #Cloþ#, _n._ a cloth, XV _f_ 8; cloth, VIII _a_ 14; #Cloþes#, &c., _pl._clothes, I 165, 236, II 408, VII 175, VIII _b_ 18, XI _b_ 257, XIII _a_9, &c. [OE. _clāþ_.]

767.entry: #Cloþe-merys#, _n. pl._ ? mare-clothers (? contemptuous reference toblacksmiths as fashioning pieces of horse-armour; for similar compound_see_ Brenwaterys), XV _h_ 21. [Prec. + OE. _mēre_.]

768.entry: #Cloude#, _n._^1 clod of earth; _under cloude_, in the ground, XV _b_31. [OE. _clūd_, mass of earth, or rock.]

771.entry: #Cloute#, _v._ to patch; _cloute more to_, stick more on to it, XI _b_200; _go cloute thi shone_, go and cobble your shoes, 'run away andplay', XVII 353; #Yclouted#, _pp._ patched, VIII _a_ 61. [OE._clūtian_.]

777.entry: #Coffes#, _n. pl._ mittens, gloves, VIII _a_ 62. [Unknown; _cf._ Prompt.Parv., '_cuffe_, glove or meteyne'.]

778.entry: #Coyll#, _n._ _lit._ cabbage; pottage, cabbage or vegetable soup, XVII389. [OE. _cāl_; _oy_ = _ō_ (see the rimes).] _See_ Koleplantes.

779.entry: #Coke#, _v._ to put hay into cocks, VIII _b_ 13. [From (obscure) ME._cocke_, hay-cock; see _N.E.D._]

780.entry: #Coker#, _n._ a labourer (at haymaking or harvest), VIII _b_ 13. [Fromprec.; _cf._ Cath. Angl., '_coker_, autumnarius'.]

781.entry: #Cokeres#, _n. pl._ leggings, VIII _a_ 62. [OE. _cocor_, quiver; _cf._Prompt. Parv., '_cocur_, cothurnus'.]

782.entry: #Coket#, _n._ very fine flour next in grade to the finest (_wastell_),VIII _a_ 299. [_Panis de coket_ occurs in 14th c. legal Latin; connexionbetween this and AFr. _cokkette_, Anglo-L. _coketa_, cocket, seal ofKing's Customhouse, has been suggested, but not proved.]

784.entry: #Cold(e)#, _n._ cold, I 163, IX 31, XV _f_ 13; _for colde of_, to keepthe cold from (_see_ For, _prep._), VIII _a_ 62. [OE. _cáld_.] _See_Chelde.

785.entry: #Col(e)#, _n._ live coal, IV _a_ 13; coal, XV _h_ 5. [OE. _col_, livecoal.]

786.entry: #Coloppes#, _n. pl._ 'collops', eggs fried on bacon, VIII _a_ 280. [See_N.E.D._, s.v. _Collop_, and _Cockney_.]

787.entry: #Colour#, _n._ colour, IX 34, XII _a_ 55, &c.; outward appearance, XI_b_ 217. [OFr. _colour_.]

788.entry: #Com#, #Come(n)#, #Cum# (X), _v._ to come, I 80, 176, II 137, V 43, X45, 173, XVII 241, &c.; #Comest#, _2 sg._ wilt come, XV _g_ 5; #Commys#,_3 sg._ XVII 507; #Cam#, _pa. t._ I 77, II 153, VIII _a_ 294, &c.;

789.entry: #Com(e)#, I 32, II 91, III 3, V 107, VI 222, VII 83, &c.; _pa. t. subj._(should come, &c.), VI 214, 238, VIII _a_ 108, X 29, XV _g_ 30;

791.entry: #Comne#, IV _a_ 23; #Cumen#, XIV _b_ 8, 87; #Ycome(n)#, II 203, 319,404, 422, 478, 592. With _dat. refl. pron._ in: _foret hym com_, forthcame, XV _g_ 18; _in him com ... gon_, came (walking) in (cf. OE._cōm inn gān_), XV _g_ 24; _him com_, III 19. _Comen of_,descended from, II 29. [OE. _cuman_, _cōm_, _cumen_.]

792.entry: #Coma(u)nde#, #Comawnde#, #Commaund#, _v._ to command, I 105, VIII _a_16, XI _b_ 66, XV _i_ 1, XVI 341, XVII 118, &c.; with _to_, XI _b_ 40;to commend, V 343; to entrust, give, XI _b_ 222. [OFr. _comander_.]

793.entry: #Com(m)aundement#, &c., _n._ commandment, IV _b_ 15, XI _b_ 63, 86, 226;_gaf in comm._, commanded, XVII 32. [OFr. _comandement_.] _See_Maundement.

794.entry: #Comenci# (II), #Comse# (VIII), _v._ to begin, VIII _a_ 34, 309; _pres.subj._ II 247 (note to l. 57). [OFr. _comencer_.] _See_ Comessing.

795.entry: #Comendacion#, _n._ 'Commendation of Souls', an office for the dead(made a part of daily office) which originally ended with the prayer_Tibi, Domine, commendamus_, XI _b_ 132.

798.entry: #Comyng(e)#, _n._ coming, advent, XII _a_ 35, XVI 315, 363, &c.; _homcomynge_, homecoming, IX 285. _See_ Com.

800.entry: #Comly(ch)#, _adj._ fair, beautiful, V 343, XVII 71. [OE. _cȳmlic_,influ. in ME. by assoc. with _becomen_.]

805.entry: #Comounly#, _adv._ usually, IX 51; in common, IX 60. _See_ Comun.

807.entry: #Cumpany(e)#, X 147, &c.; _in cumpanye_, in the society of men, I_introd._, IX 288. [OFr. _compai(g)nie_.]

814.entry: #Comun(e)#, _adj._ common (people), XIV _b_ 67; as _sb._, the community,VIII _b_ 20, 79; #Comunes#, #Comyns#, _pl._ the common people; theCommons (as an estate of the realm), XIV _b_ 67, _c_ 73; lay men, XI _a_39, 59. [OFr. _comun_; and direct from L. _commūnis_.]

819.entry: #Confesse#, _v._ to confess, XI _b_ 143; _confessed clene_, made cleanby confession, V 323. [OFr. _confesser_.]

821.entry: #Confort#, #Coumforde#, _n._ support, comfort, consolation, VI 9, VIII_b_ 79, XII _a_ 151. [OFr. _con-_, _cunfort_.]

822.entry: #Conforte#, #Com-#, _v._ to comfort, succour, support, IV _a_ 15, VIII_a_ 214; #Comford#, _pa. t. pl._ VII 173. [OFr. _conforter_.]

827.entry: #Connynge#, _n._ intelligence, IV _b_ 56, 79. [From _cunn-_, old infin.stem of Can, _v._^1]

831.entry: #-sayll#), _n._ counsel, deliberation, advice, II 179, VIII _a_ 309, X15, XIV _b_ 40, 43, XVI 114, 163, XVII 157; prudence, IV _b_ 56, 57, 61;council, VIII _a_ 312, IX 296, 298. [OFr. _conseil_, _c(o)unseil_,counsel, council.]

833.entry: #Consente#, _v._ to agree; _consented to o wyl_, was agreed, I 49. [OFr._consentir_.]

835.entry: #Constreyne#, _v._ to force, VIII _b_ 56, XI _b_ 248. [OFr._constreign-_, stem of _constreindre_.]

837.entry: #Constru(w)e#, _v._ to construe, interpret, XIII _b_ 18, 34; _pres.subj. pl._ in _ȝif ȝe c. wel þis clause_, if you see the point ofwhat I say, XIV _c_ 11. [L. _construere_.]

838.entry: #Conteyne#, _v._ to contain, IX 337, XIII _a_ 20. [OFr. _contenir_,_conteign-_, stem of subj.]

840.entry: #Contemplatyf#, #-if#, _adj._ contemplative, devoted to prayer andcontemplation of God, VIII _a_ 245, XI _b_ 1, 8, &c. [OFr._contemplatif_.]

844.entry: #Cuntray# (II), #Cuntré# (I), #Cuntrey# (XI), _n._ country, land,region, I 253, II 351, IX 4, 9, 26, 134, 138, XI _a_ 35, XIII _a_ 41,_b_ 63, XVII 487 (_see_ Sere), &c., as _adj._ in _contray longage_,language of the land, XIII _b_ 13. [OFr. _contrée_, _c(o)untrée_.]

846.entry: #Contrefetes#, _n. pl._ imitations, IX 117. [OFr. _contrefet_, pp., madelike.] _See_ Counterfete, _v._

848.entry: #Cope#, _n._ long cloak, XII _a_ 53; _esp._ the out-door cloak of anecclesiastic, VIII _a_ 182. [OE. _*cāpe_, from Med.L. _cāpa_.]

850.entry: #Copuls#, _3 sg. pres._ links, IV _a_ 12; #Coppled#, _pp._ linked (inrime), Introduction xv; _see_ Kowe. [OFr. _copler_.] _See_ Couple, _n._

853.entry: #Corde(n)#, _v._; _corden into on_, agree together, XV _i_ 6. [Shortenedfrom Acorde, _q.v._]

855.entry: #Coround(e)#, _pa. t._ crowned, VI 55; _pp._ II 593, VI 120. [OFr._corouner_.] _See_ Crouned(e).

858.entry: #Corseynt#, _n._ shrine of a saint, I 239. [OFr. _cors saint_, holybody.]

859.entry: #Cortays(e)#, #Curteys# (II), _adj._ gracious, II 28, VI 73; as _sb._,gracious lady, V 343. [OFr. _corteis_, _curteis_.] _See_ Kort.

860.entry: #Cortaysye#, #Cortaysé#, #Courtaysye#, _n._ courtesy, grace, VI 72, 84,96, 109, 121 (_of cortaysye_ prob. only equivalent to _cortayse_,_adj._); _of courtaysye_, _by cortaysye_, &c. by especial favour, VI 97,108, 120. [OFr. _corteisie_, _curteisie_.]

864.entry: #Cost#, _n._^2 expenditure, cost, XI _b_ 169; ? means (to meet expense),XI _b_ 141. [OFr. _cost_.]

869.entry: #Cote#, _n._^2 coat; here a tunic (_cf._ 'waistcoat') worn beneath theouter gown, XVII 262. [OFr. _cote_.]

871.entry: #Cou#, #Cow#, _n._ cow, III 49, 52, 54, VIII _a_ 282; _pl._ #Ken#, III56; #Kyȝn#, IX 256; #Kyn(e)#, VIII _a_ 134, _b_ 18. [OE. _cū_; pl._cȳ_ (Kt. _*cē_).]

872.entry: #Couaytyng#, #Coueytynge#, _n._ coveting, IX 90; object of coveting (cf._louyng_, &c.), IV _a_ 23. [From OFr. _coveit(i)er_.]

873.entry: #Couaytise# (III), #Coueitise# (XI), #Couetyse# (V), #Coueteis# (XVII),_n._ covetousness, avarice, III 22, V 306, 312, XI _b_ 55, 256, XVII 52.[OFr. _coveitise_.]

879.entry: #Covenant#, #Couenaunde#, #-aunt#, _n._ covenant, agreement, V 260, 272,VI 202, 203, VIII _a_ 153, XII _b_ 41, 96, 199; _pl._ terms of theagreement, V 174; _in c. þat_, on condition that, VIII _a_ 28. [OFr._covenant_.]

882.entry: #Counted#, _pa. t._ reckoned on (_or_ heeded), VII 115; _countednouȝt a bene beo_, gave not a bean for, XIV _c_ 43. [OFr. _cunter_.]

883.entry: #Counterfete#, _v._ to imitate (fraudulently), IX 114; to resemble, VI196 (bad connotation often absent in this use, but possibly herepresent--'make them unjustly resemble us'). [Formed from ME._counterfete_, imitated, OFr. _contrefet_.] _See_ Contrefetes.

886.entry: #Countre note#, _n._ counterpoint, a melody added as an accompaniment toanother, XI _b_ 137 (note). [OFr. _countre_ + _note_.]

887.entry: #Couple#, _n._ match, pair, II 458 (note); #Copple#, couplet (in verse),Introduction xxxiii. [OFr. _couple_.]

888.entry: #Cours(e)#, _n._ course, VII 102, XIII _a_ 61, &c.; _cours ... about_,circuit, X 157; flow, VII 123; force, rushing, VII 115; _by course_, indue order, VII 73. [OFr. _cours_.]

890.entry: #Courtpies#, _n. pl._ short jackets, VIII _a_ 182. [Current in 14th and15th centuries; cf. MDu. _korte pie_, short coat of coarse woollenstuff.]

892.entry: #Couwee#, _adj._ tailed, in _(ryme) couwee_, rime in pairs followed by ashorter line, or 'tail', tailrime, Introduction xv. [OFr. _rime couée_.]_See_ Kowe.

895.entry: #Crache#, _v._ to scratch, II 80. [Obscure; cf. MDu., MLG. _kratsen_.]

897.entry: #Craft(e)#, _n._ craft; industry, VIII _b_ 20; knowledge, in _to ken allthe cr._, to know the whole story, VII 25. [OE. _cræft_.]

900.entry: #Crak#, _v._ to crack, XIV _a_ 10; #Crakked#, _pp._ XIV _a_ 11. [OE._cracian_, to crack (sound).]

901.entry: #Craue#, #Crafe# (XVII), _v._ to demand, VIII _a_ 86; to plead for, XVII174; _craue aftir_, ask for, XVI 242. [OE. _crafian_, demand.]

903.entry: #Crede#, _n._ the Creed, VI 125; _sall ken ȝow ȝowre crede_ = willteach you what you ought to know, a lesson, XIV _b_ 4. [OE. _crēda_,from L. _crēdo_, I believe (cf. VIII _a_ 83).]

906.entry: #Cren#, _n._ crane (machine), X 16, 28. [OE. _cran_ (bird); the aboveare the earliest recorded instances of the transferred sense.]

909.entry: #Cri(e)#, #Cry#, _n._ lamentation, II 114, 220; _held in o cri_,lamented in the same strain, II 95; shouting, clamour, II 285, XV _h_ 4;a cry, appeal, II 511 (_see_ Sette). [OFr. _cri_.]

910.entry: #Crie(n)#, #Crye(n)#, #Cry#, _v._ to cry out (shout, call, lament),proclaim, XI _b_ 48, XII _a_ 76, 140, XVI 186, 363, XVII 384, &c.;_pres. subj._ XVI 141; #Crid(e)#, _pa. t._ II 78, XII _b_ 31, 69;

911.entry: #Cryit#, X 86; #Criand#, #-ende#, _pres. p._ XVI 73, XII _b_ 16. _Cryenafter_, shout for, XV _h_ 5; _crie on_, appeal to, XVI 107; _cry memercy_, cry to me for mercy, XVII 384 (the earliest recorded sense inE.). [OFr. _crier_.]

913.entry: #Criing#, #Criyng(e)#, _n._ (loud) shouting, XI _b_ 133, 249; _at ocriing_, with one voice, II 581 (cf. _at one cri_, Havelok 2773);lamentation, II 195. [From Crie(n).]

916.entry: #Cristen(e)#, #Crystene#, #Crystyn# (I), #Krysten# (VI), _adj._Christian, I _introd._, 82, VI 101, IX 211, XI _a_ 37, &c.; as _sb. pl._VIII _a_ 89. [OE. _crī̆sten_.]

921.entry: #Croun(e)#, #Crowne#, _n._ crown, II 235, 415, VI 67, &c.; crown of thehead, XIV _a_ 10, 11. [OFr. _coroune_; cf. ON. _krúna_. In the sense'crown of head' only the _cr-_ forms appear.] _See_ Corouneȝ.

922.entry: #Crouned(e)#, _pp._ tonsured, admitted to holy orders, VIII _b_ 58, 62,67. [OFr. _corouner_.] _See_ prec. (which also in ME. had sense'tonsure'), and Corounde, Vncrouned.

924.entry: #Crowe#, _v._ to crow, XV _g_ 33 (with pleonastic reflex. pron.); toannounce by crowing, XII _a_ 77. [OE. _crāwan_.]

928.entry: #Cultur#, _n._ coulter, iron blade fixed in front of the share in aplough, VIII _a_ 98. [OE. (from L.) _culter_.]

933.entry: #Cuntek#, _n._ contest; _yn cuntek_, vying with one another, I 31. [OFr.(only AFr.) _contek_, of unknown origin.]

937.entry: #Curse#, _v._ to curse, I 98, 130, &c.; #Corsed#, #Cursed#, _pp._ and_adj._ V 128, 306, IX 85, &c.; _cursed shrewe_, VII 183, VIII _a_ 153.[OE. (late) _cū̆rsian_, from OIr. _cúrsagim_.]

941.entry: #Dai#, #Day(e)#, _n._ day, I 138, VI 56, XII _a_ 68, &c.; dawn, XII _a_77; life-time, II 572, &c. (also _pl._ VI 56, VII 39); _daies olde_, oldage, XII introd.; time, in _withinne tuo monthe day_, in two months'time, XII _a_ 29; _þise dayeȝ_ (gen. sg.) _longe_, all (this) daylong, VI 173 (_see_ Longe); _by dayes_, once upon a time, II 15; _bi__this dai_, (for) this day, VIII _a_ 274; but an oath at XV _a_ 24, XVII386; _on a day_, one day, II 303; _þis othir daye_, the other day, XVI148; _þis endre dai_, a day or two ago (_see_ Endre), XV _a_ 4. [OE._dæg_.]

944.entry: #Dam(e)#, _n._ dame, lady, queen, II 63, 113, 322, VIII _a_ 72, XVII298, &c.; mother, VIII _a_ 73, XVII 324. [OFr. _dame_.]

946.entry: #Dampne#, _v._ to damn, condemn, XI _b_ 197, 306; #Dampnet#, _pa. t.pl._ VII 50; #Dampned#, _pp._ XVI 272; as _sb._ XVI 377. [OFr._dam(p)ner_.]

947.entry: #Dan(e)#, #Danȝ#, Master, Dom, an honourable title esp. prefixed tonames of members of religious orders, I _introd._, III _introd._ [OFr._Dan_ (nom. _Danz_, _Dans_); L. _Dom(i)nus_.]

950.entry: #Dar#, _v._ dare, _1 sg. pres._ II 336, VIII _a_ 263, &c.; _3 sg._ IX88, &c.; #Dare#, _pres. pl._ XVI 145; #Dore(n)#, XI _b_ 36, 199;

951.entry: #Dorst(e)#, _pa. t. sg._ dared, XII _b_ 109, XIV _c_ 21; #Durst#, II140, 427, 482; _pl._ II 73, 84, X 130; #Durst#, _pa. t. subj._ (would)dare, XVII 479. [OE. _dearr_, _durron_; _dorste_.]

952.entry: #Dare#, _v._ to cower, V 190; ? #Dard#, _pa. t. sg._ VI 249 (_see_note). [OE. _darian_.]

953.entry: #Dase#, _v._ to be dumbfounded, XVII 314. [OE. _*dasian_; cf. _darian_,and ON. _dasa-sk_.]

954.entry: #Dastard#, _n._ wretch, vile fellow, XVI 180, 203. [Perhaps formed withFr. suffix _-ard_ from _dased_, _dast_, pp. of prec.]

955.entry: #Date#, _n._ date, used in VI in various senses, some strained; point oftime, hour, VI 169, 181; season, 144 (_see_ Dere), 145; limit (beginningor end), 133, 156, 157, 168, 180; _to dere a date_, ? too soon, 132(_cf._ 126). [OFr. _date_.]

960.entry: #Dawing#, #Dawyng#, _n._ daybreak, first signs of dawn, IV _a_ 94, X 42.[OE. _dagung_.]

962.entry: #Deaw#, #Dew#, _n. pl._ dew, IX 59, XV _b_ 28, &c.; _May dew_, dewgathered in May (believed to have medicinal and magical properties), IX63. [OE. _dēaw_.]

963.entry: #Debate#, _n._ parleying, wrangling, V 180, XVI 142; _wythouten debate_,putting aside contention, VI 30. [OFr. _debat_.]

965.entry: #Declare#, _v._ to set out, declare, VII 77, XII _b_ 210. [OFr._declarer_.]

966.entry: #Declyne#, _v._ (to decline), fall; _con d. into acorde_, came to anagreement (cf. ME. _fall at_ (or _of_) _accorde_), VI 149. [OFr._decliner_.]

967.entry: #Ded(e)#, _adj._ dead, I 195, 209, II 108, &c.; used as pp. of 'slay',VII 92, XVI 148; _was broght dede_, was brought to death, died, I 213.[OE. _dēad_.] _See_ next, and Deþ.

968.entry: #Ded(e)#, _n._^1 death, I 212, IV _a_ 48, _b_ 71, X 51, 77, 118, XVI317, XVII 193, 543. [A variant, usually Northern, of Deþ, _q.v._]

969.entry: #Ded(e)#, _n._^2 deed, act, feat, event, III 45, VII 38, 88, IX 312, XI_b_ 255, XVI 24, &c.; as obj. to _do_, I 79, VIII _b_ 9, XII _a_ 111;behaviour, way of acting, IV _a_ 62, XI _b_ 62; _Dedis of Apostlis_,Acts of the Apostles, XI _b_ 285; _in dede_, in the actual performance,VII 23, XVI 72; _to fre of dede_, too lavish in its action, VI 121; _indede and þoȝte_, in performance and intention, VI 164. [OE._dēd_.]

970.entry: #Ded-day#, _n._ death-day, VIII _introd._ [OE. _dēaþ-dæg_; see Dede(death), but here assimilation of _þd_ to _dd_ is possible.]

975.entry: #Defaute#, _n._ defect, XI _a_ 43, 44, 57; lack, in _for defaute of_,for lack of, VIII _a_ 200, XI _b_ 250. [OFr. _defaute_.]

976.entry: #Defence#, #Defens# (_of_), _n._ defence (against), IX 332, X 64, 135;_of noble defens_, nobly fortified, II 48. [OFr. _defense_.]

977.entry: #Defend(e)#, _v._ to defend, V 49, VIII _a_ 82, X 52, &c.; to makedefence, X 61, 191; make defence against, ward off, VII 85; #Defending#,_n._ defence, X 194. [OFr. _defend-re_.]

982.entry: #Degré#, #Degree#, _n._ position, rank, VIII _b_ 71, XVII 21, 489; state(of preparedness), X 40. [OFr. _degré_.]

983.entry: #Deye# (VIII), #De# (X), #Dye(n)#, _v._ to die, II 189, VIII _a_ 269,325, IX 150, X 73, &c.; #Deye#, _pres. subj._ VIII _a_ 92, 114; #Deyd#,_pa. t. sg._ I 215; #Dyȝede#, XIV _c_ 106; #Deyden#, _pa. t. pl._VIII _b_ 41; _do ... deye_, _garre ... dye_, kill, VIII _a_ 269, XVI164. [ON. _deyja_.]

988.entry: #Dele#, #Deill#, #Deyll#, _n._ part, quantity, in _a grete dele_, agreat deal, XVII 450; _ich a deyll_, all, XVII 299; _ylk a dele_, _ilkedeill_, altogether, IV _a_ 27, X 75. [OE. _dǣl_.] _See_ Euerydel,Halvendel, Somdel, &c.

989.entry: #Dele(n)#, _v._ to divide, distribute, deal, mete out, perform, V 124,217, VI 246, VIII _a_ 91, XI _b_ 270, 272; #Dalt#, _pa. t. sg._ V 350;

990.entry: #Deled#, _pp._ XIII _b_ 49; _dele with_, have to do with, XVI 63; withcognate obj. _dele penny doyll_, XVII 390 (_see_ Doyll); _delen ato_,part (_intr._), II 125. [OE. _dǣlan_.]

992.entry: #Delit(e)#, #Delyte#, _n._ delight, IV _b_ 39, XII _a_ 88, XVI 63;_delytes of_, delight in, IV _b_ 62. [OFr. _delit_.]

994.entry: #Delytte#, _v._ in _delyttes þaym (in)_, _3 pl. refl._, take delight(in), IV _b_ 42. [OFr. _delit(i)er_.]

997.entry: #Deluen#, _v._ to dig; to bury; VIII _a_ 135; #Dalf#, _pa. t. sg._ XIV_introd._; #Doluen#, _pa. t. pl._ VIII _a_ 184; #Doluen#, _pp._ (deadand) buried, VIII _a_ 173. [OE. _delfan_.]

1000.entry: #Deme#, #Dieme#, _v._ to judge, sentence, XII _b_ 216, XVI 34;criticize, VIII _a_ 75; consider, deem, XI _b_ 190, 209, 211; _ne demethow non other_, imagine nothing different, VIII _a_ 173; speak, say, V115 (note), VI 1; with cognate obj. _domes for te deme_, to tell theirtales, XV _b_ 30. [OE. _dēman_.]

1003.entry: #Deneȝ#, _adj._ Danish; _Deneȝ ax_, an axe with a long blade andusually without a spike at the back, V 155 (note). [OE. _denisc_; OFr._daneis_.]

1006.entry: #Departed(e)#, #Depertid#, _pa. t._ separated, VI 18 (_intr._), VII 145(_trans._); departed, IX 308, 320; _pp._ divided, IX 1. [OFr._de(s)partir_.]

1007.entry: #Dep(e)#, #Deop# (XIII), _adj._ deep, XII _b_ 11, XIII _a_ 39, XVI 377;as _sb._, the deep (sea), VII 154, XII _a_ 160; _adv._ deeply, VI 46.[OE. _dēop_; adv. _dēope_.]

1012.entry: #Dere#, _adj._ dear; prized, I 258; beloved, I 125, VI 8, VIII _a_ 91,XIV _c_ 1, XV _f_ 1, XVII 172, 190, 419, 527; _my dere_, my friend, VIII_a_ 251; pleasing, VI 40; good, &c. (vaguely applied in allit. poems),VI 132, 144, VII 61; #Derrist#, _superl._ best, VII 39. [OE. _dēore_;_dē̆orra_, compar. (whence also stem of ME. superl.).]

1013.entry: #Dere#, _n._ harm, I 166, XVII 317; _maken þe worlde dere_, do injury tomankind (? _or_ 'make the world dear to live in'; but _cf._ 166), VIII_a_ 154. [OE. _daru_, influenced by _derian_.]

1015.entry: #Dere#, _adv._ dearly, at great cost, IV _a_ 80, VIII _a_ 75, XVII 373;_as me dere liketh_, to my liking, VIII _a_ 286. [OE. _dēore_.]

1026.entry: #Desert#, _adj._ uncultivated and desolate, IX 200; _n._ desert,uninhabited land, IX 179, XI _b_ 24. [OFr. _desert_.]

1027.entry: #Deserue(n)#, _v._ to deserve, VIII _a_ 43, _b_ 32; to earn, VIII _a_211, _b_ 43, 47. [OFr. _deservir_.] _See_ Serue(n).

1030.entry: #Desport#, _n._ amusement, IX 276; _do desport_, play, make merry, XII_a_ 174. [OFr. _desport_.]

1039.entry: #Deþ(e)#, #Deth#, _n._ death, II 332, V 37, VII 9, VIII _a_ 324 (thePlague), &c. [OE. _dēaþ_.] _See_ Ded(e), _adj._ and _n._

1040.entry: #Deuel(l)#, #Deuelle#, #Deuyl(l)#, #Dele# (V), _n._ devil, Devil, IV _b_20, 26, V 120, VIII _a_ 56, 114, XI _b_ 105, XV _h_ 16, XVI 341, 399,&c.; _what deuel_, what the devil, XVI 223. [OE. _dēofol_.]

1041.entry: #Deuelway#; _in þe d._, in the Devil's name, XVI 133. [See _N.E.D._,s.v. _Devil_ 19.]

1044.entry: #Deuise#, #-yse#, #Devise#, _v._ to descry, II 312; to describe, relate,IX 267, 268, 271. [OFr. _deviser_; see _N.E.D._, s.v. _Devise_.]

1045.entry: #Deuocio(un)#, #Deuocyun#, _n._ devotion, devoutness, pious practice, I18, V 124, XI _b_ 110, 120, XII _a_ 14, &c. [OFr. _devocion_.]

1049.entry: #Dyacne#, _n._ deacon, III 9, 12; #Diaknen#, _dat. pl._, III 5. [OE._diacon_, OFr. _diacne_.] _See_ Archidekenes.

1051.entry: #Diche#, #Dyche#, _n._ moat, dike, II 361, VI 247; notion in VI appar.releasing of water pent up by a dam. [OE. _dīc_.]

1057.entry: #Digge#, #Dyggen#, _v._ to dig, II 255, IX 231; #Digged#, _pa. t. pl._VIII _a_ 101. [? OFr. _diguer_; see _N.E.D._]

1061.entry: #Diȝte#, #Dighte#, #Dyȝte#, #Dyghte#, _v._ to arrange, prepare,make, I 30, V 155, VIII _a_ 286; _diȝte_, arrayed for battle, XIV _b_34; _dyght to dede_, put to death, XVII 543. [OE. _dihtan_.]

1069.entry: #Dyne#, _v. trans._ to eat (at dinner), VIII _a_ 303; _2 sg. pres.subj._ VIII _a_ 257; #Dyned#, _pp. intr._ had dinner, VIII _a_ 274.[OFr. _di(s)ner_.]
