1071.entry: #Dynge(n)#, _v._ to strike, smite, beat, V 37 (MS. dynneȝ), VIII _a_135, XVI 180, 203; #Dang#, _pa. t. pl._ X 54. [OE. _*dingan_; cf._dencgan_, ON. _dengja_.]

1073.entry: #Dynt#, _n._ stroke, blow, V 48, 155, 196, XV _h_ 2; _dynt of honde_, ablow (with a weapon), V 37, VII 92. [OE. _dynt_.]

1075.entry: #Dirige#, _n._ (dirge), matins in the office for the dead, VIII _b_ 48,XI _b_ 132 (note). [L. _dirige_.]

1080.entry: #Discord#, _n._ discord; _without discord_, in peace (_or_incontestably; _cf._ Distance), XVII 31. [OFr. _discord_.]

1085.entry: #Dyspleseȝ#, #Displeases#, _v._ _3 sg. pres._ displeases, VI 95, XVII85; _imper. pl._ (_intr._) be displeased, VI 62. [OFr. _desplaisir_.]

1091.entry: #Distroie#, #-oy(e)#, #Destroye#, _v._ to destroy, VII 28, IX 215, XI_b_ 215, XVII 93; #Disstryeȝ#, _pres. pl._ V 307. [OFr. _destrui-re_;with _disstryeȝ_ cf. Byled, Nye.]

1095.entry: #Diuers(e)#, #Dyuers(e)#, _adj._ varying, divergent, XIII _b_ 44;different, various, IX 16, 287, 289, XII _a_ 55, &c.; _dyuers maner(e)_,different kinds of, XIII _b_ 47, 48; _ich maner diuers animal_, everykind of different animal, II 364. [OFr. _divers_.]

1097.entry: #Do(n)#, #Doo#, _v._ I 219, IV _b_ 65, IX 169, &c. to do; _to done_ (OE._tō dōnne_), VIII _a_ 104, 197, IX 160; _2 sg._ #Dos#, XVII 196;

1098.entry: #Doste#, VIII _a_ 75; #Dotȝ#, VI 196; _3 sg._ #Deþ# (OE. _dēþ_),III 60; #Dose#, IV _a_ 57, &c.; #Dotȝ#, V 143; #Doþ#, II 112, &c.;_pl._ #Don(e)#, II 2, VIII _a_ 220, &c.; #Dos#, I 157; #Doþ# (MS. doh),*XV _b_ 22; _imper. pl._ #Dotȝ#, VI 161, 176; #Doþ#, I 82, II 218._Pa. t. sg._ #Ded(e)#, I 176, II 232, III 17, &c.; #Dyd#, I 166, &c.;

1099.entry: #Did(e)#, XI _b_ 13, XVII 11 (_2 sg._), &c.; _pl._ #Dede(n)#, II 32, XV_i_ 13; #Diden#, XI _b_ 247. _Pres. p._ #Doande#, IV _b_ 9; _pp._ #Do#,XI _b_ 271, XII _a_ 107, &c.; #Doyne#, XVII 139; #Don(e)#, IX 326, XIV_a_ 24, &c.; #Ydo#, II 381; #Ydone#, II 76. (i) To act, do, make,perform, work, II 32, III 17, IV _b_ 9, 25, VI 161, XIV _b_ 38, &c.; toexert, XI _b_ 6; representing any verb understood, I 157, II 112, &c.;_be to done_, _es to doo_, is to be done, IV _b_ 65, VIII _a_ 197; _doþat_, act according to, I 82; _don gret pyne_, toil hard, VI 151; _donhim felaschipe_, bear him company, XII _a_ 24; _doþ ȝour best_, doyour best, II 218; _do þi best_, get on as best you can, II 126; _madehymself to done_, set himself to work, VIII _a_ 104. (ii) To make, causeto, III 60, VI 196; _ded come_, fetched, I 176; _do deye_, kill, VIII_a_ 269; _dotȝ me drede_, makes me afraid, V 143; _do(n) to wyte_,_to vnderstande_, give (one) to understand, inform, II 2, VIII _a_ 56;followed by _infin._ (without expressed subj., as _did it wryte_, had itwritten), I _introd._, 218, VIII _a_ 79 (note), and (merging into mereauxil. as in Mn.E.) I 167, XVI 203, XVII 326, &c. (_cf._ Gar). (iii) Toput, I 219, VI 6; _dede on_ (_upon_), donned, II 343, XII _a_ 53; _donawei_, set aside, abolished, XI _b_ 206. (iv) _Refl._ in _dede him out_,went out, II 232, 474. (v) _Pp._ finished, I 68, XVII 139; at an end,XIV _a_ 24; past, over, II 76, VII 167, XVII 148; _haue done_, (get itdone), be quick, XVII 316, 352, 480. _I haue at do_, I have something todo, XVII 235 (_see_ At); _do way!_, enough!, II 226. [OE. _dōn_;_dyde_ (_dē̆de_, _dǣde_), pa. t.; _see_ Morsbach, ME. Gram., §130, _n._ 6.] _See_ Vndo.

1102.entry: #Doȝty#, #Doughty#, #Douhti#, _adj._ doughty, V 196, VII 84, XIV _c_106; as _sb._, V 266. [OE. _dohtig_.]

1106.entry: #Doyll#, _n._ dole, what is distributed in charity; _penny doyll_,masspenny, the offering for a mass for the soul of one dead, XVII 390.[OE. _(ge-)dāl_.] _See_ Dele(n).

1107.entry: #Doynge#, _n._; _d. awaye of_, putting away, IV _b_ 61; _doyngis_,affairs, XI _b_ 290. [OE. _dōung_.]

1108.entry: #Dold#, _adj._ stupid, XVII 266. [? Related (as _dulled_ to _dull_) toOE. _dol_.] _See_ Dull.

1109.entry: #Dole#, #Diol# (II), _n._ lamentation, grief, misery, II 198, VIII _a_114, XIV _b_ 10, XVI 347. [OFr. _dol_, _doel_, _deol_, _diol_, &c.]

1112.entry: #Dome#, _n._ judgement, XVI 319; doom, I 173; award, VI 220; _domes forte deme_, to converse, XV _b_ 30 (_see_ Deme). [OE. _dōm_.]

1120.entry: #Dote#, _v._ to talk folly, XVII 367. [Cf. MDu. _doten_; ? OFr._redoter_.]

1129.entry: #Dout(e)#, _n._ fear, I 147, XII _a_ 144, XIV _a_ 14; (fear of) danger,X 38. [OFr. _doute_.]

1130.entry: #Doute#, _v._ to fear, VII 114; #Dutte#, _pa. t. sg._ V 189. [OFr._douter_.]

1137.entry: #Draught#, _n._ (a move in chess), an artful trick, XVI 399 (_see_Drawe). [OE. _*dræht_, related to next.]

1138.entry: #Draw(e)#, _v. trans._ to draw, drag, pull, bring, &c., IV _b_ 19, IX124, X 82, XIII _a_ 33, XVI 319; to cart, VIII _a_ 283; _intr._ move,proceed, &c., XVII 245; #Drogh#, _pa. t. sg._ XV _a_ 12; #Drou#, XV _g_16; #Drouh#, #Drowh#, XII _a_ 155, _b_ 73, 124; #Droghe#, _pa. t. pl._VII 88; #Drew#, X 58; #Drawe#, _pp._ XII _b_ 90, XIII _a_ 35; #Drawyn#,X 124; #Ydrawe#, II 295. _Þou drawes to wittenesse_, thou citest, XVI279; _drawe vs no draught_, make no move against us, play us no trick (achess metaphor; cf. Chaucer, _Bk. Duchesse_, 682), XVI 399; _drouhymselue bi þe top_, tore his hair, XV _g_ 16; _drawe to_, _toward_,approach, XII _b_ 124, XIII _a_ 57; _draweth <to> colour lyke_, approachesthe colour of, IX 34 (note); _drawe after_, take after, resemble, XIII_b_ 6. [OE. _dragan_.] _See_ Vp-, With-drawe.

1141.entry: #Drede#, _n._ fear, I 147, 211, &c.; doubt (_cf._ Dredles), in _I puitȝou holly out of d._, I assure you, XIV _c_ 12; _ensample and dredeaȝens_, a fearful caution against, I 261; _for drede_, in fear, V190, XVII 212; in spite of their fear (of me), XVI 146. [From next.]

1142.entry: #Drede(n)#, #Dred#, _v. trans._ to fear, IV _b_ 85, V 287, XI _b_ 141,XVII 47, 55; _intr._ to be afraid, IV _a_ 31 (with _of_), 61, V 143;_refl._ to be afraid, XI _a_ 61, XII _b_ 67, 108 (_dradde him vnto_, wasafraid of). #Dradde#, _pa. t._ XII _b_ 67, 108; #Dredde#, I 145, XIV _c_30, 62; #Drad#, _pp._ XIV _c_ 19. [OE. _(on)-drēdan_, _-drǣdan_.]_See_ Adrad.

1145.entry: #Dregh#, #Dreȝ#, _adj._ heavy; tedious, IV _a_ 12; _adv._ heavily,forcibly, V 195. [ON. _drjúg-r_, older _*dreog-_.]

1149.entry: #Dremys#, _n. pl._ dreams, XI _b_ 73. [ON. _draum-r_, appar. identifiedin form with OE. _drēam_, noise, music; _see_ prec.]

1151.entry: #Dresse#, #Dres#, _v._ (to direct); to arrange, ordain, VI 135; to set(up), X 16; _I will dres me to_, I will get ready to, XVII 238. [OFr._dresser_.]

1154.entry: #Drink#, #Drynk(e)#, #Dryng#, _n._ drink, XV _e_ 14, 15; _esp._ in _meteand drink_, &c., _see_ Mete; _pl._ potions, VIII _a_ 269. [From next.]

1155.entry: #Drynke(n)#, _v._ to drink, IX 6, 256, &c.; drink strong drink, VIII _a_257; _fig._ pay the penalty, pay for it, XVII 380 (_or_ drown; but cf._N.E.D._, s.v. _Drink_ 16); #Drank#, _pa. t. pl._ I 158; #Dronken#,_pp._ in _ben lyghtly d._, easily get drunk, IX 14; #Ydronke#, VIII _a_274. [OE. _drincan_.]

1156.entry: #Dryue#, #Driue#; #Dryfe#, #Drife# (XVII), _v. trans._ to drive, VIII_a_ 128, 184, _b_ 19, XV _h_ 2, XVII 273; _intr._ to hasten, I 171, XVII193; _as þai miȝt driue_, as fast as they could go, II 141; #Dryuen#,_pp._ (_intr._) hurtled, V 195. [OE. _drīfan_.] _See_ To-dryue.

1164.entry: #Du#, #Dew#, _adj._ belonging; _was dew to_, belonged to, VII 61; _hordu nyghtis_, the nights belonging to them, VII 127; #Duly#, #Dewly#(XVI), _adv._ correctly, rightly, as is due, VII 60, 64, XVI 248. [OFr._deü_, _du_.]

1169.entry: #Dulle#, _v._ to make dull, stupefy, XII _introd._ [From prec.]

1170.entry: #Dure#, #Duyre#, _v._ to endure, last, remain, VIII _a_ 58, _b_ 25, XIII_a_ 3, XIV _c_ 4. [OFr. _durer_.]

1175.entry: #Dwelle(n)#, #Duell(e)#, _v._ to linger, tarry, XII _b_ 146; _to dwellein_, to dwell on, XI _b_ 130; to remain, abide, IV _a_ 90, IX 173, XII_b_ 172, XVI 304, &c.; to live, dwell, IX 10, 165, 288, &c. #Dwelling#,_n._ XIV _a_ 24. [OE. _dwellan_.]

1177.entry: #Eche#, _adj._ each, VIII _a_ 104, XI _b_ 6, 19, &c.; _eche a_, every,VIII _a_ 2, 189, 243; _pron._ each one, II 403, XI _b_ 47. [OE._ǣlc_.] _See_ Ich, Ilk, Vch.

1180.entry: #Eft(e)#, _adv._ afterwards, again, once more, thereupon, I 141, 143,229, 235, II 211, V 227, 320, XVII 241, 448. [OE. _eft_.]

1182.entry: #Eftsoneȝ#, _adv._ soon afterwards, straightway, V 349; #Eftsonis#, X4. [Prec. + adv. _-es_.]

1185.entry: #Eggyng#, _n._ incitement, IV _b_ 84. [From ON. _eggja_, to egg on.]

1187.entry: #Egle#, _n._ eagle, IX 247, 251; _egle hys_ for _egles_ (gen. sg.), XIII_a_ 22. [OFr. _aigle_, _egle_.]

1188.entry: #Eiȝe#, _n._ eye; _sg._ #Eye#, IX 304; #Ye#, I 149, 192; #Yȝe#, VI207; #Yhe#, XII _a_ 71; _pl._ #Een#, VII 57; #Eȝe#, XV _c_ 14;

1192.entry: #Eyleþ#, _3 sg. pres. ind._ ails, troubles, VIII _a_ 122, 254; #Alis#,XVII 294. [OE. _eglan_, to molest.]

1196.entry: #Elles#, #-eȝ#, #-is#, #Els# (XVII), #Ell# (IX), _adv._ otherwise,else, if not, VI 131, VIII _a_ 175, 227, IX 132, XI _b_ 25, 241, 246,XVI 305, &c.; pleonastic in apodosis to _bote_, _but if_, I _introd._,VIII _a_ 307; (any one) else, V 40; (introducing threat), or (else),XVII 299. [OE. _elles_.]

1202.entry: #Emperise#, _n._ empress, VI 81. [OFr. _emperesse_, with substitution offem. suffix _-ice_.]

1205.entry: #En#, _prep._ in Fr. phrase, _en exile_, in exile, II 493. [OFr. _en_.]

1210.entry: #Enchesone#, #Enchesun#, _n._ cause, occasion, I 202; _for þat enchesoneof_, on account of, I 43. [OFr. _acheso(u)n_, _encheso(u)n_, &c. For asimilar alteration, _see_ Endorde.] _See_ Chesouns.

1211.entry: #Enclose#, _v._ to shut up, enclose, IX 165, 168, 174, 227. [_en_ +Close; cf. _in cloos_, s.v. Cloos, _n._]

1213.entry: #Ende#, _n._ (i) end, limit I 95, 187, V 112, VII 98, &c.; _at þe ende_,on the end, XII _b_ 54; _sette an e. of_, put finishing touch to, XII_introd._; _withouten e._, for ever, XVI 300, 404; _the vttiremeste e.of all þi kynne_, the furthest point (to which one can go back) in yourancestry, XVI 232; _see_ Fer, Laste, Partener, Toune, Tweluemonth; (ii)borders, confines, IX 180; (iii) object, XII _a_ 21; _to þat e. þat_,&c., in order that, IX 111, 281; (iv) result, success; _[ben] triet inþe e._, turn out trustworthy, VII 17; _bryng to an e._, accomplish, IX169; _make an e._, bring it about, XII _a_ 48; _betre (wors) ende_,advantage, disadvantage, XIII _a_ 59, 60; (v) fate, death, VII 180;_make e. of_, destroy, XVII 104. [OE. _énde_.]

1214.entry: #Ende#, _v. trans._ to end, I 206; to complete, VII 4; _intr._ to cometo an end, VII 29; to continue to the end, XI _b_ 110. [OE. _éndian_.]

1215.entry: #Endyng#, _n._; _withowten e._, for ever, eternally, IV _a_ 96, IX 335.[OE. _endung_.]

1216.entry: #Endyte#, _v._ to suggest or dictate (the form of words to be said orsung), I 56. [OFr. _endit(i)er_.]

1219.entry: #Endorde#, _pp._ as _sb._ adored (one), VI 8. [OFr. _adorer_; confusionof prefix is probably English, but _cf._ Enchesone.]

1220.entry: #Endre#, _adj._ latter, just passed; _þis endre dai_, a day or two ago,XV _a_ 4, Introduction xii. [ON. _endr_ adv., formerly.]

1221.entry: #Enduir#, #-dure#, #Induyr#, _v._ to last, VII 39, XIV _c_ 36, XVII 148,283; to bear, have the strength (to), XIII _a_ 42; _endured in worldestronge_, suffered severely in the world (_or_ ? remained strong in thisworld), VI 116. [OFr. _endurer_.]

1234.entry: #Eny#, _adj._ any, III 5, VIII _a_ 251, XIII _a_ 48; _eny wyle_, anylength of time, VIII _b_ 25; _in eny weie_, by any means, XII _a_ 16;

1235.entry: #Enes cunnes#, XV _g_ 22, #Eny kyns#, VIII _b_ 20, of any kind, any kindof (OE. _*ǣniges cynnes_). [OE. _ǣnig_, Kt. _ēni(g)_.] _See_Ani, Ony.

1238.entry: #Enquestes#, _n. pl._ inquests (inquiries into matters of public orstate interest), VIII _b_ 59. [OFr. _enqueste_.]

1239.entry: #Ensa(u)mple#, _n._ example, instance, I 202, XI _b_ 298, 301;cautionary instance, warning, I 261 (_see_ Drede; _cf._ next). [AFr._ensample_ altered, by confusion of prefixes, from OFr. _essample_.]_See_ Sample.

1240.entry: #Ensamplen#, _v. refl._; _wherof [he] may ensamplen him_, from which hemay take warning, XII _b_ 223 (_cf._ prec.). [From prec.]

1242.entry: #Entent(e)#, _n._ purpose, VII 27; _to what e._, for what reason, XII_b_ 168; _to þat e. to_, _to þat e. and ende þat_, in order to, that, IX120, 280; mind, X 184; will, desire, IV _a_ 22; _with all thare e._,with their whole minds, XVII 113. [OFr. _entent_, _entente_.]

1244.entry: #Entyrludes#, _n. pl._ comic dramatic pieces, farces, I 5. [AFr._*entrelude_, Anglo-L. _interlūdium_.]

1246.entry: #Entre#, #Entere#, _v._ to enter, XVI 270, 282; _entered in Iudas_,inspired Judas, XVI 165. [OFr. _entrer_.]

1248.entry: #Enveremyt#, _pa. t._ surrounded, X 46. [OFr. _environner_; the forms_enverom-_ &c. first appear in English in 14th c.]

1250.entry: #Eorne#, _v._ to run; to flow, XIII _a_ 23, 37, 54, 62; #Yarn#, _pa. t.sg._ ran, III 43; #Ourn#, _pl._ II 85; #Vrn#, II 89. [OE. _éornan_; pa.t. _éarn_, _úrnon_.] _See_ Ryn.

1253.entry: #Erde#, _n._ dwelling-place, own land, VIII _a_ 194; in tag _in erde_(on earth, among men), V 348, it is perh. a form of Erth(e). [OE._éard_. The frequent ME. (Northern) form _erd(e)_, earth, may, in part,be due to this; but _cf._ Dede _n._^1]

1254.entry: #Er(e)#, #Eir# (X), _adv._ before, V 209, XII _b_ 113; ere now, XVII328; formerly, VI 12; earlier (with _befor_) X 140; _conj._ before(usually with _subj._), II 190, 256, V 152, 204, 223, XII _a_ 104, _b_19; _prep._ before (in time), VIII _a_ 140. [OE. _ǣr_.] _See_ Ar,Are, Or.

1255.entry: #Er(e)#, _pres. ind. pl._ are, I _introd._, IV _a_ 60, _b_ 8, 53, 54,XIV _a_ 6, 7, 12, 18, _b_ 85, &c. [ON. _eru_.] _See_ Ar(e), Es, &c.

1258.entry: #Erles#, #Erls#, _n. pl._ earls, II 202, 503, VII 84. [OE. _éorl_, infl.in sense by cognate ON. _jarl_.]

1259.entry: #Erliche#, _adv._ early, VIII _b_ 15; #Erly#, VI 146; _e. and late_, atall times, VI 32. [OE. _ǣr-līce_.] _See_ Er(e), Ar.

1260.entry: #Ernde#, _n._ the business (on which one has come), V 235. [OE._ǣrende_, message; ON. _erinde_, &c. message, business.]

1262.entry: #Errour#, _n._ error, falsehood, heretical opinion, VII 46, XI _b_ 44,77, 215; _speke errour_, say what is mistaken, VI 62. [OFr. _errour_.]

1264.entry: #Erth(e)#, #Eorþe# (XIII, XIV _c_), #Vrþe# (VI), _n._ earth, soil, IV_b_ 4, 12; the ground, IV _b_ 36, V 161, IX 149, XIII _a_ 8, 15; theworld, VI 82, XI _a_ 8, XVII 180; _in erth(e)_, on earth, in the world,IV _a_ 47, IX 332, XVI 363, XVII 42, &c.; _in eorþe_, XIV _c_ 110; _vponerthe_, V 30; _in erth_ (sc. _lufe in erth_), earthly (love), IV _a_ 10.[OE. _eorþe_, _éorþe_.] _See_ Erde.

1267.entry: #Es#, _3 sg. pres. ind._ is, I 7, *128 (note), IV _a_ 1, 5, 10, &c., _b_65, XIV _a_ 5, 20, _b_ 8, 9, XV _a_ 9. [A Northern form. ON. _es_.]_See_ Is, &c.

1269.entry: #Ese#, #Ays#, _n._ comfort, pleasure, in _him is ays_, gives himpleasure or comfort, II 239; _at ese_, comfortable, VIII _a_ 144; welloff, XVII 388. [OFr. _aise_, _eise_.] _See_ Malais, Missays.

1270.entry: #Esely#, #Esily#, _adv._ without discomfort, XII _b_ 91; easily, IX 119.[From ME. _esé_, OFr. _aisié_ (related to prec.).]

1271.entry: #Est(e)#, #Eest# (XVII), east; _adj._ IX 2; _adv._ XVI 333; _n._ IX 73,XIII _b_ 51, XVII 453. [OE. _ēast_, adv., _ēaste_, n.]

1272.entry: #Ete(n)#, _v._ to eat, VIII _a_ 129, 258, 298, IX 142, 242, XV _g_ 25,XVII 395 (_see_ Bred), &c.; #Eet#, _pa. t. sg._ VIII _a_ 291; #Ete#,_pa. t. pl._ I 158, II 396; #Eten#, _pp._ VIII _a_ 261, IX 144; #Etin#,XIV _b_ 74, 76, 77. [OE. _etan_.]

1275.entry: #Euen#, #Eve#, _n._ evening, III 54, VIII _a_ 178, XII _b_ 18, XVII 205;_see_ Morwe. [OE. _ǣfen_, _ēfen_.]

1276.entry: #Euen(e)#, #Euyn#, #Evin#, _adv._ equally, exactly, just, quite, indeed,I _introd._, VII 27, XII _b_ 49, XVII 125, 290, 379, 462, &c.; also,too, VII 51, 154; _evin (till)_, just opposite, X 81; _euene ryȝt_,exactly, XIII _a_ 47; _euen Hym by_, on a level with Him, XVII 18;_ful(l) euen_, equally, as well, quite, XVI 280, XVII 10, 344. [OE._efen_, _efne_.]

1280.entry: #Euer(e)#, _adv._ ever; always, continually, for ever, I 94, VII 2, VIII_a_ 271, _b_ 100, &c.; at any time, II 42, V 57, IX 327, &c.; added toindef. relatives (_q.v._), I 2, XVII 210, &c. [OE. _ǣfre_.]

1281.entry: #Euerich#, #Euerych(e)#, #Eueri#, _adj._ every, each, I 9, II 60, 517,580, IX 63, XIII _a_ 22, 26, &c.; _euerich a_, every, II 490, XVII 544.[OE. _ǣfre-ylc_.] _See_ Eche, Ich, &c.

1282.entry: #Euerichon#, _pron._ every one, II 189; #Euerilkone#, XVI 311 (inapposition to prec. noun). [Prec. + OE. _ān_.]

1283.entry: #Everydel#, _adv._ in every detail, XII _a_ 147. [Eueri + Dele, _q.v._]_See_ Somdel.

1284.entry: #Euermare#, #Euermore#, _adv._ (for) evermore, ever after, I 97, II 213,IV _a_ 20, VIII _a_ 236, XIV _b_ 64, &c.; now and always, VI 231. [OE._ǣfre_ + _māre_.] _See_ Mor(e).

1287.entry: #Evidence#, _n._ evidence, indication (of what is to come), XII _a_ 128.[OFr. _evidence_.]

1291.entry: #Excellent#, _adj._ surpassing, IX 270, 330; #Exellently#, _adv._;_exellently of alle þyse oþer_, conspicuously among all these others, V355. [OFr. _excellent_.]

1294.entry: #Expownd#, _v._ to expound; _I expownd_, it is my opinion, XVII 440.[OFr. _expondre_.]

1297.entry: #Fabill#, #Fable#, _n._ fable, fabulous tale, VI 232, VII 34, X_introd._ [OFr. _fable_.]

1298.entry: #Face#, _n._ face, V 303, &c.; _distrib. sg._ (_see_ Hert), XIII _a_ 33;_in His face_, to His face, openly, XI _b_ 179; _mannes face_, VIII _a_234 (note). [OFr. _face_.]

1299.entry: #Fader#, #Fadir#, #-yr#, #Uader# (III), _n._ father, I 122, II 29, III_introd._, VIII _b_ 37, IX 286, &c.; #Fadir#, _gen. sg._ XVI 79;

1304.entry: #Fai#, #Fay#, _n._ faith, XIV _c_ 7; in French formula _par ma fay_, bymy troth, VI 129. [OFr. _fei_.] _See_ Feith, Parfay.

1307.entry: #Fail(l)e#, #Fayl#, _v._ to fail, be wanting, VIII _a_ 320, XI _b_ 186,XIV _c_ 35, XVII 274, &c.; _faile (fayl) of_, to fail in, miss, XVI 157,XVII 492; #Fayled#, _2 sg. pa. t._ were at fault, V 288; #Failet#, _pl._in _f. hym_, he lacked, VII 175. [OFr. _faillir_.]

1308.entry: #Fayn(e)#, _adj._ glad, VI 33, 90, VIII _a_ 266, 295; _fayn I wold(that)_, I would be glad (if), XVII 526. [OE. _fægen_.]

1310.entry: #Fair(e)#, #Fayr(e)#, #Feyre# (I), #Uayre# (III), _adj._ fair,beautiful, I 63, II 70, XV _c_ 13, &c.; excellent, good, &c., I 260, III2, V 250, VI 130, XIII _a_ 30, &c.; seemly, I 80; as _sb._ in _þatfaire_, that fair being, IV _a_ 81; _fayre myght the befall_, may goodluck come to you, XVII 514; #Feyrest#, #Fairest#, #Farest#, _superl._ II53, XV _c_ 28, XVII 79, &c.; as _sb._ the fairest (season), VII 99. [OE._fæger_.]

1311.entry: #Faire#, #Fayre#, _adv._ fairly; courteously, VIII _a_ 25; well, V 161,XVII 255; deftly, V 241; properly (set out), VII 82. [OE. _fægre_.]

1313.entry: #Fairi#, #-y#, #Feyré#, #Faierie# (XII), _n._ faëry, fairyland, II 10(_the feyré_), II 283, 562; magic, II 193, 404, 492, XII _b_ 67. [OFr._faierie_.]

1316.entry: #Faitest#, _2 sg. pres._ beg under false pretences, VIII _b_ 30.[Back-formation from Faitour.]

1318.entry: #Faitour#, _n._ impostor; beggar, or idler, feigning disease or injury,VIII _a_ 115, 177; (as term of abuse), XVI 157, 209. [OFr. _faitour_.]

1321.entry: #Falle(n)#, #Fall#, _v._ to fall; #Fel#, #Fell(e)#, _pa. t. sg._ I 23,VII 25, XII _b_ 28, &c.; #Fyl#, I _introd._, 25, 28, 186; #Falled#, V175; #Fell(en)#, _pl._ VII 95, IX 149; #Fyl#, #Fillen#, I 194, II 15;

1322.entry: #Fal#, #Falle(n)#, _pp._ VII 93 (slain), XII _b_ 57, XVII 521, &c.; _falyn a swone_ (corrupt. of _fallyn aswone_; _see_ Aswone), I 195. To fall(down), I 194, II 327, &c.; _fel on slepe_, fell asleep, II 72; tohappen, turn out, come to pass, I 23, II 8, V 183, 310 (_see_ Foule),VII 25, XII _b_ 18, &c.; (with _dat. pron._) to happen to, befall, VII171, XII _b_ 28, 184; to fall to one's share, V 175, 259, VII 76; _hitfell hom of a foule ende_, an evil fate overtook them, VII 180; _as fellfor the wintur_, for winter, VII 124. _And my fry shal with me fall_, mychildren who will share my fate (? _or_ who I may happen to have) XVII66; #Fallyng#, _n._ VII 109. [OE. _fallan_.] _See_ Befalle.

1323.entry: #Fals(e)#, #Falce#, _adj._ false, lying, dishonest, V 314, VII 18, VIII_a_ 213, XI _a_ 11, XVII 35, 201, &c.; as _sb._ VII 41; #Falsly#, _adv._XI _b_ 81. [OE. _fals_, from L. _falsus_.]

1325.entry: #Falssyng#, _n._ breaking of faith (applied to the girdle as the cause;_cf._ Kest), V 310. [From ME. _fals(i)en_; cf. OFr. _falser_.]

1326.entry: #Fame#, _n._ rumour, tale, XII _b_ 189; _of good f._, of good repute,XVII 141. [OFr. _fame_.]

1332.entry: #Fare#, _n._ behaviour, practices, V 318, XVI 158; _his feynit fare þathe fore with_, the deceit he practised, VII 44. [OE. _faru_.] _See_Wel-fare.

1333.entry: #Fare#, #Fayre# (XVII), _v._ to go, fare, behave, II 604, XVII 190, 255,415; _fare by_, _to_, _wiþ_, behave towards, treat, I 256, VI 107, XIV_c_ 95; _fareȝ well_, &c., farewell, V 81, XVII 238; #Fore#, _pa. t._VII 93; _fore with_, practised, VII 44; dealt with, VII 176; #Faren#,_pp._ departed, gone (by), VII 29, VIII _a_ 99. [OE. _faran_.] _See_Ferde, _pa. t._

1337.entry: #Fast(e)#, _adv._ securely, I 101, II 94, IX 173, XII _b_ 30, &c.; asintensive adv. varying with context, II 118, V 335, VIII _a_ 102, XI _b_187, XII _b_ 69, XVI 107, XVII 488, &c.; quickly, V 147, XI _b_ 274, XII_b_ 104, &c.; _fast by_, hard by, XIII _a_ 50. [OE. _fæste_.]

1343.entry: #Fautlest#, _adj. superl._ in _on þe f._, the (one) most faultless, V295. [Error for, or red. of, _fautlesest_; OFr. _faute_ + OE._-lēas_.]

1347.entry: #Feaw#, #Few(e)#, _adj. pl._ few, VI 212, VII 52, XIII _b_ 50, XV _a_19, &c. [OE. _fēawe_.] _See_ Fone.

1348.entry: #Fecche#, _v._ to fetch, VIII _a_ 150; #Fette(n)#, _pa. t._ VIII _a_287, XII _b_ 150, XVI 382; #Yfet#, _pp._ II 170. [OE. _fetian_,_feccan_.]

1349.entry: #Fede#, _v._ to feed, VIII _a_ 247, XI _b_ 281; #Fedde#, _pa. t._ VIII_a_ 292, XI _b_ 278, &c.; #Uedde#, _subj._ would feed, III 8; #Fedde#,_pp._ IV _b_ 39. [OE. _fēdan_.]

1350.entry: #Fedynge#, _n._ feeding; _in f. of_, for feeding, XI _b_ 258. [OE._fēding_.]

1352.entry: #Fee#, _n._^2 fee (as a term of venery, the share given to the dog,falcon, &c.); some small gain in their hunting, XVII 490. [OFr. _feu_,_fe_, &c.]

1358.entry: #Feyne(n)#, #Fayne# (VII), _v._ to feign, pretend, invent, VII 41, XI_b_ 1, 81, &c.; _feyned hem_, pretended to be, VIII _a_ 115; to falsify,VII 34; #Feynit#, _pp._ false, VII 18; _feynit fare_, deceit, VII 44.[OFr. _feindre_, _feign-_.]

1360.entry: #Feith#, #Fayth#, #Fath# (XVII), &c., _n._ faith, XI _b_ 13, 171, XVI364, &c.; plighted word, troth, V 216; _bi my feith_, _in (god) fayth_,&c., upon my word, V 297, VIII _a_ 266, XVII 228, 330, &c. [OFr. _feid_,later _fei_.] _See_ Fai.

1361.entry: #Feythful#, _adj._ honest, VIII _a_ 247; #Feithfulliche#, _adv._honestly, VIII _a_ 71; #Faithfully#, accurately, VII 78. [Prec. + OE._-ful_.]

1363.entry: #Felaȝschip#, #Felaschipe# (XII), #Felaushepe# (I), #Felowship#(XVII), _n._ community, I _introd._; company, in _bere_, _don f._ (with_dat. pron._), keep (one) company, V 83, XII _a_ 24; friendship, XVII363. [Next + OE. _-scipe_.]

1364.entry: #Felawe#, #Felowe#, _n._ fellow, I _introd._, XIV _d_ 7, 16;(contemptuous), XVI 284. [OE. _fēo-laga_, from ON. _fé-lagi_.]

1365.entry: #Feld(e)#, #Filde#, #Fylde#, _n._ field, II 60, VIII _a_ 134, 232; fieldof battle, VII 45, 93; #Feeldes#, _pl._ XIII _a_ 19. [OE. _féld_.] _See_Afelde.

1366.entry: #Fele#, #Feele# (XVI), #Feill# (X), #Uele# (III), _adj._ many, II 401,522, III 2, V 349, VI 79, VII 29, X 55, 63, 141, XV _b_ 10, XVI 61, &c.[OE. _fela_, adv.]

1367.entry: #Fele#, #Feele#, _v._ to feel, perceive, experience, IV _a_ 25, _b_ 45,V 125, XIII _a_ 26, XVI 346 (_see_ Fitte), XVII 121, &c.; _2 sg. subj._V 204; #Felte#, _pa. t._ I 156, 163. [OE. _fēlan_.]

1370.entry: #Fell(e)#, _adj._ deadly, cruel, V 154, VI 7, VII 82, 109, XIV _b_ 33;

1374.entry: #Fend(e)#, _n._ devil, Devil, V 125, VIII _a_ 82, IX 93, XI _b_ 3, 220,XVI 340, &c.; #Feende#, XVI 9, 14, &c.; #Feynd#, XVII 35, 43. [OE._fēond_.]

1378.entry: #Fer#, #Ferre#, #Far#, _adj._ and _adv._ far, IV _b_ 36, V 24, XIII _a_27, XV _g_ 5, XVII 439, &c.; _as fer as_, in so far as, IX 293; _(vn)tothe fer(re) ende_, to the very end, VII 78, 95. #Fer(re)#, #Fyrre# (V,VI), _compar._ farther, V 83, XIV _b_ 18; away, XVI 156, 336; further,VII 97; moreover, V 53, VI 184; _fyrre þen_, beyond, VI 203. [OE._feorr_; _feorr_, _firr_ compar.] _See_ Ferforth, Fyrþer.

1379.entry: #Ferde#, _n._ fear, in _for ferde_, in fear, V 62, 204, XVII 315. [Prob.false division of _for-fer(e)d_, pp., terrified; OE. _*for-fǣran_,_-fēran_.] _See_ next.

1380.entry: #Ferd(e)#, _pp._ afraid, V 314, XIV _b_ 93, XVII 102; at XVI 209 rimerequires _flaide_ (_see_ Flay and note). [OE. _fǣran_, _fēran_.]

1381.entry: #Ferd(e)#, _pa. t._ fared, XII _a_ 43, 145; _ferd with_, dealt with, X172. [OE. _fēran_.] _See_ Fare, _v._

1383.entry: #Fere#, #Feere#, _n._^2 company, in _in fere_, &c., all together,collectively, XVI 126, 364, 385. [OE. _ge-fēre_; but this use isprob. partly developed from ME. _y-fere(n)_, OE. _ge-fēran_, pl.,(as) companions.] _See_ Yfere.

1386.entry: #Fere-flunderys#, _n. pl._ fiery sparks, XV _h_ 12. [_See_ Fyr; _cf._Mn.E. and dial. _flinders_, splinters.]

1389.entry: #Ferly#, _adj._ wonderful, II 4 (note); _adv._ wondrously, extremely, I145, XV _b_ 10. [OE. _fǣr-līce_, suddenly, prob. infl. by ON._ferliga_ monstrously; _see_ next.]

1390.entry: #Ferly#, _n._ a marvel, V 346, X 134; #Farleis#, #Ferlies#, _pl._ VII95, XVI 61. [OE. _fǣr-lic_, sudden, prob. infl. by ON. _ferlíki_ (ME._ferlike_) monster.] _See_ prec.

1392.entry: #Ferryit#, _pp._; _f. wes_, had farrowed, X 109. [Formed on _farrow_,_ferry_; OE. _færh_, _ferh_, young pig.]

1393.entry: #Fers(e)#, _adj._ fierce, bold, II 293, XIV _b_ 33, XVI 131. [OFr._fer-s_, nom. sg.] _See_ Fuersly.

1396.entry: #Feruent#, _adj._ hot, IX 10; burning bright, XVII 8; eager, XVII 77.[OFr. _fervent_.]

1397.entry: #Fest#, #Feest# (XVII), _n._ feast, festival, V 333, XVII 454 (? withtopical allusion to the Corpus Christi festivities). [OFr. _feste_.]

1399.entry: #Fest(e)#, _v._ make fast, confirm, XVI 340; _pa. t._ V 279; _pp._fixed, made fast, IV _a_ 1, 82, XVI 335, 337. [OE. _fæstan_; on thevowel _see_ Cast.]

1409.entry: #Fight#, #Fyght(e)#, #Fiȝte#, _v._ to fight, IV _b_ 26, VIII _a_ 36,XVI 131, &c.; #Ficht#, X 66; #Fiste#, XV _g_ 31 (_see_ Appendix, p.278); _fyght with_, oppose, XVII 138; #Faght#, _pa. t. sg._ XVI _b_ 48;

1410.entry: #Foght#, _pl._ VII 45; #Feghtande#, _pres. p._ in _are f._, fight, IV_b_ 18; #Yfouȝte#, _pp._ VIII _a_ 146. [OE. _fe(o)htan_.]

1413.entry: #Fyked#, _pa. t. sg._ flinched, V 206. [OE. _*fician_; cf. _be-fician_,and next.]

1418.entry: #Fyled#, _pp._ sharpened, V 157. [OE. _fīlian_, to file; or OFr._afiler_.] _See_ Fylor.

1421.entry: #Fille#, _n._ chervil (_see_ Cheruelles), _or_ wild-thyme, XV _b_ 18.[OE. _fille_; in glosses _fil_, _cerfille_ = _cerpillum_ (i.e._serpyllum_ thyme, but perhaps confused with _chærephyllum_, chervil).]

1427.entry: #Fynde(n)#, #Finde#, #Fynd#, _v._ to find, discover, II 1, 256(_subj._), VI 148, VII 82, IX 75, XIII _a_ 17, XVI 6, XVII 330, &c.; toget, XII _a_ 17, XVI 288; to invent, devise, II 4, 14, XI _b_ 137; toprovide for, VIII _b_ 80; to provide one with (as _fynden hem tode_),VIII _a_ 71, _b_ 21, 27, 51, 92; _founden me to scole_, provided themeans to put me to school, VIII _b_ 37; _founden with_, provided with,XI _b_ 140. #Fint#, #Fynt#, _3 sg. pres._ (OWS. _fint_) II 239, VIII _b_92; #Fand#, _pa. t. sg._ X 182, 186; #Fond(e)#, I 37, II 426, VIII _b_41, XII _a_ 59, XV _a_ 13, &c.; #Founde#, II 537, 569 (_subj._);

1428.entry: #Fande#, _pl._ XVI 62; #Found#, #Founde(n)#, II 309, VII 172, VIII _b_37; #Fon#, _pp._ XVII 503; #Fonden#, IV _a_ 63; #Founde(n)#, I 229, VII66, XI _b_ 140, &c.; #Fun#, XIV _b_ 93; #Funden#, XIV _b_ 47, 50;

1431.entry: #Fine#, _adv._ extremely, very, II 94. [Cf. Afine, Fyn; _see_ Zupitza,(15th c.) _Guy of Warwick_, l. 9086 (note).]

1435.entry: #Fyr(e)#, #Fire#, #Fuyr#, _n._ fire, II 398, IV _a_ 6, XII _a_ 69, XIII_a_ 3, 4, &c.; #Fere#, in _fere-flunderys_ (q.v.), XV _h_ 12. [OE._fȳr_ (Kt. _fēr_).]

1436.entry: #Firmament#, _n._ firmament, heavens, VII 124, 134, XVII 7, 422.[(Christian) L. _firmāmentum_; first appears in E. _c._ 1050.]

1439.entry: #Fyrþer#, _adv._ further, I 255. [OE. _furþor_, ? infl. by _firr_.]_See_ Fer, Forþer.

1442.entry: #Fitte#, _n._; _fele þi fitte_, undergo your turn of woe, XVI 346. [ME._fit_, terrible or violent experience, &c.; ? OE. (once) _fitt_,contest.]

1443.entry: #Fyue#; #Uif#, #Vif#, #Vyf# (III); _adj._ five, III 22, 23, 27, V 125,VI 91 (_see_ Þo, _adv._), VIII _a_ 319, XIII _b_ 32, &c. [OE. _fīf_.]

1444.entry: #Flaggatis#, _n. pl._ fagots, X 23, 25, 27. [? Alteration of Faggatis,_q.v._; another reading is _fagaldis_.]

1446.entry: #Flay#, _v._ to put to flight; terrify, XVII 380; #Flaide#, _pp._ *XVI209 (required by rime; MS. ferde). [OE. _flēgan_.]

1448.entry: #Flapten#, _pa. t. pl._ lashed, laid on, VIII _a_ 178. [Cf. Du., G.,_flappen_.]

1452.entry: #Fle(n)#, _v._ to flee, V 57, 62, XV _i_ 16, XVII 292, 296; #Fles#, _2sg. pres._ V 204; #Flese#, _pres. pl._ IV _b_ 86; #Fleth#, _imper. pl._XIV _d_ 14; #Flaȝ(e)#, _pa. t. sg._ V 206, 208 (second); #Fley#, XI_b_ 273; #Flowen#, _pl._ VIII _a_ 177; #Fled#, _pa. t._ and _pp._ XIV_b_ 48, 51, 80. [OE. _flēon_, str.] _See_ Flye.

1455.entry: #Flemmynges#, _n. pl._ Flemings, people from Flanders, XIII _b_ 7. [OE._*flǣming_; cf. ON. _flǽming-r_, MDu. _vlāming_.]

1457.entry: #Flesch(e)#, #Flessche#, #Flessh(e)#, _n._ flesh, meat, I 129 (note), V245, VIII _a_ 18, 150, 305, IX 141; _flesshe or bone_, a limb, I 197.[OE. _flǣ̆sc_.]

1460.entry: #Flete#, _v._ to float; #Flietende#, _pres. p._ XII _a_ 157; #Flett#,_pp._ XVII 436. [OE. _flēotan_, str.]

1464.entry: #Flye#, #Flyghe#, #Flee# (IV), _v._ to fly, I 193, IV _b_ 4, 30, 38, 41,&c.; #Flaȝ#, _pa. t. sg._ V 208 (first); #Flaw#, X 92; #Fleȝe#,was, VI 71 (note); #Fle(e)ynge#, _pres. p._ IX 148, 252; #Flone#, _pp._XVII 487. [OE. _flē(o)gan_.] _See_ Fle(n).

1465.entry: #Flyeghynge#, #Flyghyng(e)#, _n._ flying; _of gude (ill) fl._, strong(weak) in flight, IV _b_ 34, 35, 38. [From prec.]

1470.entry: #Flood(e)#, #Flod(e)#, _n._ flood, water, stream, V 105, VII 160, XII_a_ 166, XVI 76; (in pl.) waters, waves, VII 123, 142, 171; floods, VII109, VIII _a_ 320, XVII 101, &c. [OE. _flōd_.]

1477.entry: #Fode#, #Foode#, _n._ food, VII 175, VIII _a_ 21, 71, 200, 264, XVI 10(_see_ Frute), &c. [OE. _fōda_.] _See_ Fede.

1482.entry: #Folde#, _v._ to fold; enfold, XV _f_ 9, 10; #Folde#, _pp._ (? or _pa.t._) in _folde vp_, ? covered with her hands, _or_ upturned, VI 74. [OE._fáldan_.]

1489.entry: #Folwen#, _v._ to accompany, VIII _a_ 2; #Folȝed#, _pa. t._ V 354(_see_ note). [OE. _folgian_.]

1493.entry: #Fonde#, _v._ to endeavour, seek (to), VIII _a_ 213, XII _a_ 183, XII_b_ 171, XIII _b_ 24; #Fondet#, _pa. t._ V 57. [OE. _fándian_,_fóndian_.]

1494.entry: #Fone#, #Fune#, _adj._ and _pron._ few, XIV _a_ 28, 29, XVII 99. [ME.also _fo_; ? obscurely rel. to Feaw, _q.v._]

1495.entry: #Fonge#, _v._ to get, take, VI 79, 119; #Fang#, XVII 245. [OE. _fōn_,_ge-fángen_; cf. ON. _fanga_.] _See_ Onderuonge.

1498.entry: #Foo#, _n._ foe, XIV _d_ 12; #Fo#, II 112, VIII _b_ 60; _frende norfoo_, nobody, XVI 287; _ichon other fo_, each hostile to the other,every man against his neighbour, XVII 112; #Fais#, _pl._ X 55, 65, 197,

1501.entry: #For#, _conj._ for, I 109, XVII 231, &c.; #Uor#, III 6, 8, &c.; because,V 300, VII 178, VIII _a_ 235, 237, XIII _b_ 16, XVI 258, 295; so that,XII _a_ 93, 194, XVI 251; _for that_, so that, XII _b_ 133. [OE. _forþam (þe)_, for, because; _for þȳ þæt_, so that.] _See_ Forþi.

1502.entry: #For#; #Uor#, #Vor# (III); _prep._ for (i) _Cause_: because of, onaccount of, through, I 134, II 32, III 17, IV _b_ 35, V 279, VII 183, IX130, X 136, XI _a_ 32, _b_ 28, 256, XV _b_ 24, &c.; _for of_ (OFr. _depar_) for sake of, XV _d_ 5; _for why (whi)?_ and why?, XVII 14, 284,518; for (fear of), V 57, 199, XVII 102, &c.; (as precaution) against,VIII _a_ 9, 62, 87, 209, 306, XIV _a_ 36, XV _h_ 12. (ii) _Indir.object_: for (benefit of), III _introd._, VIII _a_ 278, &c.; for sake,on behalf, of, I 90, III 40, IV _a_ 88, &c. (iii) _Dir. object_: for(purpose of), with a view to, to get, &c., IV _a_ 69, VII 32, 88, VIII_a_ 230, X 41, XI _b_ 126, 182, 235, XVI 220, &c.; _for (uor) to_, _forte_, in order to, so as to, I 81, II 568, III _introd._, 44, XV _b_ 30,_c_ 18, &c.; _for till_, X 149, 169; as equiv. of _for_ with vbl. sb., X8, 33, 105; merely equiv. of _to_, _till_, I 21, II 37, X 143, &c. (iv)_Equivalence_: in favour of, VII 13, XI _b_ 215; (in exchange, return,&c.) for, IV _a_ 42, V 284, VIII _b_ 76, IX 190, XI _b_ 162, XV _g_ 20,&c.; as result of, IX 201; for, as, VII 49, 50, VIII _a_ 206, XII _a_180, XIV _c_ 92, &c. (v) _Reference_: with regard to, III 9, &c.; _forthe_, for all you care, XVII 193; in spite of, II 571, V 64, XIV _a_ 24,XVI 146; _for all(e)_, despite (all), I 73, 86, XIV _b_ 23, XVI 158.(vi) _Time_: during, VI 226, VIII _a_ 236, &c. _See_ Maystrie, Nones,Soþe; Þar(e), Þere(fore), &c. [OE. _for(e)_.]

1503.entry: #Forbede#, _v._ to forbid, VI 19; _forbede þat_ (with neg.), forbid to,I 78; #Forbodyn#, _pp._ I 7. [OE. _for-bēodan_.] _See_ Bede, _v._

1509.entry: #Forest#, _n._ forest; wild, unenclosed, and partly wooded, land, II160, 246. [OFr. _forest_.]

1511.entry: #Forfete#, _v._ to transgress, V 326; #Forfette#, _pa. t._ XVI 352.[From OFr. _forfait_, _-fet_, n.]

1513.entry: #Forgete#, _v._ to forget, IV _a_ 79; #Forgetynge#, _n._ IV _b_ 68. [OE._for-_ + ON. _geta_; cf. OE. _forgetan_.] _See_ Gete, Forȝete.

1514.entry: #Forgon#, _v._ to give up, XV _b_ 35; #Forgoo#, V 142; #Forgaa#, IV _b_31. [OE. _for-gān_.]

1515.entry: #Forȝ#, _n._ force, waterfall, V 105 (the earliest recorded instancein E.). [ON. _fors_.]

1517.entry: #Forȝete#, _v._ to forget, XI _b_ 157; #Forȝete#, _pp._ XII _b_202, XIV _c_ 8, &c. [OE. _for-getan_.] _See_ Forgete, Vnderȝete.

1520.entry: #Forlorn#, (_pp._) _adj._ ruined, in pitiful plight, I 136, II 127. [OE._for-loren_, pp.] _See_ Lese, _v._^1

1527.entry: #Forschreynt#, _pp._ withered (by fire), II 398. [OE. _for-screncan_,oppress, rel. to _forscrincan_, wither.]

1531.entry: #Fortune#, _n._; _by (be) f._ by chance, VII 99, 180, IX 207; by goodfortune, VII 171. [OFr. _fortune_.]

1549.entry: #Fowe#, _adj._ streaked or variegated (fur), vair, in _fowe and griis_(partial transl. of ME., OFr. _vair & gris_), II 241. [OE. _fāg_.]

1551.entry: #Fowre#, #Four(e)#, _adj._ four, I 232, V 33, 157, XIII _a_ 37, &c. [OE._fēower_.] _See_ Feurþe, Fourty.

1599.entry: #Fulfille(n)#, #Fulfylle#, _v._ to fill, IX 331, XII _introd._; tofulfil, finish, perform, accomplish, IV _b_ 15, 73, VIII _a_ 36, 319, IX317, XI _b_ 86, 88, XVI 6, &c.; #Uolueld#, _pp._ III _introd._ [OE._fulfyllan_ (Kt. _-fellan_).]

1610.entry: #Gadre#, _v._ to gather, pick up, assemble, XII _b_ 22, 113, 117;

1637.entry: #Gere#, #Geir# (X), _n. sg._ tools, apparatus, necessary things, X 110,XVII 245, 316, 326; arms, XVI 211; contrivance (the ark), XVII 274;affair, business, V 137. [ON. _gervi_.]

1638.entry: #Gered#, _pp._ attired, V 159. [From prec. in frequent sense 'apparel'.]

1646.entry: #Get#, _v._^2 to guard; _get for_, look out for, XIV _a_ 36. [ON._gǽta_.]

1655.entry: #Gill#, _woman's name_, Jill, XVII 219; _for Iak nor for Gill_, fornobody, XVII 336. [Shortened from _Gillian_, OFr. _Juliane_.]

1656.entry: #Gylofres#, _n. pl._ in _clowe gylofres_, cloves, IX 157. [OFr._gilofre_.] _See_ Clowe.

1659.entry: #Gynour#, _n._ engineer (contriver of machines), X 98, 126. [Shortenedfrom OFr. _engigneor_.] _See_ Gyn(e), Engynour.

1666.entry: #Glad(e)#, _v._ to make glad, VIII _a_ 113, XVII 491; #Gladde#, IV _a_49. [OE. _gladian_.]

1667.entry: #Gladde#, #Glad(e)# (_of_), _adj._ happy, glad (at), II 583, XII_introd._, XVI 42, 241, &c.; #Gladly#, _adv._ XII _b_ 37; _berengladly_, are glad to wear, IX 109. [OE. _glæd_, _glæd-līce_.]

1673.entry: #Glyfte# (_on_), _pa. t._ glanced sideways (at), V 197. [Obscure; ME._gliffen_, and _gliften_, with same senses as Blenk, _q.v._]

1674.entry: #Glode#, _n._ ? glade, open space, V 113; _on glode_, appar. a variantof _on bent_ (q.v.), on earth, where he stood, V 198. [Unknown.]

1680.entry: #Gnauen#, _v._ to gnaw, grind the teeth, XV _h_ 9. [OE. _gnagan_.]

1682.entry: #Gotȝ#, VI 150; #Goþ#, XIII _b_ 64, 65; _subj._ #Go#, VI 170, XVI156; _imper. pl._ #Gos#, VI 161; #Gotȝ#, V 51, 175; _pp._ #Gane#, X84, 100, &c.; #Go#, I 222, II 196; #Gon(e)#, I 161, II 492 (ago), VI 16,XVII 408 (done for), &c.; #Ygo#, II 349, 541 (ago); #Goande#, _pres. p._V 146. To walk, V 146, IX 18, XIV _a_ 25; _in him com ... gon_ (OE._cōm inn gān_), came walking in, XV _g_ 24; to be (alive), V 41;_gon on bodi and bones_, _see_ Bodi; to go, II 190, 345, XV _g_ 12, &c.;_gon (be)_, travel (about), IX 112; _go hunte_, &c., go and hunt, &c.,VIII _a_ 30, 32; _go slepe_, go to sleep, VIII _a_ 296; _hadde go_, hadgone on, I 222; _hou it geþ_, what is the (inevitable) course of things,II 551; _is go(n)_, &c., went, II 196, X 176, XII _b_ 176; _war tharingane_, were in it, X 128; to come, get, IX 164, 186, &c.; _gotȝ(goth) out_, issues, VI 5, IX 178. [OE. _gān_.] _See_ Ȝede.

1684.entry: #God#, _n._ God, I 89, V 81, VI 241, &c.; #Godd(e)#, I 78, V 51, 137,&c.; #Godys# (MS. God; _see_ XVII 88, note), _gen. sg._ XVI 241;

1685.entry: #Godes#, #Goddes#, _pl._ gods, II 31, VII 45, 176, 181, &c.; _gef hymGod and goud day_, wished him Godspeed and good day, V 5. [OE. _god_.]_See_ Goddes.

1686.entry: #God(e)#, _adj._ good, I 9, II 35, V 281, &c.; #Good(e)#, VIII _b_ 71,XI _b_ 121, &c.; #Goud(e)#, V 50, 202, VI 208; #Gud(e)#, IV _b_ 15, X47, XIV _a_ 14, &c.; #Guod#, III 59 (_guode_, wk., III 30, 31, &c.);_goud day_, _see_ God. [OE. _gōd_.]

1687.entry: #God(e)#, #Good(e)#, #Guode# (III), #Gude# (IV, XIV _b_), _n. sg._ good,IV _b_ 9, V 59, XII _a_ 149; good thing, II 230; _collective_, goods,wealth, III 8 (_dat._), IV _b_ 81, VIII _a_ 225, XII _b_ 35, XIV _c_ 75,&c.; #Godes# (and forms as above) _pl._, goods, III 1, VII 122, VIII _a_218, XI _b_ 272, XII _b_ 48, XIV _b_ 11, &c. [OE. _gōd_, n.]

1690.entry: #Godhede#, _n._ divinity, VI 53, XI _b_ 280, XVI 249. [OE. _god_ +_*-hǣdu_; cf. OE. _god-hād_.]

1692.entry: #Goyng#, _n._; _for goyng_, as a result of moving about, I 157. [From_Go(n)_.]

1694.entry: #Golde-hemmed#, _adj._ bordered with gold, V 327. [Prec. and OE. _hemm_,border.]

1699.entry: #Gore#, _n._ triangular strip (of cloth), gore; by synecdoche for'gown', in _under gore_, in gown (among women, alive), XV _c_ 35. [OE._gāra_.]

1701.entry: #Goshauk#, _n._ goshawk (usually a large short-winged hawk), XII _a_ 9.[OE. _gōs-hafoc_.]

1702.entry: #Gost#, _n._ spirit, soul, V 182; #Haly Gast(e)#, #Hooly Gost(e)#, &c.,Holy Ghost, IV _b_ 53, IX 331, XI _a_ 11, XVI 77, XVII 162, &c. [OE._gāst_.]

1710.entry: #Gowtes#, _n. pl._; _gowtes artetykes_, attacks of arthritic gout, IX314. [OFr. _goute_.] _See_ Artetyke.

1711.entry: #Grace#, _n._ favour, IX 296, XIV _b_ 46, &c.; consideration, VIII _a_117; grace, mercy (of God), I 186, VI 76, 252, VIII _a_ 120, _b_ 106, XV_i_ 8, XVII 551, &c.; personified in our Lord, VI 65; what God may send,XVII 334; favour of fortune, luck, VII 76, VIII _b_ 102, XII _b_ 169,186; lot, II 547. [OFr. _grace_.]

1715.entry: #Graielis#, _n. pl._ books containing the 'gradual' (part of the Mass),XI _b_ 229 (_see_ note). [OFr. _graël_.]

1717.entry: #Grayþed#, _pa. t._; _grayþed hym_, got ready, V 191; #Grathed#, _pp._made ready, XVI 211 (rime requires Graide). [ON. _greiða_.]

1718.entry: #Grayþely#, #Grathely# (XVI), #Graidly# (VII), _adv._ readily; ready, V224; aptly, VI 139; carefully, VII 54; directly, XVI 92. [ON._greið-liga_.] _See_ prec., and Grath.

1720.entry: #Gramer(e)#, _n._ grammar, XIII _b_ 36; _mayster of gr._, (title of) alicensed teacher of grammar, XIII _b_ 28. [OFr. _gramaire_.]

1722.entry: #Grant merci#, gramercy, thank you (_lit._ great thanks), V 58, XII _b_92. [OFr.]

1725.entry: #Grath#, _n._ readiness, in _with grath_, promptly, XVII 482. [ON._greiði_.] _See_ Grayþed, &c.

1727.entry: #Graunt(e)#, #Grante#, _v._ to consent, I 51; to grant, VII 3, VIII _a_326, XIV _b_ 46, XV _i_ 8, XVII 178, &c.; (with _infin._) I 199, II 604.[OFr. _graanter_, AFr. _graunter_.]

1730.entry: #Grede#, _v._ to cry out, II 104; #Gradde#, _pa. t._ XII _b_ 68. [OE._grǣdan_.]

1734.entry: #Grem(e)#, #Gremy# (VII), _n._ anger; resentment, VI 105; mortification,V 302; cause for anger, harm, V 183; _with greme_ (_gremy_), wrathfully,V 231, VII 176. [ON. _gremi_; OE. _gremian_, v.] _See_ Grame.

1735.entry: #Grene#, #Greyn# (XVII), _adj._ green, II 353, V 35, VIII _a_ 276, &c.;_n._ green, V 123, 159, 191, 227; green sward, II 72; earth, XVII 534.[OE. _grēne_.]

1737.entry: #Gret(e)#, #Greate# (III), _adj._ great, large, I 22, 210, II 101, 240,III 9, 17, &c.; greatly esteemed, VII 40; big, boastful, XVII 379; _manygrete_, many important people, XI _b_ 207; _smale and grete_, _grete andsmall_, all, XIV _c_ 22, XVII 90, 344; #Grettere#, _compar._ IX 70, 91;

1740.entry: #Grete#, _v._^2 to weep, V 89; #Grette#, _pa. t._ IV _a_ 87. [OE._grētan_ (_*grǣtan_), or _grēotan_.]

1744.entry: #Greue#, _v._ to grieve, offend, VI 111, VIII _a_ 225, XV _f_ 3;oppress, VIII _a_ 313; injure, VIII _b_ 60; _greueth hym aȝeines_,voices a grievance against, VIII _a_ 311; #Greuyng#, _n._ offending,insulting, VII 181. [OFr. _grever_.]

1747.entry: #Gryed#, _pa. t._ sorrowed (inwardly), V 302. [Not known; _cf._ XI Painsof Hell (OE. Miscell.) l. 160, _gryd and wept_.]

1751.entry: #Gryndel#, _adj._ wrathful, V 270; #Gryndelly#, _adv._ wrathfully, V231. [? Back-formation from _*grindlaik_ (_gryndellayk_ Sir Gaw. 312),ON. _grimmd_ + _leik-r_; cf. ON. _grimm-leikr_.]

1755.entry: #Gryste#, _n._ resentment (? _lit._ grinding of the teeth), VI 105. [OE._grist_, grinding.]

1757.entry: #Gron(e)#, _v._ to lament, complain, V 89, XVII 409; groan, VIII _a_255, XV _h_ 9. [OE. _grānian_.]

1758.entry: #Gronyngys#, _n. pl._ lamentations (as a sign of repentance), XI _b_ 99.[OE. _grānung_.]

1759.entry: #Grot#, _n._ small bit; _euerich a grot_, every detail, II 490. [OE._grot_.]

1760.entry: #Ground(e)#, #Grownd# (XVII), _n._ ground, XII _a_ 80, &c.; bottom, XII_b_ 71; bottom of the sea, XVII 439, 462; deep pool, XIII _a_ 52; land,XVII 465; foundation, cause, VI 12, 24, 36, 48, 60, VII 80; _(vp)ongrounde_, on earth, V 82, VIII _a_ 225; _to grounde_, on the ground, II549, VI 74. [OE. _grúnd_.]

1761.entry: #Grounde#, _v._ in _nouȝt groundiþ hem_, they have no foundation, XI_a_ 4; _groundid (in)_, based (on), XI _b_ 52; _ben not gr. in God_,have no divine sanction, XI _a_ 62. [From prec.]

1764.entry: #Growe(n)#, #Grufe#, _v._ to grow, VIII _a_ 113, IX 33, 53, XII _a_ 80,&c.; to come into being, in _begynnys to grufe to vs_, is about to beginfor us, XVII 463; #Grew(e)#, _pa. t._ I 164, 236, VI 65, VII 80;

1765.entry: #Growe#, _pp._ II 266, XIV _c_ 89, 98; #Growynge#, _n._ growth, IX 71.[OE. _grōwan_; _grufe_ is freq. Northern form.]

1766.entry: #Grucche#, #Gruch#, _v._ to grumble, VIII _a_ 210, 311; grumble at, V183; #Gruchyng#, _pres. p._ reluctant, V 58. [OFr. _gr(o)ucher_.] _See_Grochinge, Bigruccheth.

1768.entry: #Grwe#, _n._ jot, in _no grwe_, not a jot, not at all, V 183. [? OFr._gru_, grain; _cf._ Grot.]

1781.entry: #Ȝateȝ#, #-es#, #-iis#, _pl._ V 2, IX 223, XVI 124, &c. [OE._ge(a)t_, _gæt_ (pl. _gatu_); the pls. above show infl. of sg.] _See_Gate, _n._^1

1783.entry: #Ȝe#, _pron. 2 pl. nom._ you, I 38, II 215, &c.; #Ȝee#, IX 187,219, 284; #Ye#, XV _g_ 25, &c.; #Yee#, XVII 397. #Ou#, _acc._ and _dat._(to) you, XIV _c_ 97; #Ȝou#, II 24, 204, &c.; #Ȝow#, I 22, VIII_a_ 6, 14, &c.; #You(e)#, XVI 402, XVII 294, &c.; #Yow#, V 23, 26, &c.;_refl._ (_acc._) yourselves, VIII _a_ 112, XIV _b_ 7, XVI 178; yourself,V 49, VIII _a_ 25; (_dat._) for yourselves, II 216, 217; _ȝif ȝoulyke_, _it lyke ȝou_, if it please you, IX 74, 284; _ȝou to_, foryourselves, XIV _d_ 7. #Ȝor#, _poss. adj._ XIV _c_ 13, 106;

1784.entry: #Ȝour(e)#, I 84, II 218, &c.; #Ȝowre#, VIII _a_ 14, 21, XIV _a_ 8,10, _b_ 4, &c. The plural forms are often used to a superior, as: II582, VIII _a_ 118, _ff._, &c.; but also without special reason andintermingled with _þou_, &c., as: II 466, V 42, 256-7, &c. [OE. _gē_,_ēow_, _ēower_.]

1785.entry: #Ȝede# (_pa. t._ of Gon, _q.v._), fared, went, &c., I 53, 104, II301, 476, VIII _a_ 93, &c.; walked, II 509; was, V 265; _ȝedeatwynne_, broke apart, separated, I 191; _ȝede on fote_ = lived, V295; _ȝede his gate_, went his way, VI 166. [OE. _ēode_; see_N.E.D._, s.v. _Yede_, and Luick, Hist. Gramm. d. engl. Sprache § 261 n.3; § 360.]

1786.entry: #Ȝederly#, _adv._ ? promptly, ? fully, V 257. [? OE. _ǣdre_,_ēdre_, quickly, fully; cf. Yendles.]

1788.entry: #Ȝef#, #Yef#; #Ȝif#, #Ȝyf#, _conj._ (usually with _subj._) if,I 17, II 169, III 13, 28, V 230, VI 122, VIII _a_ 163, XIII _a_ 35, 48,XV _b_ 34, &c.; whether, I 17, III 5, &c.; #Hyf#, VIII _b_ 43; #If(f)#,VIII _a_ 123, XVI 331, &c.; #Iif#, V 275; #Yf#, IV _b_ 24; #Yiif#, XV_a_ 23; _ȝif (if) þat_, if, IV _a_ 24, 88, IX 219, 271, XII _a_ 16,_b_ 46, XIV _c_ 69; whether, XII _a_ 184; _all if_, although, XVII 231;_see_ also Bote. [OE. _gef_, _gi(e)f_.] _See_ Gif.

1790.entry: #Ȝelde(n)#, _v._ to yield, give (back), pay, repay, V 155, 257, VIII_a_ 44, IX 189; #Yelde#, III 50; #Ȝelde#, _subj._ (_imper._) in_ȝ. hit ȝow_, requite you for it, V 342; _ȝ. ȝow (of)_,reward you (for), VIII _a_ 121; #Ȝolden#, _pp._ surrendered, XIV _b_89; #Yyolde#, restored, III 58 (_see_ the French). 1795.entry: #Ȝerne#, _v._ to desire, long for; #Yȝyrned#, _pp._ XV _c_ 32 (therelative before _ychabbe_ is omitted); #Ȝhernyng#, _n._ (the objectof) desire, IV _a_ 22 (_cf._ Couaytyng, Lufyng). [OE. _géornan_,_gírnan_; _géorning_.]

1798.entry: #Ȝut# (VIII _b_); _adv._ yet; up to now, even now, XI _b_ 243, XII_a_ 196, XIV _c_ 84, XVI 373, XVII 359, &c.; strengthening _(n)euere_,II 103, 147, VI 89, VIII _b_ 41, XVI 136; still, once more, in addition,moreover, II 464, VI 14, VIII _a_ 38, 250, IX 40, 200, XII _b_ 75, &c.;all the same, none the less, I 225, II 174, V 151, VI 83, VIII _b_ 98,XI _b_ 119, XV _g_ 31, XVII 12, &c.; _conj._ and yet, but, XVII 17, 197;_ac ȝete_, _but ȝit_, _bot yit_ (_ȝeit_), &c., and yet, II 191,IX 99, X 95, XI _b_ 239, XVII 35, &c. [OE. _gēt(a)_, _gett_,_gī(e)t_, _gȳt_, &c.]

1799.entry: #Ȝete#, _v._ to grant, give; _no waning I wyl þe ȝete_, I wish togive you no curtailment (of what is due), VI 198. [OE. (late)_gēatan_, prob. modelled on ON. _játa_.]

1800.entry: #Ȝeue#, #Yeue# (III), _v._ to give, grant, III 7, IX 79, 293, XI _b_162, &c.; #Ȝiue(n)#, II 454, VIII _a_ 121 (_subj._), XII _b_ 35, 42,&c.; #Ȝyue#, XI _b_ 300; #Ȝifth#, _3 sg. pres._ XII _a_ 87.

1802.entry: #Yeaf#, III 10, 22, 52; #Ȝaf#, _pa. t. pl._ II 20; #Yeaue#, _pa.subj._ III 21, 51. #Ȝouen#, _pp._ IX 90, XI _b_ 264; #Yeue#, III 7,14; #Y-yeue#, III 25, 29; _ȝaf of_, gave (cared) for, XIV _c_ 54.[OE. _gefan_, _giefan_, _gyfan_.] _See_ Giffe, Forȝeue.

1805.entry: #Ȝiftis#, _n. pl._ gifts, VIII _a_ 42, XI _b_ 265. [OE. _gift_; see_N.E.D._, s.v. _Gift_.] _See_ Gyfte.

1810.entry: #Ȝole#, _n._ Yule, Christmas; _ȝole nyȝt_, Christmas night, I187. [OE. _gēol_; cf. ON. _jól_, n. pl. Yule; _jóla-nátt_,Yule-night.]

1812.entry: #Ȝong(e)#, #Yong# (XVII), _adj._ young, VI 52, 114, 175, VIII _b_ 36,IX 21, XVII 397; _old or ȝong_, any one, II 221; _ȝong and alde_,every one, IV _a_ 49. [OE. _geong_.]

1814.entry: #Ȝore#, _adv._ (since long ago), a long while, II 559, V 46, VI 226,XV _c_ 32. [OE. _geāra_.]

1819.entry: #Habbe(n)#, _v._ to have, possess, get, take, put, and _auxil._, XIII_a_ 59, 60, XV _g_ 23; #A#, I 127; #Haf(e)#, IV _a_ 64, V 150, &c.;

1820.entry: #Haif#, XVII 286; #Han#, XIV _c_ 6, XV _h_ 22; #Haue(n)#, I 107, VIII_a_ 74, XII _a_ 66, &c.; #Hawe#, X _introd._ #Haf#, #Haue#, _1 sg.pres._ V 23, IX 289, &c.; _see_ Ichabbe, Ichaue; #Has(e)#, _2 sg._ XVI243, XVII 430, &c.; #Hast(e)#, I 131, XVI 223, &c.; #Hatȝ#, V 173,228, 273, 324; #Hauest#, VIII _b_ 26; #Habbeȝ#, _3 sg._ *V 271(note); #Hase#, IV _a_ 39, XVII 550, &c.; #Haþ#, #Hath#, I 11, XVI 356,&c.; #Hatȝ#, V 46, 126, 340; #Haues#, XV _a_ 20; #Haueþ#, VIII _b_98; #Habbeþ#, _pl._ III 2, XIII _a_ 15, &c.; #Haf(e)# (with _pron._), IV_b_ 16, VI 159, X 16, &c.; #Han# (the commonest form), II 21, V 25, &c.;

1822.entry: #Haue#, _pres. subj._ V 219, VIII _a_ 114, 261; _as haue I_ (_thou_), somay I (you) have, XVII 237, 333, 402. #Haf#, #Haue#, _imper. sg._ V 75,I 124, &c.; #Haueth#, _pl._ XIV _d_ 13. #Hadde#, _pa. t._ I 100, II 51,XI _b_ 265, &c.; #Had(e)#, I 116, V 13, XI _b_ 202, &c.; #Hedde#, III 5,42, &c. (OKt. _hefde_); #Hadde#, _2 sg._ XVI 219; #Hadestow#, II 533(_see_ Þou); #Hadyn#, _pl._ VII 126. #Haade#, _pa. t. subj._ had, would(should) have, XI _b_ 270; #Hadde#, #Had(e)#, II 559, I 195, V 196, &c.;

1823.entry: #Hed(d)e#, III 13, 30, &c.; #Hadeȝ#, #Hadest#, _2 sg. subj._ II 573,V 326. #Yhad#, _pp._ II 249, 253. _Haf (haue) at þe_, have (_i.e._ letme get) at thee, V 220, XVII 219; _haue done_, be quick, XVII 316, 352,480; _his lyf hade_, preserved his life, VII 163. [OE. _habban_.]

1826.entry: #Hacches#, _n. pl._ hatches; of a buttery, or kitchen, VIII _b_ 29; of aship, VII 147. [OE. _hæcc_.]

1829.entry: #Hafyng#, _n._ possession, VI 90. [From stem of Habben; cf. OE._hæfen_.]

1835.entry: #Haywarde#, _n._ hayward (who had charge of fences, enclosures, &c., andwas sometimes keeper of the cattle on the common land), VIII _b_ 16(_see_ note). [OE. _hægweard_.]

1838.entry: #Hale#, _v._ to draw, pull, XII _b_ 87; #Halt#, _pp._ in _vp halt_,uplifted, high, V 11. [OE. _*halian_ (OFris. _halia_), or OFr. _haler_.]

1839.entry: #Half#, #Halue#, #Haf# (III), _n._ side, X 198; _vpon boþe halue_, onboth sides, V 2, 97; _o this half_, on this side (of the world), IX 250;behalf, in _ane ... haf_ (with intervening _gen._) on behalf of, III 11;_(vp)on Goddeȝ halue_, _a (on) Goddes half_, &c., in God's name, forGod's sake, V 51, 81, XI _a_ 15, XII _b_ 80; _adj._ and _adv._ half, IX241, XII _b_ 35, 79, &c. [OE. _half_.] _See_ Behalue.

1842.entry: #Halydam#, _n._ halidom, holy thing (such as relics of the saints, butfrequent coupling with _God_, and _help_, seems to show word to implythe saints as a body; _cf._ prec. line), V 55. [OE. _hāligdōm_.]

1843.entry: #Hall(e)#, _n._ mansion, hall, home, II 219, V 261, XVI 136, XVII 67,348, 516, &c. [OE. _hall_.]

1845.entry: #Halpeny#, _n._ halfpenny in _halpeny ale_, ale at a halfpenny a gallon,small beer, VIII _a_ 300. [OE. _half-penig_.] _See_ Pené.

1847.entry: #Halsed#, _pa. t._ embraced, greeted, XVI 64. [OE. _h(e)alsian_,*embrace, implore, usually confused with next. Cf. ON. _heilsa_ (=next), greet; _hálsa_, embrace.]

1856.entry: #Hamese#, _n. pl._ alleged oriental name for diamonds, IX 37 (so inFrench original).

1859.entry: #Hange#, _v._ to hang (_trans._ and _intr._), I 219, VIII _a_ 63, XVI307; #Hongeþ#, _3 sg. pres._ II 506, 507; #Heng(e)#, _pa. t. sg._ II344, 500; #Yhonged#, _pp._ XIII _a_ 14. [OE. _hōn_ (pa. t._hēng_), trans.; _hángian_, intr.; cf. ON. _hanga_ (str.) intr.]

1860.entry: #Hap#, #Happ#, _n._ chance, fortune, XII _b_ 8, XV _c_ 9; #Happes#,_pl._ happenings, II 8, XIII _a_ 62. [ON. _happ_.] _See_ Myshap.

1861.entry: #Happe#, _v. impers._ happen, VIII _a_ 47; #Happed#, #Happit#, _pa. t._it befell, VII 117, VIII _b_ 99. [From prec.]

1862.entry: #Happene#, #Happyn#, _v._ to happen, IX 47, 207, XVII 481; #Hapneth#, _3sg. pres._ XII _b_ 6. [Extended from prec.]

1864.entry: #Hard(e)#, _adj._ hard, harsh, cruel, I 28, 135, II 243, &c.; strong,immovable, IV _a_ 48; as _sb._, what is hard, VI 246; _adv._ hard, V 85,XV _h_ 13; grievously, VII 117; closely, X 150, XVI 151. [OE. _heard_;_hearde_.]

1865.entry: #Hardely#, #Hardily#, #Hardiliche#, _adv._ boldly, VIII _a_ 30, XVI 143;(parenthetic), certainly, I may say, V 322, XVII 522. [From next.]

1869.entry: #Hardis#, _n. pl._ hards (coarser part of flax), X 20. [OE. _heordan_,pl.]

1873.entry: #Harm(e)#, _n._ grief, misfortune, injury, detriment, I 147, V 204, 209,VI 28, XII _a_ 162, XIII _b_ 39, XIV _a_ 26, XVI 323, &c. [OE. _hearm_.]

1879.entry: #Harrowe#, #Herrowe#, _interj._ a cry for help, XVI 185, 343; as _sb._,uproar, XVI 98. [OFr. _harou_.]

1882.entry: #Harwen#, _v._ to harrow, VIII _b_ 19. [Cf. ON. _herfi_, OSwed. _harva_,a harrow.]

1884.entry: #Hast(e)#, _n._ violence, haste, VIII _a_ 291, XVII 411, &c; _an haste_,III 22, 43, 47; _in hast(e)_, V 150, VIII _a_ 167, XVII 158, 293, 447,speedily, immediately. [OFr. _haste_; cf. Heste, _n._^2]

1885.entry: #Hast(e)#, _v. intr._ and _refl._ to hasten, VIII _a_ 317, XVII 182;_hastis hemselue to hange_, rashly (precipitately) hang themselves, XVI307. [OFr. _haster_.]

1889.entry: #Hate#, #Hatie#, _2 sg. pres. subj._ (you should) hate, IV _a_ 47, VIII_a_ 52. [OE. _hatian_.]

1893.entry: #Haþel#, #Haithill# (VII), _adj._ noble, VII 38; _n._ knight, V 263,340. [OE. _æþele_, adj., and _hæleþ_, warrior; _see_ Björkman, _MorteArthure_, 358 (note, and refs.).]

1896.entry: #Haukin#, _n._; _on haukin_, a-hawking, II 308. [OE. _hafoc_, ON._hauk-r_, a hawk.]

2108.entry: #Ich#, _pron. 1 sg._ I, II 113, III 2, VIII _b_ 1, XV _c_ 5, _d_ 4, _f_6, &c.; #Ic#, XV _g_ 26, 31; #Icche#, XV _a_ 2, 11; #I#, #Y#, _passim_;coalescing with foll. word in Ichabbe, Icham, Ichaue, Ichil, Ichim,Ichot, Ichulle, _q.v._ #Me#, _acc._ and _dat._ (to, for) me, V 138, 145,VI 205, XV _a_ 20, _c_ 10, 31 (_see_ Reue), and _passim_; #Mee#, XVI274; _ethic dat._ (I beg), V 76; in impers. constr. (where Mn.E. has'I'), II 177, IV _a_ 10, XV _b_ 34; _me is wo_, woe is me, II 331;_refl. acc._ myself, IX 279, XVI 325, XVII 238, &c.; _dat._ (pleonasticwith verb of motion) XV _a_ 4. #Mi#, _poss. adj._ II 120, 124, &c.;

2109.entry: #My#, _passim_; #Min#, #Myn(e)#, I 126, II 205, VIII _a_ 31, XV _g_ 11,&c.; as _sb._ (my property, people, &c.), VI 206, VIII _a_ 142, XVI 217,312, XVII 226 (_see_ Þat, _pron._). #Miself(f)e#, #Myselue(n)#, _nom._myself, II 566, V 293, VIII _a_ 80, IX 292, &c.; I myself, VIII _a_ 252,XVI 67, 212; _acc._ and _dat._ (me) myself (not _refl._), VIII _a_ 28,131. [OE. _ic_, _mē_, _mīn_, _mē selfan_, &c.] _See_ Self.

2110.entry: #Ichabbe#, _1 sg. pres. ind._ I have, XV _c_ 9; #Ychabbe#, XV _c_ 32;

2112.entry: #Icham#, _1 sg. pres. ind._ I am, II 127, 382, 513, XV _c_ 8, 29, _d_ 1;

2114.entry: #Ichil#, _1 sg. pres. ind._ I will, intend to, II 132, 212, 341, 451;(with ellipse of verb of motion) I will go, II 129, 316; #Ichulle#, XV_c_ 19; _ichil þatow be_, may you be, II 471. [OE. _ic wile_, _wylle_.]_See_ Wille, _v._

2116.entry: #Ichon#, #Vchon# (VI, VIII), _pron._ each one, every one, II 161, VI 90,VIII _a_ 202, &c.; in apposition with pl. noun, XVII 279. [OE. _ylc_ +_ān_.] _See_ Ich, _adj._^2; Echone, Euerichon, Ilkane.

2117.entry: #Ichot#, _1 sg. pres. ind._ I know, XV _b_ 23, _c_ 10. [OE. _icwāt_.] _See_ Wite(n).

2121.entry: #Ieu#, #Iewe#, _n._ Jew, IX 163, XI _b_ 201, XV _g_ 18, XVI 147, &c.[OFr. _giu_, older _ju(i)eu_.]

2127.entry: #Ilkane#, #Ilkone#, _pron._ each one, every one, X 160 (note), XIV _b_74. [OE. _ylc_ + _ān_.] _See_ Ilk, _adj._^2; Ichon; Echone.

2128.entry: #Ilk(e)#, _adj._^1 (only after _þe_, _þis_, _þat_) very, same, III 45, V65, VIII _a_ 155 (_see_ While), XII _a_ 190, _b_ 29, &c.; _þe ilkezelue_, (namely) that same man, III 27. [OE. _ilca_.] _See_ Ich,_adj._^1; Thilke; Þe.

2129.entry: #Ilk(e)#, #Ylk# (IV), _adj._^2 each, every, X 35, XVI 273; _ilk(e) a_,every, IV _a_ 27 (_see_ Dele, _n._), X 133, XVI 130, 253. [OE. _ylc_.]_See_ Ich, _adj._^2; Eche.

2130.entry: #Ill#, #Yll#, _adj._ bad, IV _b_ 35; grievous, IV _a_ 31; evil, wicked,IV _b_ 84, XVII 208; as _sb._ (_pl._), the wicked, XVI 34; #Ill(e)#,_adv._ ill, XV _b_ 24 (_see_ Like); badly, evilly, cruelly, unluckily,VIII _a_ 198, XIV _a_ 31, XVI 139, XVII 203, 220, 246, &c. [ON. _ill-r_;_illa_, adv.]

2132.entry: #Imete#, _v._ to meet, XV _g_ 6; _imette wid_, he met, XV _g_ 7. [OE._ge-mētan_.] _See_ Mete(n).

2134.entry: #In#, #Yn#, _adv._ in (of motion), I 80, II 347, XIII _a_ 9, XV _g_ 24,XVI 270, &c.; #Inne#, V 128. [OE. _inn_.] _See_ Into, Intill; Inne;Þare.

2135.entry: #In#, _n._ lodging, II 565; _pl._ in _takes he his ines_, takes up hisquarters, XIV _b_ 27. [OE. _inn_, n.]

2136.entry: #In#, #Yn#, #I# (XV _a_, _g_), _prep._ (i) In, I 3, II 13, XIII _a_ 3,XV _a_ 9, _g_ 5, 13, &c.; into, II 349, XII _a_ 125, &c.; according to,as regards, with respect to, &c., VI 239, IX 141, XI _b_ 26, 204, &c.;_in all his myghte_, with &c., IV _b_ 77. (ii) On, IV _b_ 41, V 157, 279(of time), IX 122, 286, XIII _a_ 45, &c. _In cas_, _in feere_ (_fere_),_see_ Cas, Yfere (Fere). [OE. _in_.] _See_ In, Inne, _advs._

2143.entry: #Inne#, #Ynne#, _adv._ in (inside), IX 188, XIII _a_ 21; after rel. in_þat ... in(ne)_, in which, I 190, VIII _a_ 298, XV _i_ 10; #Ine#,_prep._ in, III _introd._ 16, 33, 35, 49, 50; on (of time) III _introd._[OE. _innan_, prep., adv.; _inne_, adv.] _See_ In, _adv._, _prep._;Þare; Þer(e).

2149.entry: #Intil(l)#, #Intyl(l)#, _prep._ into, IV _a_ 3, 9, 16, 21, _b_ 30, &c.;in, X 118, 122. [OE. _inn_ + ON. _til_.] _See_ In, _adv._; Til, _prep._

2150.entry: #Into#, #Ynto#, _prep._ into, I 146, II 163, &c.; onto, in _putten heminto_, embark on, IX 183; up to, until (_cf._ To), XII _a_ 190, 221;(un)to, XIV _c_ 25. [OE. _inn tō_, _intō_.] _See_ In, _adv._

2156.entry: #Ioie#, #Ioy(e)#, _n._ joy, II 6, 45, IV _b_ 54, XII _a_ 175, &c.;_makes ioie_, rejoice, XVI 383. [OFr. _joie_.]

2159.entry: #Ioparde#, _n._ hazard; _lys no ioparde of_, there is no question of, VI242. [OFr. _ju (jeu) parti_, even game, doubtful chance.]

2161.entry: #Ipotayne#, _n._ hippopotamus, IX 240. [_Ipotaine_, mistake (_in_ for_m_) for OFr. _ypotame_, convenient corruption of L. _hippopotamus_.]

2163.entry: #Irnebandis#, _n. pl._ iron bands, X 24. [OE. _īren_ + ON. _band_;cf. OE. _īren-bend_.] _See_ Bond; Yre, _n._^1

2164.entry: #Is#, #Ys#, #His# (XI), _3 sg. pres. ind._ is, I 9, 19, VIII _b_ 105, XI_b_ 256, &c.; exists, IX 146; (without _pron._) it is, I 253, 254, V121, &c.; _2 sg._ art, XVI 360; _pl._ are, VIII _b_ 48, X 124, XVII 10,&c.; rime requires Es (_q.v._) at I 128 (note), XVII 10. [OE. _is_.]_See_ Es, Nis.

2177.entry: #Iwis#, #Iwysse#, _adv._ certainly, indeed (often, _esp._ in rime,practically meaningless), V 121, 172, VI 34, XIV _b_ 17, XVII 550. [OE._ge-wiss_, adj.; cf. _mid (to) gewisse_.]

2179.entry: #Kache#, _v._ to chase, catch; _kacheȝ his caple_, urges on hishorse, V 107; #Kaȝt# (_to_), _pa. t._ took hold (of), V 308; #Cawht#,_pp._ caught, XII _a_ 161. [ONFr. _cachier_, conjugated on anal. of ME._la(c)chen_.]

2185.entry: #Karolle#, _n._ a carol, a dance accompanied with song (often used withref. to song only), I 1, 14, &c. [OFr. _carolle_.]

2188.entry: #Kele#, #Keill#, #Keyle#, _v._ to cool, IV _a_ 26 (_intr._); _to kele(keill) cares_, to assuage sorrows, XVI 84, XVII 300; with person asdir. obj., _from cares the to keyle_, to preserve thee from grief, XVII118. [OE. _cēlan_.]

2189.entry: #Ken#, #Kenne#, _v._ to make known, VII 25 (see note); to teach, VIII_a_ 14, 22, 24, XIV _b_ 4 (_see_ Crede), XVI 50, &c.; to know, in _dawto ken_, to be known for a fool, XVII 248; _will ȝe it ken_, if youwill recognize the fact, XIV _b_ 8; understand, I _introd._; _pp._(well) known, XIV _b_ 9. [OE. _cennan_, prob. infl. by senses of ON._kenna_.] Cf. Knowe(n).

2192.entry: #Kepe#, _n._ heed; in _tok no kepe of_, XII _a_ 159. [From next.]

2193.entry: #Kepe#, _v._ to guard, preserve, keep, tend, II 208, V 80, 230, VIII _a_85, 134, 153, IX 206, XI _b_ 146, XVII 235 (_see_ Charité), &c.; _kepeseyntewarie_, minister in the sanctuary, VIII _b_ 83; to care to, in _þelette I ne kepe_, I have no wish to stop you, V 74; #Kepynge#, _n._ XI_b_ 70. [OE. _cēpan_.] _See_ Vnkept.

2196.entry: #Kest#, _n._ a 'cast' (_see_ Cast, _v._); a blow, V 230; plot,treachery, V 345; used as 'treacherous thing' (_cf._ Falssyng), V 308.[ON. _kast_.]

2199.entry: #Keuer(e)#, _v._ to (re)gain, recover; _intr._ recover, survive, V 230;_keuereȝ_, 'gets', makes his way, V 153. [OE. _ā-cofrian_, intr.,and OFr. _(re-)covrer_, 3 sg. _-keuvre_, trans.] _See_ Recoueren.

2201.entry: #Kille#, #Kylle#, _v._ to kill, VIII _a_ 32, V 43. [? OE. _*cyllan_;earliest ME. sense appar. 'beat'.]

2202.entry: #Kyn#, #Kynne#, #Ken# (III), _n. sg._ kindred, relatives, III _introd._,VIII _b_ 81, XVI 232 (_see_ Ende); kind, sort: #Cunnes#, #Kyns#, _gen.sg._ in _enes cunnes_, (of any kind), any sort of, XV _g_ 22; _enykyns_, VIII _b_ 20; _nones cunnes_, (of no kind), no sort of, XV _g_ 20;(with loss of inflexions) _na kyn_, X 59 (_see_ Þing); _nor ... no kyn_,nor ... any (sort of), XVII 138; _cf._ Alkyn, Wolues-kynnes. [OE. _cynn_(Kt. _cenn_).] _See_ Eny, No(ne).

2203.entry: #Kinde#, #Kynd(e)#, #Kyend# (IV), _n._ nature, natural character (ofbody or mind), kind, IV _a_ 41, 44 (_see_ note), V 312, VIII _a_ 157, IX56, XII _a_ 8, 125, &c.; _in hir kinde_, in her own way, XII _b_ 128;species, in _ich kynd_ (without _of_), every kind of, XVII 151;

2205.entry: #Kynde#, _adj._ inborn, naturally belonging to one, VIII _a_ 243, _b_58; _to his kynde name_, as his proper name, VII 70; _Kynde Witt_,natural intelligence, common sense, VIII _a_ 243 (personif.). [OE._(ge-)cýnde_.] _See_ Vnkinde.

2206.entry: #Kynd(e)ly#, _adv._ kindly, VI 9, VII 173, &c. [From prec. in developedsense 'having natural feeling'; OE. _ge-cýnde-līce_, naturally.]

2207.entry: #Kindel#, _v._ to kindle; _trans._ to cause (sorrow), XIV _a_ 10;_intr._ to begin, XIV _a_ 19. _Cf._ Kele. [Rel. to ON. _kynda_ (cf._kyndill_, torch); distinct from ME. _kindlen_, beget.]

2209.entry: #Kyng#, #King#, #Keyng# (IV), _n._ king, I 27, II 25, IV _a_ 8, 66, V207 (note), XIV _d_ 10 (note), &c.; #Kynggis#, _pl._ XI _b_ 284. [OE._cyning_, _cyng_, &c.]

2211.entry: #Kirke#, #Kyrk#, _n._ church, Church, V 128, VIII _a_ 85; _see_ note toVIII _b_ 63. [ON. _kirkja_.] _See_ Cherche.

2212.entry: #Kirtel(l)#, #Kertel# (III), _n._ kirtle (a short coat reaching about tothe knees, worn under an outer garment), II 229, III 39, XIV _b_ 61.[OE. _cyrtel_, Kt. _*certel_.]

2213.entry: #Kysse#, _v._ to kiss; #Kyssedes#, _2 sg. pa. t._ V 283; #Keste#, _3sg._ XII _a_ 178. [OE. _cyssan_ (Kt. _cessan_).] _See_ Cosseȝ.

2215.entry: #Kyþe#, _v._ to make known, reveal; #*Kyþeȝ# (MS. lyþeȝ), _imper.pl._ show, VI 9; #Kidde#, _pp._ revealed, XII _b_ 188, XVI 251; #Kyd#,shown, offered, V 272; acknowledged, VII 173; #Kud#, famed, XIV _c_ 91.[OE. _cȳþan_, pp. _(ge-)cȳ̆dd_.]

2216.entry: #Knacke(n)#, _v._ to sing in a lively or ornate manner (ref. esp. to thebreaking up of simple notes into runs and trills; cf. _smale brekynge_),XI _b_ 161, 173, 177; #Knackynge#, _n._ trilling, XI _b_ 159, 182.[Prob. same as ME. _knacken_, to crack, snap, &c.]

2220.entry: #Knarreȝ#, _n. pl._ ? crags, ? gnarled boulders, V 98. [? Cf. LG._knarre_, knot.]

2221.entry: #Knaue#, #Knafe# (XVII), _n._ a lowborn man, servant, VIII _a_ 51, _b_66, XVI 244, XVII 173; #Knauene#, _gen. plur._ VIII _b_ 56, XV _h_ 4.[OE. _cnafa_.]

2223.entry: #Kne#, #Kneo# (XIII), _n._ knee, II 507, XIII _a_ 39, XVII 488(_distrib. sg._; _see_ Herte). [OE. _cnēo_.]

2224.entry: #Knele#, #Kneole# (XIII), _v._ to kneel, II 223, 418, 472, V 4, XIII _a_48; #Kneland(e)#, _pres. p._ II 250, VI 74, XVII 488. [OE._cnēowlian_.]

2226.entry: #Knight(e)#, #Knyght(e)#, #Kniȝt#, #Knyȝt(e)#, #Kniht# (XIV), _n._knight, II 86, III 14, V 63, VII 87, VIII _a_ 22, IX 108, XIV _c_ 58,&c.; #Kniȝte#, _dat. sg._ III 11, 25; #Cnistes# (for Cniste, _gen.pl._) XV _g_ 30 (note). [OE. _cniht_, servant; on _cnistes_, seeAppendix, p. 278.]

2227.entry: #Knyght-fees#, _n. pl._ estates of land (held by a knight underobligation of armed service), VIII _b_ 81. [Prec. + OFr. _fé_.]

2228.entry: #Knit#, #Knyt#, #Knet# (XII), _pp._ tied, bound, closed together, XII_b_ 30, 54, XIV _c_ 29, XVII 451. [OE. _cnyttan_.]

2229.entry: #Knok(ke)#, #Knock(e)#, _n._ knock, blow, V 311, XV _h_ 4, XVII 342.[From next.]

2231.entry: #Knokled#, _adj._ knobbed, rugged, V 98. [From ME. _knok(e)le_, knob,knuckle; _cf._ OFris. _knok(e)le_.]

2234.entry: #Knaw(e)#, I, IV, VI, XVI, XVII; #Knewe(n)#, #Knew#, _pa. t._ II 408, IV_a_ 43, IX 291, &c.; #Knowe(n)#, _pp._ VII 46, XI _b_ 231, XIV _c_ 91;

2235.entry: #Knowun#, XI _a_ 2, 7, &c.; #Yknowe#, XIII _a_ 12, _b_ 1: to know,understand, recognize, I 220, IV _b_ 86, V 174, VI 50, VIII _a_ 51, IX75, 114 (_subj._), XI _a_ 40, &c.; _knowe_ (_fro_, _fram_), distinguish(from), VIII _a_ 50, XIV _d_ 12; to experience, in _vnrid to knowe_,grievous to endure, XVII 41; to confess, acknowledge (_cf._ Biknowe),XVI 315; _the soth for to knaw_, to tell the truth, XVII 246; to makeknown, declare, XVI 283. [OE. _(ge-)cnāwan_.] _See_ Icnowe, Ken.

2237.entry: #Knoweleche#, #Knowlage#, _n._ knowledge, VII 73; _for knoweleche_, forfear of recognition, II 482. [? Stem of ME. _knowelechen_, OE._*(ge-)cnāwlǣcan_; but the noun is recorded first.]

2239.entry: #Kokeney#, _n._ (_lit._ cocks' egg), small egg, VIII _a_ 280. [ME._cokken(e)_, gen. pl. (OE. _cocc_) + _ey_ (OE. _ǣg_); see _N.E.D._,s.v. _Cockney_.]

2240.entry: #Kole-plantes#, _n. pl._ cabbages (and similar vegetables), VIII _a_281. [OE. _cāl_ + _plante_.] _See_ Coyll.

2241.entry: #Kongons#, _n. pl._ changelings, misshapen creatures, XV _h_ 5. [ME._conjoun_ (frequent); from ONFr. _*ca(u)ngiūn_, OFr. _changon_ (veryrare).]

2245.entry: #Kowe#, _n._ tail, (verse in) tail-rime; _couthe not haf coppled a k._,could have made nothing of an intricately rimed verse, Introduction xv.[OFr. _coue_.] _See_ Couwee.

2249.entry: #Kutten#, _v._ to cut, IX 140; #Cut#, VII 146; #Ketten#, _pa. t. pl._VIII _a_ 182. [? OE. _*cyttan_; see _N.E.D._]

2251.entry: #Labor(e)#, #Labour(e)#, _v._ to labour, VIII _a_ 118, _b_ 8, 70, &c.;_laboure with londe_, till the soil, VIII _a_ 267; _trans._ to labourupon, cultivate, VI 144. [OFr. _labo(u)rer_.]

2252.entry: #Laborer(e)#, _n._ labourer, VIII _a_ 302, 313, _b_ 77, XI _b_ 296.[From prec.; cf. OFr. _laboreor_.]

2254.entry: #Lacche#, _v._ to catch; to get, VIII _a_ 223; #Laghton#, _pa. t. pl._in _laghton þe watur_, put to sea, VII 119. [OE. _læccan_, _læhte_.]

2261.entry: #Lay#, #Legge# (VIII), #Lei#, #Ley(e)#, #Leyn#, _v._ to lay, set, put, I217, IX 125, XV _f_ 12, _g_ 13, XVII 461; _lay on_, smite, XVI 143;_leid to wedde_, deposited in pledge, mortgaged, VIII _b_ 77; to wager,VIII _a_ 263, XVII 479; lay down, establish (law), XVI 329. #Layde#,_pa. t._ in _layde þeron_, applied to it, II 38; #Leyde#, VIII _a_ 116;

2267.entry: #Layne#, _v._ to conceal; _layne yow_ (_me_), keep your (my) secret, V56, 60. [ON. _leyna_.]

2270.entry: #Lake#, _n._ lake, IX 182, XIII _a_ 63, 64. [OE. _lacu_, stream infl. byunrelated OFr. _lac_, lake.]

2271.entry: #Lakke#, _v. intr._ with _dat._ to be lacking (to); _yow lakked alyttel_, you were somewhat at fault, V 298; _trans._ to find fault with,VIII _a_ 219. [From Lac, _n._; cf. MDu. _laken_.]

2279.entry: #Lapidarye#, _n._ treatise on precious stones, IX 75 (_see_ note). [L._lapidārium_.]

2280.entry: #Lappe#, _n._ loose end, or fold, of a garment, VIII _a_ 288, XV _f_ 11.[OE. _læppa_.]

2281.entry: #Large#, _adj._ generous, II 28; ample, VI 249; broad, large, V 157, IX18, 155, 254 &c.; #Largelich#, _adv._ generously, II 451. [OFr._large_.]

2284.entry: #Lasse#, #Les(se)#, _adj. compar._ less, smaller, IV _a_ 92, V 158, VI131, IX 29, 48, XIII _b_ 36, &c.; _quasi-sb._, less, VI 241, &c.; ? asmaller piece, XV _h_ 17; _þe lasse in werke_, those who have workedless, VI 239, 240 (_see_ Longe, _adv._); _more and les(se)_, _les andmore_, _see_ More; _adv._ less, V 300, VIII _a_ 161, XI _a_ 58, &c.;_neuer þe lesse_, nevertheless, I 71. #Leest#, #Leste#, _superl._ least,IV _b_ 85; _both the most and the leest_, all, XVII 452. [OE._lǣ̆ssa_ (_lǣ̆s_, adv.); _lǣ̆st_.]

2286.entry: #Last(e)#, _superl. adj._ last, VI 187, 211, &c.; _quasi-sb._ in _atþe_, _atte_, _ate last(e)_, at last, in the end, II 93, VIII _b_ 99 (MS.latiste), XII _a_ 105, _b_ 188, &c.; _at þe laste ende_, in the end,VIII _b_ 101. [OE. _latost_, _lætest_.] _See_ Atte, Late, Furst.

2287.entry: #Last(e)#, _v._ to endure, last, extend, IV _a_ 1, 25, IX 199, XVI 66,XVII 265, &c.; #Last# (OE. _lǣ̆st_), _3 sg. pres._ II 335; #Last#,_pa. t. sg._ VII 56; _be lastand_, endure, IV _a_ 58; _euer to last_,everlasting, VII 2; #Lastynge#, _n._ endurance, perseverance, IV _b_ 73,XI _b_ 122. [OE. _lǣ̆stan_.]

2289.entry: #Late#, _adv._ late, I 108, VI 178, XIV _b_ 91, &c.; lately, recently,XVII 442; _erly and late_, at all times, VI 32; _nowe late_, justlately, XVI 162, 329. [OE. _late_.] _See_ Laste.

2294.entry: #Laue#, _v. trans._ and _intr._ to pour, VI 247, XV _g_ 16. [OE._lafian_.]

2296.entry: #Launchet#, #-it#, _pa. t._ darted, leapt, VII 135, 153; _launchet to_,reached, VII 163. [ONFr. _lancher_.] _See_ Lance.

2300.entry: #Law(e)#, _n._^1 law, VIII _a_ 159, 313, XI _a_ 2, 22, XIV _b_ 63, XVI313, &c.; practice, customary behaviour, in _doþ at Crystyn mennys l._,behave as Christians, I 82. [OE. _lagu_, from ON.]

2302.entry: #Lawse#, _v._ to loose(n), undo, V 308; #Lowsyd#, _pa. t._ delivered,XVII 209. [From ME. _laus_, _lous_, adj.; ON. _laus-s_.]

2307.entry: #Lede#, _n._^1 man, knight, V 27, VII 62, 75; _voc._ my good man, VI182; #Leyde#, XVII 48, in _euery liffyng l._, everybody; #Leude#, V 265,321, 353. [OE. (allit.) _lēod_, prince.]

2308.entry: #Lede#, #Leede#, _n._^2 people, country, in _þurgh land and lede_, overthe earth, I 227; _in leede_, on earth, XVI 70, 135. [OE. _lēode_,pl., and _lēod_, fem.]

2309.entry: #Lede(n)#, #Ledyn#, #Leyd# (XVII), _v._ to lead, bring, I 153, IX 214,XVI 391; guide, direct, XI _a_ 55; to pass, lead (life), IV _a_ 49, 63,VI 32, XV _h_ 20, XVII 393. #Ledys#, _pres. pl._ IV _b_ 55; #Ladde#,_pa. t._ II 584; #Ledde#, I 63, III 55; #Led#, _pp._ treated, XVII 202.[OE. _lǣdan_.]

2310.entry: #Ledeing#, _n._; _at his l._, under his control, XIV _b_ 54. [Fromprec.]

2314.entry: #Leef#, #Lef#, _n._ leaf; item (with ref. to books), VIII _a_ 251;_sette ... at a lef_, made light of, VIII _b_ 101; #Leues#, #Leves#,_pl._ II 244, VII 103, IX 154, XV _b_ 14. [OE. _lēaf_.]

2318.entry: #Lef#, #Leof# (XIV), _adj._ dear, II 102, *406; eager, XIV _c_ 6; #Leue#(_wk._ in _voc._), XV _g_ 10; as _sb._, dear one, VI 58. #Leuer#,_compar._ in _l. me were to_, I would rather, II 177; #Leueste#, mostpleasing (to God), VIII _b_ 89. [OE. _lēof_.]

2320.entry: #Leggaunce#, _n._ (performance of) duty to his liege lord, XIV _c_ 67.[OFr. _legiance_.]

2326.entry: #Lele#, #Leel#, _adj._ lawful, VIII _b_ 109; faithful, XVI 65; accordingto covenant, XVII 446. [OFr. _leël_.]

2328.entry: #Leme#, _v._ to shine, flash, V 158; #Leymonde#, _pres. p._ VII 153.[OE. _*lēomian_; ON. _ljóma_.]

2331.entry: #Lende#, _v. trans._ and _intr._ to 'land'; _lende (on)_, to come, fall(upon), XVI 47, 54; _lendes (in)_, brings (into), IV _a_ 44; #Lended#,_pa. t._ remained, XIV _b_ 45; #Lent#, _pp._ gone, taken away, XV _c_11, 39; #Ylent# (_on_), come (upon), XV _c_ 24. [OE. _lendan_, go,arrive; the ME. sense development is obscured by confusion with Lene,_v._^1]

2342.entry: #Lepe#, _v._ to leap, run; _lepeȝ hym_, gallops, V 86; #Lepte#, _pa.t._ leapt, XII _a_ 160. [OE. _hlēapan_, str.]

2343.entry: #Lepys#, _n. pl._ leaps; _wyth sundyr lepys_, ? dancing separately, I234 (but _see_ Sonder, and note). [OE. _hlēp_.]

2345.entry: #Lere#, #Leere#, _v. trans._ to teach, instruct, VIII _a_ 251, XVI 55,127, 330, 391; _intr._ to learn, IV _a_ 17, XIV _b_ 57, XVI 313, 321;

2348.entry: #Lernyng(e)#, _n._ learning, XI _b_ 169; instruction, in _for l. of us_,for our instruction, VII 32; knowledge, XVI 85. [OE. _léornung_, intr.]

2350.entry: #Lese#, _v._^1 to lose, II 178, V 74, IX 130; #Lose#, XVII 363; #Lore#,_pp._ XII _a_ 187; #Lorne#, XVI 198; #Lost#, VII 148, VIII _b_ 99;

2351.entry: #Ylore#, II 209, 545. [OE. _(be-, for-)lēosan_, pp. _-loren_; cf._losian_, be lost.] _See_ Forlorn.

2353.entry: #Lesing#, _n._ a lie, II 465; #Lesyngis#, _pl._ XI _b_ 39; _lesyngison_, lies against, XI _b_ 98. [OE. _lēasing_.] _See_ Lees.

2359.entry: #Let(e)#, II 114, V 140, &c.; #Leteȝ#, _pl._ V 319. #Leet#, _pa. t.sg._ IX 223, 232; #Let(e)#, II 386, III 34, &c.; #Lette#, V 189; #Lete#,_pl._ II 74; #Ylete#, _pp._ III 32, *VIII _b_ 3. (i) To let, allow, II74, IV _b_ 41, &c.; bequeathe, III 32, 34; cause to (as _leet make_,caused men to make, had it made), IX 223, 232, XII _b_ 192; _letuntrusse_, unloaded, XII _b_ 52; forming periphrastic imper., XIV _b_90; _lete ben_, _latte be_, cease, stop, II 114, XVI 234; _let be_, leftunheeded, XII _b_ 94. (ii) To give up, abandon, IV _a_ 88, VIII _a_ 266,XIV _c_ 6; lose, II 177; cease, II 279; neglect (to), XIV _c_ 70. (iii)_Lette as_, behaved as if, V 189; _lete liȝte of_, make (made) lightof, give little thought to, VIII _a_ 161, XIV _c_ 63; _lytel ylete by_,held in small esteem, *VIII _b_ 3. [OE. _lǣtan_, _lētan_; formswith _a_ perhaps due partly to ON. _láta_, and partly to earlyshortening (? orig. in imper. sg.).]

2360.entry: #Lette#, _n._ hindrance, obstacle, XII _a_ 72; delay, XII _a_ 154. [Fromnext.] _See_ Ylet.

2361.entry: #Lette(n)#, #Let# (_of_, _fro_), _v._ to hinder, prevent, keep (from), V74, 235, XI _a_ 41, _b_ 3, 155, 179, XVII 341 (_subj._), 470; #Let#,_pp._ XII _b_ 10; #Lettid#, XI _b_ 181; _lette to sue_ (_studie_),prevent from following (studying), XI _a_ 41, _b_ 112. [OE. _lettan_.]_Distinguish_ Lete.

2362.entry: #Lettynge#, #-ing# (_to_), _n._ hindering (from), hindrance, XI _a_ 26,_b_ 307; delay, interruption, VIII _a_ 7, XI _b_ 80. [OE. _letting_.]

2364.entry: #Leþeȝ#, _3 sg. pres._ softens, is assuaged, VI 17. [OE._(ge-)liþian_, _-leoþian_, distinct from _līþian_.]

2366.entry: #Leue#, _n._ permission, VIII _a_ 68; leave, in _tok his leve_, XII _a_31. [OE. _lēaf_, fem.]

2367.entry: #Leue(n)#, _v._^1 to leave (alone, behind, off), abandon, neglect, cease(to), V 86, XI _b_ 10, 50, 301, XIII _a_ 56, XVI 284, &c.; #Lef(f)e#, IV_b_ 66, XVI 376; #Leif(f)#, X 156, 198; #Leueþ#, _imper. pl._ stop, I265. #Left(e)#, _pa. t._ and _pp._ I 71, IV _b_ 74, VII 26, XI _b_ 261,XII _b_ 179, XVI 314, &c.; #Leuid#, #Leuyt#, #Levit#, VII 74, 126, X159, XIV _b_ 78; #Yleft#, _pp._ XIII _b_ 8, 41. _For to leue for to_,that you may cease to, I 21; _to lefe_, to be left undone, avoided, IV_b_ 66. [OE. _lǣfan_.] _See_ Bleue.

2368.entry: #Leue(n)#, #Leeue#, _v._^2 to grant, in _Crist leue_, Christ grant, XIV_c_ 87, 95. [OE. _lēfan_.] _See_ Leue, _n._

2374.entry: #Ladi#, XII _a_ 50, 144, &c.; #Lady#, _gen. sg._ in _oure Lady day_, I242. [OE. _hlǣ̆fdige_.]

2376.entry: #Levyr#, _n._ liver; _l. and long_, allit. elaboration of _hert_, XVII399. [OE. _lifer_.]

2378.entry: #Lewed(e)#, #Lewid#, _adj._ lay, ignorant, uneducated, III _introd._,VIII _b_ 4, XI _a_ 3, XII _b_ 144; _lerid and lewid_, XI _a_ 38. [OE._lǣwede_.]

2382.entry: #Libben#, _v._ to live, XV _a_ 10; #Libbe#, _1 sg. pres._ XV _c_ 5;

2387.entry: #Lif#, #Lyfe# (obl. stem #Lif-#, and #Lyu-# &c.), _n._ life, manner oflife, lifetime, I 199, V 44, VI 32, VIII _a_ 170, XI _a_ 57, _b_ 40,XVII 398, &c.; #Liffe#, XVI 66; #Liif#, II 124, &c.; living being, IV_a_ 43, XII _a_ 117, 121; _lef liif_, beloved (one), II 102, *406.

2388.entry: #Lyfes#, _gen. sg._ IX 328; #Lyueȝ#, VI 117 (_see_ Longe, _adv._),218; #Liue#, #Lyue#, _dat. sg._ II 583 (being still alive), III 16, XII_a_ 168; _bi my lyue_, during my life, VIII _a_ 95; _yn þys lyue_, inthis world, I 170; _vpon lyue_, alive (_lede vpon l._ = man), V 27. [OE._līf_.] _See_ Liue(n).

2391.entry: #Liflode#, #Lyflode#, _n._ (means of) living, sustenance, food, VIII _a_17, 230, 267, 284, _b_ 43, 47, XII _b_ 25. [OE. _līf-lād_.]

2394.entry: #Lyfte#, _v._ to raise, IV _a_ 15, V 241; #Lyft(e)#, _pp._ IV _a_ 9, VI207 (_see_ Lyþer). [ON. _lyfta_.]

2396.entry: #Ligge(n)#, #Lygge#, #Lig#, _v._ to lie (down, idle, &c.), be (lodged,situated, &c.), II 74, VIII _b_ 16, XIII _a_ 53 (_subj._), XVII 409;

2398.entry: #Lyeþ#, _3 sg._ is to the point, is admissible, VIII _b_ 93; #Liggeth#,lies idle, VIII _a_ 156; #Ligis#, XVII 84; #Lys#, exists, VI 242; #Liþ#(OE. _līþ_), II 243, XII _a_ 95; #Liggeþ#, _pl._ II 441, VIII _a_ 15;

2399.entry: #Lyse#, IV _a_ 61. #Lay#, _pa. t. sg._ I 181, II 133, IX 286, &c.; _pl._II 394, 399, X 1 (were encamped), &c.; #Layȝ#, _subj._ XI _a_ 52.

2400.entry: #Lyand#, _pres. p._ X 55; #Ligand#, XIV _b_ 71; #Liggeand#, II 388(_see_ note); #Lyggyng#, I 139. _Liggen oute_, be abroad, out of doors,VIII _b_ 16. [OE. _licgan_; the _g(g)_ forms in I, XIV _b_, XVII prob.represent dial. _lig_ from ON. _liggja_.]

2405.entry: #Lyȝt#, #Liȝte#, #Light#, _v._^2 _trans._ to lighten, relieve, IV_a_ 70; _intr._ to alight, V 108; come down, V 152; #Lyht# (_on_), _pp._lit (on), settled (on), XV _c_ 12. [OE. _lī̆thtan_.^2]

2407.entry: #Liȝte#, #Lyght#, #Liht#, _adj._^2 light, slight, easy, I _introd._,IV _a_ 49; _lete liȝte (liht) of_, make (made) light of, give littlethought to, VIII _a_ 161, XIV _c_ 63; #Lyȝttere#, _compar._ easier,XI _b_ 238. [OE. _lē̆(o)ht_, _lī̆(o)ht_, adj.^2]

2411.entry: #Lik#, _v._ to sup, taste; _lik on_, have a taste of, XVII 378; _cf._Drynk. [OE. _liccian_.]

2412.entry: #Lyk(e)#, #Like#, #Lich(e)#, _adj._ and _adv._ usually foll. by_(un)to_, like, IV _a_ 16, VI 72, 141, IX 35, 98, XII _a_ 57, XVII 506.[OE. _(ge-)līc_; _(ge-)līce_, adv.] _See_ Ilyche.

2413.entry: #Like#, #Lyke#, _v._ to please, II 251, 449, 529, VI 206, VIII _b_ 42,XI _b_ 142; _impers._ with _dat._ (as _vs liketh_, it pleases us, weplease), V 66, 178, VIII _a_ 150, 286, IX 177, XII _a_ 115, XVI 321 (or_pers. pl._ 'like', as below), &c.; _ȝif ȝou lyke_, if it pleasesyou, IX 74 (cf. _ȝif it lyke ȝou_, 284); _for loue þat likesille_, that are wretched bec. of love (_or_ bec. of love that ispainful), XV _b_ 24; _quasi-pers._ (with _it_) V 267, IX 284; _pers._ tolike, XVII 361. [OE. _līcian_.]

2414.entry: #Likeing#, #Likyng#, #Lykyng(e)#, _n._ delight, pleasure, IV _a_ 30, VII20, 75, XI _b_ 158, XVII 75, &c.; _for likyng to here_, to be heard withdelight, to give pleasure in the hearing, VII 71; _of gode likeing_,well-pleasing, II 599. [OE. _līcung_.]

2415.entry: #Likne#, #Lykne#, #Lyken#, _v._ to make like, XIII _b_ 23; to compare,IV _a_ 6, VI 140, XIV _c_ 74; #Lyckend#, _pp._ (to be) compared, IV _a_33. [From Lyk, _adj._]

2420.entry: #Lymbo#, #Lymbus#, _n._ limbo; the 'border' (of hell) where the souls ofthe just who died before Christ awaited His coming, XVI 102, 198. [L._limbus (patrum)_; _in limbo_.]

2421.entry: #Lymp(e)#, _v._ ? to limp; _lympit of the sothe_, ? stumbled from, fellshort of, the truth, VII 36. [Cf. OE. _lemp-healt_, limping; MHG._limphin_, to limp. Not recorded otherwise in E. until much later.]

2425.entry: #Lynt#, _n._ lint, refuse of flax used as an inflammable stuff, X 20.[ME. _lin(e)t_, obscurely rel. to OE. _līn_ (OFr. _lin_), flax.]

2431.entry: #List(e)#, #Lyst(e)#, _v. impers._ to desire, wish (as _me list_, Idesire), IV _a_ 77, V 65, 74, XVI 68, 277; prob. _pers._ at IX 302, XVI313; _þat hym list after_, what he has a desire for, VII 20; #List#,_pa. t._ VII 166. [OE. _lystan_.]

2432.entry: #Lyste#, _n._ joy, VI 107. [Alteration of Lust, under infl. of prec.; orON. _lyst_.]

2434.entry: #Lite#, _adv._ little; _bot gode lite_, of but little worth, II 258.[OE. _lȳt_.]

2435.entry: #Lyte#, _n._ waiting; _on lyte_, in delay, V 235. [From ME. _līten_,to expect, await, tarry; ON. _hlíta_, to trust.]
