2436.entry: #Litel#, #-ill#, #Lytill#, #Littel#, #Lyttel#, #Lutel# (XV _c_), &c.,_adj._ little, small, slight, unimportant, IV _b_ 45, VI 214 (or _adv._'little time there'), 244, IX 14, 21, 141, XV _a_ 6, _c_ 3, &c.;_quasi-sb._ in _a lityl(l)_, &c., a little, V 298, IX 62; ? a smallpiece, XV _h_ 17; somewhat (_adv._), V 199, IX 103, 110; a little way(_adv._), V 78, 103, XVII 507; _for litill_, for little cause, XVII 187;_litel or nouȝt_, little or nothing, XI _b_ 188 (_adv._), 258; _wythlyttel_, with little result (_or_ ? soon), VI 215; #Litel#, #Litle#,

2437.entry: #Lyttill#, _adv._ little, IV _b_ 24, VII 36, VIII _b_ 3, XI _b_ 253, &c.[OE. _lȳtel_, adj.] _See_ Lite.

2440.entry: #Lyþer#, #Leder#, _adj._ bad; sluggish, XVII 289; as _sb._, in _to lyþeris lyfte_, ? is turned towards evil, VI 207. [OE. _lȳ̆þre_.]

2443.entry: #Leue#, XVI 243, 322, 353, &c.; #Lyfed#, _2 sg. pa. t._ VI 123; _pres.p._ living, (while) alive, IV _b_ 31, XII _a_ 171, XVI 55, XVII 47, 48,73, &c.; _lyue men_, let men live, XI _a_ 46; _liuen bi_, &c., live on,II 257, VIII _b_ 26 (but _lyue on_, VIII _b_ 46, &c.); _lyue (leue)with_, live by, VIII _b_ 44, XVI 160. [OE. _lifian_, _leofian_.] _See_Libben, Lif.

2444.entry: #Lo#, #Loo#, _interj._ lo! II 381, 556, XVII 239; look, see, II 505,507; #Lew#, XVII 507; _we loo_, alas! V 140 (_see_ We, _interj._). [OE._lā_; ME. vowel and usage show infl. of Loken.]

2448.entry: #Lofte#, _n._ air, in _on lofte_, aloft, V 193. [ON. _loft_, _á loft_.]_See_ Alofte, Lyft.

2452.entry: #Loke(n)#, #Look#, _v._ to look, I 124, XVII 129, &c.; #Lokyt#, _pa. t._VII 36; #Yloked#, _pp._ III 58. _Intr._ (i) to look, gaze, I 124, II112, III 34, V 78, &c.; have an expression, VIII _a_ 315; appear, VIII_a_ 170; _loken (app)on_, look at, VIII _a_ 179, XI _b_ 175; read, VII75; _on lusti to loke_, pleasant to read, VII 15; _loke agaynste_, gaze(straight) at, XVI 92; _loke to_, look at, V 265; (ii) to makeinvestigations, VII 36; (iii) to see to it, take care; foll. by _þat_and _subj._, II 165, XVI 152, 211; without conj., IV _a_ 19, 46, VIII_a_ 39, XIV _d_ 7, XVII 129. _Trans._ to watch over, in _God þe motloke_, may God have you in his keeping, V 171; adjudicate, III 58;ordain, decree, VIII _a_ 313. _Loke what_, consider what (_i.e._whatever, _interrog._), VI 103 (cf. OE. _lōc(a) hwæt_, indef.). [OE._lōcian_.]

2455.entry: #Lollare#, #-ere#, _n._ idler, vagabond, VIII _b_ 2, 4; #Lollarene#,_gen. pl._ VIII _b_ 31. [From ME. _lollen_, to lounge; _see_ Piers Pl. CX 215.]

2456.entry: #Lomb(e)#, #Lamb#, _n._ lamb, IX 142; used of Our Lord, VI 47, 53. [OE._lómb_, _lámb_.]

2458.entry: #Lond(e)#, #Land(e)#, _n._ land, country, soil, I 25, II 208, 355, VII163, VIII _a_ 267, IX 179, XIV _b_ 63, &c.; _in land(e)_, on earth, XVI68, 314, XVII 145; _þurgh land and lede_, I 227 (_see_ Lede, _n._^2).[OE. _lónd_, _lánd_.]

2461.entry: #Long(e)#, _adj._ long, II 506, IX 152, 155, &c.; _longe clothes_,clerical garb, VIII _b_ 42; tall, VIII _b_ 24; lasting long, I 203, VIII_a_ 7; _þy long home_, your eternal home (after death), I 207 (OE. _langhām_); _for long ȝore_, a long while, VI 226; _þe long day_, _thel. night ouer_, _al þe woke l._, all day (&c.) long, VI 237, VII 166,XIII _a_ 28 (_cf._ next); tedious, IX 267. [OE. _láng_, _lóng_.]

2462.entry: #Long(e)#, #Lang#, _adv._ a long while, II 335, V 232, VIII _a_ 19, _b_84, XV _c_ 19, XVII 244, &c.; after an _advb. gen._, in _hys lyueȝlonge_, _þise dayeȝ longe_, all his life (this day) long, VI 117, 173(_cf._ prec.); #Leng#, _compar._ longer, II 84; #Lenger(e)#, #Lengar#, I79, II 330, V 235, XI _b_ 130, XII _b_ 146, XVI 68, 193; _euer þe lengerþe lasse þe more_, the further (you pursue the argument) the less (work)the more (pay), VI 240; #Longer#, XVII 531. [OE. _lónge_, _lánge_;compar. _léng_ (adv.), _lengra_ (adj.).]

2463.entry: #Long(e)#, _v._^1 to long, VII 113; #Langand#, _pres. p._ in _langandes_, longs, IV _a_ 91. [OE. _lóngian_, _lángian_.]

2464.entry: #Long(e)#, _v._^2; _longe to_ (_into_), to belong (to), befit, V 313,XIV _c_ 25, 53; #Longande#, _pres. p._ that belongs, VI 102. [From ME._(i)long_, adj.; OE. _ge-láng (on)_, dependent (on).] _See_ Bylongeth.

2466.entry: #Longith#, _3 sg. pres._ lengthens, ? beats out long, XV _h_ 17. [FromLong, _adj._]

2467.entry: #Lording#, #-yng#, _n._ man of high rank, II 26, 520; sir (as a politeaddress, _esp._ of minstrel to his audience), II 23, 204. [OE._hlāfording_.] _See_ Louerd.

2471.entry: #Lorel(l)is#, _n. pl._ good-for-nothings, wastrels, XI _b_ 140, 161,173. [Prob. from prec.] _See_ Loseles.

2473.entry: #Loseles#, _n. pl._ wastrels, VIII _a_ 116. [Prob. from ME. _lose(n)_,variant of _lore(n)_ pp. of Lese, _v._^1] _See_ Lorel(l)is.

2476.entry: #Lost#, _n._ loss, VIII _b_ 101. [Rel. to Lese, _v._^1; cf. OE., ME._los_.]

2478.entry: #Loþ#, #Lothe#, _adj._ hateful, I 9; loath, unwilling, XIV _c_ 6. [OE._lāþ_, adj.]

2481.entry: #Loud(e)#, _adj._ loud, II 511, XII _a_ 138; _loud or still_, under allcircumstances, XIV _b_ 54. [OE. _hlūd_.]

2482.entry: #Loue#, _n._ love, II *12, 55, &c.; #Louue#, XV _a_ 21; #Luf(e)#, I_introd._, IV _a_ 1, 5, XVII 82; with _object. gen._ (as _mi lordesloue_, love for my master), II 518 (note), VIII _a_ 19, 214; _þi loue_,love of thee, VIII _a_ 27; _for loue or ay_, in any event, II 571. [OE._lufu_.] _See_ Louye.

2483.entry: #Louely#, _adj._ gracious, beautiful, pleasant, VIII _a_ 10, 272, XVI119. [OE. _luf(e)lic_.] _See_ Luflyly.

2486.entry: #Lhord#, III _introd._, 11, 29, 46; #Lord(e)#, II 120, 518, VIII _a_ 19,272, XII _a_ 157, &c.; #Lordene#, _gen. pl._ VIII _b_ 77. [OE._hlāford_.]

2490.entry: #Louȝ#, _pa. t. sg._ laughed, II 314; #Loȝe#, V 321; #Loh# (_on_),smiled (upon), XV _c_ 15. [OE. _hlæhhan_, pa. t. _hlōh_.]

2492.entry: #Loue(n)#, II 34, IX 100, 101, XII _a_ 5, &c.; #Luf(e)#, #Luffe#, IV _a_4, _b_ 7, V 300, XVI 403, XVII 47, &c.; #Yloued#, _pp._ II 123. [OE._lufian_.]

2496.entry: #Loupe#, _n._ any jewel of imperfect brilliance (_esp._ sapphire, withwhich it is often joined), IX 116. [OFr. _loupe_.]

2498.entry: #Low(e)#, #Law#, _adj._ low, VII 102, X 137, XVII 21; near the bottom,VI 187; lowly, VIII _a_ 223, &c.; _heiȝe and lowe_, all men, XIV _c_100; _adv._ low, V 168, XII _b_ 11, &c.; _thus low_, here below, in solowly a place, XVII 173. [ON. _lág-r_.]

2500.entry: #Lowe#, _v._ to praise; _to lowe_, praiseworthy, II 12 (MS. Harl.);_cf._ _Sir Gaw._ 1399, and (for idiom) Wale. [OFr. _louer_.] _See_Allowe.

2502.entry: #Lowte#, _v._ to bow; _trans._ (but _see_ Þat, _rel._) bow before,reverence, XV _i_ 4; #Lutte#, _pa. t. sg._ bowed, V 187; _refl._ V 168.[OE. _lūtan_, str.]

2503.entry: #Lud#, _n._, in _on hyre lud_, ? in her own language, XV _c_ 4. [? OE._lēoden_, _lȳden_, language.]

2506.entry: #Luflyly#, _adv._ courteously, V 321; in seemly manner, V 108. [FromLouely.]

2507.entry: #Lunatyk#, _adj._ suffering from recurrent fits of insanity (thought todepend on the changes of the moon), IX 93. [L. _lūnāticus_.]

2510.entry: #Lust#, _n._ pleasure, desire, IV _a_ 16, 59; lust, IV _b_ 17, IX 277.[OE. _lust_.] _See_ Lyste.

2521.entry: #Mai#, _v. 1_ & _3 pres._ (_ind._ and _subj._), am able to, can, may,may well, have reason to, &c., IV _a_ 31, XII _a_ 66, XIV _c_ 1, &c.;

2524.entry: #Myȝt(e)#, II 452, VIII _a_ 217, _b_ 35. #Mai#, #May#, _pl._ IV _a_61, IX 213, &c.; #Moun#, VI 176; #Mowe#, I 115, VIII _a_ 40, IX 164, &c.

2525.entry: #Micht#, #Mycht#, _pa. t._ (_ind._ and _subj._), was able to, could,might, &c., X 17, 139, &c., #Miȝt(e)#, #Myȝt(e)#, I 16, II 221,VIII _a_ 133, XI _a_ 44, _b_ 283, &c.; #Myȝtte#, XI _b_ 30, 103;

2526.entry: #Myght(e)#, I 184, IX 276, &c.; #Mihte#, #Myhte#, XII _a_ 16, 75, XIV_c_ 36, &c.; #Moȝt(e)#, VI 67, 115, 119, #Moghte#, IV _b_ 31. [OE._mæg_ (_meaht_, _miht_, 2 sg.); late pl. _mugon_, subj. _muge_; pa. t._mihte_ (late _muhte_).]

2527.entry: #Mai#, #May#, _n._^1 maiden, VI 75, XV _a_ 6, 16, _c_ 28, Introductionxii. [ON. _mǽ-r_, gen. _meyj-ar_; cf. OE. _mǣg_, woman (inverse).]

2528.entry: #May#, _n._^2 May, II 57, IV _a_ 57; #May dew#, dew gathered in May(thought to have special properties), IX 63. [OFr. _mai_.] _See_ Deaw.

2530.entry: #Mayde(n)#, #Maiden#, _n._ maiden, virgin, I 41, II 64, VIII _a_ 323, XV_i_ 7, &c. [OE. _mægden_.]

2535.entry: #Maistre# (#-er#, #-ur#), #Mayster#, _n._ lord, Lord, II 413, VI 102,VII 1, XIII _a_ 2; master, V 22, VIII _a_ 41, 236, 314, XV _h_ 17;_mayster of gramere_, a title, XIII _b_ 27 (_see_ note). [OFr._maistre_; OE. _mægester_.]

2536.entry: #Maistrie#, #Maystrie#, _n._ mastery, VIII _a_ 323; _for the maystrie_(OFr. _pour la maistrie_), to the utmost possible degree, IX 233; _pl._(partly due to OFr. _maistrise_, sg.) in _make maistries_, do awonderful, mighty (_here_ masterful, high handed) deed, XVI 116, 202,216, 217. [OFr. _maistrie_.]

2538.entry: #Make(n)#, #Mak#, _v._ to make, do; (with or without _to_) cause,compel; VIII _a_ 205, 280, IX 120, 206, XIV _b_ 87, &c.; #Ma#, X 14,167; #Mase#, _3 sg._ IV _a_ 15; #Matȝ#, VI 250; #Mais#, _pl._ X 72;

2539.entry: #Man#, VI 152; #Mase#, XIV _b_ 34, XVI 116; #Makes#, #Maketh#, _imper.pl._ VIII _a_ 14, XVI 383. #Mad#, #Made(n)#, _pa. t._ I 39, II 20, VI179, &c.; #Maid(e)#, X 5, XVII 3 (_2 sg._), 28, &c.; #Maked#, II 329,498, &c. #Maad(e)#, _pp._ XI _b_ 101, 196, &c.; #Mad#, VI 126, VIII _b_74, &c.; #Maid(e)#, X 3, XVII 73, &c.; #Ymad#, III _introd._; #Ymaked#,VIII _a_ 180. _Mad sumoun_, caused (men) to summon (them), VI 179;_makes ioie_, rejoice, XVI 383: _it maketh_, brings it about (that),VIII _a_ 199; _ich made of_, I summed up (as Mn. E. idiom), VIII _b_ 5;_see also_ Dere, Qwart, Ylet, &c. [OE. _macian_; with the reduced formscf. Taken.]

2541.entry: #Maker#, _n._ maker, causer, I 204; Creator, VII 1, XVI 2, XVII 1. [FromMaken.]

2544.entry: #Malice#, #Malis#, _n._ evil purpose, ill-will, VII 177, IX 119, XVI302. [OFr. _malice_.]

2545.entry: #Malt#, _pa. t. sg._ melted, V 12. [OE. _meltan_, pa. t. _malt_.]

2547.entry: #Man(e)#, #Manne#, _n._ man, mankind, (any)body, one, I 102, II 27, IV_a_ 12, _b_ 62, XVII 236, &c.; #Mon#, V 32, 170, 271 (note), VI 160, &c._Gen. sg._ (often generic, equiv. to 'human', &c.), #Manes(se)#, II 552,XV _i_ 16; #Mannes#, #-is#, #-ys#, #-us#, III 54, VIII _a_ 234 (note),XI _b_ 113, 114, XII _b_ 139, XVI 246, &c.; #Mans#, in _mans wonder_,monster, XVII 408. #Manne#, _dat. sg._ III 19. #Men(e)#, _pl._ I 32, IV_b_ 9, &c.; #Men(ne)#, #Mene#, _gen. pl._ men's, people's, &c., IV _b_69 (footnote), VIII _b_ 29, XIII _b_ 20; #Mennes#, #-ys#, #-us#, I 82,VIII _a_ 96, XI _b_ 119, 192; #Mens#, IV _b_ 50, *69 (footnote). [OE._man(n)_, _mon(n)_.] _See_ Men, Noman.

2548.entry: #Manaced#, _pa. t._ threatened, VIII _a_ 163; #Mansed#, V 277. [OFr._manecier_, _manasser_; cf. Comsed, for the reduction.]

2549.entry: #Manans#, _n._ threat, X 72. [OFr. _manace_, with confusion of suffix.]

2551.entry: #Maner(e)#, #Manyere# (III), _n._ (a) manner, way, I 80, X 103, XI _a_11, XIII _b_ 30 (without foll. _of_), &c.; _in his manere_, after hisfashion, VIII _a_ 104; custom, II 431, XIII _b_ 17, 26; kind, sort, IX102, 139, &c.; _any (ich) maner_, any (every) kind of, II 364, VIII _a_213; with _sg._ form after _al(le)_, _meny_, and numerals (usuallywithout _of_), II 302, III _introd._, VIII _a_ 20, XIII _a_ 37, _b_ 1,9, &c.; _deuyse, tell, the maner (of)_, describe, IX 264, 268;

2556.entry: #Mani(e)#, #Many(e)#, _adj._ many, I 133, II 294, III 41, VIII _a_ 100,&c.; #Meny(e)#, VIII _b_ 36, XIII _a_ 6, &c.; #Moni#, #Mony#, V 201, VI212, &c.; _mani (moni) a_, &c., many a, II 432, XIV _c_ 68, 92, &c.;(without _a_), I 157 (note), II 520, XVII 355, 436; _many ... fold(e)_,_see_ Fold(e). [OE. _manig_, _menig_, _monig_.]

2558.entry: #Manyfold#, _adj._ many times multiplied, great, XII _b_ 154. [OE._manig-fáld_.] _See_ Fold.

2562.entry: #Mappa Mundi#, _n._ map, _or_ descriptive geography, of the world, IX301. [Latin; also appears in ME. in Fr. form _mappe-mounde_.]

2563.entry: #Mar#, #Marre#, _v._ to hinder, stop, XVI 116, XVII 129 (_subj._);_marre ... to_, prevent from, XVI 173; to destroy, V 194, XVI 208. [OE._merran_, hinder, spoil.]

2567.entry: #Marche#, _v._; _marcheth_ (_to_, _upon_), borders on, IX 193, XII _a_61. [OFr. _marchir_, from prec.]

2569.entry: #Maryage#, _n._ marriage; _to Hys m._, as His spouse, VI 54. [OFr._mariage_.]

2570.entry: #Mark#, _n._ a mark (about 2/3 of a pound, 13_s._ 4_d._), XI _b_ 162.[OE. _marc_, a borrowed word of disputed origin.]

2575.entry: #Masse#, _n._^1 Mass, VIII _a_ 88, XI _b_ 131, &c.; #Messe#, I 8, 69, VI137, &c. [OE. _mæsse_, _messe_; OFr. _messe_.]

2581.entry: #Mater(e)#, #Matiere#, _n._ matter, subject, VII 35, 98, IX 111, XII _a_45, XIV _c_ 14. [OFr. _mat(i)ere_.]

2583.entry: #Matyn(n)es#, #-ys#, _n. pl._ matins (first of the canonical 'hours',properly recited at midnight or before daybreak), V 120, XI _b_ 131,189, &c.; applied to all the morning office preceding public Mass, I 68,? XI _b_ 208; _matynes of Oure Lady_, matins proper to Our Lady (made apart of daily morning office), XI _b_ 132. [OFr. _matines_.]

2585.entry: #Maugré# (#-ee#), #Mawgree#, _prep._ in spite of, VIII _a_ 69, IX 197,314; #Magré#, X 197; _m. Medes (þi) chekes_, in spite of Meed (you),VIII _a_ 41, 151 (an extension of ME. _maugré þin_, _his_, &c. where_þin_, &c., are orig. _gen._). [OFr. _maugré_.]

2593.entry: #Mede#, _n._ reward; Lady Meed (personif. of bribery, &c.), VIII _a_ 41;_to mede_, in payment, as reward, IV _a_ 64, XIV _b_ 2, XVII 122; _qwitehym his m._, pay him out, XVII 216. [OE. _mēd_.]

2597.entry: #Medyn#, ? _n. pl._ meadows, XV _i_ 14 (such a pl. form is remarkable inthis text, if genuine). [OE. _mǣd_, _mēd_.]

2600.entry: #Meyny#, _n._ household, body (of servants, &c.), retinue, company, VI182; #Meneye#, XVII 290; #Menȝhe#, X 39; #Menye#, VII 37, XVII 22.[OFr. _mai(s)nee_.]

2601.entry: #Meyntene(n)#, #Mayntene#, _v._ to maintain, defend, support, keep up,VIII _a_ 37, XI _b_ 43, 55, 166, XIV _c_ 76; _subj._, XIV _c_ 100;

2604.entry: #Meke#, _adj._ meek, humble, submissive, IV _a_ 74, VI 44, VIII _a_ 199,XI _b_ 58, XVI 1. [ON. _mjúk-r_, earlier _*meuk-_.]

2605.entry: #Mekenesse#, _n._ meekness, gentleness, VI 46, VIII _a_ 41(personified), XI _b_ 118, 122. [From prec.]

2609.entry: #Mekis#, _2 sg. pres._ in _mekis þiselffe_, humblest thyself, XVI 350.[From Meke, _adj._]

2610.entry: #Mele#, _v._ to speak, say, V 227, 268, 305, VI 137, 229, ? *XV _b_ 20(MS. miles). [OE. _mǣlan_.]

2612.entry: #Mell#, _v._^1 to announce, declare; ? grant, XVII 44 (_or_ from next,in vague use extended from that seen in XVI). [OE. _meðlan_.] Cf. Mele.

2617.entry: #Memoire#, #Memorye#, _n._ memory, XII _b_ 221; commemoration (of thefaithful departed), VIII _a_ 89. [OFr. _memoire_, _memorie_.]

2618.entry: #Men#, _impers. subject sg._ one, IX 69; also freq. (esp. in _men may_)in syntactically doubtful cases prob. apprehended as pl., as IX 75(first), 118, XV _h_ 3, &c.; #Me#, III 3, 16, 48, 51, XIII _a_ 9, XV _g_8, 28. [OE. _man_, reduced under wk. stress.] _See_ Man (_esp._ V 170).

2620.entry: #Mend(e)#, _v._ to improve; make better (free from fault), XVI 359;increase (joy), XVI 79; _mend ȝow of ȝoure misdede_, reform yourevil ways, XIV _b_ 7; #Mendyng#, _n._ improvement, VI 92. [Shortenedfrom Amend.]

2624.entry: #Mene(n)#, _v._^1 to mean; signify, I _introd._, VIII _b_ 38, XVI 46;declare (as one's intention), XVI 174; to intend, *XVI 301 (MS. mouys);to imagine, suppose XI _b_ 74 (_or_ imply); _impers._ in _me menys_, Icall to mind, XVI 231; #Menede#, _pa. t._ VIII _b_ 38; #Mente#, _pa. t._I _introd._; _pp._ XVI 174; #Ymende#, _pp._ noted, III _introd._ [OE._mǣnan_.]

2625.entry: #Mene#, _v._^2 to complain, XV _b_ 22; _refl._ in _mened hem_, madetheir complaint, VIII _a_ 2. [OE. _mǣnan_, v.^2; prob. distinct fromprec., and rel. to Mon(e), _q.v._]

2632.entry: #Menskes#, _n. pl._ honours, V 342. [ON. _mennska_, humanity, kindness,? hence in ME. grace, courtesy, honour; cf. senses of OE. _ār_.]

2636.entry: #Merci#, #Mercy(e)#, #Mersy#, _n._ mercy, I 167, II 113, III 1, VI 23,VIII _a_ 40 (personified), XVI 359, &c.; _grant merci_, thank you, V 58,XII _b_ 92 (_see_ Grant). [OFr. _merci_.]

2637.entry: #Mercii#, _n. pl._ Mercians, men of the Midlands, XIII _b_ 54. [Med.L._Mercii_; OE. _Merce_.]

2643.entry: #Meruayl(l)e#, #-uail(e)#, #-ueyl(l)e#, &c. (_of_), _n._ amazement,wonder (at), I 211, IX 151, 226; marvel, II 409, 598, IX 143, 146, 292,&c.; a marvel (without _a_), I 115, 205, IX 18; _no meruayle þaȝ_(with _subj._), no wonder (if), V 239. [OFr. _merveille_.]

2655.entry: #Mette#, XVI 230; _esp._ joined with _drink_, I 158, II 254, VIII _a_20, XI _b_ 257, XVII 197; _at(te) mete_, at table, II 519, VIII _a_ 55,XV _g_ 24. [OE. _mete_.]

2656.entry: #Mete(n)#, _v._ to meet, II 510, V 138, 167, VI 20, XIV _a_ 27; #Mette#,_pa. t._, VIII _a_ 163, _b_ 6. [OE. _mētan_.] _See_ Imete.

2660.entry: #Meue#, #Moue#, _v._ to move; _trans._ (inspire), XI _a_ 66, _b_ 246;_intr._ proceed, pass on, VII 98; #Meuyt#, _pa. t._ passed, VII 30;

2664.entry: #Miche#, #Myche#, _adj._ great, much, II 278, 523, 560, VII 41, 122.[OE. _micel_.] _See_ Mekill, Mochel, More.

2669.entry: #Myddel-erde#, #Medill-erd#, _n._ the world, V 32, XVII 100, 234.[Altered by assoc. with prec. from OE. _middan-(g)eard_.]

2673.entry: #Mighty#, #Myghty#, _adj._ mighty, VII 177, &c.; _was so myghty to_, hadthe power to, XVI 91; _quasi-sb._ mighty princes, VII 118. [OE._mihtig_.]

2674.entry: #Myȝt(e)#, _n._ might, power, strength, capacity, I 84, 186, VIII _a_195, XI _b_ 114; #Mycht#, X 48, 65, &c.; #Myght#, IX 197, XVI 233, &c.;

2675.entry: #Miste#, #Myste# (_see_ App. p. 278), XV _g_ 29; _of myste_, mighty, VI102; _pl._ deeds of power, XVI 174; _do (all) his myȝt_, &c., do allin his power, X 79, XI _b_ 6; _with thair mychtis all_, with all theirmight, X 95; _at my myght_, as far as I can, XVII 322. [OE. _miht_.]

2679.entry: #Mile#, #Myle#, _n._ mile; _sg._ for _pl._ after numerals, II 350, XIV_b_ 42; _wel a four grete myle_, fully (a distance of) four 'longmiles', IX 200 (_see_ note). [OE. _mīl_.]

2680.entry: #Miles#, ? _n. pl._ XV _b_ 20; ? read _meles murge <wi>þ_, call lovingly to;_see_ Mele, _v._

2681.entry: #Myn#, _adj._ smaller, _in more and myn_, all, XVII 112, 278. [ON._minni_; _meiri ok minni_.]

2682.entry: #Myn#, #Mynne#, _v._ to remember, recall, mention, VII 30, 37; _myn(ne)of_, be mindful of, VI 223, XVII 551. [ON. _minna_, remind; _minna-sk_,remember.]

2684.entry: #Mynd(e)#, _n._ mind, memory, VII 10, 11, 30, IX 319, XVI 2; _take inm._, recollect, XII _a_ 194, _b_ 223. [OE. _(ge-)mýnd_.]

2690.entry: #Mynt#, #Munt#, _n._ aim; feint, pretence at a blow, V 277, 282, 284.[From next.]

2691.entry: #Mynte#, _v._ to aim, swing (an axe), V 222; #Mynte#, #Munt#, _pa. t.sg._ V 194, 206. [OE. _myntan_.]

2693.entry: #Mire#, #Myre#, mire; _fig._ a desperate situation, XIV _b_ 71, XVI 256.[ON. _mýr-r_.]

2694.entry: #Miri(e)#, #Myrie#, _adj._ merry, joyous, gay, II 58, 436, VIII _a_ 151,XV _a_ 11, 16, &c.; #Mery#, VIII _a_ 69, XVII 463; #Myryest#, _superl._VI 75; #Muryly#, _adv._ pleasantly, playfully, V 227, 268, 277. [OE._myrge_.] _See_ Mirth(e), Murgeþ.

2695.entry: #Mirke#, #Merke#, _adj._ dark, VII 108; _n._ darkness, XVI 53. [OE._myrce_, ON. _myrk-r_, adj.]

2702.entry: #Myschefe#, #-cheif#, #-chief#, _n._ distress, damage, misfortune, I175, VIII _a_ 199, X 136, 178; #Meschief#, XII _b_ 14. [OFr._mesch(i)ef_.]

2707.entry: #Myslyke#, _v. impers._ it displeases, is unpleasant to; _subj._ IV _b_58, V 239. [OE. _mis-līcian_.]

2709.entry: #Mysse#, #Mys#, _n._ (sense of) loss, VI 4; misery, XVII 551; #Mysses#,_pl._ offences, faults, V 323. [OE. _miss_, and _mis-_ prefix.] _See_Amys.

2710.entry: #Misse#, #Mys(se)#, _v._ to miss; _misse (of)_, fail (in), VII 118, XVII404; to do without, XVII 237; lack, VI 22. [OE. _missan_.]

2714.entry: #Mister#, #Myster#, _n._ need, IV _b_ 58, 67, X 151, 161; #Maister#, in_hom maister were_, was their duty, VII 35. [OFr. _mest(i)er_,_meistier_.]

2717.entry: #Mo#, _adj._ and _quasi-pron._ more (in number), others, I 133, II 90,350, V 254, IX 153, XIV _d_ 7, XV _b_ 22, XVI 358, XVII 134, &c.; #Moo#,XVI 208, 328. [OE. _mā_, compar. adv.]

2718.entry: #Moche#, _adv._ greatly, much, IX 101, 300, XI _b_ 107, 183, &c.; to agreat extent, XIII _b_ 41; #Much(e)#, VI 14, XI _b_ 297, &c. [OE._mycel_, _mycle_.] _See_ Mekill, Mor(e), Mo.

2720.entry: #Moche#, II 36, III 25, 32, XIII _a_ 51, &c.; #Much#, V 72, 268, VI 244,&c.; _in so moche_, to the corresponding extent, XI _b_ 232; _in somoche þat_, in as much as, IX 299. [OE. _mycel_.] _See_ Mekill, Miche,More.

2724.entry: #Moder#, _gen. sg._ XI _b_ 29; as _adj._ in _modir tunge_, XI _a_ 40.[OE. _mōdor_.]

2729.entry: #Mold(e)#, _n._ earth, in tag _(ap)on mold(e)_, on earth, alive, XIV _b_3, XVI 1, 91, XVII 62. [OE. _mólde_.]

2731.entry: #Mon(e)#, _n._ complaint, lamentation, grief, II 198, VI 14, VIII _a_117, XIV _a_ 27. [OE. _*mān_, rel. to Mene, _v._^2]

2732.entry: #Mone#, _n._ moon, XV _b_ 16, 25, XVII 355; #Moyne#, XVII 6; lunarmonth, 478; _abouen þe m._, to the skies, ridiculously high, XI _b_ 182.[OE. _mōna_.]

2738.entry: #Monthe#, _n._ month, VIII _b_ 52, XII _a_ 34, &c.; _pl._ (orig. _gen._)in _tuo monthe day_, two months' time, XII _a_ 29 (_see_ Day). [OE._mōn(a)þ_.] _See_ Tweluemonth(e).

2741.entry: #More#, _adj. compar._ greater, V 32, IX 28, 245, &c.; more, further,&c. (easily passing into _adv._, as XIV _b_ 3, &c.), II 264, V 180, XVI106, &c.; _quasi-sb._ a greater amount, more, VI 193, 217, 240 (_see_Longe _adv._), &c.; _more and les(se)_, _les and more_, all, XVI 383,XVII 11, 94; _more and myn_, all, XVII 112, 278 (_see_ Myn). #Mast#,_superl._ greatest, most, X 18, 38, 104; #Most(e)#, XI _b_ 25, XIV _c_15, XVI 360; _both the m. and the leest_, all, XVII 452; _þe most_,(the) most (part), I 23. [OE. _māra_; _mǣst_ (late Nth. _māst_,with vowel of compar.).] _See_ Mekill, &c.

2742.entry: #Mor(e)#, #Mare# (IV, XIV), _adv. compar._ more, VI 193, &c.; forming_compar._, VI 239, IX 248, XII _b_ 130, &c.; longer, further, in thefuture, again, &c. (_esp._ in _no more_, _na mare_, &c.), I 83, 144, IV_a_ 58, XIV _b_ 3 (or _adj._), &c.; moreover, VI 205; _noȝt ...more_, not ... either, VI 228; _no more bot_, none the more except that,V 243. #Mast# (IV), #Moost#, #Most(e)#, _superl._ most(ly), for the mostpart, II 12, 33 (_see_ Ony), IV _a_ 77, VII 10, XI _a_ 20, &c.; forming_superl._, IX 42, &c. [As prec.; for older compar. adv. _see_ Mo.] _See_Mekill, &c.; Nomore.

2743.entry: #Moreyn#, _n._ plague; _þe furste moreyn_, the Black Death (1349), XIII_b_ 26. [OFr. _morine_.]

2744.entry: #Morn(e)#, _n._ morning, morrow, I 137, V 282. [OE. _morne_ dat. sg.]_See_ Morwe.

2745.entry: #Mornyf#, _adj._ mournful, VI 26. [Stem of Mournen + OFr. _-if_; cf.OFr. _morni_.]

2750.entry: #Morwe#, #Morow#, _n._ morning, morrow, VIII _a_ 140, XII _a_ 152, _b_176, &c.; _fram m. til euen_, all day, VIII _a_ 178, (reversed for rime)XVII 205. [OE. _morgen_.] _See_ Morn(e).

2752.entry: #Mot(e)#, _v._ may, II 532, V 52, XI _b_ 115, XIV _c_ 87, &c.; must, II125, 248, VIII _a_ 284, XI _a_ 38, &c.; #Most# (_to_), _2 sg. pres._must go (to), XV _g_ 3; #Most(e)#, _pa. t._ might, II 233, 330; must, is(was) bound to, II 468, IX 197, 287, XI _b_ 205; #Must(e)#, XVI 274,XVII 130 (_2 sg._); _impers._ in _must vs_, we must, XVII 292, 334. [OE._mōt_, pa. t. _mōste_.]

2755.entry: #Mournen#, _v._ to mourn, XV _c_ 34; #Mournyng#, _n._ mourning, sorrow,IV _a_ 72; #Murning#, XIV _b_ 2; #Mornynge#, XI _b_ 118, 125, 130, &c.[OE. _múrnan_.]

2760.entry: #Mouþe#, _n._ (_dat. sg._) mouth, II 465; _be mouthe_, by word of m.,XII _b_ 199. [OE. _mūþ_.]

2763.entry: #Mowe(n)#, _v._^2 to stack (in mows), VIII _b_ 14 (second). [OE._mūga_, _mūwa_, a mow, heap.]

2766.entry: #Muged#, _pa. t._ drizzled, was damp, V 12. [Cf. Norw. _mugga_, drizzle,and _Mug_^4 in _E.D.D._]

2770.entry: #Multiplye(n)#, _v._ to multiply, increase; _trans._ III 1, VIII _a_120, 323; _intr._ IX 60, XVII 31, 179. [OFr. _multiplier_.]

2777.entry: #Mused#, _pa. t._ mused; existed, were, V 356 (characteristic action of'_homo rationalis_' standing for verb 'to be'; cf. _flaȝe_, VI 71).[OFr. _muser_.]

2780.entry: #Nabbe#, _1 sg. pres. ind._ have not, XV _f_ 8, 11; #Nade#, _pa. t._ hadnot (with another neg.), II 392. [OE. _nabban_, _næfde_.] _See_ Habbe,Ne.

2782.entry: #Naȝt#, _n._ night; _be naȝt_, by night, by the time night hascome, VI 163. [OE. _næht_.] _See_ Nyght.

2784.entry: #Nauȝte#, _adv._ not, VIII _a_ 43; (with neg. verb) III 42. [OE._nā-wiht_, _nā(u)ht_.] _See_ Nat, Noȝt.

2785.entry: #Nay(e)#, _adv._ nay, II 131, III 26, XVI 335, &c.; as sb., in_withoutten nay_, undeniably, XVII 2 (_cf._ No). [ON. _nei_.]

2788.entry: #Nale#; _atte nale_ = _atten ale_, at the ale, over their ale, VIII _a_109. [OE. _alu_.] _See_ Atte.

2789.entry: #Nam#, _1 sg. pres. ind._ am not; _nam bot_, am only, II 430. [OE._nam_.] _See_ Ne.

2791.entry: #Name#, _n._ name, I 37, VII 60, XV _i_ 10, &c.; good name, praise, XI_b_ 257; #Nome#, VII _introd._; _be name_ (_nome_), by name,individually, I _introd._, 46, VII 37; _by name_, especially, XVI 190;_bi Godes name_ (oath), II 316. [OE. _nama_, _noma_.]

2795.entry: #Nar(e)#, _pres. ind. pl._ are not (with neg.), II 390, V 24. [OE._naron_.] _See_ Ne.

2797.entry: #Nas#, #Nes# (III), _pa. t. sg._ (usually with neg.) was not, II 98,150, 354, III 42, XV _g_ 28; #Nere#, _pl._ II 123; _subj._ would be, II457. [OE. _næs_ (Kt. _nes_); _nǣron_, _nǣre_.]

2798.entry: #Nat#, _neg. adv._ not, I 12, 97, 132, VIII _b_ 93. [Reduced form ofNaȝt, _q.v._]

2805.entry: #Nauþer#, #Nawþer#, V, VI; #Noþer#, I, VIII, XIII; #Nouþer#, #-ur#, XIV_c_; #Nowder#, XVII; #Nowþer#, #Nowther#, XIV _b_; #Nowthir#, XVI;_adv._ neither, either (after a neg.), V 299; _conj._ neither (foll. by_ne_, _nor_), I 118, V 206, XIV _b_ 75, 78, _c_ 57, 62, XVI 287, XVII534, &c.; (foll. by _then_) XVII 535; nor, XIII _a_ 13, 37. [OE._nā-hwæþer_, _nō-hwæþer_, _nā(w)þor_, _nōþer_, &c.] _See_Neyther, Noiþer.

2807.entry: #Ne#, _adv._ not (preceding verb), I 73, V 74, VIII _a_ 138, 172, &c.;(usually with another neg., esp. _noȝt_, &c.), I 71, 156, III 18, VI2, &c.; coalescing with auxil. verbs, _see_ Nabbe, Nam, Nar(e), Nas,Nil, Nis, Not; _conj._ nor, I 118, 160, IV _a_ 2, &c.; _ne ... ne_,neither ... nor, nor ... nor, I 158, IX 201; (foll. by another neg.)and, I 12, 153, VIII _a_ 280, IX 181, &c. [OE. _ne_.]

2808.entry: #Nede#, #Neid# (X), _n._ need, IV _b_ 67, X 18, XI _b_ 259, XVII 426;_at nede_, in time of need, VIII _a_ 113; _pl._ wants, business, V 148.[OE. _nēd_.]

2809.entry: #Nedes#, _adv._ needs, of necessity, II 468, IX 288, XI _b_ 205. [OE._nēdes_.]

2810.entry: #Nedeth#, #Nudeþ#, _pres. (impers.) sg._ (it) is necessary, VIII _a_240, _b_ 20; _hem nedeth_, they have need, VIII _a_ 203; #Neyd#, withmixed constr. in _neyd thowe_, you need, XVI 242. [OE. _nēodian_;_cf._ next.]

2813.entry: #Nedy#, _adj._ needy, in want, VIII _a_ 15, 218; as jocular name, XVII405. [OE. _nēadig-_, _*nēdig_.]

2816.entry: #Negh# (_nere_), _v. intr._ to approach, XVI 224; #Nyghys#, _3 sg.pres._ XVII 370; #Neighed#, _pa. t._ VIII _a_ 294. [From Nyȝ, _q.v._]

2818.entry: #Neyther#, #Neiþer#, _adv._; _ne neyther_, and neither, VIII _a_ 276;_neiþer ... ne_, neither ... nor, XI _b_ 190, 286. [OE. _ne_ +_ǣgþer_; cf. _nāhwæþer_.] _See_ Nauþer, Noiþer.

2823.entry: #Ner(e)#, #Neir# (X), _compar. adj._ and _adv._ nearer, I 255; as_pos._, near, X 77, XII _b_ 114, XVI 43, 224, XVII 370; _adv._ nearly,VIII _a_ 171, XVII 412; _prep._ near (to), VI 44, VIII _a_ 294, X 67;

2824.entry: #Nest#, _superl._ next, I 215; #Next(e)#, nearest, VII 13; next, I 138,&c. [OE. _nēar(a)_, compar. (cf. ON. _nǽr_, compar. and pos.);_nē̆st(a)_, _nē̆xt(a)_.] _See_ Nyȝ.

2830.entry: #Neuer(e)#, _adv._ never, I 152, VIII _a_ 23 &c.; not at all, I_introd._, XVII 313; _neuer sa_, _so_, no matter how, IV _a_ 75, V 61,VI 211; _neuer þe lesse_, nevertheless, I 71. [OE. _nǣfre_.]

2831.entry: #New(e)#, #Nw(e)# (V, VI), _adj._ new, II 217, V 176, 332, VI 167, VIII_a_ 294, &c.; _quasi-sb._ IX 275; _na new_, no new thing, IV _a_ 42;_for new_, in exchange for new (ones), VII 13; _adv._ anew, II 593;newly, V 155; _now newe_ (OE. _nū nīowan_), just lately, XVI 314.[OE. _nīowe_.]

2834.entry: #Nyght#, #Niȝt#, #Nyȝt#; #Nycht# (X); #Nyht# (XII); _n._ night, I29, II 370, VII 127, X 197, XII _a_ 68, &c.; _be nyȝt_, _nyhte_(dat.), at night, XII _a_ 117, 131, XV _i_ 15; _on nyght_, at night, XV_h_ 22; _see_ next. [OE. _niht_.] _See_ Naȝt.

2835.entry: #Nyghtes#, #Nihtes#, #Nytes# (XV), _adv._ at, by, night, XV _c_ 21; withprep., _a nyghtes_, _be nytes_, VIII _b_ 16, XV _i_ 20. [OE. _nihtes_.]

2837.entry: #Nygromansye#, _n._ necromancy, black magic; (used vaguely as) impiousnonsense, XI _a_ 5. [OFr. _nigromanc(i)e_.]

2838.entry: #Nyȝ#, #Nyh#, #Nee# (IV), #Neiȝe# (II), _adv._ nigh, at hand,close (by), XII _a_ 155, _b_ 13, XIII _a_ 52, _b_ 61; _nyh aboute_, nearat hand, XII _a_ 74; almost, II 199; _prep._ near (to), IV _a_ 11(note), XII _b_ 29. [OE. _nē(a)h_.] _See_ Ner(e), Welneȝ.

2839.entry: #Nyȝt-olde#, _adj._ kept over night, a day old, VIII _a_ 303. [OE._niht-áld_.]

2840.entry: #Nyhte#, _v._ to become night, grow dark, XII _b_ 19. [From Nyght, _n._]

2842.entry: #Nil#, _1, 3 sg. pres. ind._ will not (usually with another neg.) II211, 332, 338; #Nul#, XV _g_ 20; #Neltow# (nelt + þow), _2 sg._ VIII _a_149; #Nule#, _pl._ XV _g_ 25; #Nold(e)#, _pa. t._ would not, wasunwilling to, II 140, 280, V 163, VIII _a_ 232; _subj._ V 82; _wold ichnold ich_, whether I would or not, willy nilly, II 154. [OE. _nyllan_,_nellan_; _nólde_.] _See_ Ne.

2843.entry: #Nym(e)#, _v._ to take, catch, seize; receive; take one's way, go (cf._haþ þe way ynome_, II 477); VIII _a_ 43; _nyme to þyseluen_, take uponyourself, be responsible for, V 73; #Nymmeth#, _imper. pl._ VIII _a_ 15;

2844.entry: #Nam#, _pa. t. sg._ I 76, II 154, XII _b_ 84, 156; #Nom#, III 53; XII_b_ 182; #Nom(e)#, _pl._ I 233, II 92, 287, VI 227; #Ynome#, _pp._ II182, 193, 403, 477, 565 (note). [OE. _niman_.] _See_ Vndernome.

2846.entry: #Nis#, #Nys#, _3 sg. pres. ind._ is not (usually with another neg.), II131, 306, 552, XII _b_ 118, XIV _c_ 27, XV _c_ 25. [OE. _nis_.] _See_Ne.

2848.entry: #No#, #Na# (IV), _adj._ no, none, (with neg.) any, I 11, 156, IV _a_ 16,36, 42 (_see_ Newe), &c.; #Non(e)# (before _h_ or vowel, or sep. fromnoun) I 15, 160, II 354, 392, V 38, VIII _a_ 54, IX 182, &c.; _na (no)kyn_, _see_ Kyn, Þinge; _non oþer_, nothing different, _see_ Oþer(e);_na thyng_, _no þing_, _see_ Þinge; #Nones#, _gen. sg._ in _n. cunnes_,_see_ Kyn. [OE. _nān_.] _See_ Non(e), _pron._

2849.entry: #No#, #Na#, _adv._ not, no, I 79, II 84, IV _a_ 58, &c.; _see_ Mor(e),No-more. Used in II as equivalent of Ne (_q.v._); _adv._ not, II 84,147, 225, &c.; _conj._ nor, and (with neg.), II 140, 150, &c.; _no ...no_, neither ... nor, II 229. As _sb._ in _wiþouten no_, undeniably, II50 (_cf._ Nay). [OE. _nā_.]

2850.entry: #Noble#, #Nobel#, #-ill#, #-ull#, _adj._ noble, excellent, II 48, VII 5,49, XIII _b_ 67, XIV _b_ 65, _c_ 18, XVII 128, 276, &c. [OFr. _noble_.]

2851.entry: #Nobleie#, _n._ splendour; _fame and n. of þe world_, ? reputation forsplendour among men, XI _b_ 235. [OFr. _nobleie_.]

2852.entry: #Noblesse#, _n._ nobility, in _ȝoure ... noblesse_ as form ofaddress, IX 270. [OFr. _noblesse_.]

2854.entry: #Noȝt#, #Noght(e)#, #Noth# (XV _f_), #Nouȝt(e)#, #Nouht#, #Nout#,&c., and reduced #Not#, _adv._ not at all, not, I 64, 86, II 22, 73,348, IV _b_ 2, VIII _a_ 46, _b_ 94, XV _f_ 7 (_see_ App. p. 278), &c.;(with further neg.) I 15, II 306, 336, IX 196, &c. [OE. _nā-(wi)ht_,_nō-(wi)ht_.] _See_ Naȝt.

2855.entry: #Noȝt#, #Noght(e)#, #Nocht#, #Nouȝt(e)#, _n._ nothing, VIII _a_142, 241, X _introd._, XI _a_ 4, XVII 96, 287; (with addit. neg.), VI160; _for noȝt_, to no purpose, I 183, XIV _b_ 55; no good, in_nouȝt nis_ (_nere_), is (would be) impossible, II 131, 457 (_cf._OE. _nāht_, worthless). [As prec.]

2856.entry: #Noy(e)#, #Nuy#, #Nye# (V), _n._ harm, distress, V 73, VII 149, XIII _a_49; _noy for to here_, grievous to hear (_cf._ Pine, Reuþe), VII 133.[Shortened from OFr. _anoi_, _anui_; with Nye compare Byled, Strye.]

2857.entry: #Noye#, _v._ to do harm, XIII _a_ 36. [Shortened from OFr. _anoier_.]

2859.entry: #Noise#, _v. intr._ to make a noise, XII _a_ 78 (note). [From prec.]

2860.entry: #Noiþer#, _pron._ neither, II 324; _conj._ in _noiþer ... no_, neither... nor, II 346. [Nauþer, Noþer infl. by Neyþer.]

2865.entry: #Nomore#, _n._ nothing more, VIII _a_ 90; #Namore#, VIII _a_ 140. [OE._nā_ + _māre_, neut.] _See_ Mor(e).

2866.entry: #Non(e)#, #Nane# (IV, X), _pron._ none, not one, I 197, V 102, X 143,XII _b_ 13, XIII _a_ 23, &c.; no one, (with neg.) any one; I 153, II423, IV _a_ 13, V 36, VI 83, X 130, &c. [OE. _nān_.] _See_ No, _adj._

2867.entry: #None#, #Noyne# (X), #Noon#, _n._ noon, mid-day hour, II 372, VII 129, X67, XIII _a_ 28, XVII 317, &c.; #Nones#, _pl._ mid-day meal, VIII _a_139. [OE. _nōn_, L. _nōna (hōra)_.]

2869.entry: #Nones#; _for þe nones_, for the nonce (practically meaningless tag), II53, XII _a_ 83. [For _for þen ones_ (OE. _*for þam ānum_ + adv._-es_) as regards that particular thing, occasion, &c.]

2875.entry: #Not#, _1 sg. pres. ind._ know not, XII _b_ 164, XIV _c_ 110; #Nist#,_pa. t._ (with neg.) knew not, II 288, 296, 494. [OE. _nāt_,_nyste_.] _See_ Ne, Wite(n).

2876.entry: #Note#, _adj._ ? useful, required; desired, V 24. [? Rel. to next.]

2877.entry: #Note#, _n._^1 affair, business, XVI 268 (with pl. vb.), XVII 264; ado,XVII 368. [OE. _notu_.]

2878.entry: #Note#, _n._^2 (musical) note, II 438, XI _b_ 162, &c.; tune, II 602, XV_a_ 11. [OFr. _note_, L. _nota_.] _See_ Countre note.

2880.entry: #Notemuges#, _n. pl._ nutmegs, IX 157. [Prec. + OFr. #mug(u)e#, musk;_cf._ OFr. _nois mug(u)ede_, &c.]

2882.entry: #Notwiþstondinge#, _prep._ in spite of, XI _a_ 25. [Noȝt + _pres. p._of ME. _wiþstonden_, OE. _wiþstándan_.]

2885.entry: #Noþer#, _adj._ no other; _<no> no noþer_, nor any other, II 230. [OE._nān_ + _ōþer_.]

2890.entry: #Nouþe#, #Nouthe#, _adv._ just now, II 466; at present, VIII _a_ 199.[OE. _nū-þā_.] _See_ Now(e).

2892.entry: #Now(e)#, #Nou#, _adv._ now, I 128, IV _b_ 43, XI _a_ 21, &c.; _oþer nowoþer neuer_, now or never, V 148; _see_ Late, New(e); _conj._ since, nowthat, V 352, VI 29; _now ... now_, now that, VI 17. [OE. _nū_.]

2894.entry: #Nowhar(e)#, #-where#, #Nawhere# (VI), _adv._ nowhere, V 96, VI 174,XIII _a_ 17; in no case, not at all, V 186. [OE. _nā-hwǣr_.] _See_Whar(e).

2898.entry: #Obediand#, _adj._ obedient, XVII 121. [OFr. _obedient_ withsubstitution of pres. p. _-and_.]

2899.entry: #Obediencer#, _n._ an obedientiary, one owning obedience (to amonastery, &c.); an administrative officer of a religious house, VIII_b_ 95. [OFr. _obediencier_.]

2902.entry: #Occean#, _n._ Ocean (as name of Indian Ocean), IX 9. [OFr. _occean_.]

2904.entry: #Occupied# (_aboute_, _in_), _pp._ occupied (with, in), XI _b_ 114, 218,242, 262. [OFr. _occuper_, altered on anal. of verbs in _-fier_,_-plier_, &c.]

2907.entry: #Of#, #Offe#, _adv._ off, V 181, 340; of, out of, from (after _þat_relative), VI 65, IX 135, 282, &c.; (with infin.) IX 257, 282, &c.; _ofthe whiche ... offe_, _see_ next. [OE. _of_.] _See_ Her(e), Þar(e),Þer(e).

2908.entry: #Of#, #Off#, VII 5; #O#, II 12, 283, VI 69, VII 18; _prep._ of. (i)From, off, out of, II 29, III 4, 36, V 131, 153, 179, VI 247, VII 169,VIII _a_ 204, &c.; out of, (made) of, in, II 4, 362, IX 115, XVII 119,&c. (ii) By, III 18, IV _b_ 5, V 99, IX 55, XI _b_ 31, 204, &c.; by(means of), with, II 364, IX 65, &c. (iii) Of, about, concerning, I 160,II 5, 12, III 3, VIII _a_ 197, IX 147, XI _b_ 1, 295, &c. (iv) _Formingequiv. of gen._: as _possess._, I 34, 216, &c.; _adjectival_, II 3, IV_b_ 34, &c. (_see_ the nouns); in, as regards, &c., V 170, VI 71, VII18, 38, 164 (first), VIII _a_ 52, XII _a_ 9, XVI 129, XVII 543, &c.; _ofbreed_, &c., in breadth, &c., XVII 123, 125, 259, 520; (introd. actualmeasurement), IX 155, XVII 126; _objective gen._, at, for, on acc. of,&c., II 471, 573, VIII _a_ 38, 117, XI _b_ 10 (first), XII _a_ 144, &c.;_grame ... of_, wrath against, XVII 90; _partitive_, of, among, in, VII43 (_see_ Oþere), VIII _a_ 259, IX 182, XI _a_ 39, XVI 388 (_cf._ noteto II 388); after Fr. idiom, IX 158, 227, 275, XII _a_ 66; _see_ Ony,Oþer(e), Owen; _adverbial_ (of _time_), for VIII _a_ 253; in, XI _b_136. _Of the whiche ... offe_, _of whom ... from_, of which, from whom(mixed E. and Fr. constr.), IX 25, 77; _of preiere of holy lif_ (XI _b_83), _see_ Vnderstonden; for other idiomatic uses see the nouns, &c.,concerned. [OE. _of_.]

2910.entry: #Office#, _n._ duty, XI _b_ 18, 21, 47, 60; _houses of offyce_,quarters, stables (orig. places set apart for menial duties), XVII 134.[OFr. _office_.]

2912.entry: #Of-hild#, _pa. t. sg._ withheld, III 10. [OE. _of-héaldan_, pa. t._-hēold_.]

2915.entry: #Oftesithes#, #Oft(e)sythes#, _adv._ often, IV _b_ 27, VII 182, IX 63.[OE. _on oft-sīþas_.] _See_ Sithes.

2917.entry: #Oght(e)#, #Oȝt#, #Ought#, #Ouȝt#, _pron._ anything, IV _b_ 45, V147, XII _b_ 99, 107, XVI 100; _adv._ in any way, at all, XIV _c_ 69.[OE. _ō(wi)ht_.]

2922.entry: #Old(e)#, #Alde#, _adj._ old, V 114, VII 5, XII _introd._ (_see_ Dai),&c.; as _sb._, in _old or ȝong_, _ȝong and alde_, any one, everyone, II 221, IV _a_ 49; _of olde_, of old, VII 26, 182. [OE. _áld_.]

2924.entry: #On#, _adv._ on, II 343 (_see_ Do); (still) V 232; (with _infin._ or_relative_), upon, at, in, I 89, II 367, VII 15, XV _f_ 9, 10, XVI 179.[OE. _on_.] _See_ Þer(e).

2925.entry: #On#; #O#, VII 106, IX 250, XV _a_ 5, _g_ 28; _prep._ on. (i) On, upon,I 92, 194, II 303, XV _c_ 24 (following pron.), &c.; _on him seiȝe_,saw he had, II 325; _on my frenship_, as you value my f., XVII 362. (ii)At, V 112 (first), XV _c_ 15, _h_ 3, 22, XVII 137, &c.; (iii) In, I 99,XIV _b_ 79, XV _a_ 5, XVII 422, &c.; _see_ Bodi, Lyte, Lud, &c.; after'believe', I 89, VI 65; with _manere_, _wise_, I 80, V 124, VII 65, 77,XI _a_ 11, XIV _b_ 95, &c.; (reference) II 455, XV _c_ 13, &c.; _onEnglyssh tunge_, into English, I _introd._ (iv) Of (after 'think') I221, &c. (v) A, in _on a day_, a day, VI 150 (OE. _on dæg_). (vi) A-, on(in adv. expressions), as _on haukin_, a-hawking, II 308; _see_ Behalue,Fote, Lofte, Slep, &c. [OE. _on_.] _See_ A-; A(n), _prep._; Vpon.

2927.entry: #On(e)#; #Oon(e)#, XI _a_ 41, XVII 2, &c.; #Oo#, I 180, 231; #O#, I 49,&c.; _adj._ one, a single, II 306, V 83, VI 170, IX 17, XI _a_ 45, XIII_b_ 45, XIV _d_ 8, XVII 136, &c.; one (and the same), I 49, 231, II 95(_see_ Cri); one (indivisible), VII 2, IX 334, XVII 2, 169; one (asopposed to 'other'), I 180, IX 180, &c. (_see_ Þe, Ton); _o_, a certain,II 308; _oone or two_, one or two, some, XVII 133, 484; _quasi-sb._ in_into on_, together, XV _i_ 6; _at on_, at one, in harmony, VI 18; _aloon_, (all) one and the same thing, XI _a_ 41. [OE. _ān_.] _See_A(n), Ane, One.

2928.entry: #On(e)#, _pron._ one (thing _or_ person), V 348, VI 197, IX 24, XI _b_223, XIII _a_ 24, XV _b_ 23, 34, &c.; #Oone#, XVII 209; #Onen#, _dat.sg._ III 4; one (opposed to 'another'), IX 53, XIII _b_ 16; _boþe þat onand þat oþer_, both, V 344; _see_ Þe, Ton; (some) one, a certain person,V 149, VII 54 (with name). [As prec.]

2929.entry: #One#, _adj._ alone, only, V 6, VIII _b_ 54, XIV _b_ 61; strengthenedwith _al_, V 87, XII _a_ 131, _b_ 15; _a ... one_, one ... only, V 181,277; _oure one_, by ourselves, V 177 (note); _let ... one_, leave alone,avoid (_cf._ OE. _ān-forlǣtan_), v 50. [OE. _āna_.]

2930.entry: #Onehed#, _n._ unity, _or_ ? simplicity; _onehed of wit_, the uniformityof men's understanding (interpretation) of the Bible, _or_ ? the ease ofunderstanding it, XI _a_ 32. [OE. _ān_ + _*-hǣdu_.]

2931.entry: #Onely#, _adj._ in _onely alepy_, a single solitary, I 159; #Oon(e)ly#,_adv._ only, XVII 288, 307. [OE. _ān-lic_, adj.] _See_ Anely.

2932.entry: #Ones#, #Oneȝ# (V), #Onys# (XVII), _adv._ once, on a single occasion,I 182, II 122, V 212, XII _b_ 92; formerly, V 150, VIII _a_ 202; at some(future) time or other, XVII 207, 389. [OE. _ānes_.]

2934.entry: #Ony#, _adj._ any, IX 85, 245, XI _b_ 300, &c.; _most of ony þing_,above all things, more than anything, II 33; _pron._ any, IX 326, XI _b_147. [OE. _ǣnig_, infl. by _ān_.] _See_ Ani, Eny.

2944.entry: #Or#, _conj._^1 or, I 1, &c.; _or ... or_, either ... or, VIII _a_ 244.[Reduced form of Oþer, _conj._]

2945.entry: #Or#, _conj._^2 before, ere (usually with _subj._), VIII _a_ 79, X 2,XVI 154 (_see_ Ware), _adj._ 156, 278, XVII 110 (_see_ Blyn), 153, 263,&c.; (postponed) XVII 130; lest, XIV _d_ 11. [_See_ next.]

2946.entry: #Or#, _prep._ before, ere, XVI 224, XVII 317, 481. [? OE. _ǣr_, pos.and compar. (once late Nth. _ar_) infl. by ON. _ár_, pos.] _See_ Ar(e),Er(e).

2948.entry: #Ordayn(e)#, #Ordainy#, _v._ to decree, establish, appoint, direct,arrange, contrive, fashion, &c., II 205, XVII 309; #Ordand#, XVII 119,468; #Ordeigne#, XII _b_ 216; #Ordeyn(e)#, I 55, 148, VIII _b_ 57, XI_b_ 125, 132, &c.; #Ordand#, #Ordanit#, _pa. t._ X 11, 34, XVI 25, 226;_ordaynede to_, destined to, IV _b_ 54. [OFr. _ordener_, 3 sg._ordei(g)ne_, _-aine_.]

2949.entry: #Ordynal(e)#, #-alle#, _n._ a book setting out the order and manner ofchurch services and ceremonies, XI _b_ 1, 183, 186. [Med.L._ordināle_.]

2950.entry: #Ordenaunse#, #Ordynaunce#, _n._ ordinance, decree, law, XI _a_ 15, _b_100, &c.; _preie oure ... ordynaunce_, say the prayers we haveappointed, XI _b_ 38. [OFr. _ordenance_.]

2951.entry: #Ordre#, #Order#, #-yre#, _n._ order, rank, VIII _a_ 159, XI _b_ 20;_pl._ religious orders, XI _a_ 61; the (nine) orders of angels, XVII 10;moderation, in _holde þe ordyre of_, keep the rule of, observemoderation in, IV _b_ 22. [OFr. _ordre_.]

2952.entry: #Orgon#, _n._ diaphony; singing in two parts, XI _b_ 138 (note). [OE._organ_, song, from L. _organum_.]

2954.entry: #Oritore#, _n._ oratory, chapel, V 122. [OFr. _oratour_, infl. by prec.]

2956.entry: #Ost#, #Host#, _n._ (armed) host, army, II 290, X 43, 45; multitude,XIII _a_ 32. [OFr. _(h)ost_, army.]

2958.entry: #Oþer(e)#, #Other(e)#, #-ir(e)#, #-yre#; #Oder#, XVII 160; #Ouþer#, I,(i) _Adj._, other, another, other kinds of, I 18, 258, IV _b_ 16, 45, V274, IX 227, XII _b_ 170, XVII 298 (_see_ Garn), &c.; #Othre#, _pl._ XII_a_ 82, 136; _many oþer folde_, _see_ Folde; _othere gude_, some othergood (thing), IV _b_ 9; _oþer mani_, many other, II 496; _þat oþer_,_see_ Þe; _þis othir daye_, the other day, XVI 148. (ii) _Pron. sg._another, some one (something) else, the other, I 101, II 324, VI 89, X22 (_see_ Aither), &c.; #Oþereȝ#, _gen. sg._ VI 90; _ichon other_,each man to his neighbour, XVII 112; _non other_, nothing different(from what has been said), VII 42, VIII _introd._, _a_ 173; _oþer oþer_,_þat oþer_, _see_ next and Þe; _pl._ (uninflected), others, I 211, IV_b_ 67, 78, V 355, VII 48, X 154, &c.; #Othre#, _pl._ XII _introd._, _a_41; #Oþren#, _dat. pl._ III 53; _derrist of other_, most excellent of(illogically for 'more worthy than') all others, VII 39. [OE._ōþer_.] _See_ Anoþire, Toþer.

2959.entry: #Oþer#, #Other#; #Auþer#, V 225; #Ouþer#, #Outhire#, #Owthyre#, IV _b_8, 23, IX 276; _adv._ and _conj._ or, I 3, II 350, V 39, VIII _a_ 305,&c.; _oþer oþer_, or any one else, V 34; _oþer ... oþer_, either ... or,V 148; _oþer ... or_, I 197, IV _b_ 8, 23, IX 276; introducingalternative questions, VIII _b_ 34, 35; _adv._ in _or oþer_, or else, I6; _oþer ... auþer_, or else, V 225. [OE. _ā-hwæþer_, _ā(w)þer_;_ō-hwæþer_, _ōwþer_.] _See_ Or^2, Ayther, Euþer.

2960.entry: #Oþer-while#, #Other-while#, #Oþer-wyle# (VIII _b_), _adv._ on anotheroccasion, XVII 213; at other times, II 289, 297; now and again, VIII _b_52; _other while ... other while_, sometimes ... sometimes, XII _a_ 128.[Oþer, _adj._ + While.]

2962.entry: #Ouer(e)#, #Our(e)#, _prep._ over, I 177, V 246, X 84, 112, &c.; overand above, XI _b_ 150; (of _time_) through, VII 166 (following noun);_adv._ over, II 578, V 164, &c.; _all ... ouer_, all over, in all parts,VII 134 (_cf._ next); too, I 130, IV _b_ 23, 24, VI 113, VII 36, &c.[OE. _ofer_.]

2967.entry: #Ouerheghede#, _pp._ raised too high, IV _b_ 5. [Ouer, _adv._ + ME._heiȝen_ from Heigh.]

2969.entry: #Ouermoche#, _adj._ and _n._ too much, VIII _a_ 255, XI _b_ 219; _cf._IV _b_ 23. [OE. _ofer-mycel_.] _See_ Mochel.

2980.entry: #Out(e)#, #Owt(e)#, _adv._ out, I 50, IV _b_ 3, XI _b_ 26 (_see_Charité), XVI 18, &c.; abroad, out of doors, VIII _b_ 16; as exclam. ofanger, dismay, &c., XVI 185, 195, 343; _out(e) apon the_, fie on thee,XVII 229, 408. [OE. _ūt_, _ūte_.]

2981.entry: #Outguoinge#, _n._ _ate outguoinge of_, on departing from, III 4. [FromOE. _ūt-gān_.] _See_ Go(n).

2985.entry: #Owe#, #Owyn#, #Oȝe#, _v._ to have; to have (to), be bound (to),ought, XI _b_ 6, XV _i_ 4; with mixed _pers._ and _impers._ constr., in_vus oȝe_, we ought, VI 192; to owe, VI 183; #Awe#, _2 sg. pres._XVII 171; #Oghte#, _pa. t._ possessed, XII _b_ 48; #Ouhte#, ought to,VIII _b_ 73; #Auȝt#, was bound to, II 555. [OE. _āgan_, pa. t._ā̆hte_.]

2987.entry: #Oghne#, XII _a_ 4; #Oȝene#, III _introd._; #Oune#, XIII _a_ 47, _b_18, &c.; #Owhen#, II 163, &c.; #Awen#, V 73, 233; #Awne#, XVI 237, XVII74; _quasi-sb._ in _of hire owne_, of their own, IX 188; _haue of mynowen_, have property of my own, VIII _a_ 77. [OE. _āgen_.]

2990.entry: #Owth#, _adv._ on top, X 6. [? Reduction of OE. _ufan_, _ufe-_ + _wiþ_;cf. ME. _out-wiþ_.]

2995.entry: #Paie#, #Pay(e)#, _v._ to please, satisfy, VIII _a_ 304; _payes to_, ispleasing to, IV _a_ 29; _impers._ in _me paies_, I am pleased, XVI 82;to pay, II 451, VI 164 (_fut._), VIII _a_ 87, XIV _d_ 10; #Paied#,

2996.entry: #Paid(e)#, &c., _pp._ satisfied, content, V 273, XVI 325, XVII 283;paid, VI 224, 243. [OFr. _payer_.] _See_ Apayed.

2998.entry: #Payn(e)#, #Peyne#, _n._^1 pain, suffering, torment, I 163, XI _b_ 32,XVI 4, 122, XVII 547, &c. [OFr. _peine_.] _See_ Peynen.

3002.entry: #Pale#, _adj._ pale, II 110, IV _a_ 10; wan, chill (connoting 'fatal','ill-omened'), VII 100, 116, 125. [OFr. _pale_.]

3003.entry: #Palfray#, _n._ palfrey, saddle-horse (_esp._ for use of women), II 156.[OFr. _palefrei_.]

3004.entry: #Palmer#, _n._ pilgrim (properly one that had been to the Holy Land andbore a palm-branch in token of this), VIII _a_ 66. [OFr. _palm(i)er_.]

3008.entry: #Par#, #Per# (XII), _prep._ (with French words), by, through, for, VI129, VIII _a_ 250, XII _a_ 7, _b_ 18, &c. (_see_ the nouns); transl. (inFr. phrases) by _for_, _thurgh_, XII _b_ 8, XV _d_ 5, XVII 557, &c.[OFr. _par_, _per_.] _See_ Paramoure, -aunter, -fay, Perdé.

3011.entry: #Paramoure#, _adv._ with all (his) heart, XVII 80. [OFr. _par amour_.]_See_ Par.

3012.entry: #Paraunter#, #Peraunter# (IX), #Peraventure# (XVII), _adv._ perhaps, V275, VI 228, IX 272, XVII 503. [OFr. _par aventure_.] _See_ Auentur(e),Par.

3015.entry: #Parfay#, _interj._ by my troth, II 315, 339, 382. [OFr. _par fei_(_fai_).] _See_ Fai.

3018.entry: #Parforme#, #Performe#, _v._ to complete, IX 170; to perform, XI _b_194, 286. [OFr. _parfourmer_.]

3022.entry: #Part#, _n._ part, share, VI 213, IX 31, 325, XI _b_ 57, &c.; _more bean hundred part_, more (by) a hundred times, IX 301 (_lit._ more by thehundredth part: the use seems modelled on that of ME. _dele_; see_N.E.D._, s.v. _Deal_, I _e_). [OFr. _part_.]

3023.entry: #Part(e)#, _v._ to divide, share, XII _b_ 201; separate, I 103; _refl._in _part me ... with_, part with, leave, VII 96; #Partinge#, #-yng#,_n._ distribution, XI _b_ 275; separation, IV _a_ 31. [OFr. _partir_.]

3024.entry: #Partener(e)#, _n._ sharer, IX 325; _parteners of þe endes_, sharers (intheir linguistic peculiarities) with the extremes, XIII _b_ 55. [OFr._parson(i)er_, infl. by Part.]

3025.entry: #Party#, #Partie#, _n._ part, IX 1, 2, X 156, XIII _b_ 52, &c.; side, IX72; party (in legal proceeding), XII _b_ 215; _most party_, most (part)of, XVII 49. [OFr. _parti_, _partie_.]

3026.entry: #Pas#, _n._ pace, gait; _queynt pas_ (as _adv._), with skilful steps, II300. [OFr. _pas_.]

3028.entry: #Passe(n)#, #Pas#, #Pasi# (III), _v._; #Passed#, #-it#, #Past(e)#, _pa.t._ and _pp._ (i) _Intr._ to pass, proceed, go, get, IV _b_ 34, VII 125,VIII _a_ 78, XVI 296, &c.; go one's way, depart, pass on, V 61, VII 112,VIII _a_ 196, XVI 66, 96, 152, 194, &c.; pass away, XI _a_ 9; _passe bi_(_be_), pass (by), V 36, &c.; go over (through), IX 8, 137, &c.; _passethe see_, go abroad, IX 308, XIII _b_ 39; _was past to_, had reached,VII 100; _pp._ past, gone by, over, VII 9, IX 317, XVI 105, XVII 181,&c. (ii) _Trans._ to cross, go over (through), pass (safely), V 3, VII116, 171, IX 308, XIII _b_ 39, &c.; to surpass, VI 68; _passynge_,exceeding(ly), IX 11, 232; to pass (time), III 44. #Passed#, #Passit#,_pp._ as _prep._ past, VI 168, X 2. _Cf._ Apassed. [OFr. _passer_.]

3029.entry: #Pater#, #Pater-noster#, _n._ the 'Our Father', Lord's prayer, VI 125,VIII _b_ 48, 91, IX 323, XI _a_ 33, 35.

3030.entry: #Patrones#, _n. pl._ patrons, those holding advowson, or right ofpresentation to benefices (earliest use in E.), VIII _b_ 82. [OFr._patron_.]

3035.entry: #Peiere#, _v._ to impair, damage, XI _b_ 250; _peierid_ imperfect, XI_b_ 26. [Shortened from Ap(p)eyre, Empeyre.]

3037.entry: #Peynen#, _v. refl._ to take pains, endeavour, IX 272. [OFr. _se pener_,3 sg. _peine_.] _See_ Payne, _n._^1

3041.entry: #Pené# (VI), #Peny#, #Penny#, _n._ penny (a silver coin, a twelfth ofthe shilling), III 13, VI 150, 186, VIII _a_ 275, &c.; _penny doyll_,_see_ Dele, Doyll; #Pans#, _pl._ pence, III 6, 10, &c. (_cf._ ME._paneyes_, and OFris. _panning_). [OE. _peni(n)g_, _pæn(n)ing_.] _See_Halpeny.

3042.entry: #Peny-ale#, _n._ ale at a penny a gallon, thin ale, VIII _a_ 304 (_cf._Halpeny-ale). [Prec. + OE. _alu_.]

3043.entry: #Pennes#, _n. pl._ quills, barrels of the feathers, IX 257. [OFr._penne_.]

3044.entry: #Peopull#, #People#, _n._ people, VII 16, 82, XIII _b_ 1, &c.; #Peple#,VIII _a_ 287, IX 165, XI _b_ 19, &c.; #Pepul(l)#, VII 145, XVI 194;

3053.entry: #Peril(l)ous#, #Perelous#, #Perlous#, _adj._ perilous, dangerous,parlous, V 29, VIII _a_ 45, XI _b_ 44, XVII 431, &c. [OFr. _perillous_.]

3058.entry: #Pese#, #Pees#, _n._ a pea, V 296, IX 48; _at a pees_, at nought, VIII_a_ 162; #Pesen#, _pl._ peas, pease, VIII _a_ 189, 293; Peses, VIII _a_180. [OE. _pise_, _peose_.]

3059.entry: #Pese-coddes#, _n. pl._ peascods, pea-pods, VIII _a_ 287; #Pese-lof#,_n._ loaf made of pease-meal, VIII _a_ 172. [Prec. + OE. _codd_,_hlāf_.]

3064.entry: #Picche#, _v._; _picche atwo_, ? to thrust apart, divide (on the sharppoint of the _pyk-staf_), VIII _a_ 97; to pitch, load (hay, in homingthe crop), VIII _b_ 13. [Perh. distinct verbs; see _N.E.D._, s.v._Pitch_.] _See_ Pike.

3068.entry: #Pike#, _v._ to pick; _piked vp_, ? dug out (with a pointed implement),VIII _a_ 105; #Pykeȝ#, _3 pl._ ? pick out, get, VI 213. [ME._pi(k)ken_, with variety of senses prob. due to confusion of distinctwords; see _N.E.D._, s.v. _Pick_, _Pike_, &c.]

3070.entry: #Pykstaf#, _n._ pikestaff, staff with a spike at lower end, VIII _a_ 97.[OE. _pīc_ + _stæf_; cf. ON. (late) _pík-stafr_.]

3072.entry: #Pylgrym#, #Pilgryme#, _n._ pilgrim, VIII _a_ 59, 96, 99, XIII _a_ 48.[OFr. _pele(g)rin_, &c.; cf. OHG. (from Fr.) _piligrim_.]

3077.entry: #Pine#, #Pyne#, _n._ torment, suffering, grief, I 213, III 9, IV _a_ 32,50, 60, XVII 227, 437; toil, VI 151; _pyne to behold_, (parenthetic),grievous to see, VII 145 (_cf._ Noy, Reuþe). [OE. _*pīn_; cf. next.]

3079.entry: #Pypynge#, _n._ piping, playing on pipes, I 6. [OE. _*pīpian_, from_pīpe_, pipe.]

3080.entry: #Pyt#, #Pitte#, #Pet# (XII), _n._ hole, pit, I 143, XII _b_ 9, 11, 29,&c.; pit (of hell), XVI 271, 348. [OE. _pytt_ (Kt. _pett_).]

3081.entry: #Pité#, #Pyté#, #Peté#, _n._ compassion, pity, II 101, IV _b_ 57, 75,VIII _a_ 193; _es ... pyté_, is pitiful, IV _a_ 87. [OFr. _pité_.]

3082.entry: #Piteuous#, _adj._ full of pity, III 39; #Pytosly#, _adv._compassionately, VI 10. [OFr. _pitous_; _piteuous_ is due to anal. ofwords like Plenteuous, _q.v._]

3084.entry: #Placebo#, _n._ Vespers of the Dead, VIII _b_ 48, XI _b_ 131 (_see_note).

3086.entry: #Play(e)#, #Pleie#, _v._ to play, amuse oneself, II 66, XIII _b_ 22;rejoice, XII _b_ 159; #Playinge#, _n._ disport, XV _a_ 5. [OE._pleg(i)an_.]

3087.entry: #Plain#, #Playne#, _adj._ flat, level, II 353; plain, clear, XVI 48;

3089.entry: #Playni#, #Pleigne#, #Pleyne#, #Pleny#, _v._ to complain, III 19, VI189; _refl._ in _pleyned hym_, made complaint, VIII _a_ 152; to sue (atlaw), XII _b_ 215. [OFr. _plaindre_, _plaign-_.]

3092.entry: #Platen#, _n. pl._ (plates), pieces of (silver) money, XV _g_ 4, 15, 21,23 (_cf._ 'plates' in Wiclifite version, Matt. xxvi 15, &c.). [OFr._plate_.]

3095.entry: #Plenté#, #-ee#, _n._ plenty, abundance, II 253, VIII _a_ 156, XIII _a_63, XVI 392; _quasi-adv._ in _plenté_, abundantly, XVII 146; _moreplentee_, in greater abundance, IX 245. [OFr. _plenté_.]

3098.entry: #Plesynge#, _n._ in _to pl. of_, so as to please, *XI _b_ 108. [OFr._plaisir_, _ple(i)sir_.]

3099.entry: #Plesance#, _n._ pleasure, liking, IX 327, X _introd._; _do theplesance_, perform the pleasant office, XII _a_ 185. [OFr. _plaisance_,_ples-_.]

3101.entry: #Plete#, _v._ to sue for; claim, VI 203. [OFr. _plaitier_, _pleder_,&c.] _See_ Plee.

3104.entry: #Plom#, _n._ plummet; as _adj._ vertical, straight down (measured by theplumb-line), XVII 520. [OFr. _plomb_.]

3108.entry: #Plow-fote#, _n._ a stave supporting the plough-beam and regulatingfurrow's depth, but here appar. = 'plough-staff' (_cf._ other readings'_plou-bat_'), a staff ending in a small spade for clearing earth, &c.,from mould-board, VIII _a_ 97. [Prec. + OE. _fōt_.]

3114.entry: #Poynt(e)#, #Point#, _n._ (i) (sharp) point, V 324, IX 118; (ii) point(of time or place), VII 100, XII _a_ 68; _at the poynt_, to hand, IX253; _bryng me to þe poynt_, come to the point with me, V 216; item,detail, instance, matter, &c., VI 234, VIII _a_ 38, IX 287, XI _b_ 106,XVI 105, 326, &c. [OFr. (i) _pointe_, (ii) _point_.]

3119.entry: #Polyse# (V), #Pollis(s)che#, #Pollysch#, _v._ to polish, IX 35, 41,119, 121, &c.; to cleanse, V 325. [OFr. _polir_, _poliss-_.]

3127.entry: #Poret(te)#, _n._ (young) leek or onion, VIII _a_ 281; _collect. sg._VIII _a_ 293. [OFr. _poret_, leek; _porette_, small onion.]

3133.entry: #Post(e)les#, _n. pl._ apostles, XV _g_ 24, 25; itinerant preachers,VIII _a_ 143. [OE. _postol_.] _See_ Apostel.

3139.entry: #Poeuere#, XI _b_ 272; #Poure#, III 48, IV _b_ 20, VIII _b_ 82; #Pore#,VI 213, VIII _a_ 18, XI _b_ 255, &c.; _adj. pl._ as _sb._, poor(people), the poor, III 8, 41, VIII _a_ 18, &c.; #Pouren#, _dat. pl._III 7. [OFr. _pov(e)re_, _poure_.]

3141.entry: #Power(e)#, #Pouer#, #Poure#, _n._ ability, power, VIII _a_ 35, XII _a_187, XVI 219; authority, VIII _a_ 143; forces, XIV _c_ 46. [OFr._po(u)eir_, _pouer_.]

3142.entry: #Pray(e)#, _n._ prey, II 313, XVI 175; _fig._ (of good things won asprize) VI 79. [OFr. _preie_.]

3143.entry: #Prece#, #Pres(s)#, _v._ to press; thrust, force, X 49, 69, &c.; _intr._and _refl._ to press forward, hasten, V 29, X 131; _pressit on_,assailed, X 190; _hardest pressit_, most hard pressed, X 150. _See_Prees. [OFr. _presser_; on forms _prece_, _pre(e)s_, see _N.E.D._]

3146.entry: #Precious#, #Precy(i)ous(e)#, _adj._ precious, costly, IX 42, 99, XI _b_257; _precious ston_, II 151, 366, IX 123. [OFr. _precious_.]

3148.entry: #Prees#, #Press#, _n._ press; crowd, XII _b_ 213; uproar, commotion, XVI125. [From Prece, _q.v._]

3150.entry: #Preie#, #Preye(n)#, #Prey#, #Pray(e)#, _v._ to pray, beg, II 534, IV_b_ 8, VIII _a_ 119, 250, XI _b_ 37, XVII 242, &c.; #Praid#, #Preide#,

3151.entry: #Preyd(e)#, _pa. t._ I 89, II 224, VIII _a_ 117, XII _b_ 69; _pray_,pray to, VI 124; _preye of_, beg for, VIII _a_ 38, 117; _preye to_, pray(to), IX 320, 322; #Preiynge#, _n._ in _p. of lippes_, prayer with lips(only), XI _b_ 89. [OFr. _preier_.]

3152.entry: #Preiere#, #Preyer(e)#, #Preȝer# (XIV _c_), _n._ prayer, VIII _a_244, _b_ 88, XI _b_ 36, XIV _c_ 78, &c.; _preiere in lippis_, p. withthe lips (only), XI _b_ 90. [OFr. _preiere_.]

3153.entry: #Preise(n)#, #Preyse#, #Prayse#, _v._ to praise, esteem, V 4, VIII _a_102, _b_ 31, XI _b_ 176, 182. [OFr. _preis(i)er_.] _See_ Prese, Prys,Prist.

3156.entry: #Prese#, _n._ praise, great worth, VI 59. [Stem of Preise(n) with AFr.monophthongization.]

3158.entry: #Present(e)#, _adj._ present, IX 128, 336; as _sb._ in _in yourpresente_, in your presence, VI 29. [OFr. _present_.]

3161.entry: #Prest#, _adj._ prompt, quick, VIII _a_ 190, XIV _b_ 67; #Prestly#,_adv._ promptly, VIII _a_ 87. [OFr. _prest_.]

3164.entry: #Pretermynable#, _adj._ who predetermines, fore-ordains, VI 236. [Appar.invented for rhyme from _pre_ + _terminable_ used actively.]

3165.entry: #Preue#, #Preeue#, _v._ to prove, show, VII 47, IX 298; to test, IX 297;to approve, IX 305. [OFr. _preuv-_, _proev-_, &c. accented stem of_prover_.] _See_ Preef, Proue.

3166.entry: #Pryde#, #Pride#, _n._ pride, magnificence, IV _a_ 59, _b_ 14, XI _b_55, XVII 543, &c.; _of pryde_, proud, XVI 182. [OE. _prȳdo_.] _See_Proude.

3168.entry: #Prike#, _v._ to spur; _intr._ gallop, II 141, XIV _a_ 15. [OE._prician_, to prick.]

3169.entry: #Pryme#, _n._ prime, first division of the day according to the sun(varying with the season), _or_ a fixed period 6-9 a.m.; _heighe pryme_,fully prime, end of the period of prime, about 9 a.m., VIII _a_ 106.[OE. _prīm_, from L. _prīma (hōra)_.]

3170.entry: #Prymer#, _n._ devotional manual, VIII _b_ 48 (note). [Origin of namedoubtful; see _N.E.D._]

3174.entry: #Principaly#, _adv._ in the first place, XI _b_ 96. [OFr. _principal_,or L. _principālis_.]

3175.entry: #Pryour#, _n._ priory, VIII _b_ 95. [OFr. _priorie_; with this form ofthe suffix _cf._ Oritore.]

3176.entry: #Prys#, #Prise#, #Priis# (II), _n._ worth, excellence, V 296, VI 59; _ofpriis_, &c., worthy, excellent, noble, II 51, 64, 249, V 330, VII 47.[OFr. _pris_, earlier _prieis_.] _See_ Preise(n), Prist.

3177.entry: #Prisoune#, #Prison#, _n._ prison, XI _b_ 126, XVI 220 (_or_ read_prisounes_, prisoners; _see_ note). [OFr. _priso(u)n_.]

3180.entry: #Proferi#, #Profre#, _v._ to offer, II 434, V 278, VIII _a_ 25, XII _b_122, &c. [OFr. _proffrir_; _proferer_.]

3181.entry: #Profession#, _n._ declaration; vows (on entering religious order), in_singular prof._, special vows, as opposed to the regular vows taken byall priests, XI _b_ 101. [OFr. _profession_.]

3189.entry: #Propre#, _adj._ proper, separate, IX 187; #Propurly#, _adv._ properly,rightly (_or_ of my own knowledge, at first hand), IX 264. [OFr._propre_.]

3190.entry: #Proude#, #Prowd(e)#, _adj._ magnificent, glorious, II 376; proud,haughty, arrogant, V 36, 201, VIII _a_ 191, XV _b_ 32, &c.; _prowdist ofpryde_, greatest in pride (_or_ splendour), XVII 543; #Prowdly#, _adv._out of pride, XVII 17. [OE. _prūt_ (rarely _prūd_), from OFr._prout_, _prou(d)_, valiant.]

3191.entry: #Proue#, #Prufe#, _v._ to prove; demonstrate, show, X 74, XVI 255; test,try, XVII 460. [OFr. _prover_; cf. OE. _prōfian_.] _See_ Preue.

3192.entry: #Prow(e)# (_to_), _n._ benefit, good (of), IV _b_ 82, XVI 220, 326; _mayto prow_, may be of benefit ('prow' prob. apprehended as infin.), I_introd._ [OFr. _prou_.]

3193.entry: #Psalme#, _n._ psalm, VIII _a_ 246; _Seuene Psalmes_, the SevenPenitential Psalms, VIII _b_ 49; note allit. with _s_. [OE. _(p)salm_,L. _psalmus_.]

3195.entry: #Pull#, _v._; #Puld#, _pa. t._; to drag, VII 178; _pull up_, hoist, VII125, XVII 153. [OE. _pullian_.]

3197.entry: #Puplisshid#, _pp._ (rime requires _puplist_), openly declared, XVI 59.[OFr. _puplier_ + _-is(h)_ from other verbs of Fr. origin.]

3199.entry: #Pure#, #Puire#, _adj._ pure; elegant, seemly (_cf._ Clene), V 330;utter, sheer, VIII _a_ 111, IX 31, XIV _c_ 13. [OFr. _pur_.]

3204.entry: #Purpos(e)#, #Pourpos#, #Porpos#, _n._ intention, purpose, resolve, IV_b_ 73, VI 148, VII 118, XII _a_ 21, XIV _b_ 39; _put in a p._,resolved, VII 112. [OFr. _po(u)rpos_.]

3207.entry: #Pursewe#, #Pursuen#, #Poursuie#, _v._ to follow, pursue, IX 229. XII_b_ 7; persecute, torment, IX 93; _pursewe to_, go eagerly to, XVI 316.[OFr. _pursiwer_, _pursuer_.]

3209.entry: #Putte(n)#, #Puit# (XIV _c_), _v._; #Put(te)#, _pa. t._ and _pp._; tothrust, IV _b_ 3, 10, X 187, XVI 259, XVII 39; to put, set, VII 112(_see_ Purpos), VIII _a_ 191, XII _b_ 141, XIV _c_ 12, XVII 21; toimpose, XI _a_ 64; _putte awey_, do away with, XI _b_ 127; _puttenerrour in_, impute error to, XI _b_ 77; _put hom þerto_, set themselvesto the task, VII 33; _putten hem into_, put out on, IX 183; _put vntopayn_, set in torment, XVII 547; _putte wryten_, set in writing, IX 318.[OE. _pū̆tian_, _pȳtan_, _potian_; see _N.E.D._]

3211.entry: #Qualitee#, _n._ degree (of goodness), question of how good, IX 335.[OFr. _qualité_.]

3212.entry: #Quantytee#, #Quantité#, _n._ limitation of greatness, question of howgreat, IX 336; capacity, quantity, X 26. [OFr. _quantité_.]

3214.entry: #Quaþ#, #Quath#, _pa. t. sg._ quoth, said, II 127, VIII _b_ 26, &c.;

3217.entry: #Queynt#, _adj._ skilful, elegant, II 299, 300 (_see_ Pas); #Koyntly#,_adv._ cunningly, V 345. [OFr. _cointe_, _queinte_, &c.]

3224.entry: #Quhedirand#, _pres. p._ whirling, _or_ whirring, X 92. [Cf. Early ME._to-hwideren_, _-hwiðeren_, whirl to pieces; OE. _hwaþerian_, make arushing noise.]

3228.entry: #Quyte#; #Qwyte#, #Qwite# (XVII); _v._ to pay, repay, V 176, 256, VI235, XVII 216, 228; Quitte, _pp._ paid, VIII _a_ 92. [OFr. _quiter_.]

3232.entry: #Qwart#, _n._ health; _mase in qwart_, heals, IV _a_ 15. [ON. _kvirt_,(neut. adj.) untroubled.]

3234.entry: #Race#, #Rase#, _n._ headlong course, XVII 429; onslaught, violent blow,V 8. [ON. _rás_ infl. by senses of related OE. _rǣs_.]

3237.entry: #Rayn#, _v._ to rain, XVII 147; #Renys#, _pl._ are raining down, XVII351. [OE. _regnian_.]

3241.entry: #Rake#, _n._ path, V 76, 92. [OE. _racu_, water-course, or ON. _rák_,streak (Norw. dial. _raak_, path).]

3242.entry: #Ram-skyt#, _n._ a term of abuse, XVII 217. [OE. _ramm_ + ON. _skita_.]

3244.entry: #Randoune#, _n._; _in a randoune_, with a rush, X 102. [OFr. _en unrandon_.]

3255.entry: #Rauysche#, _v._ to carry off captive, carry away, IV _a_ 16; #Reuey<se>d#,_pp._ II 82. [OFr. _ravir_, _raviss-_.]

3263.entry: #Receyue#, _v._ to receive, take, VIII _b_ 73; #Res(s)ayue#, V 8, XVI390; #Resceyued#, _pp._ XI _b_ 265. [OFr. _receiv-re_.]

3264.entry: #Reche#, #Recche#, _v._^1 to reck, care, VIII _a_ 114; _me no reche_, Icare not (mixed _pers._ and _impers._ constr.), II 342. [OE. _reccan_.]

3268.entry: #Recorde#, _v._ to ponder, go over in one's mind, IX 317; record, XII_introd._, _b_ 111. [OFr. _recorder_.]

3271.entry: #Red(e)#, _adj._ red, II 107, XIV _b_ 41, XV _e_ 19; _red(e) gold_, redgold, II 150, 362. [OE. _rēad_.]

3272.entry: #Red(e)#, _n._ advice, III 51 (_dat._); counsel, plan, in _can no otherred_, sees nothing else for it, XII _b_ 102 (_cf._ Wane, _n._). [OE._rǣd_, _rēd_.]

3273.entry: #Red(e)#, #Redyn#, #Reede#, _v._ to advise, counsel, IV _a_ 45, V 43(note), VIII _b_ 108, XIV _c_ 97, XVII 341, &c.; to read, II 1, IV _b_9, X _introd._, XII _a_ 112, &c.; to read aloud, I 14; to reckon, VIII_b_ 73; to think, XVII 427; _hard red_ (inf.), heard read, XVII 46;

3277.entry: #Redi#, #Redy#, _adj._ prompt, ready (to hand), II 380, VI 231, X 34,XII _b_ 119, XVI 394; _al redy_, prompt(ly), XVI 120; #Redyly#, _adv._promptly, V 256. [Extended from OE. _(ge-)rǣde_.]

3279.entry: #Reformed# (_of_), _pp._ changed back to his proper form (from), XII _a_19. [OFr. _reformer_.]

3290.entry: #Rele#, _v._ to reel, behave wildly, sway (in combat); _rele as vslikeȝ_, let us fight as fiercely as we please, V 178. [Prob. relatedto Reyll.]

3293.entry: #Releif#, #Releue#, _v._ to relieve, give relief to, X 151, 161, XI _b_255. [OFr. _relever_.]

3298.entry: #Remene# (_to_), _v._ to compare (to), interpret (as), XIV _c_ 41. [?OFr. _remener_, bring back; senses seem due to assoc. with Mene, _v._^1]

3300.entry: #Remytte#, _v._ to hand on, refer (for consideration), IX 296. [L._remittere_.]

3304.entry: #Ren#, #Renne#, _v._ to run, XIV _b_ 6; to flow, IX 179, XII _a_ 84; ?

3309.entry: #Renoun#, #Renowne#, _n._ renown, glorious name, in _of renoun_,_renouns_ (_pl._ in Fr. constr., with ref. to several persons), I 248,II 202, XIV _b_ 81. [OFr. _renoun_.]

3314.entry: #Repe#, _v._ to reap, VIII _b_ 15. [OE. _rī̆pan_; on stem-vowel see_N.E.D._ s.v. _Reap_.]

3318.entry: #Repleye#, _v._ XVI 380 (_see_ note). [Cf. OFr. _repley(i)er_, &c. or_replevir_; see _N.E.D._ s.vv. _Repledge_, _Replevy_, &c.]

3319.entry: #Reprené#, _v._ to reprehend, find fault with, VI 184. [OFr._reprendre_, _preign-_.]

3322.entry: #Rerd#, #Rurde# (V), _n._ loud voice V 269, XVII 230; noise, V 151(_see_ Rusche), XVII 101. [OE. _réord_.]

3328.entry: #Reson#, #Resoun(e)#, #Reasoune#, _n._ reason, (good) sense, VIII _a_311, XI _a_ 30, 48, _b_ 6, XII _b_ 225, XVII 501, &c.; (personified)VIII _b_ 5, &c.; what is reasonable, XVI 263; reasoning, XVI 255;argument, saying, XVI 337; _by reson_, as a logical consequence, XVII81; motive, in _by þat resoune_, with that intent, XVI 248. [OFr._raison_, _re(i)son_.]

3330.entry: #Restay#, _v._ to stop; _intr._ to pause, VI 77. [OFr. _resteir_; see_N.E.D._, s.v. _Stay_, v.]

3334.entry: #Reue#, _v._ to rob, steal, IV _b_ 20; constr. with _dat. pron._ ofperson deprived, IV _a_ 83, XV _c_ 31. [OE. _rēafian_.]

3337.entry: #Reuerence#, _n._ reverence; _at þe r._, out of respect, V 138; _do ar._, make an obeisance, XII _b_ 128. [OFr. _reverence_.]

3342.entry: #Reuþe#, #Rawþe#, _n._ (mental) pain, grief; _hedde r. þerof_, wasgrieved at that, III 20; _r. to here_, grievous to hear, V 136 (_cf._Noy, Pine). [Extended with suffix _-þ_ from OE. _hrēow_; cf. ON._hrygð_.] _See_ Rewe(ful).

3343.entry: #Reward(e)#, _n._ regard, consideration, in _takeþ r. of_ (_to_), give athought (to), XIV _c_ 105-7; reward, VI 244, XII _b_ 42. [ONFr._reward_.]

3352.entry: #Ryched#, _pp._ directed, intended, V 138. [OE. _reccan_, but form prob.due to confusion with ME. _richen_, _ruchen_ (OE. _*ryccan_), draw.]

3360.entry: #Right#, #Ryght#, #Rihte# (XII), _adj._ right, proper, true, XII _a_124, XVI 255, XVII 471, &c.; right (hand), IX 70. [OE. _riht_.]

[OE._rihte_.]

3383.entry: #Ryste#, #Rest(e)#, _v._ to rest; _intr._ IV _b_ 42, V 263; _refl._ IV_b_ 38, IX 20. [OE. _restan_; see prec.]

3396.entry: #Rode#, _n._^2 rosy hue, fair face, II 107, XV _b_ 13. [OE. _rudu_.]

3472.entry: #Sauoure#, _v._ to give a savour to, VIII _a_ 259. [OFr. _savourer_.]

3555.entry: #Se(n)#, #See(n)#, #Seo# (XV _b_), _v._ to see, perceive, I 149, II 11,462, VIII _b_ 93, IX 225, XV _b_ 17, &c.; #Seþ#, _3 sg._ II 251, 321.

3556.entry: #Sagh#, _pa. t. sg._ I 175; #Say#, I 174; #Saugh#, IX 169; #Saw#, X 161,&c.; #Seȝ(e)#, V 96, 102, &c.; #Seigh#, VIII _a_ 231; #Seiȝe#, II147, &c.; #Seih#, XV _a_ 6; #Siȝe# (riming _heiȝe_), II 355;
