3821.entry: #Spring(e)#, #Spryng#, #Sprinke#, to spring; sprout, II 67, XV _a_ 1,_b_ 9, _c_ 2, &c.; _con spryng_, was born, VI 93; #Sprang#, _pa. t. sg._rose, broke (of day), VII 167; #Yspronge#, _pp._ scattered, XIII _a_ 19.[OE. _spríngan_.]

3822.entry: #Spryng#, _n._ sunrise, early morning, IV _a_ 94. [From prec. (cf. VII167); cf. OE. _up-spríng_.]

3823.entry: #Sprit#, _pa. t._ sprang, V 248. [? OE. _spryttan_, to sprout; cf.senses of _spríngan_.]

3825.entry: #Square#, _adj._ square; of regular geometric shape, IX 55, 105;

3826.partOfSpeech: , with six (&c.) regular facets, IX106; #Squarenesse#, geometric, crystalline, shape, IX 68. [OFr.
3826.entry: #Squared#, in _six (&c.) squared_, with six (&c.) regular facets, IX106; #Squarenesse#, geometric, crystalline, shape, IX 68. [OFr._esquar(r)e_, n.; _esquarré_, adj.; _esquarrer_, v.]

3832.entry: #Stad#, #Sted(de)#, _pp._ placed, set; _stad_, _stratly stad_, _hardsted_, hard put to it, sore bested, VII 156, X 145, XVII 199; _stadwith_, furnished with, V 69; _see_ note XVI 40. [ON. _steðja_, pp._stadd-r_.]

3834.entry: #Staffing#, _n._ hitting (with a staff); beating, X 193. [From prec.]

3835.entry: #Stage#, _n._ stage; degree of advancement, VI 50; _the hihe stage_, thehigh places (of the gods), XII _a_ 51. [OFr. _(e)stage_.]

3842.entry: #Stark#, _adj._ stiff, XVII 268; _stark ded_, stiff in death, XII _a_156; hard, XV _h_ 14; strong, X 31; #Starkast#, _superl._ X 105. [OE._stearc_.]

3843.entry: #Starne#, #Sterne#, _n._ star, XVII 8; _the seven starnes_, the SevenStars, usually the Pleiades (cf. OE. _seofon steorran_,_seofon-stierre_), but here the seven 'planets' (Jupiter, Mars, Mercury,Moon, Saturn, Sun, Venus), XVII 423 (_cf._ 345). [ON. _stjarna_, earlier_*stern-_.]

3844.entry: #Start#, #Sterte(n)#, _v._ to start; flinch, V 218; _pa. t._ sprang, XII_a_ 143, 152. [OE. _styrtan_ (once), _*stertan_.]

3845.entry: #State#, _n._ state, position; _in a higher state_, at a greater height,XVII 443. [OFr. _estat_; L. _status_.] _See_ As(s)tate.

3848.entry: #Sted(e)#, #Stedde#, #Steed(e)#, _n._^1 place, I 15, IV _a_ 46, V 145,XVI 40 (_see_ note), &c.; _in þis (other) stede_, here, elsewhere, V255, XII _b_ 177; town (or _distrib. sg._ posts), X 117; stead, in _inmi stede_, _in stede of_, II 207, VIII _a_ 63; _pl._ estates, II 161.[OE. _stede_.] _See_ Stude.

3852.entry: #Steke#, _v._ to fasten, shut, &c.; #Stoken#, _pp._ shut, XVI 193;_stoken vp_, hidden away, VII 11; _hatȝ stoken me þis steuen_, has'stuck me with' this tryst, imposed it on me, V 126. [OE. in_be-stecan_; see _N.E.D._ s.v. _Steek_.]

3864.entry: #Steuen#, _n._^2 tryst, appointed meeting, V 126, 145, 170. [OE._stefn_, masc., time; ON. _stefna_, tryst.]

3865.entry: #Steward#, _n._ steward, master of (king's) household, II 205, 495, &c.;_cf._ X 36, 171. [OE. (late 11th c.) _stī-ward_.]

3868.entry: #Stiȝtel#, #Styȝtel#, _v._ to control, govern; _stiȝtleȝ_,is master, V 145; _sturn ... to stiȝtel_, ill to deal with (_or_harsh in his rule), V 69; _refl._ in _styȝtel þe vpon_, limityourself to, V 184. [Cf. OE. _stihtan_.]

3871.entry: #Still(e)#, #Styll(e)#, #Styl#, _adj._ still; motionless, I 196, II 117,V 184; quiet, silent, I 265, II 443, 525, XII _a_ 83, XV _g_ 10, 32,&c.; inactive, XI _b_ 37; calm, II 103; _holde me stille_, hold mypeace, IX 279; _stylle as þe ston_, _still as (a) stone_, firm as arock, V 225, XVII 525; perfectly quiet, XVII 406; _adv._ quietly, XV _b_21; without contention, V 317; secretly, II 567; perpetually, ever, IV_a_ 42, XVI 168. _See_ Loud(e). [OE. _stille_.]

3872.entry: #Stynk#, _v._ to stink; _to thou stynk_, until you stink, XVII 381;

3874.entry: #Stynt#, _v. trans._ to stop, check, X 65, 105; #Stint#, _pp._ ceased,II 447. [OE. _(ā)-styntan_.]

3875.entry: #Stire(n)#, #Stir(e)#, #Styr(e)#, _v. trans._ and _intr._ to stir, move,I 197, XVII 366; to toss, VII 141; to rouse, incite, induce, XI _b_ 39,93, 129, 310, XVII 37, &c.; #Steryd#, _pa. t._ I 197. [OE. _styrian_.]

3876.entry: #Stith(e)#, _adj._ stout, doughty, VII 7; violent, VII 141, 156;_quasi-sb._ doughty men, VII 21. [OE. _stīþ_.]

3879.entry: #Stok(ke)#, _n._ stem, tree-trunk, I 121, XIV _c_ 82; block, XIV _e_ 1;anvil, XV _h_ 14; _by stok oþer ston_, anywhere, VI 20; _nouþur stok norstrete_ (rime-substitute for _ston_), nothing, XIV _c_ 62; _cf._Stub(be). [OE. _stocc_.]

3882.entry: #Ston(e)#, #Stoon#, #Stane# (X), _n._ stone, rock, precious stone, II151, IX 88, X 54, 83, XI _b_ 40, XII _b_ 130, XIII _a_ 53, XV _g_ 12,&c.; stone floor, ground, II 197, V 162; _trew ... as ston in the wall_,XVII 515; for other phr. _see_ Still(e), Stok(ke), Stub(be); _cf._Stane-still. [OE. _stān_.]

3885.entry: #Stont#, II 556; #Stod(e)#, _pa. t._ I 74, II 391, V 301, &c.; #Stood#,XIII _a_ 32; #Stude#, X 196; #Standen#, _pp._ VI 159. To stand, I 8, V184, VI 154, &c.; _up him stod_, stood up, XV _g_ 27, 29 (_see_ He,_masc._); to stand firm, endure, remain, IV _a_ 42, X 196, XII _a_ 188,_b_ 221, XIV _d_ 4; _to stonde for_, stand up for, XI _a_ 66; _stonde þea strok_, stand a blow from you, V 218; to stand still, I 64, 169; _lete... stonde_, left, VIII _a_ 106; to be, XII _a_ 165, XVII 416; _hou thatit stod(e)_, how it had been settled, XII _b_ 202; how matters stood,XII _a_ 150; _how so euer it standis_, whatever the circumstances, XVII210; _to stonde in_, consist of, XI _a_ 55, 60; _upon hem stant_, isbased on, consists of, these, XII _a_ 127. [OE. _stándan_, _stóndan_.]

3886.entry: #Store#, _n._ store, stock, in _settis no store bi_, has no regard for,XVII 92. [OFr. _(e)stor_.]

3889.entry: #Stounde#, _n._ space of time; _in þat stounde_, thereupon, II 550. [OE._stúnd_.]

3892.entry: #Stout(e)#, _adj._ proud, II 293; fierce, II 184, XIV _a_ 13, XVII 304,347; _adv._ stoutly, II 360; #Stoutly#, _adv._ boldly, X 60. [OFr._(e)stout_.]

3894.entry: #Strange#, #Straunge#, _adj._ foreign, outlandish, strange, IX 274, 311,XII _a_ 13, XIII _b_ 14, 40, &c.; #Strangelych#, _adv._ in a foreigntongue, XIII 62. [OFr. _(e)strange_.]

3895.entry: #Strangere#, Introduction xv; ? _n._ stranger, foreigner, as name of(unknown) variety of stanza; ? _adj. compar._ stranger (metre; _i.e._than 'rime couée'). [OFr. _estrangier_, or _estrange_.]

3896.entry: #Stratly#, _adv._ straitly; _stratly stad_, hard put to it, X 145; _ferd... stratly with_, pressed sorely on, X 172. [From Streyte.]

3897.entry: #Strecche#, #Streche#, _v._ to stretch; _intr._ extend, IX 30, 180; todirect one's course, go, II 341; #Strauhte#, _pa. t._ (_refl._) in_strauhte him to_, made for, XII _b_ 93; #Straught#, _pp._ departed, VII11; _see_ Streght. [OE. _streccan_; _stræhte_, _strehte_.]

3902.entry: #Strenght#, #Strengthe#; #Strinth#, #Strynth# (X); _n._ strength, force,IX 71, 199, X 187, 195, XIII _b_ 65; _full strenght_, ? in full measure,fully, XVII 261. [OE. _strengþ(u)_.]

3908.entry: #Strif#, #Stryf(fe)#, _n._ strife, quarrel, VII 28, IX 83, XVII 400;_withoute stryf_, unresisting, V 255. [OFr. _(e)strif_.] _See_ Stryue.

3909.entry: #Stryke(n)#, #Strik(e)#, _v. trans._ to strike, V 31, 237, X 139, XV _h_14, XVII 231 (_subj._), &c.; _intr._ to glide, flow, II 252, XV _b_ 21;_strykeȝ_, shall come (_i.e._ for his reward), VI 210. [OE._strīcan_.]

3911.entry: #Stryþe#, _n._ stance, firm position of the feet, V 237 (cf. _stryþþe_,Sir Gaw. 846). [? Cf. OE. _stride_, stride.]

3912.entry: #Stryue#, #Stryfe#, _v._ to strive; _stryue aȝeines_, _with_, rebelagainst, disobey, VIII _a_ 315, XVII 107; #Streuyn#, _pp._ striven, XIV_b_ 86. [OFr. _(e)striver_.]

3913.entry: #Strok(e)#, #Strak# (X), _n._ blow, stroke, V 184, 255, X 105, XVII 382,&c. [OE. _*strāc_, rel. to _strīcan_, Stryken.]

3915.entry: #Strong(e)#, _adj._ strong, valiant, VI 171, VII 7, IX 92, XVI 130, &c.;violent, XIII _a_ 7, 42; severe, IX 204; _adv._ severely, VI 116 (_see_Enduir, and note); #Strongly#, _adv._ vigorously, IX 231. [OE. _stráng_,_stróng_; _stránge_, _stránglīce_, adv.]

3917.entry: #Strucyo#, _n._ ostrich (wrongly explained as 'Storke'), IV _b_ 47. [L._strūthio_, ostrich, stork.]

3918.entry: #Struye#, _v._ to destroy, VIII _a_ 29; #Strye#, V 126. [Shortened fromOFr. _destrui-re_; with vowel of _strye_ cf. Nye, Byled.] See Distroie.

3920.entry: #Stub(be)#, _n._ tree-trunk, stump, V 225; _noiþer stub no ston_,nothing, II 346 (_cf._ Stokke). [OE. _stybb_, _stubb_.]

3924.entry: #Studie#, _v._ to study, XI _b_ 112, 135, &c.; _subj. pl._ let (many)study, XI _a_ 46; #Studiynge#, &c., _n._ XI _b_ 230, 293, &c. [OFr._(e)studier_.] _See_ Vnstudied.

3925.entry: #Stuf#, _v._ to furnish, provision, XVII 155; _refl._ to gorge, glut(oneself), XVII 85. [OFr. _estofer_, to furnish; ? infl. by _estoffer_,to choke.]

3927.entry: #Sturn(e)#, _adj._ grim, V 31, 68 (_see_ Stiȝtel); #Steren#, XIV _a_13; #Sterneliche#, _adv._ grimly, VIII _a_ 315. [OE. _stýrne_,_*stéorne_.]

3929.entry: #Substance#, _n._: _þat God comaundid Himself to þe s. þerof_, of whichGod gave Himself to be the substance, XI _b_ 223. [OFr. _substance_.]

3932.entry: #Sue(n)#, _v._ to follow, VII 24, XI _a_ 38, _b_ 65, &c.; #Suiende#,_pres. p._ XII _a_ 122; #Sewyngly#, _adv._ in _seye ȝou s._, go on totell you, IX 134. [OFr. _suir_, _sewir_.]

3934.entry: #Suffise# (_to_), _v._ to be sufficient (for), IX 270; to be able,capable, XII _a_ 177 (with pleon. _mai_). [OFr. _suffire_, _suffis-_.]

3935.entry: #Suffre#, #Suffer#, _v._ to endure, suffer, bear, I 34, II 264, IV _a_88, IX 7, &c.; permit, let, VIII _a_ 74, 174, XVI 378; #Ysuffred#, _pp._II 559. [OFr. _suffrir_.]

3941.entry: #Sumoun#, _v._ to summon; _mad sumoun_, made (men) summon (them), VI179. [OFr. _sumuner_.]

3944.entry: #Suppos(e)#, _v._ to imagine, XVII 221; _suppos that_, even supposingthat, X _introd._ [OFr. _supposer_.]

3952.entry: #Swa#, #Zuo# (III), _adv. demonstr._ thus, so, in this way, III 17, 39,IV _b_ 19, 45, X 13; thereupon, III 28; therefore, III 36; in the sameway, IV _b_ 49; so mightily, X 144; _swa þat_, _zuo þet_, so that, III18, X 155, 157. [OE. _swā_.] _See_ So.

3953.entry: #Swage#, _v._ to become assuaged; to grow less, XIV _c_ 111. [Shortenedfrom OFr. _asouagier_.]

3954.entry: #Swalprit#, _pa. t._ floundered, VII 162. [? Only recorded here; cf. Du._zwalpen_; G. (dial.) _schwalpen_.]

3956.entry: #Swappit#, _pa. t._ let fly, X 83, 91, 99. [? Altered form of OE._swāpan_.]

3959.entry: #Swavnand#, _pres. p._ swooning, X 56 (_v.r._ swonande). [Not a possibleScottish form of Swone, _q.v._ Perh. scribal corruption of _swalmand_,or _swemand_; see _N.E.D._, s.vv. _Swalm_, _Sweam_.]

3963.entry: #Swere#, _v._ to swear, take one's oath, V 54, VIII _b_ 59, XII _b_ 165,XVII 227, &c.; #Swor#, _pa. t._ XII _b_ 200; #Swoir#, X 73; #Swore#,_pp._ XII _b_ 44. [OE. _swerian_.] _See_ Forsworn.

3964.entry: #Swete#, _adj._ sweet, II 414, 442, IV _a_ 73, V 169 (_see_ Sire), XV_f_ 1, &c.; #Suete#, XV _b_ 5; _swete wille_, good pleasure, II 384;_(þat) swete_, (that) sweet one, IV _a_ 78, XV _f_ 7; #Swettere#,_compar._ (_adv._) VIII _a_ 211; #Suetest#, #Swettest#, _superl._ IV _a_53, Introduction xii. [OE. _swēte_; compar. _swēttra_.] _See_Swote.

3965.entry: #Swete#, _v._ to sweat, IX 96; (joined with allit. _swynke_ or itstranslation _trauayle_), VIII _a_ 26, 122, _b_ 59, XIV _c_ 94, XVII 195;

3969.entry: #Swiche#, #Swych(e)#, _adj._ such, I 2, 92, II 198, 317, &c.; #Swech#,XV _h_ 3; #Sich(e)#, XI _a_ 41, _b_ 159, XVII 400, &c.; #Such(e)#, II46, IX 227, &c.; _swych_, _such_, such a, I 79, XII _a_ 86; _swiche a_,what a!, II 505; _swech ... a_, such a, XV _h_ 16; _suche_, of likekind, XII _a_ 82; _pron. pl._ VIII _a_ 33, 213; _alle swyche_ (with sg.verb), everything of the kind, I 9. [OE. _swelc_, _swilc_, _swylc_,_swulc_.] _See_ Swilke, Slike.

3970.entry: #Swyft#, #Swifte#, _adj._ swift, VI 211, XIV _c_ 65; #Swiftenes#, _n._swiftness, swift passing, VII 12. [OE. _swift_, _swift-nes_.]

3972.entry: #Swilke#, #Swylk(e)#, _adj._ of this kind, such, IV _a_ 35, XVI 38, 116;

3973.entry: #Sic#, X 40, 66, 74, 103, 135; _pron. pl._ such folk, IV _b_ 25.[Northern form of Swiche, _q.v._]

3975.entry: #Swimme#, to swim; #Swimmende#, _pres. p._ XII _a_ 170, 172; #Swam#,_pa. t._ VII 162. [OE. _swimman_.]

3978.entry: #Swynke#, _n._ toil; _in sudore_ (L.) _and swynke_ (var. on usual _sweteand swink_), VIII _a_ 229. [OE. _(ge-)swinc_.] _See_ Sweng.

3979.entry: #Swynke#, _v._ to toil (freq. allit. with _swete_), VIII _a_ 26, 122,188, 210, _b_ 59, XVII 195; #Swange#, _pa. t. pl._ VI 226. [OE._swincan_, and occas. in same sense _swingan_.]

3981.entry: #Swiþe#, #Swyþe#, #Swith#, _adv._ very, II 118; exceedingly, II 472;(very) quickly, I 106, II 474, V 191, XIV _b_ 51; _also swiþe_, _asswyþe_, at once, I 111, II 574 (_see_ Also, Ase). [OE. _swīþe_.]

3985.entry: #Swone#, _n._ swoon, in _fal yn a swone_, fallen in a swoon, I 195(note); orig. false analysis of _fallyn aswone_, fallen swooning (_cf._II 549). [OE. _ge-swōgen_, ME. _(y)swowen_, &c., pp.] _See_ Aswone.

3991.entry: #Tabourer#, _n._ player on the tabour, II 521. [From next.]

3993.entry: #Tache#, _v._ to fasten, V 108; _fig._, to set, implant, VI 104.[Shortened from OFr. _atachier_.]

3995.entry: #Tagyld#, _pp._ entangled, encumbered, IV _b_ 62. [Obscure; appar.peculiar to Rolle.]

3999.entry: #Take(n)#, #Tak#, #Ta# (V, X), _v._ (i) to catch, capture, VII 121, IX243, X 71, XIII _a_ 38, &c.; seize, fall upon, VIII _a_ 138, 258; get,VI 192, VIII _a_ 133, &c.; take, II 74, V 289, IX 123, X 130 (_see_Hond), 143, XIV _d_ 6, &c.; see also In(e), Mynde, Reward(e), &c.; pick(up), II 550, XII _b_ 136; assume, XII _a_ 114; choose, VIII _b_ 83,XI _b_ 76, &c.; accept, receive, XI _b_ 268, XVI 331; (ii) to commit,entrust, _see_ pp.; (iii) to make, XVII 137, 272. #Takth#, _3 sg. pres._XII _b_ 136; #Tas#, V 237; #Totȝ#, goes, VI 153 (_cf._ Nyme; _see_note). #Tok(e)#, #Took#, _pa. t._ I 136, II 19, 64, V 175 (_2 sg._) XI_b_ 273, XIV _c_ 45, &c. #Take#, _pp._ XI _b_ 271; _hath take_, hasbeen stricken with, XII _a_ 11; #Takyne#, X 71; #Tane#, X 19, XVI 172(entrusted); _hase tane_, has (got), IV _a_ 53; #Tone#, committed, V 91(_see_ VI 153, note); #Itake#, #Ytake#, XIII _a_ 38, XV _g_ 15. [ON._taka_.]

4001.entry: #Tale#, #Tayll# (XVII), _n._ tale, story; talk; word(s), what one hassaid, I 247, V 56, VI 230, XII _b_ 88, XVI 273, XVII 315, &c.; _upon thetale_, immed. after their talk, XII _b_ 147; _pl._ idle tales, VIII _a_52, 54; _see_ Telle, and next. [OE. _talu_.]

4002.entry: #Talk#, _v._ to talk; speak of, V 304; with cognate obj. in _talk þetale_, hold the converse, V 65. [Prob. OE. _*talcian_, rel. to prec.]

4005.entry: #Tappe#, _n._ tap, knock, V 289. [Echoic; cf. OFris. _tap_; OFr._taper_, v.]

4007.entry: #Tary(e)#, #Tarie#, _v._ to harass; _trans._ to hinder, delay, keep(waiting), IX 111, XVII 236; _intr._ for _refl._ to be troubled (_or_ asnext, but _cf._ Tene, _v._), XVII 210; to linger, tarry, XII _b_ 28,XVII 244, 497, 499; #Taryy(i)ng#, _n._ delay, XVII 377, 475. [OE._tergan_, &c. annoy; OFr. _tarier_, torment; the sense-development iscurious.]

4010.entry: #Tast(e)#, _v._ to test; to sound (water), XVII 448; to experience, XVI358. [OFr. _taster_.]

4011.entry: #Taterynge#, _n._ tearing (long notes) to fragments (cf. _smalebrekynge_, 138), _or_ babbling, singing without regard to the sense, XI_b_ 159. [ME. _tateren_ (i) to tear to rays; cf. ON. _töturr_, tatters:(ii) to babble; cf. MDu. MLG. _tateren_, babble.]

4014.entry: #Te#, _prep._ in _for te_ (with infin.), to, XV _b_ 30, _c_ 18.[Unaccented reduction of To.]

4015.entry: #Te#, _v._ to draw; _intr._ to go, II 212, 290, 318; #Teþ#, _pres. pl._draw near, II 274. [OE. _tēon_.]

4017.entry: #Teche(n)#, _v._ to teach, show (the way), direct, *IV _b_ 60 (_see_note), V 7, VIII _a_ 6, 76, XI _b_ 5, &c.; #Taȝt#, _pa. t._ V 311;

4018.entry: #Tauȝt(e)#, VIII _a_ 202, 296, XI _a_ 20, _b_ 12, &c.; #Tauhte#, VIII_b_ 5; #Tauȝt(e)#, _pp._ VIII _a_ 23, XI _a_ 6, &c.; #Ytauȝt#,XIII _b_ 21; #Techinge#, #-ynge#, _n._ teaching, XI _a_ 56, _b_ 121,XIII _b_ 30, &c. [OE. _tǣcan_, _tǣ̆hte_, _tā̆hte_.]

4020.entry: #Tell(e)#, #Tel#, _v._ to enumerate, recount, II 263, 373, XV _c_ 26; toaccount, consider, I 19; to tell, relate, mention (foll. by _dat._without _to_), I 22, 58, II 115, V 62, XVII 164, &c.; _herd slike talestell_, heard such tales told, XIV _b_ 35; to recite, V 120. #Telþ#, _3sg. pres._ III 38; #Talde#, _pa. t._ IV _a_ 84; #Told(e)#, I 262, II 86,&c.; #Toolde#, XI _a_ 65; #Tald(e)#, _pp._ IV _a_ 50, X 140; #Told(e)#,XII _a_ 147, XVI 149, &c.; #Ytold# (_of_), highly thought (of), XIII _b_25. [OE. _tellan_; pa. t. _tálde_.]

4023.entry: #Teme(n)# (_to_), _v._ to be attached (in loyalty to), belong, VI 100.[OE. _tēman_, appeal (to an authority).]

4025.entry: #Tempest(e)#, _n._ storm, tempest, VII 103, XII _a_ 137, &c.; _gen. sg._(before _sake_; _see_ XVII 88, note), I 177. [OFr. _tempeste_.]

4028.entry: #Tendre#, #Tender#, _adj._ soft, IX 39, 40; tender, VI 52; #Tenderly#,_adv._ tenderly, IV _a_ 87. [OFr. _tendre_.]

4030.entry: #Tene#, #Teyn# (XVII), _n._ suffering, grief, IV _a_ 36, _b_ 28, VII 81,VIII _a_ 127, XVII 533; anger, VIII _a_ 111; injury, in _in tene_,wrongfully, VII 178; as _adj._ dismal, ill, V 7. [OE. _tēona_.]

4031.entry: #Tene#, #Teyn# (XVII), _v. trans._ to injure, VIII _a_ 39; _intr._ tofeel grief, XVII 210. [OE. _tēnan_, _tēonian_.]

4034.entry: #Tent(e)#, _v._ to look after, XVI 172, XVII 433; _tent_ (_to_,_hedir_), pay attention (to, to me), XVII 291, 421. [From prec.]

4043.entry: #Text#, _n._ text; words or account of the original authority, VII 51(_cf._ Destr. Troy 407). [OFr. _texte_.]

4045.entry: #Tyde#, _n._ time; _þat yche tyde_, at the same time, together, I 208;(_at_, _in_) _þat tyde_, then, thereupon, V 18, 100, XVII 39; _þistyde_, now, XVI 184, 215. [OE. _tīd_.]

4046.entry: #Tide#, _v._ to happen, befall; _tide wat bitide_, come what may, II339; #Tid(e)#, _pa. t._ VII 81; _þat tid for to_, chanced to, did, VII178. [OE. _tīdan_.]

4048.entry: #Tiding#, #Tydinge#, #Tythyng# (XVII), _n._ (piece of) news, tidings, II97, XII _a_ 36; _pl._ news, II 487; _newe tydynges_, _tythyngis_, IX278, XVII 199. [OE. _tīdung_; ON. _tíðindi_.]

4049.entry: #Tyȝe#, #Tye#, _v._ to tie, XVII 225; as an allit. synonym of Tache(_q.v._), VI 104. [OE. _tēgan_.]

4052.entry: #Til#, #Tyl#, #Till(e)#, _conj._ until, VII 167, VIII _b_ 38, XII _a_150, XVI 24, &c. [From next.]

4053.entry: #Til#, #Till(e)#, #Tyl(l)#, _prep._ (in Northern texts synon. andinterchangeable with To; _not_ with To- _prefix_, as scribal error at X75), to, towards, into, up to, IV _a_ 6, 18, 33, X 26, 81, XIV _b_ 72,XVI 32, &c.; (postponed) IV _a_ 30, X 77, XVI 393; with _infin._ X 4,14, &c. (and _see_ For); for, IV _a_ 93, _b_ 25; until, I 185, II 75, IV_a_ 35 &c.; _till þat_, _tyl ... þat_, until (_conj._), VI 188, IX 224,229, XIV _c_ 98, &c. [OE. (rare Nth.) _til_; ON. _til_.] _See_ Intil,Þar(e).

4055.entry: #Tilye#, _v._ to labour for, earn, VIII _a_ 229; to till, VIII _a_ 232.[OE. _tilian_.]

4056.entry: #Tyme#, #Time#, time, period, season, occasion, I 142, VI 143, VII 19,VIII _b_ 106, XII _a_ 27, &c.; _whan tyme is_, when it is (the) time,VIII _a_ 11, 72; (life)time, day, I 27, VII 8, VIII _b_ 107, &c.; _pl._periods, hours, VIII _b_ 107; _any tyme_, at any time, IV _b_ 44; _atþis tyme_, (for) now, V 23, IX 270; _for þe tyme_, for the time being,XI _b_ 128; _fram tyme þat_, from the time (_conj._), XIII _b_ 21; _intyme_, opportunely, XVI 149; _many tyme_, often, IX 44; _see_ Heigh,Ofte(n), Som(e), &c. [OE. _tīma_.]

4059.entry: #Tyne#, _v._ to lose, IV _a_ 52; _to tyne_, for nothing, in vain, XVII441; #Tynde#, #Tynt#, _pp._ VII 103, VIII _b_ 97. [ON. _týna_.]

4062.entry: #Tyste#, VI 100. Usually interpreted as _tyȝte_ (_see_ App., p. 278),tight, close; this is not else recorded until early Mn.E. (where it isobscure alteration of ME. _þiȝt_, ON. _*þéht-_, _þétt-r_). _Read_Tryste, _q.v._

4063.entry: #Tyte#, _adv._ quickly, XVI 332; _as tyte_, at once, XVII 219. [ON._títt_, neut. of _tíð-r_.] _See_ Tydely.

4066.entry: #To#, _adv._ too, I 108, II 335, V 232, VI 121, VIII _a_ 260, _b_ 23,24, IX 267, XIV _a_ 2, _b_ 91. [OE. _tō_; orig. same word as To,_prep._]

4067.entry: #To#, _conj._ till, XVII 241, 381, 499; _cf._ Til. [From next; cf, OE._tō-þæs-þe_.]

4068.entry: #To#, _prep._ to, I 9, &c.; (postponed) II 119, 517; _to him was_, hehad, XI _b_ 285-6; (hunt) after, VIII _a_ 30, 31; at, II 441, 579, V265, VII 85, XVII 343 (_see_ Biholde); _to my hend_, in, under, myhands, XVII 255; in, according to, XVII 28; (turn) into, IV _a_ 94, _b_26; on, on to, II 549, V 264, VI 74, VII 174, VIII _a_ 66, IX 182; upto, III 56; until, XI _b_ 25; towards, with regard to, VI 108 (_see_Fare, _v._); against, XI _b_ 111; for, II 485, VI 147, VIII _b_ 14, XI_b_ 56, 59, XVII 109, &c.; _ȝou to_, for yourselves, XIV _d_ 7; _tome_ (IX 100), _see_ note; for, by way of, as, in, VII 70, IX 150, XI _b_223, XII _a_ 3; _see_ Mede; _to plesynge_ (&c.) _of_, so as to please,&c., IX 333, XI _b_ 108, &c. _Adv._ to it, on, XI _b_ 200; _go to_, getalong, XVII 236; _þat ... to_, to which, I 33, V 29; _to and fro_, XVII111. [OE. _tō_.] _See_ Te, Þar(e).

4070.entry: #To-breke#, _v. intr._ to burst, break, IV _a_ 78; _subj. sg._ in _þinherte þe_ (dat.) _tobreke_, may your heart be stricken with remorse (_orliterally_ break) within you, XV _g_ 10. [OE. _tō-brecan_.]

4074.entry: #To-for(e)#, _adv._ before, XII _a_ 188; _nou tofore_, just now, XII _b_43; _prep._ before, in front of, XII _b_ 131, XIII _a_ 43, _b_ 26. [OE._tō-foran_.]

4075.entry: #To-fruschyt#, _pa. t._ smashed to pieces, *X 75 (MS. till frusche;_see_ Til). [OE. _tō-_ + OFr. _fruissier_.]

4076.entry: #Toȝere#, _adv._ this year; _noȝt toȝere_, not for a long timeyet, VI 228. [OE. _tō gēare_.]

4077.entry: #To-gidre#, #-gider(e)#, #-gyd(e)re#, _adv._ together, II 121, IX 173,253, XI _b_ 9, XV _h_ 9, &c.; #To-gedre#; #-geder#, #-yr#, #-ur#, I 229,VII 131, IX 53, XIV _c_ 29, &c. [OE. _tō-gædere_.]

4079.entry: #Toȝt#, _adj._ taut, firmly bound; _made hit toȝt_, ? made acompact of it, VI 162. _Maken hit tough(t)_, is a fixed expr. = raiseobjections, make conditions (see forms and senses in _N.E.D._, s.v._Tough_); but this would require _ne_ for _and_. [OE. _*toht_, rel. to_tēon_, draw.]

4082.entry: #Token#, #-yn#, #Tokne#, _n._ token; sign, omen, XII _a_ 149, XVII 471,517; memento, V 330. [OE. _tācn_.]

4086.entry: #Tolled#, _pa. t._ enticed, I 53. [OE. _*tollian_, rel. to Tyl, _v._]

4087.entry: #Tom(e)#, #Tume# (X), _n._ leisure, opportunity, VII 43, X 143; time, VI225. [ON. _tóm_.]

4089.entry: #Ton#, _pron._ in _þe ton_, the one, XI _b_ 27, 104. [False division of_þet on_; on _þet_ see Þe, _def. art._] _See_ On(e), Toþer.

4091.entry: #Tong(e)#, #Tung(e)#, _n._ tongue, II 222, IV _a_ 89, XVII 398(_distrib. sg._; _see_ Herte); speech, language, I 58, VIII _a_ 52, XI_a_ 7, XIII _b_ 2, &c.; _hold þi tong_, XVII 217; _(spekynge) in tonge_,(words) on tongue, on our tongues, XI _b_ 121. [OE. _túnge_.]

4093.entry: #Top#, #Toppe#, _n._ hair on the crown of the head, XV _g_ 16; top, XVII469; (of a ship = Topcastell), XVII 271; _fro toppe to taile_, from topto bottom, beginning to end, XVI 159. [OE. _topp_.]

4094.entry: #Topcastell#, _n._ fighting top, embattled platform at mast-top forarchers, &c., VII 148, X 121. [Prec. + Castell, _q.v._]

4095.entry: #To-rett#, _pa. t._ rent in pieces, II 81 (riming _witt_). [OE. _tō-_ +ME. _ritten_, OE. _*rittan_.]

4100.entry: #Toþer#, #-ir#, #Toiþer#, #Touþer#, _adj._ and _pron._ in _þe toþer_,&c., the other, I 181, VII 63, IX 4, X _introd._, XI _b_ 104. [Falsedivision (not merely in spelling--_see_ allit. at VII 63) of _þet oþer_;_see_ Þe, _def. art._] _See_ Oþer(e), Ton.

4104.entry: #Touche#, #Toche#, #Towch#, _v._ to touch, reach, affect, *IV _b_ 60(note), XV _h_ 18 (note), XVII 462; _toucheth to_, joins on to, IX 182;_touche of_, touch on, treat of, IX 282, XII _a_ 90. [OFr. _toucher_.]

4106.entry: #Toun(e)#, #Tounne#, #Town(e)#, _n._ town. I 32, II 588, VII 112, 121, X12, 46, XIV _a_ 7, _b_ 83, XVII 539, &c.; _out of toun_, out of the town(_or_ from the society of men; _see_ below), II 236; _to toune_, totown, XII _b_ 27; _þe tounes ende_, end of the main street, outskirts ofthe town, II 481, 564; the dwellings of men, the world, XV _b_ 1, _c_ 28(cf. OE. _lencten gǣþ to tūne_); _in ilke a toune_, among all men,XVI 253. [OE. _tūn_.]

4107.entry: #Tour#, #Towre#, _n._ tower, II 159, 245, 359, XVII 349; (of a ship =Castell), XIV _c_ 18. [Late OE. _tūr_ from OFr. _tour_.]

4110.entry: #Toward(e)#, _prep._ towards, in the direction of, IX 31, 71, 136, &c.;_me towarde_, to me, VI 78; with regard to, in the eyes of, XII _a_ 17;

4115.entry: #Trayne#, _n._^2 error for _tayner_, burrow, fox's earth, IX 222. [OFr._taignere_.]

4116.entry: #Trayst#, _adj._ faithful, IV _a_ 41. [ON. _traust-r_, infl. by next.]_See_ Tryste, Trystyly.

4117.entry: #Traist(e)#, #Traste# (_on_, _to_), _v._ to trust (in), rely (on), IV_a_ 68, XVI 179; _tru for to traist_, to be relied on, trustworthy, VII17 (_cf._ XVII 515). [ON. _treysta_.] _See_ Trist.

4119.entry: #Transforme#, _v._ transform, XII _a_ 123; _of that he hadde betransformed_, from that (into which) he had been changed, XII _a_ 20.[OFr. _transformer_.]

4122.entry: #Trantis#, _n. pl._ tricks, XVI 159. [? Cf. MDu. _trant_, step.]

4124.entry: #Trauail(le)#, #Trauayl(e)#, #Traueile#, #Trauel#, &c., _n._ labour,toil, I 206, IV _a_ 3, _b_ 8, XI _b_ 227, XII _b_ 197; _trauel andtene_, toil and trouble, IV _a_ 36, VIII _a_ 127; affliction, I 204;travel, journey, V 173. [OFr. _travail(le)_.]

4125.entry: #Trauail(l)e#, #Trauayl(l)e#, #Traval(e)#, #Trauele(n)#, _v._ to toil,labour, IV _b_ 11, VI 190, VIII _a_ 133, X 142, XI _a_ 17, 49, XII _b_140, XIV _c_ 94; travel, XIII _b_ 40; _trans._ subject to hardship, IX272; afflict, IX 93; #Trauaillynge# (_in_), _n._ assiduity (in), VIII_a_ 244. [OFr. _travailler_.]

4128.entry: #Tre#, #Tree#, _n._ tree, II 268, 508, XII _a_ 74, XVII 34, &c.; wood,XIII _a_ 44; piece of timber, XVII 253; cross, IV _a_ 86; #Trees#, _pl._VII 103, &c.; #Treis#, logs, X 21; #Tren#, trees, XIII _a_ 51, 53;pieces of wood, XIII _a_ 44. [OE. _trēo_.]

4131.entry: #Treson#, _n._; _do him tr._, work treason against him, XIV _b_ 38.[OFr. _traïson_, AFr. _treson_.]

4135.entry: #Treuthe#; #Trouthe#, #Trowthe#, XII; #Trawþe#, V, VI; #Truth(e)#, VII;_n._ truth, VII 42, 51, 94; (personified) VIII _a_ 16, 39, &c.;fidelity, XII _a_ 164; faith, (plighted) word, troth, V 219, VIII _a_35, XII _b_ 164, 203; compact, V 280; honesty, VIII _a_ 70, 90; equity,VI 135. [OE. _trēowþ_.] _See_ Vntrawþe.

4136.entry: #Trew(e)#; #Treue#, XI _b_ 51; #Tru#, VII 17; #Truee#, V 173; #Trwe#,V 286, VI 61; _adj._ faithful, loyal, II 554, IV _a_ 41, XI _b_ 51,XII _a_ 195, XV _a_ 21, &c.; trusty, honest, V 173, 286; (vaguely, ascompliment), II 23; true, truthful, VIII _a_ 52, IX 298, XI _a_ 27, _b_71, 121, XVI 273, &c.; true (in fact), VI 61, XVII 201; #Trwe#, _adv._loyally, VI 100; honestly, V 286. [OE. _(ge-)trēowe_.] _See_ Vntrewe.

4138.entry: #Trew(e)ly#, #Treuly# (IX), #Trw(e)ly# (V), _adv._ loyally, faithfully,V 280; correctly, rightly, VIII _a_ 23, XI _a_ 37; indeed, IX 247;confidently, IV _a_ 68, V 44, XVI 95. [OE. _trēow-līce_.]

4142.entry: #Trifuls#, _n. pl._ nonsense, foolish lies, VII 43. [Cf. OFr. _trufle_.]

4144.entry: #Trist#, #Tryst#, #Trust#, _v._ to trust, XVII 505; _trew for to trist_,to be relied on, trusty, XVII 515 (_cf._ VII 17); _trust ye non other_,believe nothing else, VII 42 (_cf._ Deme); _þerto ȝe tryst_, be sureof that, V 257. [OE. _*trȳ̆stan_, or ON. _*trýsta_, rel. toTraist(e); cf. MHG. _trǖst_.]

4145.entry: #Tryste#, _adj._ trusty; _adv._ faithfully, in _trwe and tryste_, *VI100 (MS. tyste). [Related to Traiste as prec.]

4149.entry: #Troteuale#, _n._ idle tale, I 257. [Unknown (used several times byManning); ? cf. _walt(e)rot_, Piers Pl. _B_ XXI, 146.]

4152.entry: #Trow(e)#, _v._ to believe (in), be sure, think, I 23, II 429, V 137, IX151, XI _a_ 31, XIII _b_ 60, XVI 95, &c.; #Traw(e)#, VI 127, XVII 45,244, &c.; #*Trod#, _pp._ I 254 (MS. trowed; riming _God_--_see_ etym.and note); _trowe þe ... of_, trust you in, V 170; (with double obj.)_trawe me þat_, believe me in that, V 44. [OE. _trēowan_,_trūwian_, and perh. OEast Scand. _tróa_ (I 254).]

4156.entry: #Truse#, _n._ truce, VII 94. [Orig. pl.; OE. _trēow_, and _trēowa_(pl. in sg. sense).] _See_ Trewe.

4160.entry: #Tuaye#, #Twey(n)#, _adj._ two, I 41, III 10, XIII _b_ 16, XV _h_ 18.[OE. _twēgen_, masc.] _See_ Tuo.

4161.entry: #Tulk(e)#, _n._ man, V 65, VII 63. [? Cf. ON. _túlk-r_, spokesman.]

4163.entry: #Tuo#, _adj._ (orig. _fem._ and _neut._ of Tuaye, and still sodistinguished in use in III), two, II 83, III 12, XII _a_ 29, 136, 180;

4164.entry: #Two#, V 284, &c.; #Twa#, IV _b_ 14; #To#, II 64, 111, 135; _in two_,(broken) in two, XVII 412; _oone or two_, one or two, several, XVII 133,484. [OE. _twā_.] _See_ Ato.

4167.entry: #Turn(e)#; #Teorne#, XIII _a_ 53; #Torne#, IV _a_ 44 (_see_ note), XII_passim_; #Tourne#, IV _a_ 3, V 7; _v. trans._ to turn, IX 73, XIII _a_32; _turned into_, diverted to, XI _a_ 229; with _(in)til_, _(in)to_,change, turn (into), IV _a_ 94, _b_ 26, VIII _b_ 107, XII _a_ 168, XIII_a_ 43, &c.; pervert, VII 42, XVI 332; translate, XI _a_ 36; _refl._turn, IV _b_ 37; _intr._ turn (back), IV _b_ 83, XII _a_ 33, _b_ 142;_turne vntill_, turn upon, XVII 218; _turne to_, return upon, IX 87;pass, proceed (to), V 7, XIV _a_ heading; (with _til_, _into_) change,turn (into), IV _a_ 72, XIII _a_ 30, 53; _turneth to ben_, turns,becomes, IX 23. #Yturnd# (_to_), inclined to, fond of, XIII _b_ 64;

4172.entry: #Tweluemonth(e)#, #Twelmonyþ#, _n._ twelvemonth, year, I 97;_quasi-adv._ a year ago, V 175; _þat tweluemonþe_, all that year, I 103;_(at þe) tweluemonth ende_, at the end of a year, I 95, 187. [OE. _twelfmōn(a)þ_, pl.]

4173.entry: #Twyneth#, _3 sg. pres._ twines, joins, XV _h_ 18 (_see_ note). [ME._twīnen_; ? from OE. _twīn_, twine, _n._]

4174.entry: #Twynkelyng#, _n._ twinkling, in _yn tw. of an ye_, I 192. [OE._twinclian_.]

4175.entry: #Twyn(ne)#, _v. intr._ separate, part, IV _a_ 19, XVI 278. [Cf. OE._(ge-)twinn_, double.] _See_ Atwynne.

4176.entry: #Twyys#, _adv._ twice, I 182; for the second time, XVII 362. [OE._twi(g)a_ + adv. _-es_.]

4177.entry: #Twnnys#, _n. gen. sg._ tun's, great cask's, X 26. [OE. _tunne_.]

4178.entry: #Þaȝ(e)#, #Þau# (XV), _conj._ (with _subj._) though, even if, III 40,V 44, 68, VI 8, XV _g_ 30; if, that (after 'no wonder'), V 239, 346.[OE. unacc. form _þah_, or ON. _*þoh_; _see_ Þogh, Þei.]

4179.entry: #Þai#, #Þay#, #Þei#, #Þey#, _adj. pl._ those, X 25, 27, 135; _pron. pl._those, IX 128, 149, 216 (second), X 13, 68, &c.; they, I 32, II 32, 523,IV _b_ 8, VIII _a_ 144, XVII 24, &c.; _alle þay_, all of them, V 357, IX104. _Acc._ and _dat._ (to, for) them, those: #Þaym(e)#, IV _b_ 2, 19,23, 37, &c.; #Þam(e)#, IV _b_ 25, X 13, XIV _b_ 14, &c.; _refl._ (to,for) themselves, IV _b_ 20, 37, 39, X 3, 41, &c.; #Þamselfe#, _acc._themselves, IV _b_ 12. _Poss. adj._ (_gen. pl._), their: #Þair(e)#, IV_a_ 61, _b_ 14, 19, X 28, &c.; #Þar(e)#, IV _a_ 59, X 78, XVI 18, 310,&c.; #Þeire#, #Þeyre#, IV _b_ 27, 41; #Þer(e)#, VII 9, XI _a_ 1, XVI 20,30, &c. [ON. _þei-r_, _þeim_ (dat.), _þeira_.] _See_ Hi, _pron. pl._

4183.entry: #Thank(e)#, _v._ to thank, XVI 381, XVII 172, &c.; #Þonk(k)e#, II 472, V340, XII _b_ 135; #Thankynge#, _n._ IX 334. [OE. _þancian_, _þoncian_.]

4184.entry: #Þan(ne)#, _adv._ then, thereupon, afterwards, in that case,consequently, I 224, III 7, VII 169, VIII _a_ 34, XI _b_ 16, 150, &c.;

4186.entry: #Þan(ne)#, #Þane#, #Þen(n)#, _conj._ than, I 11, IV _b_ 82, V 32, VI195, IX 249, XVII 13, &c.; nor, XVII 108 (_see_ note), 535. [As prec.]

4188.entry: #Þar#, _3 sg. pres._ need, V 287; _impers._ in _ȝow_ (acc.) _þar_,you need, I 132. [OE. _þearf_.]

4189.entry: #Þar(e)#, #Thair#, _adv._ there, IV _b_ 39, V 105, X 31, 156, XIII _a_10, &c.; _anticipatory_ IV _a_ 70, 89, &c.; _rel._ (in cases) where,when, IV _a_ 1, 41, 82, XIII _a_ 4; combined with _prep._ or _adv._,there-, it, them: #Tharat#, X 182, 186, &c.; #Þar(e)for(e)#, on thataccount, &c., I 88, 254, XV _f_ 6, &c.; #Þarfram#, (after _þat_ rel.)from, XIII _a_ 37; #Þar(e)in#, #Þarynne#, IV _a_ 26, X 128, XIII _a_ 38;

4190.entry: #Þar(e)of#, IV _b_ 57, X 23; #Thartill#, to it, X 48; #Þarto#, IV _a_68, X *97, 181; #Tharwith#, thereby, *IV _b_ 63. [OE. _þǣr_,_þār(a)_; and prob. unaccented _þær_, _þara_.] _See_ Þer(e), Þore.

4192.entry: #Þat#, #Þet# (III), _conj._ (i) With _indic._ that, I 30, II 333, III 5,&c.; so that (of _result_), II 439, V 246, XV _b_ 12, &c.; until, II 76;after Swa (So), Swych, &c., _passim_; (with _neg._), without (with _vbl.sb._) I 156, 197, &c. (ii) With _subj._ that, to (with _infin._; _esp._after verbs of commanding, desiring, purposing, &c.), II 534, III 7, 37,XI _b_ 217, XIV _c_ 99, &c.; loosely connected with what precedes, VIII_a_ 11 (note), 52, XI _b_ 247; lest (after 'fear'), XI _a_ 61, XVII 184,372, &c.; so that (of _purpose_), in order that, lest (with _neg._), I220, IV _a_ 22, _b_ 13, XVI 199, 399, &c.; _see_ Forbede. _So that_, inorder that, XII _a_ 19, &c.; _wende ... þat_, go ... and, VIII _a_ 271._Indef._ where, if, IV _b_ 75, 83, &c. (iii) Forming conjunctions withpreps. and advs. (orig. a pro-nominal use as in OE. _for þam þe_), _see_the preps. &c.; subjoined to other conjs. (as Ȝif, &c.), _see_ theconjs.; or to rel. and interrog. advs. (_see_ Þat, _rel._), as _whanthat_, when, IX 22, &c.; hence used to obviate repetition of a conj., in_whan (that) ... and that_, when ... and when, XII _a_ 36, _b_ 155-6,180-2; similarly pleonastic in _þe more þat_, the more, XI _b_ 114. [OE._þæt_, _þætte_.]

4193.entry: #Þat#, #Þet#, _demonstr. adj._ (i) As _def. art._ (orig. _neut._), _see_Þe. (ii) _Emphatic_ that, I 93, 108, &c.; the same, that very, I 95,190, 226, &c. #Þane#, _acc. sg. masc._ that, III 9. For _pl._ _see_ Þo,Þos. [_See_ next.]

4194.entry: #Þat#, #Þet# (III), _pron._ that, it, the same, II 131, 543, III 56, V44, XIII _b_ 49, &c.; even that, VIII _a_ 306; _am I that_, is it I (youmean), XV _g_ 27; _that is myne_, there's one from me, XVII 226; _thatwithoute_, what is outside, XII _a_ 73; _quasi-adv._ (at) that, too,XVII 146; as regards that, XVII 524 (_see_ Bold). #Þan#, _dat. sg._ in_after (bi) þan_, after (by) that, II 553, 597; _see_ Bi, Wiþ. [OE._þæt_ (Kt. _þet_), neut.; _þane_, acc. masc.; _þā̆m_, dat.]

4195.entry: #Þat#, #Þet# (III), _rel. pron. indecl._ that, which, who(m), I 11, 16,47, III 17, &c.; for whom, XIV _a_ 32 (_see_ Betre; but here _þat_ isperh. already felt as _nom._); a thing which, XI _b_ 26, &c.; _þat þat_,that which, what, IV _b_ 65, IX 70, &c.; _þat at_, VI 176; _it ... þat_,VIII _a_ 242, &c.; (elliptically) _þat_, that which, I 178, 180, II 516,XVII 164, &c.; he who, V 196; him that, VIII _a_ 114; those whom, XVI 8;_same þat_, just what, XVI 71, &c.; (loosely, or with ellipse of prep.)_þat_, to whom, VI 64, XV _i_ 4; (as that) in which, I 188; (from that)in which, IX 320; that into which, XII _a_ 20. Supplemented by pers.prons., as _þat ... hym_, whom, V 37; _þat ... hit_, which, I 185, IV_a_ 36, V 127, IX 6, X 6; _þat þai_, which, XIV _b_ 76; _that ... thameilkane_, X 160 (_see_ note); similarly, _þat ... þat tyde_ (= then),when, V 17; _þat ... þerof_, of which, XI _b_ 222-3; _cf._ XIII _a_36-7. For use with separated preps. and advs. (as, _þat ... of_, ofwhom, VI 65) _see_ the preps., &c.; note _þat ... after_, that afterwhich, VII 20, _same þat ... fro_, same as that from which, IX 230.Subjoined to other relatives, and indir. interrogatives, _see_ Hou,Whan, What, &c.; _cf._ Þat, _conj._ [Substitution of prec. for OE. _þe_;_þat_, that which, may in part repres. OE. _þæt-þe_, _þætte_.] _See_App., p. 289.

4196.entry: #Þatow#, = _þat þou_, that thou, II 165, 454, 471; cf. _þat tou_, XV _g_9. _See_ Þou.

4198.entry: #Þe#, _adv._; _demonstr._ (by) so much, for that, the, V 300, VIII _b_100; (pleonastic), VIII _a_ 112; _the wars I thee see_, so much theworse for seeing you, XVII 191; _rel._ by which, in _þe better_, (so)that ... better, VIII _a_ 46, XVII 175; _correl._ in _þe ... þe (...þe)_, the ... the, I 255, VI 240 (_see_ note). [OE. _þȳ_, _þē̆_.]_See_ Forþi.

4199.entry: #Þe#, _def. art._ the, I 8, *XVI 170 (MS. ȝe), &c.; _generic_, IX109, &c.; _see_ Whiche, Whilke, Who. #Te#, in _an te_, and the, XV _e_19; #Th-# (before vowels), XII _a_ 127, _b_ 191, 211. #Þane#, _acc. sg.masc._ III 10, 14, 59; #Þat#, #Þet#, _neut. sg._ III 41, 44, 46, 57;with French _masc._ III 46; before vowels and merging into Þat_demonstr._, I 43; _esp._ in _þat yche_, _ilk(e)_, the same, &c., I 208,V 65, &c.; but _þe ilke_, masc. and fem., III 27, 45; _þat o(n)_, theone, V 244, 344, IX 176, XV _h_ 7; _þat oþer(e)_, the other, V 72, 169,200, 344, XII _a_ 118, XV _h_ 7; _see_ Ich, Ilke, Ton, Toþer, &c. [OE._se_ (late _þe_), &c.]

4200.entry: #The#, _v._ to prosper, in _as euer myght I the_, so may I prosper, onmy life, XVII 328. [OE. _þēon_.]

4213.entry: #Þouȝte#, #Thoughte#, VIII _a_ 293, IX 167; #Thoght#, #Þouȝt#,_pp._ II 390, XIV _b_ 53, &c.; to consider, XVI 3; _þ. on_ (_vpon_),think, be mindful, of, IV _a_ 78, 95, V 329, VI 10, &c.; intend to, beresolved to, VII 30, X 79; expect to, XII _a_ 28; _þ. to_ (_for to_,_till_), expect to, VIII _a_ 293, X 28, XIV _b_ 36, &c.; conceive,imagine, II 373, 390, XVII 286, &c.; #Thynkynge#, _n._ IV _b_ 68. [OE._þencan_, _þō̆hte_.] _See_ Þinke.

4215.entry: #Þens#, _adv._ thence, in _from þens_, IX 259, XVII 548. [Prec. + adv._-es_.]

4216.entry: #Þer(e)#, _adv. demonstr._ there, I 98, II 189, III 42, &c.; _correl._in _þere ... where_, where, IX 222; _indef._ (unaccented; _see_ Þyr), II10, 39, XII _a_ 75, &c.; _rel._ where, when, I 154, V 8, 52, 329, VIII_a_ 240, XII _a_ 141, &c.; equiv. to _neut. pron._ it, that, them, andoccas. _rel._ which: #Þer(e)aboute(n)#, (round) about it, IX 156, *XI_b_ 252; #Þerafter#, afterwards, V 350, VIII _a_ 108, &c.; according toit, XI _b_ 244; #Þerap(p)on#, on it, &c., VII 75, XVII 282; #Þerate#,there, II 380, VI 154; #Þerby(e)#, by that means, XI _a_ 13, XVI 161; onthat account, XIII _b_ 35; according to it, XVI 322; #Þer(e)for(e)#,

4217.entry: #Þeruore#, &c., on that account. I 71, III 41, V 211 (pleonastic), 289,XVII 20, &c.; on account of which, XVI 167; because, IX 108 (note);

4220.entry: #Ther(e)myd(d)e#, therewith, VIII _a_ 69, 151; #Þer(e)of#, #Þereoffe#,of it, from it, &c., III 20, IV _a_ 39, VIII _a_ 191, IX 6, &c.; _rel._of which, XIII _a_ 31; _see_ Þat, _rel._; #Þeron#, of it, VI 27;

4221.entry: #Þerto#, to it (that), V 257, XVII 385; at it, XIII _a_ 48; for it, XI_b_ 254; in addition, XII _b_ 200; (after _rel._) to, XI _b_ 246, XIII_a_ 37; #Þer vnder#, underneath (them), V 11; #Þerupon#, at it, XII _b_162; #Þer(e)with#, by that means, VIII _a_ 95, 102, &c.; with it (afterPart, _v._), VII 96. [OE. _þǣr_, _þēr_.] _See_ Þar(e), Þyr, Þore.

4223.entry: #Þerewhiles#, _adv._ in the meantime, VIII _a_ 8. [OE. _(on) þǣrehwīle_ + adv. _-es_.] _See_ Þerwhile.

4225.entry: #Þerwhile#, _conj._ while, VIII _a_ 156; _see_ While. [OE. _on þǣrehwīle þe_.] _See_ Þerewhiles.

4226.entry: #Þes#, _demonstr. adj._ (and _pron._) _sg._ this, VIII _b_ 78, XV _i_18; #Þis(ē)#, #Þys(se)#, I 20, II 47, VI 10, 173, &c.; #Þhis#, XVI61; _this_, this woman, XVII 403; #Þeise#, _pl._ these, IX 117, 318;

4227.entry: #Þes#, VIII _b_ 42, XI _a_ 61, &c.; _pron._ V 354, VII 50, &c.; #Þese#,I 43, 47, &c.; #Þis#, #Þys#, II 13, 340, VI 145 (_note_), XVII 445, &c.;

4234.entry: #Þyderward#, #Thederward#, _adv._ thither, in that direction, XIII _a_33, XVII 245. [OE. _þiderw(e)ard_.]

4236.entry: #Thilke#, _adj._ that (same), XII _b_ 59, 205, 220; #Þulke#, those, XIII_a_ 2. [OE. _þylc_, such; treated in sense as a contraction of Þe +Ilk(e), _q.v._]

4237.entry: #Thine#, _adv._ thence, in _fra thine furth_, thenceforward, X 130.[Obscure red. of ME. _þeþen_ (cf. ON. _þaðan_); cf. _sine_ from_siþ(þ)en_, _seþen_.]

4239.entry: #Þing(e)#, #Þyng#, #Þynk# (VI), _n._ thing, II 33, IV _a_ 29, &c.; _alþat þing_, everything there, II 417; _al this thyng_, all this, XVII154. _Na thyng_, _no þing_ (_þynk_, &c.), nothing, anything (with_neg._), II 172, IV _a_ 6, VI 136, 227, IX 275, &c.; as _adv._ no whit,in no way, I 67, II 39, V 168, XVII 289; _na kyn thing_, no whit, X 59;_for no þing_, for any (other) cause, II 98. #Þing#, &c., _pl._ things,affairs, matters, I 7, II 4, 218, 297, XI _b_ 249; #al(le) þing#, &c.(constr. as _sg._ or _pl._) everything, II 11, IV _a_ 68, VIII _a_ 203,IX 239, XIV _c_ 2, XVII 73, &c.; all things, XV _c_ 6; _bi al þing_, byevery token, II 321, 375; #Þinges#, #Thyngeȝ#, &c., II 496, IV _b_62, &c.; compositions, tasks, XIII _b_ 19. [OE. _þing_.]

4240.entry: #Þink(e)#, #Þynk(e)#, #Þenk(e)#, _v._ to seem to (with _dat. pron._), II442; #Þynkkeȝ#, thou seemest, V 294; _impers._ in _me þinkeþ_,_thynkys me_, &c., it seems to me, VIII _b_ 55, XIV _c_ 28, XVII 511,&c.; endingless form in, _me (him, vs) þink_, &c., it seems to me, Ithink, &c., II 375, IV _a_ 10, 12, V 41, VI 192, 230, XVII 399, &c.;_þynk me_, XVII 255; with _nom. pron._ in _thou thynk_, (it) seems goodto you, XVII 196, 379. #Þoȝt#, #Thoght(e)#, _pa. t._ (it) seemed to,V 95, XII _b_ 74, XVII 82, 425; with _nom. pron._ in _þey þoȝt_, theythought good, I 87. [OE. _þyncan_, _þū̆hte_. The endingless formsprob. arose in _1 sg._ by confusion with Þenche, _q.v._; but _cf._ ON._þykki mér_.]

4241.entry: #Þyr#, _adv. indef._ there, I 170. [Reduced unaccented form of Þer(e);_y_ repres. obscure vowel, as (_e.g._) in _þedyr_, 171.]

4242.entry: #Thire#, _adj._ and _pron. pl._ these, IV _b_ 55, 59; #Þer#, XVI 97,399. [Obscure; usually Northern.]

4246.entry: #Þo#, _demonstr. adj. pl._ those, V 130, VII 113, VIII _b_ 5, IX 33,&c.; _pron._ they, those, &c. II 575 (second), VI 197, VIII _a_ 155, IX48, XV _b_ 23, XVI 279, XVII 228. [OE. _þā_.] _See_ Þat.

4247.entry: #Þo#, _adv._ then, thereupon, II 49, 117, III 12, VIII _a_ 22, XII _a_6, &c.; in addition, more, in _þo fyue_, five (times) more, VI 91;_rel._ when, III 3, 32, 44, 54, 56. [OE. _þā_.]

4248.entry: #Þof#, _conj._ though, even if, IV _a_ 12, 75, VII 29. [As next, withalteration of final spirant; _cf._ Þouþ; Rof.]

4249.entry: #Þogh#, _conj._ though, (even) if, IX 207, XII _a_ 187, &c.; _þogh þat_,though, I 224; #Þou#, XV _f_ 8; #Þouȝ#, #Þough#, IX 139, XIV _c_ 37,&c.; #Þowȝ#, #Þowgh#, VIII _a_ 36, 40, &c. [ON. _þó_, earlier_*þoh_.] _See_ Þaȝe, Þei, Allthough.

4251.entry: #Þolien#, #Þole#, _v._ to endure, IV _a_ 14, V 351, XV _c_ 33; #tholid... for to be#, suffered myself to be, XVI 3. [OE. _þolian_.]

4253.entry: #Þore#, _adv._ there, then, I 96, 175, V 288, VI 202. [OE. _þāra_.]_See_ Þar(e).

4254.entry: #Þorgh#, _prep._ through; throughout, over; because of, out of; by(means of): IX 87, XV _i_ 3, &c.; #Thoro#, XVII 278; #Þorw#, VIII _a_20, XIV _c_ 19, &c.; #Thorwgh#, VIII _a_ 320; #Þourgh#, VIII _a_ 320;

4255.entry: #Throu#, X 15; #Throughe#, VII 16, 92; #Þurch#, II 237, &c.; #Þurȝ#,V 83, VI 53, &c.; #Þurgh(e)#, I 186, IV _b_ 71, VII 103, &c.; _adv._through, IX 224. [OE. _þurh_, _þorh_.]

4259.entry: #Þou#, _pron._ thou, you, I 130, II 108, &c.; #Þow(e)#, IV _a_ 22, V256, XVI 242, &c.; #Þu#, VII 94; #Tou#, #Tow# (after closely connectedwords ending in _d_, _t_, _s_), II 452, XV _a_ 17, _g_ 9; _see_ also_artow_, _canstow_, _hadestow_, _neltow_, _saltou_, _shaltow_, _þatow_,_wiltou_, _wolte_ (with further reduction). #Þe#, #The(e)#, #Te# (after_is_), _acc._ thee, you, II 116, XVII 118, 407, &c.; _dat._ (to, for)thee, II 132, V 175, 218, 291, XV _g_ 10, &c.; concerning thee, XV _g_28; _what is te_, _what þe is_, what is the matter with thee, II 102,115; _for the_, as far as you are concerned, XVII 193; _refl._ (to, for)thyself, yourself, V 184, 229 (first), 289, VIII _a_ 32, 223, XV _f_ 13,XVII 224, &c. #Þi#, #Þy#; #Þin#, #Þyn(e)# (usually before vowels);_poss. adj._ thy, your, I 125, II 105, V 235, VI 207, &c.; (_objective_)of thee, VIII _a_ 27, XV _g_ 31, &c.; #Þine#, #Þyne#, _oblique_ and_pl._ II 109, XV _c_ 23, &c.; _pron._ belonging to thee, XVI 221; thyfolk, XVI 252. #Þiselffe#, #-selue#; #Þyseluen#, #-self(e)#, _nom._(thou) thyself, XVI 206, 261, 299: _refl._ thyself, V 73, VI 113, XVI350, &c. [OE. _þū̆_, _-tū̆_; _þē̆_; _þīn_.]

4262.entry: #Þouȝt#, _n._ thought, mind, imagination, II 373; #Þoȝte#, VI 164,_see_ Dede; #Thoght(e)#, IV _a_ 5, _b_ 23, XVII 156, &c. [OE._(ge-)þō̆ht_.]

4264.entry: #Þousand(e)#, #-end#, #-ond#; #Þouzond#; #Thowsande#; _n. sg._ and _pl._thousand, III 30, 34, VIII _a_ 185, XI _b_ 279, XIII _b_ 31, XVI 39, &c.[OE. _þūsend_.]

4266.entry: #Þouþ#, _conj._ though, even if, XI _b_ 190. [As Þogh, with alterationof final spirant; _cf._ Þof.]

4268.entry: #Thrall#, _n._ slave; predic. as _adj._ in bondage, subject, XVI 134.[OE. _þrǣ̆ll_, from ON. _þrǽl-l_.]

4269.entry: #Þre(e)#, _adj._ three, I 196, II 70, IX 244, &c.; #Þri#, III 6, 15;_þre (squared)_, IX 106; _a þre_, in three, XIII _b_ 49. [OE. _þrēo_,fem., neut.; _þrī(e)_, masc.]

4272.entry: #Þrestelcoc#, _n._ (male) throstle, song-thrush, XV _b_ 7. [OE._þrostle_ + _cocc_; on form see _N.E.D._, s.v. _Throstle_.]

4273.entry: #Þrete#, _v._ to threaten, V 232, XIV _a_ 31; to wrangle, VI 201;_refl._ in _him þreteþ_, wrangles, chides, XV _b_ 7 (note). [OE._þrēatian_; ? ON. _þrǽta_ (in sense 'wrangle').]

4276.entry: #Þrewe#, _pa. t._; _ouer ... þrewe_, overturned, II 578. [OE._þrāwan_, twist; pa. t. _þrēow_.]

4279.entry: #Thirde#, #Thyrde#, IV _b_ 6, XVI 31; _at þe þrid_, on the thirdoccasion, V 288; _þe þryd(de) tyme_, for the third time, I 142, XII _b_81, XVII 460. [OE. _þridda_, late Nth. _þirda_.]

4282.entry: #Thryft#, _n._ prosperity; in oath _by my thryft_ = _as euer myght Ithrife_ (_see_ The, Þriue), XVII 218. [ON. _þrift_.]

4285.entry: #Þrynge#, _v._ to press; _intr._ make one's way, V 329; #Thringand#,_pres. p._ pressing, X 166. [OE. _þríngan_.]

4288.entry: #Þriuaund#, _pres. p._ prosperous; goodly, noble, VII 158. [From next.]_Cf._ Thrifty.

4289.entry: #Þriue#, #Thrife#, #Thryfe#, _v._ to prosper; _I may not thryfe_, I canill bear it, _or_ may scarcely recover, XVII 414; in oaths: _so mot þouþriue_, _as euer myght I thrife_, &c., so may you (I) prosper, on your(my) life, II 532, XVII 191, 243 (_cf._ The, _v._). [ON. _þrífa-sk_.]

4292.entry: #Þrowe#, _n._ time, moment, XII _b_ 59; _a þrowe_, for a time, I_introd._, V 151. [OE. _þrāg_.]

4293.entry: #Þrublet#, _pa. t._ crowded, gathered (_intr._), VII 132. [Obscure. In_N.E.D._ as var. of _Trouble_, grow dark; but cf. _Purity_, 504, 879.]

4297.entry: #Þus#, _adv._ thus, so, I 37, XI _b_ 270, XII _a_ 88, XVI 283, &c.;therefore, XI _a_ 40. [OE. _þus_.]

4300.entry: #U-#, #V-#; for init. _u_, _v_ (in III) see also F.

4301.entry: #Vayn(e)#, _adj._ frivolous, vain, worthless, IV _b_ 28; #Veyn#, XI _b_104, 124, 137, &c.; _yn veyn_, _in vayn_, in vain, I 178, XVII 360.[OFr. _vain_.]

4306.entry: #Vanyté#, _n._ frivolity, vanity, vain thing, IV _b_ 13, 52, XI _b_ 181,219, XIV _c_ 3. [OFr. _vanité_.]

4313.entry: #Venge# (_on_), _v._ to take vengeance (on); _it schal ben venged ...so_, such vengeance shall be taken, XII _b_ 100. [OFr. _venger_.]

4314.entry: #Venia(u)nce#, #Vengaunce#, _n._ vengeance, punishment, I 92, 129, VIII_a_ 138, XI _b_ 49, XVII 55, &c. [OFr. _venjance_.]

4317.entry: #Ver(r)ay#, _adj._ true, IX 65, XVII 1; _adv._ truly, very, XVII 198;

4323.entry: #Vertu(e)#, _n._ power, peculiar property, quality, IX 67, 70, 74, XII_b_ 175, XV _i_ 3, &c.; virtue, IV _b_ 16, V 307; _kyng of vertues_, XVI128 (_see_ note). [OFr. _vertu_.]

4324.entry: #Vertuous#, #Virtuus#, _adj._ in possession of its proper qualities, IX126; virtuous, VII 49. [OFr. _vertuous_.]

4331.entry: #Vylany#, #Velany#, _n._ unknightly conduct, V 307; ignominy, shamefulfate, XVII 67. [OFr. _vilanie_.]

4334.entry: #Vyndland#, _pres. p._ turning over and over, X 129. [Cf. ON. _vindla_,wind.]

4336.entry: #Violastres#, _n. pl._ as supposed name of a kind of diamonds ofinferior lustre; due to mistransl. of French _violastres_ (adj. pl.),purplish, IX 97 (note).

4338.entry: #Vyolet#, #Violet(te)#, _n._ violet (flower), IX 99, XV _e_ 13;(colour), IX 98; _see_ IX 97 note. [OFr. _violet(te)_.]

4346.entry: #Vmbethoucht# (_hym_), _pa. t._ bethought (him), reflected, X 179. [OE._*ymb(e)-þencan_ (cf. _ymbe-þanc_); but prefix is influenced by ON._umb_.]

4347.entry: #Vmbreide# (_of_), _pa. t. subj._ reproached (with), XII _b_ 98. [OE._ūp-gebregdan_, upbraid, with prefix assimilated to ME. _umb(e)_ asin prec.]

4351.entry: #Vnbynde#, _v._ to unbind, release, XVI 8; #Vnbounde#, _pp._ I 228. [OE._on-bíndan_, late _un-bíndan_.]

4358.entry: #Vnder#, #-ur#, _prep._ under, II 70, IX 179, XIII _a_ 15; (postponed) V250; _see_ Gore, Heuenryche; _adv._ underneath, XVII 409; in reality(opposed to appearance on surface), VII 18, XIV _a_ 18; _see_ Þere. [OE._under_.]

4359.entry: #Vnder#, _n._ 'the third hour', about the middle of the morning, VI 153.[OE. _undern_.] _See_ Vndertide.

4360.entry: #Vnderȝete#, _pa. t. pl._ perceived, II 576. [OE. _under-getan_, pa.t. pl. _-gē(a)ton_.]

4362.entry: #Vndernome#, _pp._ taken in (mentally), realized, II 320. [OE._underniman_, pp. _-numen_.] _See_ Nym(e).

4363.entry: #Vnderstonde#, #Vndirstand(e)#, &c., _v._ to understand; comprehend, I12, IV _b_ 76, IX 214, XI _b_ 117, XIII _b_ 55, &c.; learn, be told, I26, II 215, IX 187, &c.; _vnderst. bi_, intend (to be understood) by, XI_a_ 9; _vnderst. of preiere of holy lif_, mean by 'prayer' (thatconsisting in) holy living, XI _b_ 82; #Vnderstod#, _pa. t._ XII _b_ 36,88, &c. [OE. _understándan_, _-stóndan_.]

4364.entry: #Vnderstondyng(e)#, #-standynge#, &c., _n._ comprehension, XI _b_ 134;intelligence, IV _b_ 49, 56, 65; _of kynde vnderst._, it stands toordinary reason, naturally, VIII _b_ 58. [OE. _under-stánding_.]

4367.entry: #Vndertide#, #Vndrentide#, _n._ (orig.) mid-morning, (_esp._ as time fora rest from work), but often vaguely applied and appar. nearly equiv. to'noon', II 65, 76, 133, 181, 282; _slepe her undertides_, were taking anoontide sleep, II 402. [OE. _undernīd_.] _See_ Vnder, _n._

4369.entry: #Vndo#, _v._ to undo, open, XVI 182; #Vndede#, _pa. t._ II 385. [OE._on-dōn_, _un-dōn_.] _See_ Do(n).

4371.entry: #Vnité#, _n._ coherence of mind, sanity (? but this sense unexampled),VIII _b_ 10. [OFr. _unité_, unity.]

4373.entry: #Vnkinde#, #Vnkuynde#, _adj._ unnatural (in conduct, &c.); disloyal, XIV_c_ 103; hard-hearted, XII _b_ 1, 220, 224. [OE. _un(ge)cýnde_.]

4378.entry: #Vnneþe#, _adv._ with difficulty, hardly, II 221, 416, XIII _b_ 60, XIV_c_ 4. [OE. _un-ēaþe_.]

4382.entry: #Vnryghtwysely#, _adv._ unrighteously; more than is right, IV _b_ 24.[OE. _un-rihtwīs-līce_.]

4385.entry: #Vnsober#, _adj._ violent, VII 143; #Vnsoberly#, _adv._ violently, VII130. [From OFr. _sobre_.] _See_ Sobre.

4386.entry: #Vnsoght#, _adj._ unexpiated, not atoned for, XVII 97. [ME._un-sa(u)ght_, from ON. _ú-sáttr_ (older _*un-saht-_); cf. OE._un-seht_. The orig. rimes were prob. _naght_, _saght_, _wraght_; _see_Werche.]

4388.entry: #Vntil(l)#, _prep._ to, XII _a_ 132, XVI 370, XVII 218 (_see_ Turne);until, XVI 52. [As next with subst. of interchangeable _til_.]

4389.entry: #Vnto#; #Vntew#, XVII 505; _prep._ to, I 111, II 186, XII _a_ 25, XVI319, XVII 241; towards, for, XVI 246; up to, until, I 95, VII 95, IX328. [? OE. _*untō_; cf. OS. _untō_, prep.; Goth. _untē_,conj.]

4404.entry: #Vochen saf#, _pres. pl._ guarantee (_sc._ me), VIII _b_ 51. [OFr._vo(u)cher sauf_.]

4407.entry: #Vp#, #Vpp(e)#, _adv._ up, I 200, II 96, V 11, XVI 113, &c.; open, X185; (open) wide, XVI 122, 194; _vp wiþ_, up with, lift up, hold high,XIV _c_ 99. [OE. _ūp_, _upp(e)_.]

4408.entry: #Vpcaste#, _pa. t._ lifted up, XII _a_ 106. [OE. _up(p)_ + ON. _kasta_.]_See_ Cast(e).

4411.entry: #Vp(p)on#; #Vpo#, XV _g_ 4; #Opan#, II 506; #Opon#, II 72, &c.; #Apon#,IV _a_ 86, X 123, &c.; _prep._ (i) (up)on, V 134, VIII _a_ 135, IX 33, X183, XII _a_ 126 (_see_ Stonde), XIII _a_ 12, &c.; (postponed) II 500,506; (of _time_) I 29, &c.; immediately after, XII _b_ 147; (commenting)on, XI _b_ 20; _upon this matiere_, on this business, XII _a_ 45. (ii)in, VI 185, X 66, XII _introd._, _a_ 175; (believe) in, XV _g_ 9; into,VII 6, 140; (iii) to, V 184 (_see_ Stiȝtel); (iv) (think) of, V 329,VI 10. _See_ Grounde, Half, Out(e), Þer(e), &c. [OE. _up(p)-on_.]

4412.entry: #Vpon#, _adv._ on; _dede upon_, put on, XII _a_ 53. [As prec.]

4419.entry: #Vse#, #Vss(e)#, _n._ use, XIII _a_ 1; usage, ritual, XI _b_ 189, 196,&c. (_see_ note, XI _b_ 183). [OFr. _us_, L. _ūsus_.]

4420.entry: #Vse#, _v._ to use, practise, have dealings with, V 38, 358, XIII _b_14, XIV _a_ 30; #Y-vsed#, _pp._ XIII _b_ 26. [OFr. _user_.]

4422.entry: #Vttiremeste#, _adj._ extreme, furthest, XVI 232 (_see_ Ende). [Formedon ME. _utter(e)_, OE. _ū̆ttra_, on anal. of prec.]

4425.entry: #Wack(e)net#, _pa. t._ and _pp._ awoke, (was) aroused, VII 105, 110.[OE. _wæcn(i)an_.] _See_ Wake.

4426.entry: #Wage#, _v._ to undertake, guarantee, pay (hire), &c.; _intr._ or_absol._ ? (used for) securely continue, _or_ ? bring reward, VI 56.[ONFr. _wager_.]

4427.entry: #Wagh(e)#, #Wawe#, #Wawgh(e)#, _n._ wave, water (of the sea), VII 140,XII _a_ 157, XIV _c_ 33, XVII 426, &c. [ON. _vág-r_.]

4428.entry: #Wai#, #Way#, _interj._ woe! II 234, 546; _wai es him_, unhappy is one(who), XV _a_ 9. [ON. _vei_.] _See_ We, _interj._; Wo.

4600.entry: #Wille#, _v._ desire, wish, be willing; be likely, wont; intend, will,&c., and as auxil. of _fut. 1_ and _3 sg. pres._ #Wil#, #Wyl#, I 10, V89, 147, VIII _a_ 24, 39, IX 252, &c.; #Will(e)#, #Wyll#, III 2, IV _a_31, 52, &c.; #Wol(e)#, II 24, IX 279, XI _a_ 48, &c.; #Woll(e)#, VIII_b_ 40, XV _c_ 17, XVI 7, &c.; _2 sg._ #Wil#, #Wyl(l)#, IV _a_ 4, 17,88, VIII _a_ 222, &c.; #Wylt#, V 73. #Wolt#, VIII _a_ 271, XII _b_ 42,XV _g_ 33; (with suffixed pron.) #Wiltou#, #-ow#, II 128, XIV _a_ 21,&c.; (further reduced) #Wolte#, XV _g_ 19, 22; _pl._ #Wyl#, #Wil(l)#, I259, IV _b_ 2, IX 118, &c.; #Wol#, #Wole(n)#, VIII _b_ 85, IX 64, XI _b_64, 161, XIII _b_ 23, &c.; #Wolle#, XVI 240 (rime--_fille_); _wiltow orneltow_, whether you are willing or not, VIII _a_ 149 (_cf._ II 154);(without expressed infin.) will go (come), V 64, XVII 504; _wilt thouso_, you'll do that, will you? XVII 226. _Pa. t._ desired, wished, waswilling; was likely, used; intended, would; _subj._ would (be willing),would (should) like, could wish, &c.; as auxil. of _condit._ or _pa. t.subj._ would, should, &c.: #Vald#, X 79; #Wald(e)#, IV _a_ 39, X 21, XIV_b_ 12, &c.; #Wild#, I _introd._ (? ON. _vilda_); #Wold(e)#, I 185 (rime_colde_), II 188, 279, III 37, IV _b_ 25, V 28, VI 30, VIII _a_ 204, XI_a_ 51, XIV _c_ 20, XVI 253, XVII 47, &c.; #Wulde#, I 47, 90, 171; _2sg._ #Wold(e)#, #Woldeȝ#, #-est#, II 454, V 59, VI 50, XVI 362, XVII172, &c.; _wold awede_, was like to go mad (_or_ was going mad) II 87;_wold ich nold ich_, whether I would or no, II 154 (_cf._ VIII _a_ 149);(without expressed infin.) _wold vp_ (_in_), desired to rise (enter), II96, 378; _whider þai wold_, where they were going to, II 296; _waldeaway_, would depart, IV _a_ 75. [OE. _willan_, _wyllan_; pa. t. _wólde_,_wálde_.] _See_ Ichil, Ichulle.

4603.entry: #Wind(e)#, #Wynd(e)#, #Wynt#, _n._ wind, breath, IV _b_ 5, VII 116, XIII_a_ 8, XIV _a_ 33, _c_ 35, &c.; #Wynd blast#, blast of wind, XVII 355.[OE. _wínd_.]

4607.entry: #Wynke#, _n._ a wink (of sleep), I 159. [From OE. _wincian_, v.]

4608.entry: #Wynne#, #Wyn#, _n._ gain, profit, V 352; _hym to mekill wyn_, to hisgreat profit, XVII 109. [OE. _(ge-)winn_.]

4609.entry: #Wynne(n)#, #Winne#, #Wyn#, _v._ to win; #Wan(ne)#, _pa. t. sg._ VIII_a_ 90, XVI 9, &c.; _pl._ VII 174; #Wonne(n)#, _pp._ V 23, VI 157, &c.;

4610.entry: #Wonen#, V 347, VII 169; #Won#, IV _a_ 40, &c.; #Ywon#, II 561: _trans._to procure (with toil), VIII _a_ 21, 127; to win (in contest, &c.), winover, IV _a_ 8, 20, XIV _b_ 16, 56, XVI 9, &c.; to earn, VI 219, VIII_a_ 90, XVI 230, &c.; to gain, get, XVI 132, XVII 363, &c.; to (manageto) bring, get, IV _a_ 40, V 23, 347, VII 174; _wynne (away)_, rescue,II 561, XVI 18, 171, 266, 406; _intr._ to labour profitably, earn(something), VIII _a_ 155, 316, XII _b_ 37; to win one's way, get (to),V 163; get (away, from), escape, XVII 24, 549, &c.; _(were) wonen of_,had escaped, VII 169; _wyn to end_, succeed in completing, XVII 130; togo, come, V 147, VI 157. [OE. _ge-winnan_ and ON. _vinna_.]

4613.entry: #Wynter#, #Wintur#, #-er#, _n._ winter, II 259, VII 100; as _adj._ XV_b_ 8, 11 (_see_ note); #Winter-schours#, #-tyde#, winter storms, wintertime, II 59, XIV _b_ 26. [OE. _winter_; _winter-scūr_, _-tīd_.]

4614.entry: #Wypped#, _pa. t._ sent flying, V 181. [Cf. Fris., Du., LG. _wippen_.]

4619.entry: #Wys(e)dome#, #Wisdome#, _n._ wisdom, IV _b_ 56, 68, VIII _a_ 53; pieceof wisdom, VIII _a_ 206. [OE. _wīs-dōm_.]

4620.entry: #Wyse#, #Wise#, _n._ manner, fashion, guise. *II 158 (note), V 124, VII65, 77, VIII _a_ 59, XVI 25; _in many wise_, in many ways, XII _a_ 39;_in no(ne) wise_, at all, VIII _a_ 300, IX 283; _in the wise as_, justas, XII _a_ 101; _other wise many fold_, in many another fashion, XVII54. [OE. _wīse_.]

4621.entry: #Wish#, _n._ desire, will, XVII 4. [Stem of OE. _wȳ̆scan_, v.]

4623.entry: #Wisse#, #Wysshe#, _v._ to guide, direct, VII 4 (note); _wissed hymbettere_, directed him (to do) better, VIII _a_ 158. [OE. _wissian_.]

4625.entry: #Wysty#, _adj._ lonely, deserted, V 121. [OE. _wē̆stig_; for vowel_cf._ Ryste, and see Morsbach, _M.E. Gram._, § 109.]

4626.entry: #Wit#, #Witt(e)#, #Wyt#, #Wytt(e)#, _n. sg._ mind, senses, wits, II 82,III 46 (_dat._), XII _b_ 137, XVI 344, &c.; wisdom, XI _a_ 10;intelligence, discernment, understanding, I 11, VII 4, VIII _a_ 53, XI_a_ 12, 32 (? interpretation), 52, XII _b_ 198, &c.; sense, meaning, XI_a_ 6, 47, 53, &c.; _pl._ intelligence, II 38, XI _b_ 113; senses, wits,XII _a_ 158; _fyue wytteȝ_, five senses, V 125. _Bi my wytte_(_wit_), as I think, V 28, XVII 452; _do ... his wit_, apply his mind,XI _b_ 6; _gode wytt_, sound mind, IX 83; _Kynde Witt_, (natural) goodsense, VIII _a_ 243. [OE. _witt_.]

4628.entry: #Wite(n)#, #Wyte#, #Witte#, _v._^1 to know, learn, be aware, I 38, VIII_a_ 204, XI _b_ 82, XII _a_ 43, &c.; #Wate#, _1_ and _3 sg. pres._ IV_a_ 16, VI 142, XVII 444, &c.; #Woot#, XI _a_ 43, 50; #Wote#, I 38, VIII_a_ 124, XVII 313, &c.; _see_ Ichot, Not; #Wost#, _2 sg._ VI 51; #Wote#,XVI 222; #Wate#, _pl._ I _introd._; #Wyte#, I 250; #Wotte#, XVI 171.

4629.entry: #Wist(e)#, #Wyst(e)#, _pa. t._ I 160, II 194, III 27, 45, VII 23, XV _g_11 (_subj._), &c.; would know (_subj._), IX 184; _see_ Nist. _Don towyte_, inform, II 2; _We wille ȝe witte_, we intend that you shouldknow (_i.e._ have full warning of the rescue of the souls), XVI 176;_witte þou wele_, be assured, XVI 305. [OE. _witan_; _wāt_ pret.pres.; _wiste_, &c.] _See_ Ywyte.

4630.entry: #Wite#, _v._^2 to guard, keep, II 206, XV _f_ 13. [OE. _witian_, but inME. the senses and forms due to OE. _wītan_ (str.), _witan_ (pret.pres.), and _witian_ (wk.) were confused.]

4633.entry: #Wyterliche#, _adv._ clearly, VIII _b_ 38. [From prec. in ME. sense'plain'.]

4635.entry: #With#, #Wyþ#, #Wid# (XV _g_), #Wit# (VIII _b_ 6), #Wyt# (XV _d_ 6),&c., _prep._ with, against, XIV _b_ 36, XVII 138, &c.; (meet) with, II510, VIII _b_ 6, XV _g_ 7; (together) with, among, I 54, 133 (_see_ Wo),II 84, IV _a_ 4 (_see_ Beste), 5, XV _g_ 30, &c.; _es noghte with_, doesnot associate with,IV _b_ 2; at, XII _a_ 142; _with þat_, thereupon,VIII _a_ 239; with (_instr._) II 106, IV _b_ 62, XV _g_ 8, 29, &c.; by(means, reason of), II 404, VII 142, XVI 160, 297, &c.; by (_agent_), V348, 351, 358, VII 53, &c. _With al_, entirely, VIII _a_ 76 (OE. _midalle_); _with all this_, meanwhile, X 114; _wyth lyttel_, with littleresult, VI 215; _what with ... and with_, what with ... and, XVII 214._Bowes ... to schote with arwes_ (to shoot arrows with) is normal ME.order, IX 258; _cf._ VIII _a_ 259, 290, &c. [OE. _wiþ_ blended with_mid_ (_miþ_).] _See_ Þar(e), Þer(e).

4636.entry: #Withal#, #Vithall#, _adv._ withal, X 9; _forth withal_, straightway,XII _b_ 82, 129. [OE. _mid alle_; _see_ prec.]

4637.entry: #Withdrawe#, _v._ to withdraw; _intr._ retire, VIII _a_ 324; _pp._ reft(from her), XII _a_ 158. [OE. _wiþ_ + _dragan_.] _See_ Draw(e).

4638.entry: #Wythhalde#, _v._ to hold back, V 200; #Withhelde#, #Wythhylde#, _pa.t._ V 100, 223, &c. [OE. _wiþ_ + _háldan_.] _See_ Holde(n).

4639.entry: #Within(ne)#, #Wiþynne#, #Vithin# (X), &c., _adv._ inside, IX 141, X 13,70, XIII _a_ 16, XV _i_ 2, &c.; in (his) heart, V 302; _prep. within,in, VI 80, &c.; (freq. postponed) IV _a_ 38, 40, XVI 282, &c.; (of_time_) XII _a_ 29. [OE. _wiþ-innan_.]

4640.entry: #Withoute(n)#, #-outten#, #-owte(n)#, #-out#, &c., _adv._ outside, X 68,XV _i_ 2, XVII 127, &c.; _prep._ without, II 460, IV _a_ 96, VI 30, XVI300, XVII 149, &c.; _see_ Ende, Lees, Nay, No, &c. [OE. _wiþ-ūtan_.]

4648.entry: #Wlyteþ#, _pres. pl._ pipe, warble, XV _b_ 11. [Imit. of sound, orcorrupt for ? _wrytleþ_; cf. OE. _writian_, warble, ME. _writelinge_,n.]

4649.entry: #Wo#, _n._ woe, grief, pain, sorrow, &c., I 168, II 5, XV _b_ 8, XVII40, &c.; #Woo(e)#, XVI 18, 300, &c.; #Wa(a)#, IV _a_ 23, XVI 406, &c.;_wo was wyth (hym)_, (he) was grieved, I 132; _me is wo_, woe is me,unhappy am I, II 331, 542; (with _nom. pron._) _or ye be wo_, ere youare in trouble, XIV _d_ 11 (_see_ Ware, _adj._); _with (mochel) wo_,(very) painfully, VII 169, XII _a_ 105; _wepe and wo_, II 195, 234; _forwele ne wa(a)_, on no account, IV _a_ 2, _b_ 74; _worþe hit wele oþerwo_, whatever happens, V 66 (_see_ Worþe, _v._). [OE. _wā_.]

4650.entry: #Wod(e)#, _n._ wood(land), I 62, II 237, V 16, 84, &c.; trees, XV _b_14; wood, fuel, XII _b_ 113, 123, &c.; _to wode_, into the woods, XII_b_ 5. [OE. _wudu_.]

4651.entry: #Wode#, #Woode# (XVI), _adj._ mad, furious, II 394, V 221, XII _a_ 138,XV _g_ 17, XVI 344, XVII 426. [OE. _wōd_.] _See_ Awede.

4662.entry: #Wolues#, _n. pl._ wolves, II 539; #Wolues-kynnes#, of wolf's kind,wolvish, VIII _a_ 154. [OE. _wulf_; _wulfes_ (gen. sg.) + _cynnes_.]_See_ Kyn.

4663.entry: #Wombe#, _n._ belly, VIII _a_ 168, _b_ 54; _distrib. sg._ (_see_ Herte)VIII _a_ 209, 253; womb, XI _b_ 30. [OE. _wámb_, _wómb_.]

4666.entry: #Won(e)#, _v._ to dwell, abide, V 30, VI 44, XII _a_ 191, XIII _b_ 5, 7,XIV _a_ 23, &c.; #Wonne#, XVI 15, 235, 379, &c.; #Wonyd#, _pp._ dwelt, V46; #Wont#, accustomed, VIII _a_ 160, XII _a_ 179. [OE. _(ge)-wunian_,dwell, be accustomed.] _See_ Ywon(ed); Wones, _n. pl._

4667.entry: #Wonder#, #-ur#; #Wounder# (XV _b_); #Wunder#, #-yr#; (i) _n._ wonder,amazement, (a) marvel, IV _a_ 85, XIII _b_ 42, XVII 265, &c.; miraculousdeed, I 102; _mans wonder_, amazement of mankind, monster, XVII 408;_spake of hem wunder_, spoke wonderingly of them, I 225; #Wondres#,_pl._ marvels, XIII _a_ 6; (ii) _adj._ (orig. loose compound),marvellous, XIII _a_ 31, XVII 496; (iii) _adv._ (_cf._ OE. _wundrum_),marvellously, II 104, 356, V 132, XIII _a_ 10, XV _b_32, &c. [OE._wundor_, _wúndor_.] _See_ Wundred.

4673.entry: #Wones#, #Woneȝ#, _n. pl._ halls, II 365; (with _sg._ sense)dwelling, V 130, 332. [? ON. _ván_, expectation, occas. used as 'placewhere one may be expected to be' (cf. Norweg. _von_, expectation, hauntsof game); but the word was infl. by assoc. with Wone, dwell (_q.v._),with which it was often joined in allit. ME. rimes all require _wǭn_or _wān_.] _See_ Wane, _v._

4676.entry: #Wonte#, _v._ to be lacking; _yow_ (dat.) _wonted_, you lacked, V 298;_ȝef me shal wonte_, if I do not have, XV _b_ 34. [ON. _vanta_.]

4678.entry: #Worchinge#, #-yng#, _n._ working, operation, IX 56; _wondur w._,miraculous property, XIII _a_ 32. [OE. _wyrcung_.] _See_ Werche.

4680.entry: #Word(e)#, #Woord#, #Wurde# (I), _n._ word, I 108, II 139, 222, V 305,XI _a_ 10, XVII 380, &c.; plighted word, II 468; fame, in _þe word ofhim walkes ful wide_, his fame is spread abroad, XIV _b_ 29; _worchipand wordes_, obsequious words, VII 174. [OE. _wórd_.]

4681.entry: #Wore#, _n._ ? troubled pool, XV _c_ 30 (note). [OE. _wār_ (indoubtful gloss), turbid, muddy water (see Napier, _O.E. Glosses_, p. 49(note); but _cf._ OE. _wārig_; ME. _wōri_, muddy).]

4683.entry: #World(e)#, _n._ world, earth, men, I 225, II 41, IX 72, &c.; #Warld#,II 403, XVII 70, 303; _warld so wide_, XVII 541; #Werld#, XIV _b_ 16;_in world_, _of the w._, on earth, XV _c_ 25, IX 183; _werldes_,_worldes_, (gen.) of the world, worldly, in _worldes reches_, IV _b_ 61;_worldes wele_, _see_ Wele, _n._ [OE. _w(e)orold_.]

4685.entry: #Worm#, _n._ snake, worm, II 252, IV _b_ 27, XII _b_ 195, XV _b_ 31.[OE. _wyrm_.]

4691.entry: #Wers(e)#, XVI 200; _neuer him nas wers_, never had he been moreunhappy, II 98; #Wars#, _adv._ in _the wars_, so much the worse that,XVII 191 (_see_ Þe, _adv._). #Werst#, _adj. superl._ worst, meanest, II367; #Worst#, V 30. [OE. _wyrsa_, _wyrsta_; with _er-_ forms _cf._Werche, Scherte.] _See_ Werre.

4694.entry: #Worþe#, #Wrþe#, _adj._ worth, VI 91; worthy, in _þou were wrþe_, youwould be worthy, you deserve, XV _g_ 8 (_cf._ Worþy). [OE. _weorþe_,_wyrþe_.]

4695.entry: #Worþe#, _v._ to come to pass, become, be, and _auxil._ of _passive_(_esp._ with _fut._ sense); #Worst#, _2 sg. pres._ wilt be, II 170, 174;

4696.entry: #Worth#, _3 sg._ will be, VIII _a_ 48; will come to pass, VIII _a_ 156;

4697.entry: #Worþe#, #Worth#, #Wurth#, _subj. pres._ be, let there be, V 306, VI 2;_worþe hit wele oþer wo_, come weal or woe, V 66 (_see_ Wo); _wel worthþe_, may it go well with thee, V 59; _wele wurth þe while_, good luck tothe time, happy the occasion, XIV _a_ 5, &c. (_see_ Wel). #Warth#, _pa.t. sg._ in _hym warth_, accrued to him, VIII _b_ 102; #Worþed#, _subj._would fare, V 28; #Worþen#, _pp._ in _is w. to_, has turned to, isbecome (one of), VI 34. [OE. _weorþan_, _wurþan_.] _See_ Yworth.

4698.entry: #Worþy#, #Worthi#, _adj._ merited, just, XVI 324; worthy, deserving(constr. _to_ and _infin._), IV _b_ 10, IX 172, XVI 132; _w. toreherse_, worth repeating, XI _a_ 4; _were w. (be)_, deserve (to be),XVI 357, XVII 200 (_were_ is _subj._; _cf._ Worþe, _adj._); worthy (ofhonour), worshipful, VI 134, IX 269, XI _a_ 25, XII _a_ 165, XVII 19;_worthiest (of)_, most worshipful (in), XVII 489. #Worthier#, _compar.adv._ more honourably, VIII _a_ 48; #Worþili#, _adv._ honourably, XIV_c_ 67. [OE. _wyrþig_ merited.] _See_ Vnworthi.

4701.entry: #Wou#, _adv._ how (is it that), why, XV _g_ 25. [OE. _hū_, ? infl. by_hwȳ_, &c.] _See_ Hou.

4709.entry: #Wrang(e)#, _adj._ and _adv._ wrong, unjust(ly), VI 128, XVI 264, 265,305, XVII 188. [Late OE. _wráng_, from ON. _*wrang-_, OIcel. _rang-r_.]

4712.entry: #Wrath#, _v._ to anger; _to wrath hym_ (refl.), to become enraged, VIII_a_ 146; #Wrathed#, _pp._ wronged, brought to grief, V 352. [From next.]_See_ Wrethe.

4713.entry: #Wraþþe#, #Wrathþe#, _n._ anger, XI _b_ 94; offence, VI 2. [OE._wrǣ̆þþo_, anger, injury.] _See_ Wroþ, Wreth.

4717.entry: #Wreke#, _pp._ revenged, XV _g_ 11; #Wroken#, #Wrokin#, (banished),removed, VI 15; revenged, XIV _a_ 4, 5, XVI 199. [OE. _wrecan_, expel,punish.] _See_ Awreke.

4719.entry: #Wrethe#, _v._ to anger, offend, IV _b_ 85. [Cf. OE. _ge-wrǣþan_,refl., to be enraged.] _See_ Wrath.

4722.entry: #Wryng(e)#, _v._ to wring; wring (the hands), IV _a_ 65, XVII 211;

4723.entry: #Wronge#, _pa. t. sg._ wrung, twisted and pinched, VIII _a_ 168. [OE._wríngan_.]

4724.entry: #Writ(e)#, #Writt(e)#, #Wryt#, _n._ writing, III 36 (_dat. sg._);Scripture, I 12, IV _b_ 76, XI _a_ 10, _b_ 23, &c. [OE. _writ_.]

4725.entry: #Write#, #Wryte#, _v._ to write, VIII _a_ 79, _b_ 72, IX 122; #Wrote#,_pa. t. sg._ I 247; _pl._ VII 58; #Writen#, _pa. t. pl._ XI _a_ 23;

4726.entry: #Write(n)#, #Wryte(n)#, _pp._ I 37, 40, IV _a_ 2, VII 31, IX 318 (_see_Putte), XII _a_ 1, &c.; #Ywryte#, #Ywrite#, II 1, 13, III _introd._, 33;

4730.entry: #Wryþe(n)#, _v._ to twist; bind, VI 151; turn aside (from the justcourse), VI 128. [OE. _wrīþan_.]

4733.entry: #Wrote#, _v._ to root in the earth, II 255. [OE. _wrōtan_.]

4734.entry: #Wroþ(e)#, #Wroth#, _adj._ angry, at variance, II 122, VI 19, XV _f_ 7,XVII 36, &c.; _make hym_ (refl.) _wroth_, become angry, I 10. [OE._wrāþ_.] _See_ Wraþþe.

4738.entry: #Wruxled#, _pp._ in _wr. in grene_, ? changed into, turned, green, V123; but 'adorned' is usually assumed here and for _wruxeled_, Purity1381. [OE. _wrixl(i)an_, (ex)change. A sense 'adorned' might be derivedfrom an (unrecorded) earlier sense, 'turn, wind round' (? rel. to_wrēon_, _wrigels_), or perh. from OE. _wrixlan (blēom)_, changecolours, exhibit varied hues.]

4741.entry: #Wunne#, _n._ joy; _gen. sg._ in _wunne wele_ (_weole_), wealth of joy,XV _b_ *11 (MS. wynter), 35. [OE. _wynn_.]

4743.entry: #Y-#; _see also_ Ȝ, I. For past participles in _y-_ not entered below_see_ the verbs concerned.

4745.entry: #Y-arched#, _pp._ in _y-arched of gold_, built of gold in the shape ofan arch, II 362. [OFr. _archer_, v.]

4751.entry: #Ycore# (orig. _pp._ of Chese, _q.v._), chosen, excellent; as mereintensive rime-tag, II 105, 148. [OE. _ge-coren_.]

4752.entry: #Ydel#, #Ydill# (IV), #Hydel# (VIII), _adj._ unemployed, idle, IV _b_ 1,VI 154, 155, VIII _b_ 27, &c.; slothful, IV _b_ 9, XI _b_ 219. [OE._īdel_.]

4757.entry: #Yei#, _adv._ yes indeed, XVII 370, 458; oh yes (ironic), XVII 353. [?Reduction of a reiteration _ȝē-ȝē_, or assimilated to ME._nei_, nay; see _N.E.D._ s.v. _Yea_.] _See_ Ȝa, Ȝe.

4760.entry: #Yfere#, _adv._ in _al yfere_, all together, II 223. [Orig. _yfere(n)_,OE. _ge-fēran_, pl., (as) companions.] _See_ Fere, _n._^2

4764.entry: #Yhere#, _v._ to hear, II 420; #Yherd#, _pa. t._ II 528; #Yhyerde#, III49. [OE. _ge-hēran_.] _See_ Here.

4765.entry: #Yhyȝt#, _pp._ (adorned), arranged, XIII _a_ 1. [ME. _hihten_, prob.from OE. _hyht_, pleasure (_hyhtlic_, pleasant).]

4770.entry: #Ylet#, _n._ hindrance; _ȝif þou makest ous ylet_, if you offer anyresistance to us, II 169. [Not recorded elsewhere; usual ME. form isLette, _q.v._ Other MSS. read _ony let_.]

4771.entry: #Ylokked#, _pp._ locked up, IX 174. [ME. _lok(k)en_, from _lok_, OE._loc_, n.; cf. ON. _loka_, v.] _See_ Loke, _pp._; Vnlokynne.

4780.entry: #Ynoȝ#: #Ynouh#, _adj._ enough, XII _b_ 123; #Ynowȝ#, XI _b_ 190,192; #Ynowþȝ#, XI _b_ 149; #Inogh#, abundant, much, XV _a_ 15;

4782.entry: #Enogh#, XVII 532, #Inoghe#, VI 252; #Ynouh#, XII _b_ 74; #Ynoȝ#(_of_), abundance (of), III 8; #Ynoh#, very, XV _c_ 13. [OE._ge-nōg_, _ge-nōh_.] _See_ Ynow(e).

4785.entry: #Enew#, _pl._ in abundance, great numbers, XI _b_ 284, X 7; #Ynow#,_adv._ enough, XIII _b_ 8; very, IX 4. [OE. _ge-nōg-_, oblique formsof _ge-nōh_.] _See_ Ynoȝ.

4786.entry: #Yond#, _adj._; as _pron._ that (over there), XVII 453. [OE. _geond_,thither; cf. Goth. _jaind_.]

4787.entry: #Yone#, _adj._ that (over there), XVI 340; #Ȝon#, V 76. [OE. (once)_geon_, cf. Goth. _jain-s_. See _N.E.D._, s.v. _Yon_.]

4791.entry: #Yre#, _n._^1 iron, XIII _a_ 44; #Yrne#, V 199; #Yrnes#, _pl._ irons(supporting injured leg), VIII _a_ 130. [OE. _īren_.] _See_Irnebandis.

4792.entry: #Yre#, #Ire#, _n._^2 anger, XVII 51; _in hor gret yre_, so as greatly toanger them, VII 181. [OFr. _ire_.]

4794.entry: #Y-se#, _v._ to see, II 530; #Yzeȝ#, _pa. t. sg._ III 35, 41, 56;

4795.entry: #Yseiȝe#, _pa. t. pl._ II 328; for pp. _see_ Se(n). [OE._ge-sēon_.]

4803.entry: #Yuel(e)#, _adj._ evil, wicked, IX 237; difficult, VIII _a_ 50; #Euyll#,evil, IX 83. [OE. _yfel_, adj.]

4804.entry: #Yuel#, _n._ evil, wrong, VIII _introd._, _a_ 220; #Euel(l)#, IV _a_ 76,IX 338, XV _g_ 28. [OE. _yfel_, n.]

4812.entry: #Yworth#, #Aworthe#, _v._ to be, go on as before, in _late God yworth_,_late þow G. aworthe_, meddle not with God, it is God's affair, VIII _a_76, 220. [OE. _geweorþan_.] _See_ Worþe, _v._
